<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-INFORMATION-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOLLOWING A SCRIPT, U.S. OFFICIALS REVEAL LITTLE ABOUT NATO
CAMPAIGN
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS for general rewrite. Grafs 4, 6, 17 and 18 represent new
material.)   (See also: KOSOVO-RDP, KOSOVO-NATO-ASSESS, KOSOVO-YUGOSLAVIA,
KOSOVO-MACEDONIA, KOSOVO-SERB, KOSOVO-COUNCIL, KOSOVO-MIGS,
KOSOVO-LEGAL, KOSOVO-ALLIES, KOSOVO-REPUBS, KOSOVO-TRAVEL.) 
(wg) 
 By ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In the 1991 Persian Gulf war, the military allies
gave detailed briefings twice a day, in Washington and in Saudi
Arabia, announcing the number of combat flights, targets hit and
Iraqi troop movements.
</P>
<P>
   Reporters complained of being spoon-fed only what the Pentagon
wanted them to know, without a chance to confirm independently the
damage to Baghdad's forces.
</P>
<P>
   But at least it was something, which is considerably more than
is being disclosed about the bombing of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Even as President Clinton's national security advisers flood the
television airwaves with back-to-back-to-back interviews to justify
NATO's air campaign against Yugoslavia, the U.S. military has
clammed up on many of the most basic details of the operation.
Pentagon briefers have refused to discuss what the pilots are
trying to bomb, or whether they have destroyed particular targets.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials say they are concerned that their
colleagues have become overly casual about the handling of
classified information, a complacency that the Defense Department
spokesman, Kenneth Bacon, attributed to a belief that U.S.
interests are less at risk in the post-Cold War era. There is also,
he said, a growing hunger for operational details from a media
driven by 24-hour news cycles.
</P>
<P>
   As an example of the casual treatment of sensitive material,
Bacon said that a planned cruise missile attack against a Bosnian
Serb mobile missile battery in 1995 was called off after a
televised report of the impending strike. The Serbs, Bacon said,
moved the target after the report aired.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon said relatively little about air strikes last
summer against suspected terrorist sites in Afghanistan and Sudan
(even a subsequent awards ceremony for the pilots was held in
secret) and the current low-level bombing campaign against Iraq (so
as not to upset Persian Gulf allies.)
</P>
<P>
   The sensitivities of the 19-member NATO alliance have added
another element to the Yugoslav operation.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some European allies who don't like this portrayed
as too much of an American show, and there are other allies who
don't want information about their role put out at all,'' said a
senior military spokesman on the condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   At NATO headquarters in Brussels on Friday, a British air
commodore, David Wilby, gave the first details on the total number
of NATO flights (400), a partial list of some of the Yugoslav
targets (18 of 50 sites), the damage inflicted to them (light to
totally destroyed) and videotapes of some of the successful
bombings. But alliance spokesmen still are not talking about
casualties on the ground, the operation's cost, the dogfights that
downed five Yugoslav MiGs and the country-by-country makeup of each
day's attacking air forces.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, senior administration officials are following a
tightly choreographed script as they seek to manage information and
perceptions of the air campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright Friday appeared on three
television morning news shows, repeating the administration's
deter-or-be-destroyed mantra to the Yugoslav president, Slobodan
Milosevic. But she shied away from specific questions on reports of
massacres by Serbs in Kosovo or attacks on American Embassy
employees in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   When asked what the administration will do if Milosevic does not
bow to the bombing, the president's national security adviser,
Sandy Berger, sidestepped the question: ``There's one end state if
we do nothing. The end state in the other direction is either a
peace, which we hope to be the case, or a severely diminished
military capacity for Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   And Defense Secretary William Cohen and Gen. Henry Shelton,
chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, say it is too early to
discuss publicly the impact of the bombing.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe with journalists. But in an effort to keep a skeptical
Congress supportive, or at least not hostile, military intelligence
analysts gave lawmakers an upbeat, richly detailed classified
assessment of the early attacks on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Given the secrecy surrounding ongoing military missions,
administrations have the upper hand in controlling the flow of
information and the spokesmen for that news.
</P>
<P>
   At the Pentagon briefing Friday, reporters challenged Bacon to
provide detailed briefings, as the British have done in London, and
urged him to have Gen. Wesley Clark, the NATO military commander,
update his morning briefings to accommodate the evening deadlines
of American reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Bacon sloughed off the complaints, and said he would pass along
the request to Clark.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, when a reporter suggested to Bacon that he might
buff his credibility by admitting that some American bombs missed
their mark, as a British military spokesman said this week about
some British strikes, the Pentagon spokesman acknowledged the
information lock-down: ``You haven't heard about many bombs hitting
their targets, either. I think we've been pretty even-handed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
