<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the top stories from The New York Times News Service
report for PMs of Saturday, March 27.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, (212) 556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. ET. To get
story repeats before this hour, call (212) 621-1595 for reruns on
AP DataFeatures or (214) 980-8305 or 8306 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   ART ADV: Graphics and photos are being sent, as indicated below,
to NYT Graphics and Photos subscribers. Clients needing
retransmissions or information, or non-subscribers seeking to
arrange individual purchases, should call (212) 556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO
</P>
<P>
   (Moved in `i' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RDP (Washington) _ As NATO stepped up its bombing into
the daylight hours, Yugposlav President Slobodan Milosevic
maintained fierce resistance both on the ground and in the air. Two
of his MiG-29 fighters shot down on what NATO claimed was a foray
into neighboring Bosnia. The sweep by Serb troops through the
ethnic Albanian villages of Kosovo continued unabated, NATO said,
despite the third straight day of air assaults that NATO officials
emphasized would be unrelenting until Milosevic accepted peace. By
Francis X. Clines and Steven Lee Myers. WITH GRAPHIC.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-ALLIES (Washington) _ Iceland has no military. Luxembourg
has no air force. Greece doesn't want to bomb a neighbor. And
Poland, Hungary and the Czech Republic have only been NATO members
for two weeks. But those six countries, though not contributing
forces to the assault on Serbia, bridle at the suggestion that they
are not full partners in the allied attack. By Elizabeth Becker.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RUSSIA-LEWINSKY (Moscow) _ Russia's rage over NATO
airstrikes in Yugoslavia boiled over when it canceled the upcoming
visit by Monica Lewinsky. She had been scheduled to visit Russia in
June or July to promote a Russian-language version of her book,
`Monica's Story.' Friday night, however, the Russian publisher
announced that the trip was being canceled.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-NATO-ASSESS (Brussels) _ The allied military strategy for
stopping Serbian attacks against ethnic Albanian rebels in Kosovo
rests largely on the hope of a specific Serbian response to the
heavy NATO bombing, according to officials here. The hope, allied
officers and diplomats say, is that intense airstrikes will cause
so much damage to Yugoslavia's army and its sophisticated
air-defense system that Serb commanders may soon pressure him to
back down and accept allied terms before they lose everything. By
Craig R. Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-U.S.-SCHOOLS (Undated) _ In schools around the country, a
complicated lesson in geopolitics has suddenly sprung from the
textbook onto the television screen. And like many of their
parents, students are struggling to make sense of it. Few had heard
of Kosovo before NATO began air strikes on Wednesday. The military
assault and its historical background puzzled students at every
grade level. But they, their parents and their teachers said the
fighting in the Balkans offered a chance to link current events and
history. And teachers were seizing the moment. By Randal C.
Archibold.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-LEGAL (Undated) _ The NATO attack on Yugoslavia skirts
the edge of international law, legal experts say. But there are few
meaningful sanctions that could be imposed under international law
and legal principles are vague enough to provide justification for
the bombing as a humanitarian act. By William Glaberson.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MACEDONIA (Jazince, Macedonia) _ Since the bombing began,
accounts of Serb reprisals against Kosovars range from harrassment
and property damage to the killings of civilians. But information
is sketchy and unverifiable. For now, the world is relying on
rushed and emotional reports by a few refugees and scratchy
mobile-phone calls from Kosovars trapped in their homes. By
Alessandra Stanley. WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MIGS (Washington) _ The Yugoslav MiG-29s are among the
world's top fighter jets. But NATO has Awacs radar planes to track
their every move, long-range air-to-air missiles to shoot at them
and better trained pilots who anticipate the Yugoslav pilots'
antiquated Soviet-style tactics. And that is why NATO has shot down
5 of Belgrade's 15 most advanced MiGs in the past three days. By
Eric Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-SERB (Washington) _ The Clinton administration and a
European security group said they had received reports from
refugees fleeing Kosovo and others that an estimated 15,000 to
20,000 ethnic Albanian civilians were put on a forced march in
central Kosovo by Serbian forces. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-YUGOSLAVIA (Belgrade) _ Whispers about a face-saving
Serbian loss to the world's most powerful military alliance began
here long before NATO bombs started to fall. Forfeit of control of
Kosovo through peaceful negotiation would be humiliating. But a
hard military loss of Kosovo, after a brave struggle against an
overwhelming Western foe, could be just the ticket Milosevic needs
to survive with his Serbian manhood and his rule intact. By Blaine
Harden.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-COUNCIL (United Nations) _ In a resounding victory for
the U.S. and its NATO alliance, the Security Council overwhelmingly
rejected Friday a Russian-sponsored resolution demanding an
immediate end to NATO's airstrikes against Yugoslavia. The vote on
the 15-member Security Council was 12 against the resolution and
three in favor. By Judith Miller.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-REPUBS (Washington) _ Republican presidential contenders
are deeply divided over whether the U.S. should play any role in
Serbia, and most accused President Clinton of a misguided foreign
policy that led to this country's entanglement there. By Richard L.
Berke.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-INFORMATION (Washington) _ What senior U.S. officials are
saying publicly about the attack, and why, and the efforts to
manage information and perceptions of the air campaign. By Eric
Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-TRAVEL (Undated) _ A look at the disruption in air travel
caused by the conflict in the Balkans. By Edwin McDowell.
</P>
<P>
   OTHER FOREIGN
</P>
<P>
   (Moved in `i' category)
</P>
<P>
   EUROPEAN-UNION (Berlin) _ German Chancellor Gerhard Schroder
guided the European Union early Friday to a landmark agreement to
hold down its spending enough to enable three Central European
countries to join. The union also advocated Palestinian statehood
within the next year in more forthright terms than it had
previously used or than the United States has ever backed,
provoking a furious reaction from Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu
of Israel. By Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE-TUNNEL-FIRE (Paris) _ French and Italian officials said
Friday that at least 35 people had died in a fire that erupted
Wednesday deep inside the Mont Blanc tunnel in the Alps. The blaze,
which began in a heavy truck and quickly engulfed some 30 other
vehicles, was finally brought under control Friday. By Alan Riding.
WITH GRAPHIC.
</P>
<P>
   U.S.-RUSSIA-URANIUM (United Nations) _ Russia and the U.S. have
quietly signed an agreement that salvages a $12 billion deal aimed
at helping Russia convert uranium from its nuclear weapons into
fuel for U.S. nuclear reactors. By Judith Miller.
</P>
<P>
   U.S.-CHINA-RIGHTS (Washington) _ The Clinton administration
announced that it would sponsor a U.N. resolution next month
condemning Beijing for what the resolution calls the wholesale
violation of human rights. By David E. Sanger.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-SPY-CASE (Washington) _ The FBI has found and questioned a
Chinese researcher in connection with the inquiry into China's
suspected theft of U.S. nuclear secrets from the Los Alamos
National Laboratory. The researcher, a Chinese man who worked at
Los Alamos for several months in 1997, was located by the the FBI
on Thursday at Pennsylvania State University. By James Risen.
</P>
