<P>
   BUDGET-ANALYSIS (Washington) In passing the Republican tax and
spending plan, Congress took care of the easy part of this year's
budget battle. By managing to hold their fractious caucus together
and dampen rivalries between the party's leaders in the House and
Senate, Republicans managed to lay out a cohesive agenda built
around a sweeping tax cut, fiscal austerity and smaller government.
By Richard W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   (Moved in `a' category)
</P>
<P>
   KEVORKIAN (Pontiac, Mich.) _ Dr. Jack Kevorkian was convicted of
murder for giving a fatal injection to a terminally ill man. People
on both sides of the assisted-suicide debate say the trial will
have a profound impact on future discussion of the issue,
especially since Kevorkian may spend the rest of his life in
prison. By Pam Belluck.
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOL-VOUCHERS (Milwaukee) _ Nine years into the nation's first
school-voucher program here, there is no question that the concept
has taken hold. More than 6,000 poor children, 6 percent of the
city's students, receive publicly financed vouchers of nearly
$5,000 a year to attend private or parochial schools. But for
cities that are hotly debating vouchers, Milwaukee's experience
shows that time and familiarity neither cool passions nor _ so far
_ prove or disprove the value of vouchers. By Tamar Lewin. WITH
PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   NY-POLICE-INDICT (New York) _ After weeks of protests over the
Giuliani administration's combative police policies, Police
Commissioner Howard Safir unveiled major changes in the street
crime unit aimed at averting confrontations like that in which four
white officers gunned down an unarmed black man, and for which they
have been indicted for murder. By Robert D. McFadden. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   YOSEMITE-MISSING (San Francisco) _ The sorrowful mystery of what
happened to three tourists who disappeared from Yosemite National
Park was in large part answered Friday when the authorities
announced that a body found along a highway leading to the park was
that of the last missing person. By Evelyn Nieves.
</P>
<P>
   HMOS-MASSACHUSETTS (Boston) _ Massachusetts' secretary of state
is so mad at HMOS that he has threatened to take away their
nonprofit status because they are forcing elderly to go without
needed medicine. By Carey Goldberg.
</P>
<P>
   NY-POLICE-PROTEST (New York) _ Jesse Jackson and others plan to
be arrested Friday as demonstrations continue a day after the
indictments. By Jodi Wilgoren.
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-COLUMN (Undated) _ America's religious organizations
are divided over the NATO bombing of Yugoslavia, even though many
of these organizations echo NATO's concern over Yugoslav attacks on
Kosvars. By Gustav Niebuhr.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS DAY
</P>
<P>
   (Moved in `f' category)
</P>
<P>
   RENAULT-NISSAN (Frankfurt, Germany) _ Can a team of 40 French
executives rescue a loss-plagued Japanese car company with 40,000
employees? That is the question confronting Carlos Ghosn, executive
vice president of Renault, the French automaker. By Edmund L.
Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   ONLINE-SHOP-EUROPE (Milan, Italy) _ While Americans have
embraced online shopping, Europeans are just now warming to
electronic commerce. It is not easy to persuade Europeans, who have
a wealth of small shops and age-old shopping habits, that they
should shop on the Web. By John Tagliabue. WITH PHOTO and GRAPHIC.
</P>
<P>
   FED-MEETING (Washington) _ The Federal Reserve is almost certain
to leave interest rates unchanged when its policy-making committee
meets Tuesday, but the central bank remains wary of resurgent
inflation because of the economy's continued strength, analysts
say. By Richard W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   U.S.-AUTO-CANADA (Detroit) _ American entrepreneurs have been
buying tens of thousands of vehicles cheaply at Canadian
dealerships and reselling them in the United States. By Keith
Bradsher. WITH GRAPHIC.
</P>
<P>
   TOYS-RESIGNATION (Undated) _ Just a year after arriving at Toys
`R' Us as second in command, Bruce Krysiak has resigned as
president and chief operating officer of the beleaguered retailer.
By Dana Canedy.
</P>
<P>
   CBS-KINGWORLD (Undated) _ CBS has been in preliminary
discussions to acquire King World Productions, the syndicator of
such hit shows as `Oprah' and `Wheel of Fortune.' By Laura M.
Holson.
</P>
