<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-SUNS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KNICKS SET SUNS, 94-87 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By SELENA ROBERTS  
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ The New York Knicks' desperation to win overwhelmed
the panic they were feeling in the fourth quarter Friday night when
they nearly let another lead slip from their hands. Instead of
giving into the mental mistakes and carelessness, the Knicks found
the resolve to put the Suns away, 94-87, at America West Arena.
</P>
<P>
   Their relief was visible when the clock expired and their
three-game losing streak came to an end. The Knicks (16-13) were
led by Allan Houston's 29 points and Latrell Sprewell's 23.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks had a 9-point lead to begin the fourth quarter. They
had a reason to worry. They had blown a 9-point lead in the fourth
against Sacramento on Wednesday. With history repeating itself, the
Knicks watched as the Suns turned the Knicks' silly fouls,
turnovers and bad shot selection into a 16-6 run to take the lead,
78-77, on two free throws by Danny Manning with 5 minutes 55
seconds left in the game.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks could have panicked. But Charlie Ward grabbed a loose
ball and then forced a turnover by Jason Kidd, leading to two
scores that allowed the Knicks to retake the lead, 81-78, with 4:46
remaining.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Ewing then came up with an impact play. On a missed
jumper by Ward, he grabbed the rebound and layed it back in with
3:20 left to give the Knicks a 5-point advantage. That lead was
threatened after Luc Longley sneaked in for a putback to pull the
Suns to within 85-82. The Suns had a chance to tie it after Houston
turned the ball over and helped set up George McCloud for an open
3-point attempt. He missed, and the Knicks still had the lead.
After a flurry of misses by the Suns, Sprewell came up with a
defensive rebound and was fouled.
</P>
<P>
   He calmly hit two free throws with 51.2 seconds left in the game
to give the Knicks a 87-82 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks avoided their first four-game losing streak in three
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're going through a tough streak, the pressure
heightens to win,'' coach Jeff Van Gundy said before the game.
``So, I think they feel the pressure a little bit. And that's good,
though.''
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks have been stuck in a funk most of the season.
Whenthey have built leads, they have not had the killer's instinct
to put a team away.
</P>
<P>
   With each mental collapse, the Knicks' confidence has grown more
threadbare. Although the season is just past its halfway point, the
Knicks needed to find a way to dismiss the Suns just to let them
know that they could pull off such a feat.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of team at this point would give in mentally and get
down,'' Houston said. ``We can't do that. Mentally, this is a game
we need to get.''
</P>
<P>
   Houston needed an electric performance as much as anyone.
Wednesday night, after a sleepy effort against the Kings for three
quarters, he was benched by Van Gundy for the fourth quarter.
Houston looked on as the Knicks folded before him, helpless to do
anything about it. Houston didn't blame Van Gundy. He blamed
himself.
</P>
<P>
   Houston uncorked a load of energy in the third quarter.
Together, with an intense defense, the Knicks rode his hot streak
to a 69-56 lead with 3:08 left in the third quarter. At that
moment, a sizzling Houston had an attention-getting 29 points, 13
of them in the third quarter. Entering the fourth, the Knicks led
by 71-62.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks seemed on top of their game. But they had to be wary
of the kind of lapses that cropped up in the second quarter. After
another mental meltdown, the Knicks' 9-point second-quarter lead
was turned into a 48-47 Suns' lead at the half. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   REBOUNDS
</P>
<P>
   _ With 3 minutes 49 seconds left in the first quarter, PATRICK
EWING grabbed his fourth rebound of the game. And with that, Ewing
became the 12th player in league history to reach 20,000 points and
10,000 rebounds. Leading the list of the double-double club is
KAREEM ABDUL-JABBAR (33,387 points, 17,440 rebounds).
</P>
<P>
   _ Ewing was not amused when SHAQUILLE O'NEAL's name was
mentioned this morning after the shoot-around. In an interview with
Sports Illustrated, O'Neal blasted Ewing's leadership as president
of the players' union during the National Basketball Association's
lockout. O'Neal, who can opt out of his deal to be a free agent
this summer, could have demanded $20-million a year or more under
the old labor agreement. Now, he would be limited to $14 million
under the current deal. ``Tell him I'll see him on Sunday,'' Ewing
said. The Knicks play the Los Angeles Lakers at the Forum on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Suns were playing their third game in three nights. The
Suns were also without 3-point shooter REX CHAPMAN. He was
suspended for the game and fined $5,000 after pointing at and
making contact with an official after he was called for a blocking
foul against Portland on Thursday night.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
