<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RODMAN REPLACES KNIGHT AS STARTER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ A week ago, Dennis Rodman was missing in
action, drawing fines for an unexcused sojourn to Las Vegas. By
Friday night, he'd earned a job promotion.
</P>
<P>
   Only in L.A.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Kurt Rambis made the expected move Friday _ replacing
Travis Knight with Rodman in the starting lineup _ in an effort to
reverse the Los Angeles Lakers' recent trend of lifeless first
quarters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm in no way blaming our slow starts solely on Travis,''
Rambis said. ``That had absolutely nothing to do with it. I'm just
looking to tweak (the lineup) with a better alternative.''
</P>
<P>
   So what Rodman's seven rebounding titles couldn't do, the
Lakers' anemic starts did instead _ got him his first start since
joining the team six weeks ago. The Lakers had been outscored in
the first quarter in three straight games and four of the past five
entering Friday's game against Sacramento.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll see if that corrects itself,'' Rambis said.
</P>
<P>
   Knight, the Lakers' starter in all but three of their first 29
games, has consistently gotten in early foul trouble, limiting his
minutes and effectiveness, and was playing about half as much as
Rodman.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been up and down but he hasn't been getting consistent
playing time either,'' Rambis said. ``I've messed with him a little
bit, but him getting in foul trouble, I've gotta take him out.''
</P>
<P>
   Knight was disappointed but said he understood the change.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all right. (Rambis) is a good coach and I think everybody
on this team has faith in Kurt that he wants the team to win.
That's our common goal. And the thing that helps the team the most,
that's what we need to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm ready to do whatever Kurt thinks is best.... I'm still
gonna work hard, still gonna play hard, see where it goes.''
</P>
<P>
   Where it went was further down the depth chart, to No. 3 behind
Rodman and now Robert Horry. Rambis liked the energy Rodman brought
off the bench, but with Rodman in the starting lineup, Rambis
decided to replace that spark with Horry, last year's starter at
the position.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can continue that (spark) with (Horry's) activity and his
smart play,'' Rambis said.
</P>
<P>
   Rambis has considered other changes in the rotation as well, but
is making one at a time.
</P>
<P>
   More change: J.R. Reid has apparently cemented his position as
the No. 2 center behind Shaquille O'Neal, pushing Sean Rooks to No.
3 again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very happy about it,'' said Reid, who was fighting for
time at power forward. ``All I want is a chance to contribute....
It makes no difference what position I play. I've played it all _
small forward, power forward and center, so it's all the same to
me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
