<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-27 00:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6301 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT     03-27 0758
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: REALITY SLOWLY STARTS TO DAWN FOR 4 TEAMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By WILLIAM C. RHODEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ Scoonie Penn walked out on the court for
practice Friday afternoon and looked up at 27,662 fans who showed
up for a midday workout session. Finally it all sunk in: this
really was it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt ever since we beat St. John's last week and we've been
in the Final Four, I mean, I felt like it really hasn't hit me that
much,'' said Penn, the Ohio State guard. ``But I know when I walked
out there for the first time today and heard the crowd yell, just
seeing everybody's faces lit up, it made me feel like we are at the
Final Four. It's just a great feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   His coach, the normally low-key Jim O'Brien, was equally
impressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The concept of the Final Four was there when we beat St.
John's,'' O'Brien said. ``When you cut down nets, that was the
thing that got everybody's attention. That this is a championship
of sorts is fine. But when you finally get here and you go out for
the final practice and you see the number of people and you see the
environment, it's at that point that it really sinks in.''
</P>
<P>
   This is big-time college basketball at its best. For all the
excesses and contradictions, treading over youthful exuberance with
rules and enforcement, these last two weeks make the season worth
the wait.
</P>
<P>
   A player like Penn, who started off at Boston College, was
rookie of the year; two years later, sobered by the business of
basketball, he left and followed O'Brien to Ohio State. He spent
last season in mourning as Ohio State went 8-22. Now this.
</P>
<P>
   Of the four teams here, only one, Duke, has fresh memories of
this feeling. Ohio State has not been to a Final Four since 1968.
Connecticut has never been; watching Jim Calhoun make his
excruciating climbs up and slides back down have become a
post-season ritual. Not this year. Calhoun sat with his team Friday
and spoke about Saturday's battle with Ohio State and his old Big
East rival, O'Brien.
</P>
<P>
   Calhoun has beaten O'Brien's teams 18 consecutive times.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Jimmy had good teams we had very good teams,'' Calhoun
explained. ``When Jimmy had the Eisley-Edmund team, they were
terrific; we had Marshall, Ray Allen, Travis Knight, guys who are
now making a living in the N.B.A. We had a great team.''
</P>
<P>
   For O'Brien, Saturday night's meeting with his former Big East
rival goes beyond X's and 0's; the game is one more bizarre twist
in a dream season and a career year.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are so many coincidences and ironies,'' O'Brien said.
``I grew up in New York, we beat St. John's; I've known Mike Jarvis
forever. My first job was at UConn; playing against Jim, knowing
him from Northeastern, then all the games through the years, B.C.
and Connecticut.''
</P>
<P>
   Michigan State, which plays the second semifinal game tonight
against Duke, is celebrating the 20th anniversary of its first
national championship, with the team led by Magic Johnson. Johnson,
whose duels with Indiana State's Larry Bird set the stage for a
career-long rivalry in the pros, has been a presence throughout
this tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm as excited to be here as I think a guy could ever be,''
Michigan State Coach Tom Izzo said. ``Everybody told me how good it
gets, but words can't describe the excitement myself or the team or
the school have had.''
</P>
<P>
   The Spartans' reward for climbing a steep hill is a matchup with
No. 1 Duke, the prohibitive favorite to win the tournament and one
of the most consistently outstanding programs in college basketball
history.
</P>
<P>
   Its coach, Mike Krzyzewski, is a counterpoint to the newness and
exuberance that surround this tournament. Krzyzewski's teams have
reached the Final Four seven times, played for the title five times
and won it twice. At age 52, Krzyzewski is now the dean, the
terror, possibly the latter-day John Wooden, of college basketball.
</P>
<P>
   Some say this year's Duke team is invincible. Krzyzewski winces
at the suggestion. When Duke won its first national championship,
in 1991, the Blue Devils defeated a supposedly invincible
Nevada-Las Vegas team in the national semifinal game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We certainly don't feel like we're invincible,'' Krzyzewski
said. ``I don't think any of our players or coaching staff have
ever portrayed that mood, that opinion. I think we can lose to
anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Can Michigan State beat Duke? Sure. A victory will require more
than a miracle; it's going to take Magic. But that's what this
tournament is about.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
