<SLUG> BC-BKW-FINAL-FOUR-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUKE AND PURDUE ADVANCE TO TITLE GAME 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS to incorporate results of Purdue-Louisiana Tech game.)  (mk) 
 By BILL PENNINGTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JOSE, Calif. _ Duke, a bit player in women's college
basketball until recent seasons, continued its captivating run
through the NCAA tournament Friday night, advancing to the
championship game with a thorough 81-69 defeat of Georgia at the
San Jose Arena.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday the Blue Devils will face No. 1-ranked Purdue, a 77-63
winner over Louisiana Tech in Friday night's second semifinal.
</P>
<P>
   In the final weekend of a tournament traditionally dominated by
a few powerhouse programs, underdog Duke has stolen the spotlight
with a tough-talking coach and a savvy, scrappy, senior-dominated
team.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not surprised by this,'' Duke coach Gail Goestenkors
said after the victory, which allowed her team to hold serve in its
figurative Final Four match with the Duke men's team. ``We expect
to win the national championship.''
</P>
<P>
   Reminded that her team was considered the least talented of the
four teams in the women's Final Four, Goestenkors smiled. ``You
don't have to be athletic to be a great player,'' she said. ``We
have smart, poised players who know how to play together.''
</P>
<P>
   To dismantle Georgia (27-7), Duke used the formula that was so
effective in its stunning upset of three-time defending national
champion Tennessee in the East Regional final Monday. There was
dependable inside play by 6-foot-6 center Michele VanGorp, who had
20 points and nine rebounds, and the lively play of three nimble
guards, Georgia Schweitzer, Peppi Browne and Nicole Erickson, who
led all scorers with 22 points.
</P>
<P>
   And Duke (29-6) won with an infectious enthusiasm and a weaving,
pass-happy, team-oriented offense that involved every player on the
floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``They spread you out and kill you slowly,'' said Georgia coach
Andy Landers, who has become something of a Final Four fixture but
still seeks his first national championship. ``You find yourself
yo-yoing defensively from a talented inside post player and a
talented bunch of perimeter shooters. You choose your poison.''
</P>
<P>
   Georgia's exit means the championship game will be played
without a team from the Southeastern Conference for the first time
in five years.
</P>
<P>
   The Big Ten will be represented by Purdue (33-1). The
Boilermakers, who have won 30 consecutive games and have not lost
since Nov. 22, were led by guard Ukari Figgs, whose 18 first-half
points gave them an early advantage that they never relinquished.
</P>
<P>
   Figgs, who teams with Stephanie White-McCarty in what is
considered the best backcourt in women's college basketball,
finished with a game-high 24 points. It was her 3-point shooting in
the first half _ she made three of her first four _ that staked
Purdue to a 40-27 halftime lead.
</P>
<P>
   Louisiana Tech (30-3) mounted a comeback that cut Purdue's lead
to 58-55 midway through the second half, but led by Figgs, Purdue
scored 12 unanswered points. Louisiana Tech, which was hoping to
avenge a lopsided loss in last year's title game against Tennessee,
never seriously threatened again.
</P>
<P>
   Now Purdue will have to face Duke, which Friday night presented
its offensive attack exactly as planned. The Blue Devils also
effectively slowed Georgia's star twin guards, Kelly and Coco
Miller.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly Miller came into the game averaging 27.5 points per game
in the tournament but sank just five of 13 shots against Duke to
score 13 points. Her sister led Georgia with 18 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew we had to focus on the twins,'' Erickson said. ``We
saw on film that they liked to go to their left and then shoot, so
we tried to force them to their right. And we bumped them around a
little.''
</P>
<P>
   Interestingly, the Millers, who are 5-10, were supposed to be
the physical presence that thwarted and wore down the 5-6 Erickson.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't happen that way. Erickson came out shooting, matching
a Coco Miller 3-pointer with one of her own for Duke's first
points. She scored 8 first-half points, helping Duke to an early
10-point lead that Georgia cut to 40-34 at the half.
</P>
<P>
   For most of the half, VanGorp struggled to get shots because of
a smothering Georgia double team. But as Erickson and Schweitzer
(13 points) bombed from outside and Browne sliced through the
Georgia defense with piercing drives to the basket, the Lady
Bulldogs' defense was forced to stray from VanGorp.
</P>
<P>
   VanGorp responded with 8 of Duke's final 12 first-half points.
At the start of the second half, she hit a 3-pointer from the
corner and another pull-up jumper, leading Duke to a 13-point lead.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia's pressure defense, led by the Millers, rattled Duke
briefly, cutting the Duke lead to 6 points at the midpoint of the
second half.
</P>
<P>
   Coco and Kelly Miller each hit baskets, taking advantage of the
absence of VanGorp, who sat out three minutes at this juncture with
three fouls.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly Miller's two free throws cut Duke's lead to 60-54, but the
Blue Devils' Hilary Howard sank two free throws to rebuild an
8-point edge.
</P>
<P>
   Both teams seemed fatigued as the game _ played at a frantic
pace from the opening tip _ wound into its final eight minutes. And
with that fatigue, contact between the players was more common,
something that played to Georgia's disadvantage.
</P>
<P>
   Duke shoots 77 percent from the foul line as a team, with a
handful of its players making more than 80 percent of their foul
shots this season. Friday night, Duke made 16 of 21 free throws,
including eight of 11 in the final eight minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Two of those free throws were by Schweitzer as Duke regained its
double-figure lead, 64-54.
</P>
<P>
   Erickson followed with a driving layup, VanGorp then blocked a
shot attempt by Tawana McDonald, and Erickson hit a fallaway jumper
as the shot clock was expiring to give Duke a 15-point lead, 70-55.
</P>
<P>
   After a basket by McDonald, Erickson delivered another
staggering blow, hitting a 3-point shot from the corner. If that
didn't wound Georgia's morale, then a 3-pointer by Lauren Rice with
3:02 to go that gave Duke a 76-57 lead must have.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would disagree with anyone who says that Duke isn't
talented,'' Landers said. ``They're damned good players and so far
in this tournament there isn't much they haven't been able to do
and accomplish.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-27-99 0034EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990327.0009 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-27 00:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6305 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NETS-PACERS-NYT &LR;      03-27 0726
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETS-PACERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PACERS BEAT NETS, 100-91 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By CHRIS BROUSSARD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ The Nets executed fairly well, beat a
larger opponent on the backboards, played with fire and showed some
heart Friday night. But their failure to correct a problem that has
dogged them this season was too much to overcome against the
polished Indiana Pacers.
</P>
<P>
   Another woeful shooting display, 35.7 percent, nullified the
good the Nets did and enabled Indiana to leave the Continental
Arena with a hard-fought 100-91 victory. The loss was the Nets'
third in three games against the Pacers this season, and like the
others, it was competitive and at times dramatic.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the Nets exited their home court with another
crushing defeat, their 22nd in 27 games, and Indiana, the Central
Division leader, improved to 19-8. More unsettling than the loss
was an injury to Keith Van Horn, who is questionable for Saturday's
game against Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot-10 forward, who scored 22 points and blocked a
career-high six shots, sprained his right ankle one minute into the
third quarter while stepping on Dale Davis' foot. After having the
ankle retaped, Van Horn returned to play 11 minutes before removing
himself because of the pain. Van Horn, who missed the first 17
games of last season with a severe sprain of the same ankle, said
he would have X-rays taken Saturday morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the same tendon I injured last year, but I didn't feel it
pop like last year,'' said Van Horn, who scored only 4 points after
the injury. ``Once I started making my moves to the basket and got
in the flow of the game, it started giving out on me. That's when I
pulled myself out. I had no explosiveness and I couldn't put any
pressure on it, so I wasn't being of any help.''
</P>
<P>
   The Nets trailed, 86-74, when Van Horn left for good with 7
minutes 1 second remaining. While the Nets' porous defense was a
problem _ Indiana scored 52 points in the paint and shot 46.5
percent _ the Nets' largest obstacle was their inability to make
layups, short shots in the lane and outside jumpers.
</P>
<P>
   While no Nets starter made half of his shots, the main culprits
in the sad shooting display were Chris Carr, who started in place
of Kendall Gill, and Kerry Kittles. After scoring 8 points to help
the Nets build a 24-23 lead, Carr went frigid, missing his last 10
shots in an excruciating 4-for-18 performance.
</P>
<P>
   Carr, who was placed in the starting five when Gill (4 points,
20 minutes) suggested the move to coach Don Casey, was distraught.
``I feel like I was a big part of the reason why we lost,'' Carr
said. ``I've got to concentrate more and focus on making those
shots because that makes Stephon and Keith's job easier. When they
pass me the ball, they depend on me making the shots and I wasn't
doing it.''
</P>
<P>
   Kittles was nearly as inaccurate. He scored 15 points, but
missed 10 of 15 shots, including an open 15-footer after Stephon
Marbury (24 points, 8 assists) pulled the Nets within 94-89 by
hitting the last of his four second-half 3-pointers with 1:34 left.
The Pacers capitalized with a thunderous dunk by Antonio Davis that
turned into a 3-point play when Marbury fouled him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very frustrating,'' said Kittles, who had 10 rebounds to
help the Nets to a 53-45 rebounding advantage. ``I can't tell you
how many open looks I had tonight where I was wide open, looking at
the ball, looking at the crowd and just sitting there waiting. But
the shots aren't going in right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Indiana, which was led by Rik Smits' 20 points and Reggie
Miller's 16, got a strong performance out of Al Harrington, the
rookie who last summer became the latest high school player to
enter the National Basketball Association draft.
</P>
<P>
   Harrington, who played sparingly through the first 24 games,
scored 6 of his season-high 8 points in the fourth period to help
Indiana push a 74-70 lead to 86-74 with 7:01 remaining. The 6-9
graduate of St. Patrick's High School in Elizabeth, N.J., played a
season-high 17 minutes and had five rebounds as 30 of his family
members and friends watched from the stands.
</P>
<P>
   ``It felt great to be out there,'' said Harrington, whose 8
points matched his season total. ``I've been waiting for this for a
long time. Everything just seemed to fall into place tonight.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
