u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-SPORTS-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      03-27 0757
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SPORTS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TV SPORTS: TVKO WILL MAKE A DEAL FOR HOLYFIELD-LEWIS, EVENTUALLY
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Eventually, Time Warner will make a deal to carry Evander
Holyfield-Lennox Lewis II on TVKO. That's inevitable. Through TVKO
and HBO, Time Warner has too much tied up in boxing to use the
stench of the March 13 draw as an excuse to exit the proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   TVKO insists that it's too soon to execute a television deal,
although promoter Don King has joined the fighters in pugilistic
matrimony for $15 million each.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not running full speed to close a deal,'' said Lou
DiBella, the senior vice president of HBO Sports.
</P>
<P>
   Before TVKO makes a deal, DiBella said, several elements need to
change.
</P>
<P>
   The first is for the television network to cut a better deal.
Although the first fight netted 1.2 million pay-per-view purchases
at $50 each, DiBella said the success ``is not reflected on our
books. We made a deal with a lot of risk and virtually no upside.''
</P>
<P>
   There was probably a smidgen of profit for poor old Time Warner,
but apparently not enough after King's profit taking began once the
pay-per-view buys reached 850,000.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever role King plays may change. To promote the disputed
first bout, King bought out the interests of Panos Eliades, Lewis'
promoter. Eliades did not want the risk. King did. With Lewis
enraged with King, the WB C heavyweight champion may insist on a
larger role for Eliades.
</P>
<P>
   Most important, DiBella said, TVKO would prefer a deal that
guarantees that the judges are chosen by the local athletic
commission, in New York, Wales or Nevada.
</P>
<P>
   The controversial choice of the IBF judge, Eugenia Williams _
who scored the fight, 115-113, for Holyfield, the IBF champion _
exposed further the conflicts inherent in sanctioning bodies
choosing a fight's judges, and the questionable criteria exercised
in selecting someone with big-time experience as limited as
Williams'.
</P>
<P>
   Nevada's athletic commission chooses judges _ New York's does
not _ but only from a pool submitted by the alphabet soup of
sanctioning organizations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The audience for a rematch should be completely comfortable
that it will be administered in a fair process,'' DiBella said.
``Just imagine, the night before a game, Jerry Jones taking the
referees to Lutece,'' he added, referring to the Dallas Cowboys'
owner and a top New York restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   Also, DiBella said, promoters should not pay judges, and limits
should be placed on what is paid for judges' travel, meals and
entertainment. Not that the three Holyfield-Lewis judges were
overindulged at the Hotel Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   DiBella's points are all logical. But the pace of reform rarely
keeps pace with the speed of outrage. Last week's hearing by New
York state Sen. Roy M. Goodman was a farce, as Goodman toadied up
to King and failed to ask necessary and obvious follow-up
questions.
</P>
<P>
   The best hope for reform may emerge from the criminal inquiry of
Robert M. Morgenthau, the Manhattan district attorney, and
legislation by Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz.
</P>
<P>
   After the Williams affair, boxing fans (and pay-per-view buyers)
may feel assured that the rematch is legitimate only if King is
exiled to referee fights in South Korea; judges are required to
publicly disclose their federal income tax returns, bank accounts
and telephone records; and the leaders of the IBF, WBC, et al.,
resign, citing their need for group therapy to alleviate the stress
accumulated through years of kowtowing to promoters.
</P>
<P>
   Another `SportsCenter'
</P>
<P>
   Starting April 6, ESPN will add a live ``SportsCenter'' at 1
a.m. Eastern time, but one that is targeted to West Coast viewers
watching at 10 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``The consumers crave it, the affiliates crave it and the
affiliates want it,'' said Dick Glover, ESPN's executive vice
president. ``We've been looking to do this for a year.''
</P>
<P>
   Nowhere in Glover's rationale is any admission that ESPN is
reacting to competition from the Fox Sports Net, which has spent
lavishly to build a news presence. The newest ``SportsCenter'' will
go head to head out west with Fox's 10 p.m. program.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe I'm seeing the wrong numbers, but I'm not sure about
Fox's growth,'' said Glover, whose former boss, Steve Bornstein,
recently referred to the Fox sports empire as a mosquito.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why would they add a new `SportsCenter' now?'' asked Vince
Wladika, a Fox spokesman. ``It's obvious this is a reactionary
move. Everyone knows why they're doing it.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
