<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-27 00:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6312 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ARIZONA-FIGHTER-AZR &LR;      03-27 1291
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARIZONA-FIGHTER-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LUKE AIR FORCE BASE F-16S ARE GROUNDED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JENNIFER BARRETT  
 and DENNIS WAGNER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mystified Air Force officials have shut down flights
indefinitely at Luke Air Force Base after Friday's crash of another
F-16 fighter jet near Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Five Fighting Falcons have crashed on training missions from
Luke in the past six months. Investigators say engine failure
caused four of those accidents, but none of the malfunctions had
anything in common.
</P>
<P>
   Within hours of Friday's crash west of Phoenix, Sen. John McCain
sent a letter to the Air Force secretary expressing ``deep
concern'' and questioning whether a problem with the F-16's engine
might be the culprit.
</P>
<P>
   ``If, in fact, the F-16 engine, or some particular component of
the engine, is found to be failing at an unacceptable rate, I would
be very interested in your assessment of an immediate fix,'' he
wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's accident happened near 339th Avenue just a few miles
from the Palo Verde Nuclear Generating Station. Smoking wreckage
from the $20 million jet was strewn across the desert just north of
Interstate 10, narrowly missing drivers along the interstate.
</P>
<P>
   The jet was carrying dummy bombs, not live munition. The pilot,
Capt. Michael G. Rider, 27, ejected safely. The native Texan had 47
hours of experience flying the F-16 before the accident.
</P>
<P>
   Brig. Gen. John Barry, the commander at Luke, is so frustrated
by the series of crashes that, for the first time, he has called
for all jets to be grounded indefinitely, saying he will not allow
any of Luke's 211 jets back in the air, ``until I am convinced it
is safe to fly.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I will never put a pilot in a cockpit that is unsafe for
flying,'' Barry said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``It might be a blessing we are discovering these
problems within the safety and security of the U.S. borders, rather
than in the skies over Iraq.''
</P>
<P>
   The F-16s, already being used to patrol two no fly zones over
Iraq, are now being deployed in the Kosovo airstrikes as well.
</P>
<P>
   Barry and McCain are not alone, nor are they the first, in
worrying about the jet engines. More than two years ago, the
``Defense Daily,'' a trade publication, quoted top Air Force
officials who were complaining of constant, costly engine problems
with thousands of F-16s.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a variety of problems _ some with the fans, some with
the compressors, some with the turbines and some with the
bearings,'' said Gen. Richard Hawley, then-head of Air Combat
Command.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Hawley blamed a shortage of maintenance funds and
vowed to reverse the trend with a tough inspection program.
</P>
<P>
   But a month ago, ``Defense Daily'' published another story
blaming the spate of crashes on engine problems. In that report,
Air Force Chief of Staff Gen. Mike Ryan said, ``We have some
(pilot) problems, but for the most part, it's engines.''
</P>
<P>
   The F-16 aircraft are manufactured by Lockheed Martin but the
engines and some components are made by Pratt &AMP; Whitney and General
Electric. Officials of the engine manufactures could not be reached
for comment, and Lockheed officials are baffled as well.
</P>
<P>
   Capt. Todd Vician, an Air Force spokesman at the Pentagon, said
an additional $225 million has been allocated in the upcoming
budget to pay for spare parts for engines.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, the Air Force told Congress that it needed an
additional $257 million to buy spare engines.
</P>
<P>
   At a congressional hearing last week, Ryan cited the number of
crashes at Luke as proof that funding needs to be beefed up. He
said the base has lost four jets because of engine problems _ no
two of them from the same cause.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, bases nationwide increased inspections but
continued flying with old parts.
</P>
<P>
   Some military experts and manufacturers say the accidents stem
from larger, more complicated troubles within the Air Force.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing is for sure: There's big problems in the F-16
community,'' said Alan Diehl, formerly a senior civilian crash
investigator for the Air Force. ``I can't explain it. I don't think
there's any single cause. I think it's a manifestation of what
happens with shortcuts.''
</P>
<P>
   Diehl said the crashes stem from a dangerous mixture _ too much
work and too little funding. He said Air Force pilots and
maintenance crews have been overtaxed just when many of the top
personnel are leaving the service for civilian jobs, and when the
number of sorties has escalated.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, he said, the military has gone through a wave of
cutbacks, including the purchase of spare parts. As a result, some
F-16s are being cannibalized to keep others aloft.
</P>
<P>
   Barry confirmed the cannibalization rate (taking parts from one
jet and putting them in another) has increased nearly 80 percent in
the Air Force since 1996. At Luke, at least one jet in each of the
eight squadrons is used for spare parts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president's given 'em an awful lot of tasks,'' Diehl said.
``And Congress hasn't given 'em a lot of money. Maintenance has
become shoddy on the aircraft because of the high operational
tempo.''
</P>
<P>
   In that context, the F-16 woes have gained political importance.
</P>
<P>
   Former Vice President Dan Quayle _ who, like McCain, is
considered a potential candidate for the presidency _ blamed the
Clinton administration for jeopardizing pilots and aircraft with
military budget cuts.
</P>
<P>
   ``They simply don't have the money for (engine parts),'' Quayle
told reporters during a news conference in Phoenix earlier this
year. ``The military never has been a priority with this
administration.''
</P>
<P>
   Reserve Air Force Lt. Col John Nance, an aviation safety
analyst, said, ``We're asking almost super-human feats of the guys
we do have, the gals we do have. They're getting deployed all the
time, they're tired, they're proficiency is waning.''
</P>
<P>
   Nance and Diehl question whether the Air Force will ever be able
to get to the bottom of the crashes. Both have criticized the
service for past cover-ups.
</P>
<P>
   ``The U.S. Air Force investigates itself,'' Nance said. ``It's
wink, wink, . . . we don't talk about this problem or that
problem.''
</P>
<P>
   About 3,900 F-16s have been sold to 19 nations. Of those, 2,200
are owned by the U.S. Air Force, said Michael Nipper,
communications manager at Lockheed Martin which manufactures the
F-16 aircraft, but not the engines.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has asked Congress for funds in the 2000 defense budget
for an additional 10 F-16s.
</P>
<P>
   In fiscal 1998, which ended in September, the Air Force recorded
just 24 ``Class A'' incidents _ those in which a plane or pilot was
lost or more than $1 million of damage was done to a jet _ making
it the second-safest year in Air Force history. But more than half
the incidents involved F-16 fighter jets _ there were 14 F-16
crashes with six fatalities. Meanwhile, F-16 jets accounted for
less than 6 percent of the flying hours during that time. Luke had
no accidents during that time.
</P>
<P>
   In the past six months, the Air Force has recorded another 18
mishaps. Those involving Luke pilots account for nearly one-third
of that total.
</P>
<P>
   Nipper said the sudden surge of accidents is inexplicable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we've ever seen this big a rash of
engine-related mishaps in the history of the program,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   According to Nipper, pilot error has been responsible for more
than half of all F-16 wrecks in the history of Falcon flying.
</P>
<P>
   Nipper emphasized that Lockheed Martin does not build the
engines. It installs engines which are purchased from Pratt &AMP;
Whitney or General Electric by the government.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're concerned because it's our product,'' Nipper added.
``But there's not much we can do about it.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
