<HEADLINE>
SUITORS LINE UP FOR TMS' NAME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVID A. MARKIEWICZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Texas Motor Speedway should add a corporate
name within a year at a price of $3 million to $5 million annually,
a top executive for Speedway Motorsports Inc., which owns the
track, said yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'll probably see this in the next 12 months,'' said H.A.
``Humpy'' Wheeler, president of North Carolina-based SMI. ``You're
looking at three, four, maybe five million dollars.''
</P>
<P>
   Although there is no shortage of interest among companies
wanting to put their name on the racetrack, Wheeler said, the
selling of naming rights demands a slow, careful process.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not an easy thing to do,'' Wheeler said. ``You've got to
have a certain type of company willing to put up a lot of money to
do it, and you don't want to give up the name lightly. This is a
little bit like getting married. Everybody involved's got to be
absolutely sure it's the thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   That's especially true, Wheeler said, because SMI wants a
long-term arrangement with its sponsor _ possibly 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to do this for only three or four years,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   SMI recently sold the first track-naming-rights sponsorship in
NASCAR when its Charlotte Motor Speedway signed a deal with Lowe's,
a chain of home improvement stores.
</P>
<P>
   Wheeler said that motorsports is following the lead of football,
baseball, basketball and hockey in affixing names to its
facilities, and for good reason.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're constantly searching for new forms of revenue,'' Wheeler
said. ``We've got a tremendous investment in these speedways,
particularly this one here. You're always looking to recoup \Rthe
costs\S and you can only sell so many tickets.''
</P>
<P>
   SMI has been lobbying NASCAR for a second Winston Cup race date
at Texas Motor Speedway because it would provide a dramatic boost
in revenues for the track. The company's inability to secure a
second Winston Cup weekend, Wheeler said, makes the selling of
naming rights that much more important.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that we've got only one Winston Cup weekend sort of
accelerates our reason for doing this,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Wheeler said he understands NASCAR's scheduling problem _ too
many tracks seeking too few races _ but, speaking of Texas and
Texas Motor Speedway, he said that a second Winston Cup race only
makes sense.
</P>
<P>
   ``This track's too good and this market's too big,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While it awaits a second date, SMI is considering alternative
revenue generators at TMS. SMI and other NASCAR track owners will
certainly benefit from a new national television contract that
could boost overall TV revenue from $100 million to about $400
million annually. But the company is looking for other means, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``We may bring some other types of racing in here during race
week,'' Wheeler said. ``We need to take more advantage of the
\RWinston Cup\S race week we do have.''
</P>
<P>
   Wheeler said one possibility is a Winston West series race, an
increasingly popular circuit that's proved popular in markets such
as Las Vegas.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
