<SLUG> BC-CAR-MOTORSPORTS-REPORT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAYBE HENDRICK TEAM'S THIRD CAR IS HAUNTED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ In the great three-car NASCAR scheme that is
Hendrick Motorsports, Wally Dallenbach Jr. drives the No. 25
Bermuda Triangle Chevrolet Monte Carlo.
</P>
<P>
   OK, so officially it's the No. 25 Budweiser Chevy. But since Ken
Schrader last scored a victory in the bright red car in June 1991,
this has been a place where promising Winston Cup drivers go ...
only to disappear.
</P>
<P>
   Hendrick teammates Jeff Gordon and Terry Labonte have captured
the past four driver's championships for team founder Rick Hendrick
and his brother, John. Gordon and Labonte have accounted for 49
victories since 1995, the year Gordon scored the first of his three
Cup championships.
</P>
<P>
   The 25 car, meanwhile, has seen Schrader bow out and Ricky
Craven get the boot after never fulfilling his 1995
rookie-of-the-year potential.
</P>
<P>
   Enter Dallenbach, a championship road-racer, who got the job
full time last August after scoring top-10 finishes in three of his
first four starts with crew chief Tony Furr. But Dallenbach's best
start this year has been 14th at Atlanta Motor Speedway. His best
finish is 12th in the season-opening Daytona 500. He enters the
Primestar 500 tomorrow 25th in points, and in danger of falling off
the Cup radar screen.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can look at it that way,'' Dallenbach said yesterday
afternoon, ``but it's still the best thing I've ever had. The
Hendrick ride _ even if it was the third team and it wasn't
successful _ was the best opportunity I had \Rlast summer\S. Now if
I can make it work, or we can make it work, we're heroes.''
</P>
<P>
   This team is a direct descendant of the one that once featured
the flamboyant Tim Richmond. Dallenbach said the popular notion
that the current No. 25 car is nothing more than a research and
development program for Gordon's team is unfounded.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it is, I don't see it,'' Dallenbach said. ``If it is,
they're doing it behind closed doors and I don't know anything
about it. All the resources are there and it's a matter of
chemistry within the team.''
</P>
<P>
   Dallenbach, who has no poles, no wins and 47 Did Not Finishes in
166 Cup starts, is working under a one-year contract. Robin
Dallenbach, who negotiated Wally's deal with John Hendrick while he
was on a hunting trip in Bolivia, is keeping her husband's resume
updated.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as job security goes, I really don't worry about
that,'' said Wally Dallenbach, 35. ``I go out and drive my butt off
every time I drive this race car. I don't lose any sleep over if
John Hendrick or Rick Hendrick is going to hire me for next year.
If they want to blame the driver for not being competitive, then,
hey, I'm out of the job. I know how the business works.''
QUICK HITS
CHASING ANOTHER BGN DATE
</P>
<P>
   Lobbying for a second NASCAR Busch Grand National date at Texas
Motor Speedway continues. And Eddie Gossage hopes the crowd
anticipated for today's Coca-Cola 300 sends NASCAR a strong
message.
</P>
<P>
   Gossage, executive vice president and general manager for TMS,
classified his most recent discussions with NASCAR officials as
nothing more than ``shooting the breeze.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They know we'd like to have a second Busch race here,''
Gossage said. ``We're going to have a crowd bigger than most
Winston Cup races for our Busch race. From what we've got sold
\Ryesterday\S and what we sold walk-up last year, we'll probably
have 125,000 to 130,000 people here. It makes a statement, but
NASCAR makes the scheduling decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   Gossage said a second BGN date as the headline event to another
race weekend remains ``very possible.''
</P>
<P>
   EARNHARDT SPELLS $UCCESS
</P>
<P>
   Seven-time Cup champion Dale Earnhardt is a ``Field and Stream''
kind of guy. So what's he doing inside ``Forbes'' magazine?
</P>
<P>
   Crunching numbers, all the way to the bank. Earnhardt is ranked
fifth on the magazine's annual list of 1999 top-40 athletes,
trailing Michael Jordan, Tiger Woods, Michael Schumacher and Sergei
Fedorov.
</P>
<P>
   ``Forbes'' uses the formula of salaries and endorsements to
compile the list, excluding merchandise royalties and other sources
of income. Jordan, the retired Chicago Bulls star, tops the chart
with $69 million. Earnhardt ranks fifth at a mere $24.1 million,
behind two-time Formula One champion Schumacher. But Earnhardt is
still No. 1 among domestic drivers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've worked awful hard throughout our career and capitalized
on all the things available,'' said Earnhardt, driver of the No. 3
GM Goodwrench Chevy.
</P>
<P>
   Don Hawk, the president of Dale Earnhardt Inc., traces
Earnhardt's rise among sports' big hitters to 1993, when he began
to market ``The Intimidator'' as an athlete.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's street smarts with a business plan,'' Hawk said. ``When
you perform, you sell. But you've got to have more than
performance. You've got to have some kind of swagger to your walk
or some kind of style to your talk. Something's got to be
different. We think Earnhardt _ and Dale Earnhardt Jr. _ have got
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Among those trailing Earnhardt are Arnold Palmer, Oscar De La
Hoya, Wayne Gretzky, Greg Norman, Andre Agassi and Mark McGwire.
LITTLE E PANS RIVALRY
</P>
<P>
   The main subplot to today's Coca-Cola 300 Busch race is the
highly anticipated matchup between three-time Winston Cup champion
Jeff Gordon and BGN champion Dale Earnhardt Jr.
</P>
<P>
   It will be their second ``mano a mano'' in the BGN series.
Gordon debuted his No. 24 Pepsi Chevrolet with a fourth-place
finish at Las Vegas Motor Speedway, where Earnhardt Jr. ran sixth.
</P>
<P>
   Little E's spin on his instant rivalry with Maximum Jeff?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not beat to death yet,'' said Earnhardt Jr., driver of
the No. 3 ACDelco Chevy. ``But what we're doing here and what we
done last year and the five \RCup\S races we're going to run isn't
quite worthy of putting him in a sentence with us. He's the
champion three times over. He's winning races right and left. There
ain't nobody that can stop him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who are we to be compared to him? You know what it's like?
It's kinda like one of y'all \Rmedia members\S just opening up the
door to the old man's \RDale Earnhardt\S coach and walking in there
and saying, `Hey man! How about an interview?'''
</P>
<P>
   That is not uncomfortable. That, friends, is downright stupid.
LAST WORDS
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been pretty tough. I didn't shave one day. I got in
trouble for not shaving. About Tuesday, I could tie my shoes.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Bobby Labonte, on getting through the day with his broken
right shoulder blade
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
