<SLUG> BC-CAR-LEBRETON-COLUMN-LABONTE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOUGH TEXAN READY TO SHOULDER LOAD FOR A SUNDAY DRIVE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LEBRETON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ The man has a broken shoulder, and that
would be enough to knock most of us driving stiffs out of the car
pool line, thank you.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Bobby Labonte, eschewing even aspirin, is in the front
line.
</P>
<P>
   One week after cracking his right clavicle during practice at
Darlington, S.C., Labonte is in the front row for tomorrow's
Primestar 500.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hurts mostly when I move it the wrong way,'' Labonte said
yesterday, after climbing out of his No. 18 Interstate Batteries
Pontiac Grand Prix.
</P>
<P>
   ``But, actually, I'm not as sore as I thought I'd be today.''
</P>
<P>
   As Labonte spoke, a mini-Quasimodo bulge poked from the right
side of his driver's suit. Doctors have outfitted him with a
shoulder cast and lashed it with tape to his back.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, Labonte says, he's fine, as long as he doesn't
have to reach for the Mapsco or change radio stations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Reverse is the hardest thing,'' he said. ``I can't get to
reverse too good.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week at the TranSouth Financial 400, Labonte reported
difficulties shifting gears. The unspoken footnote to the complaint
is that Labonte even raced at all, a scant 48 hours after the
accident.
</P>
<P>
   To secure his Winston Cup standings points, Labonte only had to
be behind the wheel for the green flag that signals the race's
start. The Corpus Christi native toughed it out, however, driving
with the freshly broken shoulder for another 43 laps, before he
pitted and turned the driving over to young Matt Kenseth.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't make him either a hero or just another tough guy
from Texas, Labonte said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ask my wife,'' he corrected. ``I'm not very tough.''
</P>
<P>
   His older brother, Terry _ he's 42 and Bobby is 34 _ would
dispute that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bobby's a tough guy,'' said Terry, who sits in the No. 4
starting spot. ``He's going to try to run the whole race for
sure.''
</P>
<P>
   And there sits part of the drama for tomorrow's Winston Cup
race. Once the younger Labonte gets on the track for practice today
and sees how the shoulder holds up with traffic around him, he
thinks that he will have a better idea of how deep into the race he
will be able to drive tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll be up to him,'' said Joe Gibbs, the former Washington
Redskins coach who owns the No. 18 car. ``I always left it up to
the player when I was coaching, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bobby will be the best one to judge how far he can go.''
</P>
<P>
   Labonte is third in the Winston Cup standings, and so the points
earned in Texas have meaning. In five starts this NASCAR season,
Labonte has four top-10 finishes and has started on the pole twice.
</P>
<P>
   With that at stake, Labonte and crew chief Jimmy Makar have
already decided to have Kenseth on call. Labonte's crew has
practiced removing him from the driver's seat _ i.e., grasp snugly
in the arm pits and pull, ignoring the driver's yelping.
</P>
<P>
   Last week in Darlington, Kenseth got back in the race and drove
to a quality 10th-place finish.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bobby and Jimmy have watched \RKenseth\S and liked him, and
they feel good about it,'' Gibbs said. ``Bobby's got a lot at stake
in this. We all do.''
</P>
<P>
   In the world of NASCAR racing, scrapes and bent sheet metal are
a way of life. Duct tape rules. But there is no bench, no Mark
Rypien, for Gibbs to easily turn to when the driver turns up with a
dent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Matt's a good, young driver with a good head on his
shoulders,'' Labonte said. ``I knew he would take care of the race
car.''
</P>
<P>
   Labonte contends that the shoulder is better. He spent this week
in North Carolina, undergoing therapy with trainers from the NFL
Carolina Panthers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've done some underwater treatments,'' he said, ``and some
stimulants for working the bone, moving it and moving it. I was
down there about three or four hours a day.''
</P>
<P>
   Doctors had prescribed the pain killer Vicodin, but Labonte
stopped taking the pills four days ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like I had a hangover,'' he said. ``Everything they had
me take makes me sick.''
</P>
<P>
   His best prescription, therefore, Labonte figures, is a long
Sunday drive with plenty of drivers in his rear-view mirror.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
