<SLUG> BC-CAR-WALTRIP-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A STORIED CAREER NEEDS SOME SPEED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF CAPLAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Darrell Waltrip said his back was against
the wall before Winston Cup Primestar 500 qualifying yesterday.
Today, the season and quite possibly the legendary career of the
three-time Winston Cup champion could hit the wall.
</P>
<P>
   Waltrip ran a first-round qualifying lap of 184.666 mph,
finishing far behind the top 25 automatic qualifiers. He placed
46th out of 48 entries. His speed was more than 2 mph slower than
25th-place Ted Musgrave (186.600).
</P>
<P>
   Relying on provisionals and owner's points to qualify for the
season's first five races, Waltrip, Winston Cup's winningest active
driver, is out of free passes. Speed is his last avenue to qualify
for tomorrow's race.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sorry,'' Waltrip said to his crew as they watched his
speed plummet in the standings on a computer monitor in the garage.
Usually candid and accessible, Waltrip, 52, refused to comment on
his run and headed for his hauler.
</P>
<P>
   He will be among 23 drivers competing for 10 spots today in
final-round qualifying at 10:45 a.m. It is desperation time for one
of the sport's greatest drivers, and he knows it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our whole season is riding on what we do today,'' Waltrip said
before yesterday's qualifying run. ``My one lap is the most
critical lap I've run in a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   If Waltrip fails to qualify today in his No. 66 Big Kmart Ford,
the remainder of his season will be jeopardized only six races into
a long, 34-race marathon. He can use four more provisional entries,
but only once every fourth race.
</P>
<P>
   Since failing to qualify at Charlotte Motor Speedway in October
1997, Waltrip's decline has been swift and has lent itself to talk
of retirement: ``Soon,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He struggled through 1998 and finished 24th in the points
standings. Now driving for his third team in a year and a half, the
27-year veteran is practically starting from ground zero.
</P>
<P>
   His best finish this season is 20th, and he owns a dubious
double-digit streak of qualifying by provisionals. He dropped out
of the top 25 in points last week. He expressed unhappiness with
his car, but said he has seen improvement over the past few weeks
and expects to have a new car ready within weeks. He said he
thought the car he ran yesterday would be fast enough to get him in
the race.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked for what I'm getting,'' Waltrip said. ``If we run well
this week, we'll get a week off and the team can relax a little.
That's what this team really needs right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Waltrip wants to race into the year 2000. It would make him the
only driver to compete in NASCAR events in the '70s, '80s, '90s and
2000. He is just one victory away from 85, which would break a tie
with Bobby Allison for third on the all-time win list.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we will get it together. It is just a matter of
time,'' Waltrip said. ``I hope I stay with this team long enough to
get there.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-27-99 0109EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
