<SLUG> BC-HKN-DUCKS-STARS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUCKS ROUT STARS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG CHRISTENSEN  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Anaheim Mighty Ducks coach Craig Hartsburg
isn't one to mince words, and Friday morning he was as blunt as
ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we don't start winning games, St. Louis, San Jose, Calgary,
lots of teams are going to catch us,'' he said. ``You can't hold
your position in this league very long if you don't win some games.
</P>
<P>
   Friday night, Hartsburg's Ducks responded with a most unlikely
win, a 5-1 rout of the Dallas Stars before 16,533 at the Pond.
</P>
<P>
   After spotting Dallas a 1-0 lead on Derian Hatcher's power play
goal at 8:27 of the first, Marty McInnis got a crucial power-play
goal to tie the game with 31.8 seconds left in the period. That
gave the Ducks at least a glimmer of hope against a Stars team that
is 22-1-5 when leading after one period and has turned protecting
leads into an art form.
</P>
<P>
   Anaheim's hope then turned into a tidal wave of confidence as
the Ducks scored four times in perhaps their most dominating period
of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Cullen gave Anaheim its first lead of the year against
Dallas 19 seconds into the second when he converted Teemu Selanne's
center passing with a quick shot from the slot.
</P>
<P>
   Midway through the period Guy Hebert came up with his biggest
save of the game on a shot by Pat Verbeek to preserve the Ducks'
lead. Seconds later Kariya put a perfect lead pass on Selanne's
stick and the Anaheim winger chipped it over Ed Belfour for his
league-leading 41st goal of the year at 9:46.
</P>
<P>
   Selanne then ended Dallas' streak of 27 road games without
giving up more than three goals when he scored at 14:51 off a
rebound of Tomas Sandstrom's shot.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars had been closing in on the NHL record of 30 games set
by Detroit in 1952-53.
</P>
<P>
   To top off the second period, Kariya stole a Dallas pass in the
Stars' zone and while falling down snapped a wrist shot over
Belfour's glove with 40 seconds remaining. The fourth goal of the
period equaled the team's best output in a period and it marked the
first time Dallas had given up four in a period all season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
