<SLUG> BC-CAR-STUNT-DRIVER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROFESSIONAL STUNT MAN'S RACING IS NO PUBLICITY STUNT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Racing is dangerous. Only yesterday, a
handful of drivers smacked the Texas Motor Speedway walls at high
speeds. Two of them, Tony Raines and Ken Bouchard, were taken to
the hospital with concussions.
</P>
<P>
   The danger, however, is the least of Stanton Barrett's worries.
</P>
<P>
   Why should you care about hitting the wall at 190 mph when
you've been blown up, hit by cars, gone flying off a motorcycle,
fallen off buildings, tumbled off snowmobiles at high speed and
been slammed into a vertical cliff while hanging from a helicopter?
</P>
<P>
   Barrett, 26, is a professional stunt man. He has worked on
movies _ including ``Batman, Jurassic Park, Blade, Volcano'' and
``Dante's Peak'' _ and TV shows, including ``JAG, Beverly Hills
90210, Baywatch'' and ``Extreme TV''.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've done a lot of stuff where you have a better than 50
percent chance you're going to go to the hospital,'' he said.
``I've been hurt a lot. I've broken my tailbone, my shoulder. I've
broken lots of bones.''
</P>
<P>
   But Barrett wants to be a Winston Cup driver. He's at TMS this
week trying to put owner W.C. ``Junie'' Donlavey's No. 90 Suburban
Lodge Ford into the field for the Primestar 500.
</P>
<P>
   Barrett turned his qualifying lap at 186.136 mph, putting him
36th of the 48 cars that made attempts. That's a tenuous position,
but might be good enough to make the field if no one goes faster in
second-day qualifying today.
</P>
<P>
   Barrett also climbed into Kerry Earnhardt's backup car for
second-day Busch Grand National qualifying but failed to make the
field.
</P>
<P>
   Donlavey, an owner since 1950 who has worked with NASCAR legends
Joe Weatherly, Tiny Lund, Fred Lorenzen, David Pearson, Benny
Parsons and Buddy Baker, said Barrett has talent.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's going to be good,'' Donlavey said. ``He's got a good feel
for a car; he seems to know what he's doing and he pays attention
to you. A lot of times you'll get young drivers who want to prove
to you how good they are to start with, but you can't be good
without experience. It just takes time to get experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Experience, though, is in short supply. Barrett has raced in the
Goody's Dash Series and run late-model sports cars in North
Carolina. He has made 30 or so starts in the Busch Grand National
series. But he has never raced a full season at this level.
</P>
<P>
   He's a freelance driver, with a partial sponsorship deal with
Heritage Consumer Products but without a full-time team. He uses
his stunt work to fund his quest to go racing.
</P>
<P>
   ``My stunts have made me a living and allowed me to go to the
races,'' he said. ``When I have a shortfall from a sponsor, I put
in the rest of the money. I race as many races as I can, and then I
go back and work.''
</P>
<P>
   Work sometimes involves a stunt where a cable is anchored and
then tied to a motorcycle. The stunt man takes off, knowing what's
going to happen when the cable plays out.
</P>
<P>
   ``You ride it, it runs out and you go sailing,'' he said.
``You're getting paid to hit the ground. If you don't do it right,
you have to do it again. You know it's going to hurt when you hit.
You just hope it doesn't hurt too bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Barrett would rather drive a race car for a living, even if it
does mean hitting the wall now and then.
</P>
<P>
   ``I risked my life to get here, and this is where I want to
be,'' he said. ``I've turned down a lot of work to pursue racing.
That's cost me a lot of money, so I'd better be dedicated to what
I'm doing. Whatever it takes to survive and pursue my racing
career, I'm going to do.'' / nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
