<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-DUCKS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS DONE IN BY FINN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Plain and simple, the Stars were Finnished
last night.
</P>
<P>
   Missing their top defensive forward, Finnish sensation Jere
Lehtinen, because of an ankle injury suffered Thursday against Los
Angeles, the Stars couldn't contain Teemu ``the Finnish Flash''
Selanne in a 5-1 loss to the Mighty Ducks of Anaheim.
</P>
<P>
   The correlation between the two Finns is tangible, as Lehtinen
is considered the top defensive forward in the NHL and has taken
delight in shutting down his boyhood friend, Selanne. Before last
night, the Stars were 6-1-1 in their previous eight games against
the Ducks. Lehtinen (4 goals, 4 assists, plus 6), who's not known
as a goal scorer, had outscored the high-flying Selanne (2 goals, 3
assists, minus 4) while playing head-to-head in most situations
against him.
</P>
<P>
   Last night, Selanne went wild. He scored two goals and added two
assists _ all in the second period _ as he pushed his NHL-leading
goal total to 42. Selanne has scored 16 goals in the past 16 games.
In addition, Selanne linemate Paul Kariya, who also had struggled
against the Stars, added three points. Kariya and Selanne have
combined for 15 points in their past three games.
</P>
<P>
   While Lehtinen's absence was notable, it wasn't the Stars' only
problem. They were playing their third road game in four nights
while the Ducks were coming off a four-day rest. The Ducks also
have not traveled outside the Los Angeles area in the past 13 days,
while the Stars have been to six different cities in that span.
</P>
<P>
   The result wasn't pretty. The Stars yielded more than two goals
for the first time in the past eight games and saw an end to a road
streak in which they had not yielded more than three goals in 27
consecutive games (two goals or less on 26 occasions), the longest
such streak in the NHL since the Detroit Red Wings went 30
consecutive road games while allowing three or fewer goals in
1952-53.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the Stars hold a four-goal lead (146-150) on the
Ottawa Senators in the race for the Jennings Trophy, given to the
NHL team that allows the fewest goals.
</P>
<P>
   The loss drops the Stars to 45-15-12, still 19 points ahead of
the second-place Colorado Avalanche in the Western Conference. The
Stars need one point to clinch a Pacific Division title and two
points to clinch the top seed in the Western Conference. The also
can clinch with losses by the Avalanche or the Phoenix Coyotes.
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks move to 32-28-11, two points ahead of the St. Louis
Blues for fifth place in the Western Conference.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars opened the scoring once again as they have scored
first in 49 of 72 games this season. This time, their moribound
power play finally came to the rescue. After going without a shot
on a scattered first power play attempt one minute into the game,
the Stars received a beautifully skilled play from captain Derian
Hatcher. Hatcher took a pass on the left wing as the Stars were
breaking into the offensive zone, glided in on goalie Guy Hebert
and deftly slipped a backhand under his pads.
</P>
<P>
   It was Hatcher's ninth goal of the season and only the seventh
for the Stars on the power play in their past 18 games (a span of 7
for 59).
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks, however, answered with their own power play goal. The
Stars were whistled for too many men on the ice at the 18:26 mark
of the first period and the Ducks went to work with the best power
play in the NHL. Anaheim's Marty McInnis scored on a deflection of
a point shot for the Ducks' 74th power play goal of the season
(they would later get 75). The Stars are tied for second with 66.
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks then took their first lead of the season series (3-1-1
in favor of the Stars) 19 seconds into the second period. Selanne
fished out a puck behind the net and fed Matt Cullen in the slot
for an easy chip in past Belfour.
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks made it 3-1 on a beautiful transition play by Selanne
and Paul Kariya at the 9:46 mark of the second, took it to 4-1 on
Selanne's second goal of the night at 14:51 and made it 5-1 when
Kariya stole a pass and beat Belfour at the 19:20 mark of the
second period.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars also were without Dave Reid (back spasms) and lost
Jamie Langenbrunner to an abdominal strain during the game. The
Stars today travel to Nashville and tomorrow will finish a
four-game road trip with a 5:30 p.m. game against the expansion
Predators.
</P>
<P>
   It will end a stretch in which the Stars have played seven of
nine games on the road.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
