<SLUG> BC-MANN-BIDS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANN MAY BE READY TO SELL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVE MCNARY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- It's nothing like the massive lines expected for
``Star Wars Episode I: Phantom Menace,'' but the troubled Mann
Theatres chain has drawn several bids since putting itself up for
sale two months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Mann, whose top performers are the fabled Chinese Theatre in
Hollywood and the landmark Village in Westwood, is believed by
industry insiders to have attracted offers from a pair of Southern
California rivals -- Pacific Theatres and Edwards Theatres -- along
with an investment group headed by former Mann chief Jeff Lewine
and the recently formed Resort Theatres of America.
</P>
<P>
   Newport Beach-based Edwards, which bought Mann's Orange County
facilities in the early 1990s, had no comment on a Daily Variety
report that it has submitted a bid worth over $100 million for the
375-screen chain. Los Angeles-based Pacific has confirmed it has an
offer on the table without disclosing further details, but its bid
is reportedly far under the Edwards offer.
</P>
<P>
   Lewine, who led the 1997 buyout of Mann by Wall Street
investment firm Warburg Pincus, was a candidate even before
resigning his post at Mann last week. Resort Theatres, launched
last year by Hollywood veteran Brad Krevoy, has emerged as a
candidate because of recent deals to build a five-plex in Aspen,
Colo., and to buy five existing Metropolitan theaters in Palm
Springs with four additional sites under development.
</P>
<P>
   But rather than cash, Warburg Pincus may be looking over bids
that would swap the Mann sites for an equity stake in another
operator. Entertainment industry consultant Kevin Skislock of
Laguna Research Partners noted that both Edwards and Pacific have
embraced the strategy of building state-of-the-art megaplexes
equipped with stadium seating and massive concession stands rather
than buying existing theaters.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could mean that Edwards or Pacific are taking a long-term
view and buying the Mann facilities as knock-downs,'' Skislock
said.
</P>
<P>
   Mann has been far less aggressive at launching new theaters, and
many of its older sites face tough competition. For example, Mann's
triplex in Pasadena competes with a recently built eight-screen
Pacific and will be leveled next year when its lease runs out, the
property owner has told city officials.
</P>
<P>
   Mann, which has 60 theaters in California and Colorado, has seen
its value plunge over the past decade. Paramount bought the chain
in 1986 from producer Ted Mann for $220 million in 1986, then sold
half of it two years later to Warner for $150 million. Warburg paid
the Paramount-Warner partnership $165 million when it bought the
chain 15 months ago.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
