<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PINKERTON-ACQUIRE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PINKTERTON'S PURCHASE BY SWEDES FINALIZED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DEBORAH ADAMSON  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- It's official: Pinkerton's Inc. is now a wholly
owned subsidiary of Securitas AB of Stockholm.
</P>
<P>
   Shareholders of Pinkerton's, the international detective agency
known for tracking Butch Cassidy and providing protection for
Abraham Lincoln, overwhelmingly approved the purchase by its
Swedish rival to create the largest full-service security company
in the world.
</P>
<P>
   About 99.3 percent of shareholders -- or 12.2 million shares --
have accepted Securitas' offer of $29 a share in cash. The merger
is valued at $384 million.
</P>
<P>
   No regulatory approval is needed, said Pinkerton's spokesman
Mark Leaf.
</P>
<P>
   The marriage will lead to layoffs of an undisclosed number of
Pinkerton's employees holding certain jobs in finance and strategic
planning, he said.
</P>
<P>
   At present, Pinkerton's headquarters employs 160 people, Leaf
said.
</P>
<P>
   Denis R. Brown, president and chief executive of Pinkerton's,
will stay on as the chairman and CEO of the subsidiary. He will
also join Securitas' board of directors.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, Swedish officials said last month that they are
investigating nine people for possible insider trading connected to
Securitas' purchase of Pinkerton's. It was described as the biggest
such investigation in Sweden.
</P>
<P>
   Pinkerton's generates sales of $1 billion a year and employs
48,000 people worldwide. Securitas' revenues are $1.8 billion
annually. It employs 66,000.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-27-99 0222EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
