<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-27 02:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6341 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-POLICE-BRONX-NYT &LR;      03-27 0654
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-POLICE-BRONX-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOUBTS PERSIST IN BRONX AREA WHERE POLICE KILLING TOOK PLACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (with NY-POLICE-INDICT)  
 (bl)  
 By KATHERINE E. FINKELSTEIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For the residents of Wheeler Avenue, a modest stretch
of two-story apartment buildings in the Soundview section of the
Bronx, reports that four police officers had been indicted on
charges of second-degree murder in the killing of their neighbor,
Amadou Diallo, did little Friday to allay their suspicion of the
justice system.
</P>
<P>
   One of Diallo's roommates, who answered a knock at his door, and
neighbors who sat quietly on their stoops in the sunshine expressed
deep skepticism about the judicial process, especially the official
silence surrounding the grand jury. The Bronx district attorney's
office, which has overseen the jury for six weeks, has refused to
confirm that the officers have been indicted.
</P>
<P>
   These neighbors said they would not be satisfied until the
police officers involved answered a central question: Why did they
open fire on an unarmed 22-year-old immigrant whom everyone
remembered as being courteous, hard-working and shy?
</P>
<P>
   At Diallo's ground-floor apartment at 1157 Wheeler Ave., a
roommate, who did not give his full name, opened the door a few
inches and explained why reports Friday that the officers had been
indicted did so little to address his concerns: ``Just put yourself
in those boots. Imagine a family member killed for no reason.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the reports of the indictments, he said only: ``If that
is what is required by law, then that's the right thing. All we are
looking for is justice. We don't want anything outside the books.''
</P>
<P>
   Others on the block said that they were troubled by many
questions: Why had the officers not been arrested? Why did Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani hold his Thursday town hall meeting in Bushwick,
Brooklyn, instead of in their neighborhood? While they were in pain
over the killing, why did Police Commissioner Howard Safir fly to
the Academy Awards last weekend?
</P>
<P>
   For them, the news about possible indictments was no news at
all. ``Justice is not done until there's a trial,'' a neighbor
said. He declined to identify himself, saying he was a witness in
the case and had given testimony to the grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   His friend, a woman who identified herself only as Dee and said
she on the block, added, ``Not done until they get convicted.'' The
two expressed doubt as to whether the officers had been indicted at
all. ``What is the secret?'' the man asked. ``Why is the indictment
sealed until Monday? There's something behind the indictment.''
</P>
<P>
   For Trudy Browne, 69, who took her 12-year-old granddaughter,
Keisha, Friday to see the vestibule where Diallo was shot by police
officers who fired 41 bullets at him, the reports of indictments
came too late. ``They should have been indicted the same week,''
she said. ``They should not be working when they deliberately
killed a man.''
</P>
<P>
   The neighbors attributed their skepticism, in part, to a mayor
whom they described as ``arrogant'' and ``selfish,'' but most of
all, absent. ``As soon as one of those cops is shot, Lord, he's
there,'' Dee said. ``The other one is chilling at the Oscars. They
should have come out here for one of those town meetings.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence McDonough, a neighbor who examined the piles of wilting
flowers outside the vestibule, said Giuliani was ``the one who
caused all these things because he has no respect for people.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You are the head of the city,'' he said of Giuliani. ``You're
supposed to do something to stop the violence.''
</P>
<P>
   Inside the bullet-scarred vestibule, neighbors had left poems
and Psalms, and had scribbled angry messages about the police. Amid
the graffiti was a scrawled note that seemed to capture the
neighborhood's suspicion. Dated ``2/26/99,'' it read: ``Secret
`Grand Jury'? Why haven't they been arrested?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-27-99 0223EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990327.0031 </DOCNO>
