<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-27 02:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6361 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-SONICS-SPI &LR;      03-27 0753
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SONICS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLUTCH SHOT BY POLYNICE HELPS SONICS SURVIVE CLIPPERS SCARE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CLARE FARNSWORTH  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ With the seconds whirling off the shot clock as well
as the game clock, Detlef Schrempf knew he had to get the ball to
someone.
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, the Sonics' veteran forward settled for
anyone.
</P>
<P>
   Olden Polynice, not exactly a go-to guy with the game on the
line, took a pass from Schrempf and dropped in an 18-foot jump shot
with 38.4 seconds remaining Friday night to assure the Sonics a
hard-fought, 104-98 victory over the Los Angeles Clippers at
KeyArena.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, those Clippers. The now 2-24 Clippers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They finally realized who the shooter was,'' Polynice
deadpanned of his dead-center jumper that gave the Sonics a 102-98
lead.
</P>
<P>
   That comment drew laughter from the reporters gathered around
Poly-nice in the Sonics locker room, as well as from the team's
7-foot center.
</P>
<P>
   Losing to the Clippers would not have been a laughing matter,
especially with the Sonics embarking on a road trip where they will
play five games in six nights.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was extremely important,'' guard Hersey Hawkins said of
getting the win before the team's longest road trip of the
truncated NBA season. ``For confidence, of course, because you hate
to go on the road with a losing streak. So to get this one we'll
hopefully be able to springboard a little and just go out on the
road and be aggressive, play hard and win the majority of them.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics lost to the Washington Wizards Wednesday and had
dropped eight of their past 12 overall. Losing to the Clippers
would have been hitting rock bottom face first.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics (14-12) needed everything they could muster Friday to
avoid falling to .500 before a late-arriving crowd of 17,072.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Payton again led the way, registering 26 points, 11 assists
and eight steals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We take Gary for granted, but he made huge plays on both ends
of the floor in the second half and was the big difference in the
game,'' Sonics coach Paul Westphal said.
</P>
<P>
   Payton, however, needed help and got it from Schrempf, who added
25 points, and Dale Ellis, who scored eight of his 20 points in the
final three minutes when the game was very much in doubt.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Polynice's timely jumper, the Sonics will need more from
their big men because Vin Baker is expected to miss at least
another month with ligament damage in his right thumb. Schrempf has
picked up much of the slack since moving into the power forward
spot vacated by Baker, but Polynice (9), Aaron Williams (6) and
Jelani McCoy (2) combined for only 17 points in the post.
</P>
<P>
   ``Detlef was really good,'' Westphal said. ``Guarding (Maurice)
Taylor in the low post, scoring and playing 40 minutes. He's really
a warrior.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clippers were led, appropriately enough, by rookie center
Michael Olowokandi, who scored 16 points and had 13 rebounds. To
say the Clippers are a young team is like saying they are not a
very good team. Schrempf, who appeared in his 1,009th NBA game
Friday, has played almost three times as many games in the league
as the Clippers' starting five combined.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been playing almost good enough to win, but almost is
not good enough in the NBA,'' Clippers forward Lorenzo White said.
``Their veterans knew exactly what to do when they get the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Clippers would not go away. They made 57.9 percent of
their shots in the first half, when they led by as many as eight
points at 43-35, before the Sonics closed the gap to 54-53 at the
half.
</P>
<P>
   ``They made a lot of tough shots tonight,'' Hawkins said. ``So I
wasn't surprised they hung around, not with the shots they made.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clippers also made a lot of open shots because Westphal had
his players trapping in an attempt to force turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were hitting everything,'' Westphal said, shaking his
head.
</P>
<P>
   Except at the end, when the Sonics outscored the Clippers 16-6
over the final six minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they felt like they could steal a game tonight,''
Ellis said of the Clippers.
</P>
<P>
   Not when Polynice is knocking down 18-footers as the shot clock
expires and with the game on the line.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like Detlef said, he just saw a white jersey and it happened
to be me,'' Polynice said. ``I was shooting all the way because I
knew the clock was running out. And it went in.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes it did, which helped the Sonics avoid going down to an
embarrassing defeat.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-27-99 0238EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
