<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-27 02:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6362 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-LAKERS-KINGS-WRIT     03-27 0691
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-KINGS-WRITETHRU-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS STUNNED BY KINGS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(OPTIONAL: Adds quotes, details) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ Kurt Rambis shook up the lineup, shook up
the offense, shook up the rotation and anything else he could get
his hands on Friday night, shaking the Los Angeles Lakers'
foundation so furiously he could have changed his last name from
Rambis to Richter.
</P>
<P>
   But several temblors later, all the Lakers coach could do was
shake his head in disgust. Everything he tried to build had been
knocked into ruins by a Kings-sized earthquake.
</P>
<P>
   And all the changes, seemingly effective for one half, were
rendered irrelevant when the Lakers reverted to bad habits in the
third quarter, lost a double-digit lead, then lost the game
111-109.
</P>
<P>
   A fallaway putback by Sacramento's Chris Webber with four-tenths
of a second left sealed the Lakers' second straight loss and
negated any progress they had appeared to make.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm embarrassed, personally,'' Derek Harper said, ``because
this team did to us what we did to Orlando on Sunday.''
</P>
<P>
   He meant squandering a huge lead, in this case 19 points, on the
home court. It's the kind of performance unbecoming a team with
championship aspirations and a roster of All-Stars that was
supposed to be strengthened with the promotion of Dennis Rodman to
starter on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the Lakers lost to the Kings for the second time in 11
days, and again with turmoil surrounding Rodman. Last time, they
lost in Sacramento while Rodman vacationed in Las Vegas. He was MIA
again, but this time by design _ Rambis benched him for the final
16 minutes for undisclosed reasons.
</P>
<P>
   So while Webber was getting perfect rebounding position to score
the winning basket on a putback of Vlade Divac's missed 3-pointer,
Rodman watched from the sideline.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I have to take the blame for that,'' Rambis said,
``even though I can't tell you what happened.''
</P>
<P>
   He also wouldn't commit to leaving Rodman in the starting
lineup.
</P>
<P>
   When reporters pressed for details, Rambis cut off the query,
saying: ``Let's not start with 20 questions trying to get it out of
me. That's just the end of it, it was just a coach's decision.''
</P>
<P>
   One that possibly backfired. ``We could have used Dennis on that
last tip-in, for sure,'' Kobe Bryant acknowledged.
</P>
<P>
   Rodman, as per usual, was not available, but in comments he
issued through the team, he noted his limited playing time. ``But I
can't say nothing about that. That is a coach's decision, so don't
ask me about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the loss, he was more expressive: ``I think you need to ask
the people around here what is going on. This is just completely
ridiculous. I'm not used to this.''
</P>
<P>
   Rambis started the night by thrusting Rodman into the lineup for
the first time this season. That change came a day after he
force-fed his team a change in offensive philosophy, emphasizing
more movement and a ban on one-on-one play.
</P>
<P>
   Everything Rambis did seemed to pay off when the Lakers reversed
their trend of slow starts and played their best first half in
recent memory, gaining a 19-point lead and coasting into halftime
with a 62-46 advantage.
</P>
<P>
   All it took was a horrific third quarter to make it all seem
irrelevant.
</P>
<P>
   A 40-point third quarter by the Kings _ against the worst
defense the Lakers have played _ turned the game around, and the
Lakers trailed for most of the fourth. And yet they nearly got away
with it.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers trailed by six points with 2:43 left in the game when
Glen Rice almost singlehandedly brought them back. Rice scored
seven straight points in less than a minute as the Lakers surged
ahead 109-106.
</P>
<P>
   But Vernon Maxwell's 3-pointer over Robert Horry forged a tie.
At the other end, Harper missed an open 3-pointer, and Webber ended
up with the rebound. Seconds later, he pushed in the game-winner to
finish with a game-high 29 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just started (messing around) in the second half,'' Horry
said. ``Guys started freelancing.... It's (bleeping) ridiculous how
we played.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-27-99 0241EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
