   ``We got back to being a hardworking, tenacious team, we had
gotten away from that,'' said Hartsburg after the game. ``It's
something for us to build on. Things (the playoff race) have
tightened up so much the past week ... we have to continue to play
like this.''
</P>
<P>
   After spotting Dallas a 1-0 lead - on Derian Hatcher's power
play goal at 8:27 of the first period -- the Ducks scored five
consecutive goals against a team that they were 3-18-1 against in
their last 22 games. A team that had outscored them 81-37 in that
span.
</P>
<P>
   But like they did after a recent win over Detroit, the Ducks
tried to temper their excitement.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a great win, but we don't want to get too satisfied,''
said Teemu Selanne who took over the NHL goal-scoring lead with his
41st and 42nd goals and assisted on two other goals. ``We know they
did have as much energy as we had (Dallas played the Kings on
Thursday).
</P>
<P>
   ``But then again we haven't had much success against them, so
it's a nice confidence boost.''
</P>
<P>
   Marty McInnis got a crucial power play goal to tie the game with
31.8 seconds left in the opening period. That gave the Ducks at
least a glimmer of hope against a Stars team that is 22-1-5 when
leading after one period and has turned protecting leads into an
art form.
</P>
<P>
   Anaheim's hope then turned into a tidal wave of confidence as
the Ducks scored four times in perhaps their most dominating period
of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Cullen gave Anaheim its first lead of the year against
Dallas 19 seconds into the second when he converted Selanne's
center passing with a quick shot from the slot.
</P>
<P>
   Midway through the period Guy Hebert came up with his biggest
save of the game on a shot by Pat Verbeek to preserve the Ducks'
lead. Seconds later Paul Kariya, who had a goal and two assists,
put a perfect lead pass on the Selanne's stick and the Anaheim
winger chipped it over Ed Belfour for a 3-1 Anaheim lead at 9:46.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like a playoff-type atmosphere,'' said Hebert. ``One
big save, whether it was tough or not ... we score and it's like
monumental change in the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Selanne then snapped Dallas streak of 27 consecutive road games
without giving up more than three goals when he scored at 14:51 off
a rebound of Tomas Sandstrom's shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't believe we were scoring that many goals,'' said
Hebert, who was very aware that the Stars came into the game
allowing only 2.0 goals a game.
</P>
<P>
   To top off the second period, Kariya stole a Dallas pass in the
Stars zone and while falling down snapped a wrist shot over
Belfour's glove with 40 seconds remaining. The fourth goal of the
period equaled a Ducks' high and marked the first time Dallas had
given up four in a period all season.
</P>
<P>
   Anaheim left the ice to a standing ovation, a far cry from last
Sunday when they helped empty the building by allowing four goals
in a 5-2 loss to Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a great feeling, especially against a team like
Dallas,'' said Selanne.
</P>
<P>
   Taking a page from the Dallas playbook the Ducks sat on the lead
in the third period and wound up outshooting the Stars 32-26. In
the Ducks' last three games -- a win, a loss and a tie -- they had
been outshot 123-72.
</P>
<P>
   The victory moved the Ducks (32-28-11) two points ahead of
sixth-place St. Louis and four up on seventh-place San Jose.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
