<HEADLINE>
GRINNING WITH THE ENEMY 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For use by special arrangement
only. Asian and European points: Call Karl Horwitz in Paris for
details and prices, phone: 47 42 17 11; fax: 47-42-80-44). Latin
American points: Call Olivia Vasquez in Los Angeles, phone:
310-996-0075; fax: 310-996-0089). 
(Eds: Note language in third to last graf before optional trim) 
(lb) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ If the candidates are to be believed, the unfolding
presidential campaign will be a high-toned, polite affair.
</P>
<P>
   Among Republicans, Sen. John McCain of Arizona, in a mailing to
prospective supporters, pledged never to lambaste ``my friends and
colleagues'' in the race. Former Vice President Dan Quayle made the
same vow. Gov. George W. Bush of Texas said he has never run an
attack commercial _ and is not about to start now. Among Democrats,
former Sen. Bill Bradley of New Jersey has no plans to resort to
biting rebukes to catch up to the favorite, Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Will debates, therefore, more resemble tea parties? Instead of
those commercials featuring grainy, villainous images of their
rivals, will politicians promote themselves frolicking through
clover?
</P>
<P>
   Don't put away your television clicker just yet.
</P>
<P>
   While candidates sense that people are repulsed by the vitriolic
discourse in Washington _ and pollsters warn that attacks can
boomerang _ virtually no one in politics believes that the days of
dark, dirty presidential campaigns are over. There will always be
one candidate who is winning and one candidate who is losing. And
the candidate who is behind almost invariably will seek to alter
the dynamic by discrediting his or her opponent.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of the impeachment imbroglio, politicians are
especially sensitive to the accusation that they would rather
slaughter their enemies than save the republic. So the trick now is
to deploy attack strategies without seeming to do so.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Nicholson, chairman of the Republican National Committee,
recently warned his party's contenders that they risk ``a
bloodbath'' unless they abide Ronald Reagan's 11th Commandment:
``Thou shalt not speak ill of a fellow Republican.''
</P>
<P>
   But David Axelrod, a veteran Democratic strategist in Chicago,
said that may be for naught. ``We've heard about the 11th
Commandment for a decade,'' he said, ``but the First Commandment of
politics is: `Thou shall not lose!'''
</P>
<P>
   Politicians can promise not to go negative and then go negative
anyway because they hold divergent views of what constitutes an
