<SLUG> BC-CAR-THEFT-REVIEW-ART-875&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR CAR THIEVES, A TECHNOLOGICAL ARMS RACE 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For use by special arrangement
only. Asian and European points: Call Karl Horwitz in Paris for
details and prices, phone: 47 42 17 11; fax: 47-42-80-44). Latin
American points: Call Olivia Vasquez in Los Angeles, phone:
310-996-0075; fax: 310-996-0089). 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By KEITH BRADSHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ The end of the Cold War has had many unexpected
effects, but few are as surprising as the arms race that has
developed between the people who make cars and the people who steal
them.
</P>
<P>
   Discouraging car thieves used to be relatively simple. Until the
late 1980s, the biggest problem involved youths who hot-wired cars
for joy rides. Even small alterations in vehicle design, like
changing door locks, could dissuade some of these thieves, or at
least prompt them to choose another car to steal.
</P>
<P>
   But tearing down the Berlin Wall and loosening totalitarian
controls across Eastern Europe and the former Soviet republics
changed the auto-theft business by opening up an enormous new
market for stolen cars. Thieves supplying this international
business have become more sophisticated, and so have the
countermeasures designed by automakers to stop them.
</P>
<P>
   While criminals have been stealing cars in the United States and
selling them in Latin America for years, the growth of an Eastern
European market has attracted criminal organizations with the
ability to ship large quantities of cars across oceans, according
to U.S. insurance officials.
</P>
<P>
   In New York City and elsewhere on the East Coast, expensive cars
and sport utility vehicles that are stolen and not recovered are
usually on their way to the Baltic ports of Estonia for resale
across the former Soviet Union, said Kim Hazelbaker, the senior
vice president of the Highway Loss Data Institute, which is
financed by auto insurers.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is even worse in Western Europe, where hot-wired
cars can be quickly taken across borders. In Germany, insurers will
provide theft coverage for only two-thirds of a car's value unless
it is equipped with the latest theft-deterrence equipment.
</P>
<P>
   In Europe, automakers responded to the fall of the Berlin Wall
by redesigning their cars during the early 1990s to make them
harder to steal. The design changes are now spreading to the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   The main design change has been the placement of a tiny radio
transponder inside the base of each key. When the key is turned in
the ignition, a weak electrical current from the car battery flows
through the lock, allowing the key to broadcast a coded signal with
a range of just 2 inches. The signal is detected by a sensor in the
steering column, which then permits the engine to be turned on.
Without the signal, even a hot-wired engine will not start.
</P>
<P>
   Thieves responded to the first such keys in the mid-1990s by
trying to transmit all of the available codes, which for some
models meant as few as a dozen combinations. But technology has
leaped ahead since then. Ford's keys now have 10 quadrillion
combinations, and engines will accept the correct combination only
if it is received within 0.0007 seconds after the electrical
current flows through the lock.
</P>
<P>
   Ford says it is not aware of any successful criminal efforts to
override this system, but it plans to start encrypting the codes
anyway for the next generation of Lincolns.
</P>
<P>
   When automakers add these engine-immobilizing devices to cars,
the theft rate drops by as much as two-thirds from one model year
to the next, according to insurers. But the rapid spread of the
technology has prompted thieves to up the ante, too. Professional
criminals increasingly rely on tow trucks and flatbed trucks.
Thieves replace the immobilizing devices on expensive stolen
vehicles destined for export with $400 worth of replacement parts.
</P>
<P>
   Some criminals simply resort to carjackings. ``If it's not going
to run without the key, they're going to walk up and put a gun to
your head and demand the key,'' said Edwin Sparkman, the senior
manager for vehicle theft at the National Insurance Crime Bureau,
an industry group.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department said this month that its surveys found
there were about 49,000 attempted carjackings a year from 1992 to
1996, and in half of those cases the criminal got away with the
car. This figure is twice as high as criminologists had expected,
but because of insufficient data the department was unable to
conclude whether the annual totals were rising or falling.
</P>
<P>
   Carjackings are a much bigger problem in some poorer countries,
notably South Africa, where one entrepreneur sells flame throwers
that are attached below a car's doors and are designed to
incinerate nearby assailants. U.S. auto engineers say they have no
plans to make any devices that would injure car thieves, pointing
out that such devices are illegal in the United States anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Carjackings still account for a tiny portion of all car thefts.
Federal statistics show that 1.35 million vehicles were stolen in
1997, the most recent year available, down 16 percent from the peak
in 1992, because less serious criminals have lost interest in car
theft. But the recovery rate for stolen cars has plunged as more
are shipped overseas.
</P>
<P>
   The National Insurance Crime Bureau estimated last week that
about 200,000 stolen vehicles were shipped out of the United States
in 1997, or nearly half of the 450,000 cars that were stolen that
year and never recovered. By comparison, the United States legally
imports about 2 million cars a year, and there are more than 200
million registered vehicles on the nation's roads.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Most of the vehicles stolen for export are hidden in the big
steel containers commonly seen now on trucks and flatbed rail cars
as well as cargo ships. Customs agents focus mostly on stopping
illegal imports, not exports, although the government has been
stepping up its efforts to find stolen vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   The stolen vehicles in greatest demand overseas are luxury sport
utility vehicles, like the Mercedes M-class and Lexus RX-300, which
can handle the bad roads in places like Russia, Colombia and China,
said Julie Rochman, a spokeswoman for the Insurance Institute for
Highway Safety, another industry group. Some foreigners even order
the theft of specific vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some drug lord in Colombia says, `I want a Mercedes
M-class,''' Ms. Rochman said, ``and poof, a Mercedes disappears in
San Antonio or San Diego and it shows up in Colombia in a crate.''
</P>
<P>
   There are many lists issued each year of the most frequently
stolen cars, but most fail to adjust for the number of each type of
vehicle already on the road. As a result, such lists tend to show
that Honda Accords and Toyota Camrys are stolen most often simply
because there are so many of these vehicles on the road.
</P>
<P>
   But when the number of registered vehicles of each model is
taken into account, a different picture emerges. ``If you don't
have a luxury car, a sports car or a sport utility vehicle, you're
not really at risk,'' except in high-crime neighborhoods,
Hazelbaker said.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest loser in the arms race has been the teen-ager who
used to be able to hot-wire a car for a quick joy ride but now has
little hope of success.
</P>
<P>
   A once-popular theory of history held that Rome fell because
China built a wall. In other words, the construction of the Great
Wall of China forced nomadic peoples outside the wall to turn their
attention westward, eventually destroying the Roman Empire. The
peculiarity of auto theft in the United States today is that joy
riding is disappearing partly because Berliners tore down a wall.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-27-99 1227EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990327.0054 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-27 12:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1615 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-THEFT-REVIEW-ART-     03-27 1327
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-THEFT-REVIEW-ART-875&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR CAR THIEVES, A TECHNOLOGICAL ARMS RACE 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For use by special arrangement
only. Asian and European points: Call Karl Horwitz in Paris for
details and prices, phone: 47 42 17 11; fax: 47-42-80-44). Latin
American points: Call Olivia Vasquez in Los Angeles, phone:
310-996-0075; fax: 310-996-0089). 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By KEITH BRADSHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
