<SLUG> BC-LADN-BUDGET </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Daily News plans to move the following general
stories for use by NYTimes News Service clients, AMs and PMs of
Sunday, March 28, and thereafter. For questions about stories,
contact Stew Slavin at the Daily News, (818) 713-3702.
</P>
<P>
   MCCARTHY-COLUMN _ A High school senior is graduating from
college a month before he graduates from high school. Tom Grogan
spent his evenings the last two years attending classes at the
community college with his father, John. By Dennis McCarthy. (Will
move in the ``k'' ep-ed news file.)
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-27-99 1234EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990327.0056 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-27 12:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6391 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MCCARTHY-COLUMN-LADN     03-27 0875
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCARTHY-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAN, TEEN SONS IN LINE TO RECEIVE 5 SHEEPSKINS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(EDS, Dennis McCarthy is a columnist for the Los Angeles Daily
News 
BY DENNIS McCARTHY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Meet the Grogan boys.
</P>
<P>
   There's Tom. He's 17. In May, he's graduating from Pierce
College. A month later, in June, he's graduating from El Camino
Real High School.
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, that's right, the kid's graduating from college before
high school.
</P>
<P>
   Wait, it gets better.
</P>
<P>
   There's John Jr., Tom's older brother. He's 18. He graduated
from El Camino High last year after participating on the football
and wrestling teams, and he's also graduating from Pierce this May.
</P>
<P>
   So is John Sr., their father. He started taking classes at
Pierce when he was 18, and 22 years later is finally graduating at
40 _ with his sons.
</P>
<P>
   The Grogan boys have taken all their night classes at Pierce
together _ four nights a week for the past two years.
</P>
<P>
   When you talk to one, the other two usually finish the sentence.
It's like walking into the middle of an Abbott and Costello
routine.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first night of class, it's always the same thing,'' said
John Jr.
</P>
<P>
   ``The instructor wants to know if we're related,'' said John
Sr., picking up the line.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always say no,'' said Tom, finishing it off with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   You get the idea. The Grogan boys are tighter than the Three
Musketeers.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Bauer, principal at El Camino High, and Sandi Rubalcaba,
Tom's school counselor, think the kid is breaking new ground here
graduating from college before high school.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had seniors who have completed a quarter or two of
college before they've graduated, but none who have gone to the
extent Tom has,'' Rubalcaba said.
</P>
<P>
   Bauer likes to see the surprised look on people's faces when he
tells them about this senior he has graduating in June _ a month
after graduating from college.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have some parents who have high-powered, high-achieving
kids, and when I tell them what Tom has done, they can't believe
it,'' Bauer said. ``They think it's incredible.''
</P>
<P>
   A lot of people do. Check out this schedule Tom has just
completed:
</P>
<P>
   Up at 6 a.m. to get ready for high school. Classes from 8 a.m.
to 5:30 p.m. The extra time at school is so he can participate on
the football and wrestling teams just like his brother did.
</P>
<P>
   Then a half-hour at home before meeting his brother and father
four nights a week over at his dad's private investigation office
near the college. Catch a quick bite to eat, and finish off the day
sitting in a college class from 7 p.m. to 10 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   If you think it's too much, and that Tom and John Jr. don't have
any time for a social life, think again, the boys say.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've gone to all the proms, Disneyland nights, and lettered
in two sports,'' John Jr. said. ``We haven't been cheated out of
anything because we've gone to college at night.''
</P>
<P>
   The only thing they've lost is the three or four hours a night a
lot of teen-agers spend at home watching TV.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, we missed that, but so what?'' Tom said.
</P>
<P>
   Sweet music to the ears of John Sr. and Karen, his wife of 20
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Families do things together,'' John Sr. said. ``Our family
just likes to take college classes together, that's all. Instead of
going out to movies, we're in class learning things.''
</P>
<P>
   And by being in class, John Sr. said, he gets a candid glimpse
of his boys in action that few, if any, parents get to see in their
own children.
</P>
<P>
   ``After a while, they forget that their dad is there,'' he said.
``I get to see how they interact with their classmates, and how
they respond under pressure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see stuff parents never get to see because they're not in
the classroom with their kids,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For that, he thanks his own father _ also named John, a retired
detective who put in 30 years with the Los Angeles Police
Department.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was about 10, he took me to some night classes he was
taking over at Valley College,'' John Sr. said. ``I thought it
would be so neat to be a young guy in college. I never forgot it.''
</P>
<P>
   For the record, John Jr. is going on to California State
University, Northridge, where he wants to start a law enforcement
career after graduating.
</P>
<P>
   Paul, whose earned the nickname ``Doogie Howser'' from
classmates at El Camino _ wants to go to law school and take a few
classes with his brother at CSUN. He wants to be a licensed
attorney at 21.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've already been accepted at two law schools, but I don't
want to say which ones because I haven't made up my mind which to
attend yet,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   To enter some law schools, applicants need only 60 units toward
a four-year college degree. Tom already has those 60 units.
</P>
<P>
   John Sr. is already enrolled in La Verne Law School, and plans
to add the title ``attorney'' to his business cards as a licensed
private investigator.
</P>
<P>
   He's going to miss these Pierce College night courses he's taken
with his sons, John Sr. said, but it's only a hiatus.
</P>
<P>
   Meet the Grogan girls.
</P>
<P>
   His two daughters, Jennifer, 8, and Kathryn, 9, already are
bugging him to take college classes with them when they get into
high school.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
