<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-27 12:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6393 &Cx1f; var-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OPEC-WHY-REVIEW-700&AMP;A     03-27 1078
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPEC-WHY-REVIEW-700&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHEAP OIL FOCUSES MINDS 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For use by special arrangement
only. Asian and European points: Call Karl Horwitz in Paris for
details and prices, phone: 47 42 17 11; fax: 47-42-80-44). Latin
American points: Call Olivia Vasquez in Los Angeles, phone:
310-996-0075; fax: 310-996-0089). 
(lb) 
 By YOUSSEF M. IBRAHIM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   VIENNA, Austria _ When Arabs united in 1973 to slap an oil
embargo on the United States because it had supported Israel, the
international oil cartel known as OPEC fell into line and shock
waves reached every continent.
</P>
<P>
   In 1979, Iran's Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini launched a second
oil shock when he telegraphed his consuming wrath at the ``Great
Satan'' by slashing oil production in half. Again, the political
passion behind the action drew OPEC's cooperation. Oil prices
quadrupled in months.
</P>
<P>
   But for the next 20 years, the oil-producing countries fell into
disunity, losing their ability to panic the world by boosting oil
prices at will.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, all of that seemed to change _ or at least the
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries tried to give that
impression _ as OPEC's members rediscovered the appeal of political
unity.
</P>
<P>
   Pushing aside technocrats and oil ministers who wanted
production kept high, they decreed a cut in production of about 3
percent. They hope this will lift the rock-bottom prices to which
oil has fallen in recent years, savaging the economic hopes of
once-haughty countries like Saudi Arabia and Venezuela.
</P>
<P>
   Why now? The answer, in large measure, is in the political
climate. In the 1970s a measure of anti-American sentiment could be
counted on in virtually all of the Middle East, which dominated
OPEC. Then, in the 1980s and 1990s, divisions among the Middle
Eastern oil producers (and alliances with the United States after
Iraq's invasion of Kuwait) became much more important, even as new
non-OPEC oil production came on line in Alaska and the North Sea.
</P>
<P>
   But now a new political factor is at play _ the political cost
of low oil prices. This is uniting OPEC's members, overcoming at
least some of their rivalries, and attracting new allies like
Norway and Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   The price fall has been so steep that it has become, in the
words of an OPEC minister, ``a matter of state.'' The 11 countries
of OPEC saw their collective revenues from oil drop by a third last
year. Oil companies laid off hundreds of thousands of workers
worldwide as their profits sank by 40 percent last year.
</P>
<P>
   In Mexico, Nigeria, Venezuela, Algeria, and even in the world's
largest oil producer, Saudi Arabia, shrunken budgets are straining
social and political cohesion. Even in the United States, oil
companies dismissed 50,000 employees last year and U.S. oil
production fell by 500,000 barrels a day to a new low of 5.9
million.
</P>
<P>
   Driven by this unraveling, foreign ministers and heads of state
from Saudi Arabia, Iran, Mexico, Algeria, Norway and Russia engaged
last January in a whirlwind campaign of phone calls and meetings.
</P>
<P>
   The result was a carefully choreographed meeting in Vienna,
lasting less than an hour, to announce a 2.1 million-barrel-a-day
reduction in the world's oil production for a year. This comes on
top of an earlier reduction last year of 3 million barrels a day.
</P>
<P>
   ``How long this super-oil-producers' alliance will last is
anybody's guess,'' said Gary Ross, chief executive officer of
Petroleum Research Industry Associates in New York. ``But this is a
very aggressive agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the agreement has the blessing of the large
multinational oil companies, which find themselves in the position
of wishing the cartel good luck. Ironically, the Organization of
Petroleum Exporting Countries owes its creation 40 years ago to the
political passions of the postcolonial era, in which developing
nations sought to wrest control of their oil resources from ``big
oil.'' Now OPEC members are courting these companies to come back,
invest money, take equity and pump oil.
</P>
<P>
   The new alliance may last longer than skeptics believe because
of the confluence of interest among OPEC, non-OPEC countries and
oil companies.
</P>
<P>
   The social and political pain created by low oil prices has made
for some surprising bedfellows, the most interesting being Iran and
Saudi Arabia, which are the world's first- and second-ranking
producers. Traditional oil rivals and bitter enemies, the neighbors
now have new leaders, and they have been groping toward a new
relationship.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The ascension of Mohammed Khatami to the presidency of Iran and
the rising power of Crown Prince Abdullah in Saudi Arabia as the
ailing King Fahd slips into the background have brought two
pragmatic figures to the fore.
</P>
<P>
   For the prince, the notion of having two powerful enemies, Iraq
and Iran, nearby was becoming intolerable at a time when lower
revenues had forced Saudi Arabia to cut defense spending by some 22
percent. And the fall in revenues had weakened Khatami's hand in
his tug-of-war with sterner clerics who do not agree that Iran
should interact more with the outside world.
</P>
<P>
   One result of these two leaders' efforts to talk was that Saudi
Arabia moved away from a production level of 8 million barrels a
day that it had considered nearly sacrosanct since 1990. And Iran
stopped obstructing a deal within OPEC by agreeing to a cut of
300,000 barrels a day.
</P>
<P>
   Once this was worked out by their foreign and oil ministers, the
deal was sealed in telephone negotiations in which other OPEC
members and Mexico, Norway and Venezuela were brought on board.
</P>
<P>
   As always, there are wild cards in this deal. One is forlorn,
angry Iraq, which said it would not take part. Under the United
Nations' oil-for-food sanction regime, Iraq has nearly tripled its
oil production in the last year to 2.7 million barrels a day. The
Iraqis say they will continue to pump more oil, but their ability
to do so may be limited by their inability to get cash and spare
parts.
</P>
<P>
   There is also the temptation for many of poorer countries to
break ranks once oil prices start to rise. And there is the Asian
economic crisis, which may keep demand for oil down.
</P>
<P>
   But OPEC says if more cuts are needed, it will decree them. And
its members say they have learned the lesson of drowning oil
markets in oil.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-27-99 1248EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990327.0059 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-27 12:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1620 &Cx1f; var-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OPEC-WHY-REVIEW-700&AMP;A     03-27 1078
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPEC-WHY-REVIEW-700&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHEAP OIL FOCUSES MINDS 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For use by special arrangement
only. Asian and European points: Call Karl Horwitz in Paris for
details and prices, phone: 47 42 17 11; fax: 47-42-80-44). Latin
American points: Call Olivia Vasquez in Los Angeles, phone:
310-996-0075; fax: 310-996-0089). 
(lb) 
