<HEADLINE>
EXTRA-WITTY! THEY'VE GONE OVER-BARD 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For use by special arrangement
only. Asian and European points: Call Karl Horwitz in Paris for
details and prices, phone: 47 42 17 11; fax: 47-42-80-44). Latin
American points: Call Olivia Vasquez in Los Angeles, phone:
310-996-0075; fax: 310-996-0089). 
(lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   How have the media been recycling Shakespeare lately in the
midst of the playwright's pop-culture renaissance? Let us only
begin to count the ways with the following headlines, starting with
last week's Oscar awards, at which ``Shakespeare in Love'' won Best
Picture.
</P>
<P>
   A Winner's Tale for ``Shakespeare'' _ Upsets ``Private Ryan''
for Year's Best Picture
</P>
<P>
   _ New York Post, March 22
</P>
<P>
   Oscar in love and war; ``Shakespeare'' and ``Private Ryan''
split the top awards
</P>
<P>
   _ Boston Globe, March 22
</P>
<P>
   Love &AMP; war; All's fair in offering Oscar prognostications
</P>
<P>
   _ Telegram &AMP; Gazette (Worcester, Mass.), March 18
</P>
<P>
   All the World's in Love With Shakespeare
</P>
<P>
   _ International Herald Tribune, March 20
</P>
<P>
   All the World's His Stage
</P>
<P>
   _ Washington Post, Nov. 15
</P>
<P>
   Who was the Bard? That is the Question
</P>
<P>
   _ Houston Chronicle, Jan. 14
</P>
<P>
   Is It Fact or Is It Fantasy? That is the Question; ``Shakespeare
in Love'' Wreaks Havoc With History _ But in a Scholarly Way
</P>
<P>
   _ London Free Press (Canada), Jan. 10
</P>
<P>
   Wherefore art thou, history?
</P>
<P>
   _ Chicago Sun-Times, March 23
</P>
<P>
   Is this an Oscar I see before me? ``Shakespeare'' should win
this year, says Trevor Hodge
</P>
<P>
   _ Ottawa Citizen, March 20
</P>
<P>
   To Be _ or Almost Not to Be; the Unlikely Tale, in Five Acts, of
How ``Shakespeare in Love'' Grew From a Quirky Idea Into a Hit
Movie
</P>
<P>
   _ Newsday, March 14
</P>
<P>
   To be a hit or not to be ... that is hardly the question.
``Shakespeare in Love'' ... has charmed America and is already one
of the most talked about British films in years.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Observer (London), Jan. 24
</P>
<P>
   Bard's Labor Not Lost on Viewers; ``Shakespeare in Love'' Packs
Theaters
</P>
<P>
   _ Central Maine Morning Sentinel, March 12
</P>
<P>
   ``Love's'' labor loosed; Energetic movie finds Will to live
</P>
<P>
   _ Chicago Sun-Times, Dec. 25
</P>
<P>
   Shakespeare no surety of a taming of the shrill
</P>
<P>
   _ Hollywood Reporter, March 12
</P>
<P>
   Much ado about Shakespeare
</P>
<P>
   _ Press-Enterprise (Riverside, Calif.), Jan. 26
</P>
<P>
   Much ado about William Shakespeare
</P>
<P>
   _ Straits Times (Singapore), Jan. 10
</P>
<P>
   Much Ado About the Bard
</P>
<P>
   _ Washington Post, April 24
</P>
<P>
   Much ado about the Bard's true identity
</P>
<P>
   _ Fort Worth Star-Telegram, Jan. 31
</P>
<P>
   Much ado about this man of enduring mystery
</P>
<P>
   _ Daily Mail (London), Jan. 2
</P>
<P>
   Much Ado About ``New Found'' Play; Shakespeare's Newly
Discovered Script, ``Edward III,'' Was Never Actually Lost
</P>
<P>
   _ London Free Press, March 7
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood Proves There's Always Much Ado About Will, and More to
Come
</P>
<P>
   _ Daily News (New York), Feb. 28
</P>
<P>
   Shakespeare's plays still the thing
</P>
<P>
   _ San Antonio Express-News, Feb. 14
</P>
<P>
   The screenplay's the thing
</P>
<P>
   _ Scottish Daily Record, Jan. 29
</P>
<P>
   Shakespeare Fans Find That the Film's the Thing
</P>
<P>
   _ Buffalo News, Jan. 12
</P>
<P>
   The play's the thing; or is it the movie, or some of both?
</P>
<P>
   _ Milwaukee Journal Sentinel, Jan. 18
</P>
<P>
   Visual Play's the Thing; Teacher Uses Cartoons to Win Converts
to Shakespeare
</P>
<P>
   _ The New York Times, May 10
</P>
<P>
   For the RSC, the Plane's the Thing; Renowned Troupe (the Royal
Shakespeare Company) Crosses Atlantic in Search of Money and
Receptive Audiences
</P>
<P>
   _ Washington Post, June 7
</P>
<P>
   What a piece of work is the Bard: Shakespeare has deservedly
been voted personality of the millennium in a poll of British radio
listeners
</P>
<P>
   _ Vancouver Sun, Jan. 9
</P>
<P>
   As We Like It
</P>
<P>
   _ Denver Westword, Dec. 31
</P>
<P>
   As We Like It
</P>
<P>
   _ Miami New Times, Dec. 24
</P>
<P>
   Trinity's Shakespeare as you don't like it; Individual
performances are fine, but the play misses the Bard's combination
of spirit, maturity
</P>
<P>
   _ Providence Journal-Bulletin, Feb. 5
</P>
<P>
   Sure to stir up a tempest, Harold Bloom posits that the Bard
invented human personality as we understand it.
</P>
<P>
   _ San Diego Union-Tribune, Nov. 15
</P>
<P>
   What Light Through Yonder Film Screen Breaks
</P>
<P>
   _ London Free Press, Jan. 28
</P>
<P>
   Alas, poor Shakespeare. I knew him, Horatio ...
</P>
<P>
   _ Las Vegas Review-Journal, Dec. 18
</P>
<P>
   Shakespeare's Myths: a Comedy of Errors?
</P>
<P>
   _ The Ottawa Citizen, Jan. 27
</P>
<P>
   All's well that ends Will for ardent research; ``Pesky gnat''
amateur triumphs as drama enters Shakespeare canon
</P>
<P>
   _ The Guardian (London), Sept. 28
</P>
<P>
   I Doth Protest Too Much; I Begged Everyone to Quit Shakespeare,
But Do They Listen?
</P>
<P>
   _ Daily News, March 29, 1998
</P>
