<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: GOING TO EXTREMES
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By BOB HERBERT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There was nothing symbolic about the arrest of
Rebecca Scanlon last week.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Scanlon is no criminal. She's a solid citizen and a hard
worker. She and a partner are opening a restaurant across the
street from the Brooklyn Academy of Music. For the past few years
they owned a restaurant, the New City Cafe, that was rated at times
by Zagat as one of the top 50 in the city. She is 32 years old and
the mother of a 12-year-old girl.
</P>
<P>
   But New York is taking on the sinister coloration of a police
state, and in that environment almost anyone can be taken off the
street and thrown into the terrifying confines of ``the system.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Scanlon, driving her 1987 Subaru, was caught Tuesday morning
in one of the many sweeps and roadblocks being conducted by the
police around the city. This was a ``safety sweep'' at the
intersection of Classon Avenue and Fulton Street. Ms. Scanlon said
she saw about eight officers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were going to write me up because I didn't have my seat
belt on,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Scanlon was on her way to pick up her partner and then meet
a construction crew at the site of the new restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them I was late for an appointment,'' she said. ``This
has happened to me at least three other times. It usually takes 15
to 45 minutes. It's not pleasant.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Scanlon was told the officers would let her go as soon as
they could. Her license and registration were checked and then an
officer walked back to the car and told her to step out.
</P>
<P>
   ``All they said to me was, `Get out of the car, you're under
arrest.' And then they put me in handcuffs.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Scanlon was upset and embarrassed. An officer patted her
down and asked if she was carrying any needles or other sharp
objects. ``People were gathering and watching, wondering what I had
done,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She noted that it is widely believed that if a young white woman
is in the custody of the police in a predominantly black
neighborhood, she must have been trying to score drugs.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Ms. Scanlon was taken away in handcuffs because she had
forgotten to pay a ticket for driving with a broken taillight.
That's it. A computer check showed that her license had been
suspended. Later it would be confirmed that Ms. Scanlon had never
been notified of the suspension. She was no intentional scofflaw.
When she moved recently she notified both the Department of Motor
Vehicles and the Post Office of her new address.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just forgot to pay it,'' she said. ``Usually if your license
is in jeopardy you get some kind of notification.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the kind of town we've become. The voters put an
ambitious zealot of a prosecutor in charge and now everybody's a
suspect. All sense of proportion has been lost.
</P>
<P>
   Kit Roane had a chilling story in Friday's Times about the way
the police have treated students and teachers at Rice High,
Harlem's only Roman Catholic high school. Roane wrote:
``Administrators said that Brother Tyrone Davis, who teaches
business law at the school and is the executive director of the
Archdiocese's office of black ministry, has grown so tired of being
stopped by the police that he now rarely leaves work without
donning his religious collar.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Scanlon was fingerprinted and locked up at the 88th Precinct
stationhouse. She shared a small cell with another woman, a mother
of three, who was also arrested for a traffic violation. All of
Brooklyn breathed a sigh of relief to hear that these two had been
taken off the streets.
</P>
<P>
   Cops at the precinct told Ms. Scanlon she was going to be ``put
through the system,'' which meant she would be shackled and sent to
Central Booking with the real bad actors who had been arrested and
she probably would be jailed overnight.
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Scanlon was not without resources. Her father is John
Scanlon, a prominent public relations man. He immediately got her a
lawyer, Matthew Dunson, and began calling friends and associates to
see if they could help get his daughter out of jail.
</P>
<P>
   Several people called the precinct captain, James Guida,
including, according to Ms. Scanlon, a retired New York police
captain. It worked. Ms. Scanlon and her cellmate were finally
released about 7:30 p.m. after being locked up nearly eight hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole thing was kind of sick,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
