<HEADER>
A6406 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-MILOSEVIC-2TAK     03-27 1030
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MILOSEVIC-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRACING THE PATH TO CONFLICT: THE EVOLUTION OF MILOSEVIC 
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Calif.) (See also: KOSOVO-RDP, KOSOVO-FORCE, KOSOVO-BELGRADE,
KOSOVO-RUSSIA, KOSOVO-CLINTON, KOSOVO-TURKEY) 
(rk) 
 By MICHAEL T. KAUFMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For Slobodan Milosevic things have come full circle, returning
to Kosovo, where almost 12 years ago, with one short phrase, he
transformed himself from a colorless Communist hack into a
firebrand of Serbian nationalism and set Yugoslavia on a course of
conflict, fragmentation and violence.
</P>
<P>
   Rarely can a historical turning point be established quite so
precisely as the one that occurred on April 24, 1987, when
Milosevic, a veteran apparatchik best known for his organizational
skills, faced a crowd of enraged Serbs in a suburb of Pristina. As
they complained of being pushed back by police wielding batons, he
told them: ``No one will dare to beat you again.''
</P>
<P>
   The Serbs had gathered as in earlier protests to demand that
Kosovo's constitutional guarantees of autonomy be curbed, thus
reducing the political power of the ethnic Albanians who then
outnumbered the province's Serbs by 4 to 1.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic, who at the time was the recently appointed leader of
the Belgrade City League of Communists, had been sent to Pristina
to calm the protests. The man who sent him, Ivan Stambolic, who was
the undisputed Communist leader of Serbia, was also Milosevic's
best friend.
</P>
<P>
   They had met as first-year law students and for 25 years
Milosevic had ridden Stambolic's coattails, rising to become an
executive of a gas company and then a bank. When Stambolic took
over Serbia's League of Communists, he named Milosevic to the
leadership of the party's organization in Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic's assignment in Pristina was to paper over a growing
but local conflict. At the time, the last leader of Yugoslavia,
Tito, had been dead for seven years, but a key precept of Titoism
that remained in force _ ``brotherhood and unity'' _ forbade public
discussion of inter-ethnic tensions. Debate of nationality issues
was to be confined only to the highest and most trusted of party
ranks.
</P>
<P>
   So when Milosevic interrupted his meeting with Kosovo party
officials, most of whom were ethnic Albanians, and descended to
shout to the Serbs protesting outside the building that no one
would ever be allowed to beat them again, the impact was profound,
immediate and startling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Slobo, Slobo,'' the crowd began chanting. Television cameras
captured the image of the politician with his trademark hedgehog
hairstyle, as he identified with Serb national sentiments against
the ethnic Albanians of Kosovo, violating the longstanding taboo by
which Tito and his successors had kept the lid on Yugoslavia's
welter of ethnic and nationalistic rivalries.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of his Belgrade party position, he developed close
ties to managers of national television, and for a long time the
clip was replayed so widely, the words became a catch phrase. Serbs
in all parts of Yugoslavia took it up as a rallying cry, though for
members of old Yugoslavia's other nationalities, it was a
provocation.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic's nationalistic outburst was not entirely spontaneous.
He had made sure Belgrade television cameras would be in position
to film it, and he had held talks with local Serbs several days
before. But even he appeared surprised by the intensity of the
response.
</P>
<P>
   Since then the question of Milosevic's motivations have been
much debated in Yugoslavia. Aleksa Djilas, the Belgrade-based
historian and the son of the late Milovan Djilas, who was the most
famous dissident of the Titoist period, has written critically
about Milosevic, but contends that the Serbian leader was genuinely
driven by Serbian nationalism.
</P>
<P>
   Many others, noting that Milosevic had kept such passions to
himself for his first 25 years of political life, generally portray
him as a Machiavellian cynic who simply reached out to grasp the
overhanging branch of nationalism as the raft of communism he had
been riding was about to be swept over the cataract.
</P>
<P>
   Stambolic would later recall that when his protege returned from
Pristina ``he was transformed, set afire by Kosovo.'' Stambolic had
been shocked and disappointed by what Milosevic had done there, but
he was slow to realize that by seizing the Serbian nationalist
agenda, Milosevic was embarking on a campaign to wrest leadership
of the Serbian party from his oldest and closest friend.
</P>
<P>
   Far from transcending nationalism, as Communism had taught, he
was embracing it, linking his destiny to the yearnings of the Serbs
of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Over the summer of 1987, Milosevic gained backers in a
succession of closed-door party meetings as allies in television
and in key newspapers tailored their coverage to his advantage.
With police help, demonstrators were marshaled and strategically
sent to chant ``Slobo, Slobo.''
</P>
<P>
   He was emerging from the apparatchik's bland cocoon and was
acquiring charisma. With official help, as well as spontaneity,
Milosevic cults were forming, intoning jingles and songs, among
them one that played on his first name, which incorporates the
Slavic stem for freedom:
</P>
<P>
   Slobodan, they call you freedom,
</P>
<P>
   You are loved by big and small,
</P>
<P>
   So long as Slobo walks the land,
</P>
<P>
   People will not be enslaved.
</P>
<P>
   Among the newspaper articles attacking the men Milosevic had so
suddenly turned against were several written under pseudonyms by
his wife, Mirjana Markovic, a professor of Marxist sociology at the
University of Belgrade who was more of an ideological purist than
he.
</P>
<P>
   They had met in high school in Pozarevac, a provincial town of
some 20,000 where Milosevic was born in 1941. Milosevic's father
had hoped to become a Serbian Orthodox priest but never completed
his seminary work, and earned his living as a teacher of Russian
and Serbo-Croatian.
</P>
<P>
   While Slobodan and his older brother, Borislav, now Ambassador
to Moscow, were in grade school, their father left for his native
Montenegro. The boys then were raised by their mother, who was also
a teacher, and a dedicated Communist activist.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-27-99 1315EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990327.0069 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-27 13:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6407 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-MILOSEVIC-2TAK     03-27 0879
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MILOSEVIC-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
 
UNDATED: Communist activist.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   As a youth, Milosevic was a pudgy loner with few friends. He
shunned sports and wrote poetry. Today, he often is described in
Serbian profiles as being reclusive and moody, still with few
friends, though in public appearances and during interviews he can
be as effusive and gladhanding as a door-to-door salesman.
</P>
<P>
   In 1962 while he was in college, his father committed suicide.
His mother killed herself 11 years later. An uncle, his mother's
brother, who had been a general, also took his own life.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Markovic was similarly steeped in a sense of family tragedy.
When she was an infant, her mother, a member of Tito's partisan
resistance during the war, was captured and tortured by the
Gestapo.
</P>
<P>
   After her mother's release, she was killed by partisans who
believed she had given up her comrades under interrogation. Ms.
Markovic has spent much time trying to clear her mother's name.
</P>
<P>
   After the war, Ms. Markovic's father became a member of the
Communist political elite and left his daughter in the care of her
grandparents.
</P>
<P>
   She has long been her husband's close political partner, and she
mobilized support for him at the Central Committee meeting in
September 1987, where by pushing the nationalist themes he raised
in Pristina he virtually drove his mentor, Stambolic, from Serbia's
top party post.
</P>
<P>
   Ruefully, Stambolic would later observe: ``When somebody looks
at your back for 25 years, it is understandable that he gets the
desire to put a knife in it at some point. Many people warned me
but I did not acknowledge it.''
</P>
<P>
   Stambolic may have been the first major figure to have been
betrayed by Milosevic, but he was hardly the last.
</P>
<P>
   The list of allies he jettisoned during the last 12 years is
quite long, including men like Dobrica Cosic, the Serbian
nationalist novelist whom he chose to serve as president, and Milan
Panic, the pharmaceutical magnate from California who was lured to
be prime minister for a while.
</P>
<P>
   Among those discarded have been politicians from left and right
and military leaders inside and outside Serbia who had at various
times rallied to Milosevic's failed but alluring call for a Greater
Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   As for betraying his word, he has consistently perplexed and
infuriated scores of negotiators from dozens of countries and
international organizations, by reversing himself, stalling,
denying evidence, and steadfastly clinging to absurd explanations.
</P>
<P>
   Warren Zimmermann, the last American ambassador to the former
Yugoslavia, has called him ``the slickest con man in the Balkans.''
Less diplomatically, the British writer J.F. Brown described him as
``a consummate politician and a pathological liar.''
</P>
<P>
   Such characterizations came long after he rose to and
consolidated power over Serbia by focusing on Kosovo. Aleksa
Djilas, the historian, observed that because of his emphasis on the
Serbs of Kosovo and by extension on all ethnic Serbs, ``by mid-1988
Slobodan Milosevic enjoyed a popularity greater than any Serbian
political figure in this century.''
</P>
<P>
   In March 1989, the ethnic Albanian party leaders of Kosovo were
arrested at his behest and a new constitution was announced for the
province, stripping it of its autonomy. During two days of
protests, 22 ethnic Albanians were killed.
</P>
<P>
   Then three months later, on June 28, Milosevic celebrated his
gains and proclaimed his nationalist visions when he traveled to
the ancient Kosovo battlefield of Gazimestan, where on that day in
1389, Serbian epics say, Turkish troops overwhelmed Serbian
fighters to usher in 500 years of Ottoman rule.
</P>
<P>
   With tens of thousands cheering him, Milosevic linked the
glorious past to the present, saying, ``Six centuries later, again
we are in battles and quarrels. They are not armed battles, though
such things should not be excluded yet.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   With the loss of autonomy by Kosovo and another less incendiary
autonomous province called Vojvodina, Serbia picked up two
additional votes in the complex federal structures of Yugoslavia,
meaning that it grew more powerful than its partners in the union.
</P>
<P>
   Already chafing under Milosevic's promotion of Serbian
nationalism, the other republics began to break away, beginning
with Slovenia in 1991. Only Montenegro was to remain.
</P>
<P>
   The dismemberment was accompanied by wars that successively
pitted Serbs and Serbia against Slovenes, Croats, and Bosnian
Muslims, and streams of refugees became a common phenomenon as
tactics of ``ethnic cleansing'' proliferated. As other fronts
opened, Milosevic's attention, and that of the world, was diverted.
</P>
<P>
   Twelve years have passed, and most of the dreams of Serbian
nationalism that were set in motion when Milosevic spoke up for a
small group of Serbian demonstrators have failed terribly.
</P>
<P>
   The ensuing desires of establishing enclaves of ethnic Serbs out
of the territories of Croatia and Bosnia have not succeeded.
Serbian hopes of linking such areas to Serbia proper have also
proved impossible, at least so far.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as Slobodan Milosevic is confronted by the might of NATO,
he is back where his career, his politics and the wars of the
Yugoslav succession began.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
