<DOCNO> NYT19990327.0074 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-27 13:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6412 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-BELGRADE-NYT &LR;      03-27 1230
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-BELGRADE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOSOVO-RUSSIA, KOSOVO-CLINTON, KOSOVO-TURKEY ) 
 BELGRADE SHAKEN   BY INTENSIFYING NATO AIR RAIDS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (See also KOSOVO-RDP, KOSOVO-FORCE, KOSOVO-MILOSEVIC, By STEVEN ERLANGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Serbia _ As the price of gasoline rose more than seven
times and a prominent Serbian journalist was arrested Saturday for
offending new censorship rules, the citizens of Belgrade appeared
considerably shaken after the heaviest night of NATO bombing in and
around the capital.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, residents said in interviews, large
explosions hit in Belgrade before air raid sirens sounded, giving
credence to NATO assertions that Yugoslavia's integrated air
defense system has been damaged.
</P>
<P>
   This correspondent, ordered to depart Serbia on Thursday and
refused re-entry at the border with Croatia on Friday, was allowed
to re-enter the country early Saturday morning from the Hungarian
border with the help of the federal information minister, Deputy
Prime Minister Vuk Draskovic. Draskovic, a relatively liberal
nationalist, has been trying to reverse the deportation order for
NATO-country journalists, originally issued by the Serbian
information minister, Aleksandr Vucic.
</P>
<P>
   All of Serbia's television channels broadcast news coverage
Saturday of NATO attacks and of protests against them in Greece and
Russia. Reports that at least four NATO jets were downed were later
denied by NATO, but the denials were not shown on television here.
</P>
<P>
   After a steady diet of patriotic films, however, all seven
channels also showed the film ``Wag the Dog'' numerous times
Saturday, following the example of Iraqi television during the
early days of American air strikes last December.
</P>
<P>
   But there was very little information on events in Kosovo, and
no way for ordinary citizens to hear Western charges of a
full-scale offensive by Serb forces against ethnic Albanians there
and allegations that large numbers of civilian men are being
rounded up and killed by Serb Interior Ministry soldiers and police
officers.
</P>
<P>
   Nor was it possible for Western correspondents, expelled from
Kosovo and with many police checkpoints and roadblocks, to easily
judge the situation there. Attempts to telephone Pristina were
unsuccessful.
</P>
<P>
   It was 10 years ago that Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic
stripped away Kosovo's autonomy, causing large celebrations in
Belgrade and protests by ethnic Albanians, more than 20 of whom
were killed by Serb forces.
</P>
<P>
   None of a dozen people interviewed had seen or heard statements
taped by President Clinton and Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright and transmitted to Serbia by the American government.
</P>
<P>
   Censorship has been strict here under the rules laid down by
Vucic, the Serbian information minister, who is a member of the
strongly nationalist Radical Party of Vojislav Seselj. NATO is
normally referred to as ``criminal'' and Clinton and Albright are
labeled ``killers.''
</P>
<P>
   According to reliable Serbs, a prominent Serb journalist,
Dragoslav Rancic, a senior contributing editor of the weekly Nin
magazine, was arrested Saturday for an article considered to have
broken censorship rules.
</P>
<P>
   Editors were informed that they must provide a first edition of
newspapers to Vucic's ministry every night for approval. Most
newspapers either do not appear or are in smaller, cheaper
editions. Glas Javnosti, for instance, dropped its price in half.
The only newspaper to appear in its usual size is the
government-run Politika.
</P>
<P>
   Even on another bright and sunny day, the streets were much
emptier than normal for a Saturday, both of cars and people.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are exhausted with tension and little sleep because of
the nightly bombings and the need to tramp down to the shelters,''
said Vesna Prlja, who runs a tourist agency with ``not so many
tourists these days.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Last night, for the first time, everyone in Belgrade felt the
real impact of the war. Everyone could see the big explosions in
the central city and the suburbs.'' Ms. Prlja said. ``People use
the mornings to try to get some sleep.''
</P>
<P>
   Gasoline and diesel fuel are being rationed, with many stations
closed, and the price of gasoline has risen to about 5 deutschmarks
a liter, or more than $10 a gallon, while the value of the Yugoslav
dinar fell Saturday to about 10.2 to the deutschmark on the black
market. A liter of gas that cost about 7 dinars a week ago cost
about 55 dinars on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The price of imported items like coffee also increased, but
there were plentiful stocks of cooking oil, bread and other food
products.
</P>
<P>
   At a Saturday party in a central Belgrade apartment, Dejan, a
29-year-old medical student, said that what frightened him the most
was mobilization. He said he was ``sent an invitation to join the
army reserve,'' but has not been living at home so the invitation
could be enforced.
</P>
<P>
   Bojan, 26, a veterinary student, said he slept in different
apartments every other night to avoid mobilization. He also liked
spending time in different air raid shelters, because ``you meet a
different class of people,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Dejan complained jocularly that ``NATO only seems to bomb when
we sit down to lunch or dinner'' and complained that an air raid
siren was only 50 yards from his apartment. But he said he spent
time every day telephoning friends abroad to find out more
information about events than he can get here.
</P>
<P>
   Zaklina, a 31-year-old gynecologist, said she found herself
``calmer than in peacetime.'' But life is boring with all the
alerts, she said, ``and young children and kids have a lot of
traumas, cause they move them to shelters.'' She said the Americans
were ``completely crazy _ this is Europe and not Iraq and they
shouldn't do this.''
</P>
<P>
   Another woman, who spoke on the condition of anonymity, said
that life in her building's shelter was now well organized, with
cots assembled, men's and women's toilets arranged, a small
generator installed and a ham radio operator entertaining the
almost 100 people who gathered there.
</P>
<P>
   Ham radio operators exchanged a lot of information, but were not
careful, she said. When one operator asked: ``Is there any
indication of a nuclear attack?'' another broke in to say: ``For
God's sake, watch what you're saying.''
</P>
<P>
   When a bomb hit a missile factory or fuel depot on the edge of
Belgrade Friday night, causing a large, visible fire, television
announced that the acrid fumes released form the fuel were not
toxic, but cautioned residents to shut their windows. In the
shelter, originally built for nuclear attack, cries went up to shut
the two heavy steel doors, while others complained that then it
would be impossible to leave the shelter to smoke.
</P>
<P>
   Later, a doctor came on television to tell people that feeling
sick to the stomach was a common reaction to anxiety, and was not
necessarily a reaction to the chemical fumes. If eyes began to
burn, however, he said, he instructed people how to bathe their
eyes.
</P>
<P>
   There were renewed attacks on a large base 10 miles northwest of
Belgrade at Batajnica. During a drive past the base Saturday, two
MiG-29s, perhaps decoys, were visible by the side of the road, as
were military communication trucks and mobile radars. Traffic was
diverted from the highway, raising speculation that the road might
be used for takeoffs and landings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-27-99 1329EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990327.0075 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-27 13:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6413 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WOMEN'S-MAGS-REVIEW-2     03-27 1229
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOMEN'S-MAGS-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENOUGH ABOUT FEMINISM _ SHOULD I WEAR LIPSTICK? 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For use by special arrangement
only. Asian and European points: Call Karl Horwitz in Paris for
details and prices, phone: 47 42 17 11; fax: 47-42-80-44). Latin
American points: Call Olivia Vasquez in Los Angeles, phone:
310-996-0075; fax: 310-996-0089). 
(lb) 
 By ALEX KUCZYNSKI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When the January issue of Glamour magazine reached its 2.2
million readers, some may have been surprised to find this line
blaring from the cover: ``New for '99: You asked for it!
Horoscopes. Psychic details you need for your love, lust and work
life. Big Decisions!''
</P>
<P>
   The magazine _ once an influential voice in the feminist
movement because its gospel of modulated assertiveness appealed to
a large audience that was put off by the stridency of Ms. magazine
_ had dumped its ``Women in Washington'' column, which covered
political activity concerning women's issues. It had added
astrology.
</P>
<P>
   Glamour commonly ran articles like ``Let's Stop Lying About Day
Care'' and ``Excuse Me, Are Women Equal Yet? 18 Reasons Why We
Still Need Affirmative Action.'' Recently it featured an editorial
on e-mail privacy titled ``Why We Should All Get Down on Our Knees
and Thank Monica Lewinsky.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the sexual advice, a staple of women's magazines since the
heyday of Helen Gurley Brown at Cosmopolitan, has changed _ from
instruction on maximizing female or mutual pleasure, to guidance on
pleasing men.
</P>
<P>
   The change in Glamour, echoed in other women's magazines, is
part of a larger retreat _ not a backlash of men against women but
of women against feminism _ that vexes feminist theorists and
cheers conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   By virtue of the articles they choose to publish, youthful
women's magazines like Cosmopolitan, Glamour and Marie Claire seem
to argue that their reader doesn't want or need feminism; that she
doesn't care much about Washington or affirmative action, and that
she isn't terribly angry about being cheated out of day care.
</P>
<P>
   At the top of its March cover, Cosmopolitan features ``His
G-Spot.'' On its February cover: ``Be the best sex of his life.''
And this one: ``He Needs His Space? Why Guys in Love Say Scary
Things.'' (It would seem logical to think that the guy in question
is probably not in love if he needs his space, but in the world of
women's magazines, determination _ and learning about those G-spots
_ always wins out.) From January's Cosmopolitan: ``10
Make-Him-Throb Moves So Hot You'll Need a Firehose to Cool Down the
Bed.''
</P>
<P>
   Good Housekeeping features Maria Shriver on its current cover
promising that she will discuss ``Why forgiveness matters so much
in her marriage.''
</P>
<P>
   Marie Claire, which began publishing in 1996 with a modified
feminist tone and regular features on women's issues, now runs
articles like these: ``How Do Men See You?'' (September 1998);
``Sex Appeal: Do You Know Who He Finds Attractive?'' (December
1998); ``Men, Sex and You'' and ``What Men Think About Your Look''
(the current issue). One headline announces, ``Get a Better Body _
for Sex.'' Tellingly, Marie Claire is one of the great circulation
successes of the women's magazine categories, shooting up from
400,000 in 1996 to more than twice that now.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that American women seem to be buying these magazines
in increasing numbers points to an unsteady postfeminist
convergence in American attitudes toward feminism. The convergence
brings together magazine editors _ mostly liberal-leaning women who
consider themselves feminists _ and anti-feminists like the authors
of two recent books that argue that feminism has made women
unhappy.
</P>
<P>
   In one of the books, ``A Return to Modesty: Discovering the Lost
Virtue'' (Free Press), which was widely praised by conservatives,
the 23-year-old author Wendy Shalit argues that the sexual liberty
championed by the feminist movement is responsible for eating
disorders and other female troubles, and that men respect women who
won't accede to their sexual advances without putting up a fight.
</P>
<P>
   In the other book, ``What Our Mothers Didn't Tell Us: Why
Happiness Eludes the Modern Woman''(Simon &AMP; Schuster) 35-year-old
Danielle Crittenden, who studied decades of women's magazines in
preparation for her book, argues that if the truth about women can
be found in the magazines they read, feminism was a bad career
move. It taught women to expect to live freewheeling sexual lives,
which was a poor choice, she says, that has left her contemporaries
``even more miserable and insecure, more thwarted and obsessed with
men, than the most depressed, lithium-popping suburban readers of
the 1950s.''
</P>
<P>
   The political conservatives say the path to feminine fulfillment
lies within the orderly rows of family, child-rearing and
husband-pleasing. That view is starkly different from the one that
emerges from the pages of the women's magazines, which hold up Ms.
Lewinsky as the embodiment of the modern woman _ an
independent-minded odalisque, unshackled from sexual modesty and
constantly celebrating her zaftig sensuality.
</P>
<P>
   Yet authors like Ms. Shalit and Miss Crittenden, who attack the
gains of feminism by saying it promoted some sort of female
priapism, have become unlikely comrades-in-arms against feminism
with the magazine editors whose work they deplore. The editors
concede they are products of feminism, while the conservatives say
they are not. Yet both have dismissed it.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, some of the editors insist that feminism is alive
and well in their pages.
</P>
<P>
   Bonnie Fuller, 42, the editor in chief of Glamour, argues that
the lessons of feminism are now so densely woven into the cultural
fabric that readers don't need to revisit them, and that the
mainstream magazines no longer need to provide monthly monitoring
on the state of women's rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't speak for all women's magazines,'' Ms. Fuller said,
``but there are an enormous number of thought-provoking articles in
women's magazines and very much so in Glamour. We assign
investigative reporters, who do major articles on women's health
issues every single month.''
</P>
<P>
   This month, for example, there is an editorial about domestic
violence. And she pointed out that sexual advice is a product of
the women's movement. ``It would be unempowering for women not to
be able to read about sex as much as they wanted,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But Gloria Steinem, the editor of Ms. and arguably the last
reigning symbol of 1970s feminism, said she has been observing what
she considers to be a decade-long anti-feminist shift in women's
magazines away from coverage of women's issues and politics, and
even high-quality fiction.
</P>
<P>
   ``Advertisers in women's magazines have more influence than
ever, and don't want their ads to appear next to anything but
stories about celebrity and sex,'' she said. (Ms., which Ms.
Steinem reintroduces this month, does not carry advertising.)
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Steinem said such magazines offer sexual advice about
pleasing men as part of a larger movement toward making women feel
bad about themselves, and then fixing those imagined ills in the
pages of the magazines.
</P>
<P>
   ``So reading them becomes this self-fulfilling prophecy,'' she
said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
