<P>
   Miss Crittenden's description of these magazines is not very
different. The magazines she read from the early 1970s, she said,
``were so intelligent it breaks your heart. They were packed with
interesting things to read. It wasn't The Atlantic Monthly, but
there were serious interviews and good writing.'' She added:
``Magazines today, especially under an editor like Bonnie Fuller,
sell beauty and sex and sex and more sex. That's all there is.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Shalit argues in her book that such magazines diminish
female power by advocating sexual helplessness and round-the-clock
availability.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're all breasts and lipstick and your performance in
bed,'' said Ms. Shalit, whose book cites articles in a half-dozen
women's magazines, including Glamour and Mademoiselle. ``There's
something so desperate about it. The thinking is that if you're not
currently in a sexual relationship, you're a real weirdo.''
</P>
