<SLUG> BC-DRUG-COMPANIES-ADS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRUG COMPANIES GET FDA REPRIMANDS FOR FALSE CLAIMS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
repeating to fix slug in notes field  By ROBERT PEAR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The federal government has repeatedly reprimanded
drug companies in recent months after finding that they had made
false or misleading claims in television commercials and magazine
advertisements for a wide range of prescription drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Such advertising has exploded as drug companies market their
products directly to consumers, and the government is now
scrambling to keep up with Madison Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   In the last year alone, the Food and Drug Administration has
admonished companies about commercials advertising drugs for
allergies, asthma, high cholesterol, high blood pressure, hair loss
and sexually transmitted diseases. It has also found problems in
advertisements for birth control pills, anticancer drugs and
medicines to help people lose weight and stop smoking.
</P>
<P>
   In most cases, the regulatory agency said, the advertisements
violated the federal Food, Drug and Cosmetic Act because they
overstated the benefits of a particular drug, minimized the risks
or falsely suggested that one drug was superior to another. The
agency also found that many companies had been promoting their
drugs for uses not approved by the government.
</P>
<P>
   The FDA typically demands that the use of such advertisements
``cease immediately.'' Drug companies generally agree to stop
making the claims to which the agency objects. In rare cases, the
government has required corrective advertising, to offset what
officials saw as inaccurate information in prior advertisements.
</P>
<P>
   In a typical comment, Daniel J. Watts, a spokesman for Pharmacia
&AMP; Upjohn, cited for improper advertising in the last year, of
contraceptive drugs and those to treat male impotence, said, ``We
were not in total agreement with everything the FDA said, but we
complied with what the agency wanted us to do.'' He defended
advertising aimed at consumers, saying, ``That's how people find
out about new therapies.''
</P>
<P>
   Though companies dislike being cited for violations, they
applaud the FDA when it accuses their competitors of similar
infractions.
</P>
<P>
   Federal rules say drug companies must submit their
advertisements to the FDA ``at the time of initial dissemination''
or publication. The agency generally does not have the power to
review commercials before they run.
</P>
<P>
   But an exhaustive review of more than 100 agency letters
asserting violations of federal drug-advertising standards shows
that, in practice, the agency often operates as an editor,
criticizing the text and the design of advertisements, including
details like the size of type.
</P>
<P>
   Under the rules, information about the risks and the benefits of
a drug must be presented in ``reasonably comparable'' ways, so
there is a fair balance. But advertisements, especially television
commercials, often fail this test, the agency says.
</P>
<P>
   Premarin, for example, made by Wyeth-Ayerst Laboratories to
treat symptoms of menopause and osteoporosis, is one of the most
frequently prescribed drugs in the United States. The FDA said that
in a television commercial for Premarin, ``multiple distracting
visual images and activity occur during the audio presentation of
the risk information,'' but the drug's benefits are described
clearly and cogently, against a visual background without any
distractions.
</P>
<P>
   The government told Wyeth-Ayerst to withdraw this and certain
other advertisements because, it said, they made ``broad and
ambiguous health claims for Premarin,'' promising benefits that had
``yet to be substantiated or even identified.''
</P>
<P>
   Audrey A. Ashby, a spokeswoman for Wyeth-Ayerst, said the
company had complied with the agency's request to stop running the
advertisements. In the future, she said, the company will submit
any television commercials that mention Premarin or other drugs by
name, so they can be reviewed by the government before they are
broadcast.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, the government said, information about the risks of
Depo-Provera, an injectable contraceptive, was jumbled in the audio
and visual parts of a television commercial. The multiple messages
``virtually insure that consumers will have trouble fully
comprehending any of the information,'' the FDA said in a letter to
Pharmacia &AMP; Upjohn, the manufacturer.
</P>
<P>
   John F. Kamp, senior vice president of the American Association
of Advertising Agencies, said that prescription drug companies
spent $1.3 billion on print and broadcast advertising aimed at
consumers last year, up from $843 million in 1997 and $595 million
in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   He said that drug companies did not want to get into fights with
the FDA over advertising because they feared that the agency might
retaliate by delaying the approval of their applications for the
marketing of other drugs. Federal officials said such fears were
baseless, but Kamp said the perception was nevertheless widespread
in the industry.
</P>
<P>
   The government said recently that Novartis Pharmaceuticals had
disseminated ``false, misleading, unbalanced and incomplete
information to consumers'' in a television commercial for Lescol, a
cholesterol-lowering drug.
</P>
<P>
   The FDA said the advertisement overstated the drug's benefits,
failed to acknowledge that it could cause liver problems and misled
consumers by suggesting that it cost less than other
cholesterol-lowering medicines, when in fact ``Lescol may cost
more.'' The agency ordered Novartis to run corrective
advertisements.
</P>
<P>
   Anna M. Frable, a spokeswoman for Novartis, said the company had
submitted an ``action plan'' as the agency requested. ``When we
developed the broadcast ad,'' she said, ``we felt it was fair and
responsible. But after hearing the FDA's thoughts, we agree there
were some areas where we could have provided more information.''
</P>
<P>
   Former FDA Comissioner David Kessler, now dean of the Yale
University School of Medicine, said: ``Once a new drug has been
approved, a company is under intense pressure to promote it as
vigorously as possible. There's a risk that patients who don't need
it will be exposed to a powerful pharmacological agent and harmed
by it. That's why the role of the FDA is critical.''
</P>
<P>
   The government has also found problems with advertising for
several other drugs.
</P>
<P>
   The FDA objected to an advertisement promoting Caverject as an
alternative to Viagra pills for the treatment of male impotence.
The advertisement in Parade magazine last November said,
``Caverject can help you and your partner enjoy renewed spontaneity
and sexual satisfaction.''
</P>
<P>
   The agency said the manufacturer, Pharmacia &AMP; Upjohn, had
omitted an important fact, that ``Caverject is a prescription
medication that must be injected via a needle that is inserted
directly into the penis.''
</P>
<P>
   The government said the Bristol-Myers Squibb Company had misled
consumers by using female athletes _ a swimmer and a tennis player
_ in advertisements promoting the use of Pravachol to reduce the
risk of heart attack. The FDA said the message was misleading
because women were not included in the clinical study that showed
Pravachol's value for this purpose.
</P>
<P>
   Bonnie Jacobs, a spokeswoman for Bristol-Myers, said the
commercials were no longer running.
nn
</P>
<P>
   The government said Merck &AMP; Co. had overstated the effectiveness
of its drug Propecia by suggesting that it was guaranteed to
prevent hair loss in men. An advertisement for the drug in Time
magazine last year showed a man looking anxiously into a mirror.
``Starting today,'' it said, ``you need not face the fear of more
hair loss.'' The government said that was misleading because, while
Propecia could slow hair loss, it did not necessarily stop the
process or prevent hair from falling out.
</P>
<P>
   The FDA found that a recent advertisement in Time magazine for
Valtrex, a herpes drug made by Glaxo Wellcome, was ``false or
misleading and lacking in fair balance,'' in violation of federal
law and regulations. The advertisement failed to mention common
side effects of the drug and used small type to inform consumers
that ``there is no cure for genital herpes,'' the government said.
</P>
<P>
   Julie A. Dean, a spokeswoman for Glaxo Wellcome, said the
company had stopped running the advertisement, because it was no
longer needed for marketing.
</P>
<P>
   The government has also accused the manufacturers of three
competing allergy drugs of making unsubstantiated claims of
superiority for their antihistamines. The drugs are Allegra, made
by Hoechst Marion Roussel; Claritin, made by Schering-Plough Corp.,
and Zyrtec, made by Pfizer.
</P>
<P>
   The FDA reprimanded Hoechst and Pfizer for suggesting that their
products were more effective than Claritin. But it also reprimanded
Schering for suggesting that Claritin was more effective than
Zyrtec.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the agency has complained about materials used by
Schering to promote Nasonex nasal spray. The government said the
company selectively presented favorable data to suggest that
Nasonex was better than Flonase, sold by Glaxo Wellcome.
</P>
<P>
   William J. O'Donnell, a spokesman for Schering, said the company
had worked with the FDA to resolve its concerns, but he refused to
give details.
</P>
</TEXT>
