<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-STRIKES _ WASHINGTON or TUZLA, Bosnia-Hercegovina _ As
more reports of heavy fighting and Serb atrocities in Kosovo
emerged Saturday, tensions continued to mount along Yugoslavia's
borders with Bosnia and other countries. NATO carried its offensive
in Yugoslavia closer to Belgrade in the heaviest of three nights of
attacks, as state-run media showed pictures of explosions and fires
in Belgrade suburbs caused by ``NATO criminals'' and claimed
civilians were killed and injured. And in an escalation of the
conflict, Yugoslav helicopters crossed into Bosnia, setting off air
raid sirens and sending people scurrying at Eagle Base, a major
U.S. military compound. (Shepard-Holmes, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   WITH:
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-REFUGEES _ SKOPJE, Macedonia _ Ethnic Albanian refugees
continued to stream across the border here Saturday as Serb
military forces appeared to be clearing all villages along the
border at gunpoint. Any resistance met with with force as one man
was pounded by soldiers when he protested. Meanwhile, NATO forces
were dug in here and moved armored personnel crriers into the area
heightening tensions further. Officials with relief organizations
said they have lost contact with tehir people in Pristina, Kosovo's
provincial capital, since they went back in to help refugees.
(Roughton, Cox News Service) WITH PHOTOS
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MILOSEVIC _ An in-depth profile of Serb leader Slobodan
Milosevic, president of Yugoslvia. (Deans, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-ARMY _ ST. PETERSBURG, Russia _ He is 21, alone and
scared. Ivan (not his real name) has been on the run from the army
for three years. During his short few weeks in the army, he was
ill-fed and beaten, his rations and uniform stolen by officers
looking to sell them. The nation's economic crisis has reduced
soldiers to foraging for potatoes in the fields and begging for
change in subway stations. Since the economic squeeze last August,
the number of deserters and draft dodgers has doubled, according to
advocacy groups who work with disaffected soldiers. The only way to
strengthen Russia's army is to reduce its size, many officials
contend. In coming months, severe cutbacks are planned in military
spending and manpower controversial military reforms. It's an
uneasy task ahead: soothing the generals outraged by the plan,
holding off political rivals attempting to capitalize on the
dissatisfaction and convincing the public that their
morale-battered army can be improved by cutting it back. (Holmes,
Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-RECRUIT _ MOSCOW _ The Russian army offers dismal pay,
horrible living conditions and a reputation stained by its
regrettable experiences in Chechnya and Afghanistan. What's an army
recruiter to do? Hire a Playboy centerfold as the hostess, play a
lot of rock music videos and air the show on weekends to convince
young Russian males that its cool to be in uniform. It seems to be
working. (Holmes, Cox News Service). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   ARMY-BOX _ MOSCOW _ Highlight box listing weaknesses in Russia's
military. One finding: ``The average Russian soldier is only
marginally combat capable'' as chronic economic problems faced by
the government have curtailed training of the country's 1.2 million
soldiers, sailors and airmen. (Holmes, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   All stories MOVED Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   ADAMS-BUSH _ AUSTIN, Texas _ George W. Bush says he didn't grow
up wanting to be president. Neither did the only son of a president
who grew up to be president. Hell, the job didn't even exist until
John Quincy Adams was 22 years old. A look at the life and failed
presidency of J.Q. Adams, a man whose accomplishment G.W. Bush is
trying to match. (Herman, Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   TMI _ DAYTON, Ohio _ In a matter of about eight seconds in the
pre-dawn hours of Wednesday, March 29, 1979, the nuclear power
plant at Three Mile Island in Pennsylvania went from normal
operation to the brink of a castastrophe. Twenty years after the
United States worst nuclear accident, there is still intense debate
over the health and environmental impact of the event. (Dempsey,
Dayton Daily News) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   WITH:
</P>
<P>
   NUCLEAR _ The accident at Three Mile Island brought the nuclear
power industry in the United States to a screeching halt. Since
that time no new plants have been built, and many partially
completed plants were converted to coal. However, approximately 20
percent of the nation's power still comes from nuclear plants, and
some in the industry think nuclear power has a future. (Dempsey,
Dayton Daily News) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON/POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   USDA-BEEF _ FINLEY, Wash. _ When 12 children were sickened six
months ago by deadly E. coli bacteria after eating a school lunch,
it received little publicity. But a Cox Newspapers investigation
has found that the U.S. Department of Agriculture, which donated
the ground beef for that toxic lunch, has been feeding suspect beef
to millions of school children around the nation. (Jaspin,
Montgomery, Cox News Service). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   USDA-BOX _ Box to go with main story on USDA school lunch
program.
</P>
<P>
   All stories MOVED Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   OPED/EDITORIAL
</P>
<P>
   TEEPEN-COLUMN _ The United States is taking a bad rap for its
refusal to sign the land-mine ban, sometimes from friends _ Canada
is appalled _ but more often from nations to which the issue offers
easy posturing and even from nations so blithely evil they'll sign
anything virtuous-sounding without the slightest intention of
honoring the deal. (Tom Teepen is national correspondent for Cox
Newspapers.) MOVED THURSDAY.
</P>
<P>
   KLEINBERG-COLUMN _ Were I Bill Clinton (and I'm delighted that
I'm not) here's what I would have done. I would have picked up the
phone and placed a call to Boris Yeltsin in the Kremlin. ``Boris,''
I would begin, ``this guy Milosevic, with whom we've had trouble in
the past, is murdering a lot of ethnic Albanians and we need to put
a stop to it.'' (Howard Kleinberg is a columnist for Cox News
Service.) MOVES THURSDAY.
</P>
<P>
   GLASS-COLUMN _ WASHINGTON _ The United States declared a state
of war today as waves of Mexican warplanes pounded U.S. military
targets in a campaign to force Washington to accept an
international peace plan for Texas. (Andy Glass is a columnist for
Cox News Service in the Washington bureau.) MOVED THURSDAY.
</P>
