<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA-FEATURE28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Celtics pitiful under Pitino
 &HT;    By Curtis Bunn
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In Boston, where mediocrity is welcomed as much as red
clam chowder, the Celtics are engrossed in a funk so dastardly that
the unthinkable has happened: Highly regarded coach Rick Pitino
even questioned his ability.
</P>
<P>
   If observers wondered from afar how bad things were in Beantown,
nothing could convey that better than Pitino admitting he's as much
a part of the problem as anyone else. Yeah, it's bad.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look, I've been given, I really believe, great treatment in
this town by the press and by the fans,'' Pitino said, ``and right
now the way the team is playing, I deserve to take a lot of heat.
That is a poor performance from a team that is supposedly
well-coached. I should take the heat, and I don't mind it one bit,
and look in the mirror and say maybe this isn't a well-coached
team.''
</P>
<P>
   Truth be told, Pitino is a quality coach. But his system of
pressing at all costs is flawed because it basically is an
all-or-nothing scheme. If opponents are rattled by the frenzy that
his ``white'' and ``black'' presses create, Boston forces
turnovers, scores in transition and wears down teams. However, if
foes handle the chaos with poise, crisp passing and an attack
mentality, they get open shots and layups at a rate that the
Celtics cannot withstand.
</P>
<P>
   Guess which scenario has been played out far too often for
Pitino this season? Even after a 90-84 win Friday over
Philadelphia, which was without Allen Iverson, Boston has lost 10
of its last 12 games. Worse, the Celtics have gotten blown out in
most defeats, prompting many to contend that the players have quit
on Pitino.
</P>
<P>
   Considering his reputation as the consummate program-builder and
his status as team president, it is not likely the former Kentucky
leader's job is in jeopardy. But he is far from comfortable,
either.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've tried to stay positive, upbeat, but I've seen the
Washington Generals play defense better,'' Pitino said of his club.
``I won't be humiliated. If (players) are humiliating the Boston
Celtics, they're not going to play anymore. Everybody is going to
think of team, winning, defense. If they don't want to think about
that, they can sit there and watch other guys do it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Boston Celtics stand for winning, tradition, teamwork.
When we do that, we can be a decent basketball team. And we'll
think of that from here on out because I broke. They broke me. It's
no more.''
</P>
<P>
   The next night, the Celtics responded to Pitino's harsh words by
shooting 30 percent and scoring 68 points in losing by 19 at home
to the Milwaukee Bucks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think it could get worse,'' Pitino said, ``but it
just did.''
</P>
<P>
   The Boston fans have shown their displeasure with boos. And the
No. 1 target has been All-Star forward Antoine Walker, who shot
1-for-14 against the Bucks. He was 2-for-15 a week ago against
Chicago, and booed after going 0-for-11 in the first half. He went
8-for-18 at Cleveland and then 1-for-14 against Minnesota, again
getting booed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that's right,'' Walker said of his treatment.
``We need all the support we can get. I guess they want to see good
basketball, but (booing) on every shot? Is that going to make us
play better?''
</P>
<P>
   Apparently not. But is he making his teammates better? No, says
Chicago's Ron Harper. ``He's got to learn to play with the guys he
has out there. If he does, they have a chance to be a very good
team in a few years,'' Harper said.
</P>
<P>
   First-year forward Paul Pierce, who started the season strongly,
has lost nearly six points off his scoring average since being
named NBA Rookie of the Month for February. But as poorly as the
Celtics have shot the ball, it's defense and effort that have
killed them.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's only one way out for us,'' Pitino said, ``only one
answer: Outwork your opposition. If we have character, we'll fight
our way out and get W's.''
</P>
<P>
   Said guard Kenny Anderson: ``We've taken enough lumps and we're
going to learn from them. Either that, or all of us are going to
start looking like Elephant Man.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
