<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA-NOTES28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Courtside with Charles Barkley
 &HT;    By Curtis Bunn
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Age and injury have stunted Charles Barkley's ability
to dominate. But nothing can keep the Houston Rockets forward from
spouting off. And so, we give you Barkley's ``State of the NBA.''
</P>
<P>
   On the Eastern Conference: ``Let me tell you something. You take
Miami and Indiana and Orlando out of the East and you might as well
blow the rest of them up. They're terrible, and there's nothing you
can tell me different. We don't even pay attention to the East.
It's a dogfight out here (in the West) every night. Am I surprised?
Yeah, I'm surprised Miami and Indiana aren't 20 games ahead of
everyone else. And Orlando started fast, but they're folding now.
So you really have only two teams over there, and that's it. Two.''
</P>
<P>
   On the development of the Rockets, who added Scottie Pippen:
``I'm a little disappointed in Scottie. He has all the money, and
now he wants all the shots, too. I'll make that switch. I'll give
him all the shots and take half of his money.''
</P>
<P>
   On Houston's recent strong play, which includes a stretch of
seven wins in eight games: ``We've got the fourth-best record in
the West, and we haven't played that long together. We're going to
be good before the end of the season. We're playing better overall,
in every area. The chemistry is better.''
</P>
<P>
   WEEPING OVER SNUB
</P>
<P>
   The Utah Jazz, who cry more than any team in the league, whined
about being pulled by NBC from their scheduled broadcast a week
ago. The Lakers-Orlando game was aired instead. Karl Malone said:
``To me, it's all about people wanting to sell a couple more
jerseys.'' Bryon Russell added: ``They always want to talk to us,
but then they don't give us any respect. We're still a pretty good
team. But they didn't show our game just because they wanted to
show Dennis Rodman.''
</P>
<P>
   Really, it's a demand thing. With Michael Jordan retired, the
Lakers _ with Rodman, Shaquille O'Neal, Kobe Bryant and Glenn Rice
_ are the league's marquee team.
</P>
<P>
   THEY SAID IT
</P>
<P>
   ``When it rains, it pours,'' said Vancouver coach Brian Hill
when center Bryant Reeves hurt his right knee, joining Doug West,
Lee Mayberry and Rodrick Rhodes on the sideline.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure what's happened, but all of a sudden we
believe,'' Toronto's Vince Carter said of his team's recent
confidence and good play, including a franchise-best five-game
winning streak.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
