A6429 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-FALCONS-NOTES28-C     03-27 0824
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-NOTES28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Defensive line a draft target
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The finish line is in sight, but the hard part is
about to begin for the Falcons' scouting and coaching staffs.
</P>
<P>
   Coaches and scouts have been visiting campus sites, working out
and interviewing prospects for the April 17-18 draft. They gather
Monday to begin discussing strengths and weaknesses of the existing
roster and what's available in the draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``We start by talking defense. If we get done with defense,
we'll talk about offense,'' said coach Dan Reeves. ``Otherwise,
we'll talk about offense the next week.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta has eight draft choices, two each in the sixth and
seventh rounds. The Falcons traded away this year's second-round
pick for since-waived wide receiver Tony Martin.
</P>
<P>
   The lack of a second-round choice creates more pressure to pick
a winner in the first round.
</P>
<P>
   ``This draft is not as good as last year,'' said Reed Johnson,
the Falcons' director of college scouting. ``Last year, I thought
there were 90 good players ... There's more like 60 this year that
can make the team and be a factor for us.''
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons' first-round choice is 30th overall, and they don't
pick again until 92nd.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our strategy is best player available ... but you're always
influenced by your needs,'' Reeves said. ``I would say defensive
line and the secondary always are a premium.''
</P>
<P>
   This year's draft is deep with offensive linemen and
quarterbacks. It is shallow in defensive linemen, where the Falcons
are shallow, too.
</P>
<P>
   Other than starters Chuck Smith and Lester Archambeau, the
Falcons do not have a defensive end with NFL experience. The
Falcons love Florida linebacker-defensive end Jevon Kearse (6 feet
5, 262 pounds), but he'll be an early choice. The next best
prospects at end are considered to be Ebenezer Ekuban (6-3, 266) of
North Carolina and Patrick Kerney (6-5, 262) of Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   ``You like everything about (Ekuban), and then he goes to the
Senior Bowl and forgets to show up,'' Johnson said. ``You wonder:
Was the game too big for him? Did he get scared? It's like he
wasn't even there.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best thing (about Kerney) is he's going to get bigger. He
brings it every play,'' Johnson said. ``He takes advantage of the
situation. He knew (Georgia tackle Matt) Stinchcomb was hurt in the
(Peach) Bowl, and he said, `I'm not going to dance with him; I'm
just going to run over him,' and that's what he did.''
</P>
<P>
   Other ends that intrigue the Falcons are Lamar King (6-3, 299)
of Saginaw Valley State and Mike Rucker (6-4, 260) of Nebraska.
Robinson's fate
</P>
<P>
   Speculation continues that Atlanta will waive free safety Eugene
Robinson, who turns 36 today. Robinson's age and high salary-cap
figure ($2.3 million), in a secondary rife with big salaries, make
his release more likely. Robinson has asked his agent, Phyllis
Freed of Canfield, Ohio, to find out what's up.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta re-signed cornerback Ronnie Bradford, 28, two weeks ago
intending to move him to free safety.Bradford's cap number of
$862,000 combined with those of cornerback Ray Buchanan ($3
million), Robinson, cornerback Michael Booker ($1.62 million) and
newly signed strong safety Marty Carter ($1.42 million) count
$9,202,500 against the cap. That's 16.1 percent of the team's $57.3
million cap alllowance.
</P>
<P>
   Jamal chronicles
</P>
<P>
   Running back Jamal Anderson's agent, James Sims of Oakland, has
sent the Falcons a proposal for a contract extension. Anderson, 26,
is believed to be seeking a 5- to 7-year deal worth $25 million to
$40 million.
</P>
<P>
   Extra points
</P>
<P>
   Former Giants guard Greg Bishop probably will sign a two-year,
$4 million contract Monday or Tuesday. The team has just about
$600,000 left to spend under the cap; to create room, it is
tweaking the contract of quarterback Chris Chandler. ... Offensive
tackle Jose Portilla, the only undrafted college player to make the
team last year, will sign a two-year, $562,500 contract with
incentives related to playing time. ... The team's offseason
conditioning program, four days a week of weightlifting and running
for 15 weeks, begins Monday. Strength and conditioning coach Al
Miller expects 45-50 players. ... Fullback Bob Christian, who
suffered a partial tear of the anterior cruciate ligament on Dec.
13, is further along in his recuperation than running back Byron
Hanspard, who tore the anterior cruciate ligament and patella
tendon in his left knee in the final preseason game. ``Christian
should be ready (for training camp) with no problem,'' trainer Ron
Medlin said. ``Byron _ it's too early to say.'' Hanspard's status
could influence draft strategy. ... The Falcons have sold more than
7,300 new season ticket packages, and more than 80 percent of last
year's 29,715 season-ticket holders have renewed contracts.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
