<HEADLINE>
CIVIL DISOBEDIENCE, NEGOTIATED 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For use by special arrangement
only. Asian and European points: Call Karl Horwitz in Paris for
details and prices, phone: 47 42 17 11; fax: 47-42-80-44). Latin
American points: Call Olivia Vasquez in Los Angeles, phone:
310-996-0075; fax: 310-996-0089). 
(lb) 
 By DAN BARRY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For the last two weeks, Police Headquarters in New
York City has provided an austere backdrop for a recurring drama:
the daily noontime engagement between police officers in protective
gear and protesters decrying police misconduct and brutality. Each
session ends with the arrests of dozens of people for participating
in the time-honored act of civil disobedience.
</P>
<P>
   The protests, prompted by the death last month of an unarmed
black man struck by 19 of 41 bullets fired by four white officers,
are meant to recall memorable moments of struggle in American
history _ from Henry David Thoreau's refusal to pay a poll tax to
the Rev. Dr. Martin Luther King Jr.'s use of nonviolent
confrontation in the fight for civil rights.
</P>
<P>
   But they also reflect the cordial choreography of street theater
that has come to define many demonstrations, with protesters and
police officers acting more like co-stars than adversaries.
</P>
<P>
   The daily protests, the backdrop to the four officers'
indictment for murder last week, have certainly created stirring
images for the evening news and the morning newspapers that go
beyond the novelty of showing Susan Sarandon and Ossie Davis in
custody.
</P>
<P>
   Each day, in fact, has brought portraits of dignified
nonresistance: of Kweisi Mfume, the president of the National
Association for the Advancement of Colored People, his mouth a thin
line of determination; of former Mayor David Dinkins, his eyes
reflecting sorrow and defiance. Their faces contrasted effectively
with the masks of indifference worn by the arresting officers.
</P>
<P>
   Not captured in those images, however, were the offstage huddles
between lawyers for the protesters and high-ranking police
officials, often to confirm ground rules established in earlier
negotiations. The police politely explained that to get arrested on
charges of disorderly conduct the demonstrators would have to block
both entrances to the building.
</P>
<P>
   In turn, the demonstrators promised not to resist arrest. At
times the organizers have even provided the police with the names
of those planning to be arrested _ a thoughtful act designed to
expedite warrant checks and, ultimately, the release of the
conscientious scofflaws.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the entente that's been worked out with the police,''
said Ronald Kuby, a lawyer with two decades of experience in civil
protest who has negotiated with the police on the parameters of the
demonstrations. ``Both sides have actually developed a relationship
where they've learned to deal with each other in a candid way.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Civil disobedience in the United States has matured since the
days of Thoreau. First came the influence of Gandhi, who advocated
a more coercive, confrontational approach to nonviolence _ in
particular, the participation of large numbers of people _ to
effect change.
</P>
<P>
   Then King, among others, introduced a liberal, Christian
sensibility to protest, as well as the recognition of the power of
images. A single photograph _ of fire hoses turned on civil rights
demonstrators by Police Commissioner Eugene ``Bull'' Connor in
Birmingham, Ala. _ could immediately convey the injustice of
segregation to the nation.
</P>
<P>
   James Tracy, the author of ``Direct Action: Radical Pacifism
From the Union Eight to the Chicago Seven'' (University of Chicago
Press, 1996), said that both Gandhi and King believed in being
candid with the authorities about their plans. That commitment to
openness, he said, was so prevalent by the early 1960s that peace
campaigners intent on obstructing the progress of a nuclear
submarine plant in Connecticut even allowed agents from the FBI to
attend their meetings.
</P>
<P>
   The anti-war protests of the late 1960s brought a more
confrontational style of civil disobedience to the fore, Tracy
said, one in which surprise was essential and negotiations with the
police were rejected. Since then, he said, ``A great deal of
tension over these two methods _ openness and surprise _ has tended
to break some organizations apart.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no question that many movements continue to adhere to
the ``surprise'' approach to disobedience _ with good reason,
according to Mark Hannay, a spokesman in New York for Act Up, an
AIDS protest group. ``Once you begin the negotiations process, all
of a sudden the power dynamic shifts so that the police try to
control and almost define what your event is going to be,'' he
said. ``All of a sudden it becomes not your event.''
</P>
<P>
   Chief Allan Hoehl, a police commander for the southern half of
Manhattan, has experienced both types of protests, and he obviously
prefers cooperation. ``When we meet with demonstrators, we ask
whether there's going to be civil disobedience,'' he said. ``If we
know when and how it's going to happen, we can make sure that no
one else jumps in, that there's no interference. It can go much
more smoothly.''
</P>
<P>
   But even in cases of coordination between protesters and the
police, neither side ever drops its guard. And both take comfort in
knowing that if necessary they can make life difficult for
everybody.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Kuby and Michael Hardy, the two lawyers helping the
Rev. Al Sharpton to organize the recent police protests, have made
it clear that the acts of civil disobedience are being staged in
front of police headquarters for symbolic purposes. And if the
police try to stop them, they and their hundreds of followers will
gladly stroll a few hundred yards to block traffic on Broadway _
inconveniencing motorists and requiring the services of many more
police officers.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, they know that such an action will come at a
cost. ``So when the demonstrators are done saying, `We'll do
this,''' Kuby explained, ``the police will say, `And when you're
done, we'll do what we want to do.''' At the very least, that can
mean dragging those arrested through a booking process that can
take 24 hours or more.
</P>
<P>
   That is why negotiations beforehand have become de rigueur for
protesters and police, Tracy explained. The action that results is
respectful of the law but emphasizes the need for a higher moral
principle. It is also so much easier.
</P>
<P>
   ``The police step in and say, `Those of you with children and
strollers, step away,' '' he said. ``Then newspaper people come
around, take pictures, and it's over.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-27-99 1410EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
