<SLUG> BC-THISWEEK-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
  
 The Week in Review  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 (bl)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Oscar's Hangover
</P>
<P>
   As a four-hour endurance contest, the 71st annual Academy Awards
seemed even longer than usual. By the time it was over, the
question of the night was, what were former Sen. John Glenn and
Gen. Colin Powell doing on stage? No one knew.
</P>
<P>
   The big upset was ``Shakespeare in Love,'' beating the
front-runner, ``Saving Private Ryan.'' Miramax, the
quasi-independent company owned by Disney, won 10 Oscars, including
three for Roberto Benigni's ``Life Is Beautiful.'' Gwyneth Paltrow
won best actress and Judi Dench best supporting actress for
``Shakespeare in Love,'' and James Coburn was voted best supporting
actor for ``Affliction.''
</P>
<P>
   The aftermath of the awards was more fun than the show itself.
Miramax and Dreamworks continued sniping at one another over how
much money the other spent on its campaign for ``Shakespeare in
Love'' and ``Saving Private Ryan.'' A photograph in the trade
papers showed the three owners of Dreamworks _ Steven Spielberg,
David Geffen and Jeffrey Katzenberg _ sitting together at a
post-Oscar party, looking somewhat unhappy.
</P>
<P>
   And Fernanda Montenegro, the Brazilian star who was nominated as
best actress for ``Central Station,'' had some blunt comments that
stung because many in Hollywood believed she was on target. She
told a Brazilian television interviewer that neither Ms. Paltrow
nor Benigni were especially worthy of the awards, and called Ms.
Paltrow ``this romantic figure, thin, pure, virginal.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By BERNARD WEINRAUB
</P>
<P>
   For Detained Pinochet, A Partial Victory
</P>
<P>
   Gen. Augusto Pinochet's desire to end his house arrest in
England and return home to Chile got a boost when England's highest
court threw out the bulk of the charges that could be used in the
Spanish effort to extradite him to Madrid to stand trial for crimes
against humanity.
</P>
<P>
   The 83-year-old former Chilean dictator was arrested in October
and has been detained since then. His lawyers argued that the
lesser charges are not sufficient to hold him any longer.
</P>
<P>
   _ By WARREN HOGE
</P>
<P>
   Jackson Says, `No Thanks'
</P>
<P>
   Campaign after campaign, supporters of the Rev. Jesse Jackson
greeted the civil rights leader with the rallying cry, ``Run Jesse
Run!''
</P>
<P>
   This time, he could not be enticed. Jackson, who has run twice
for president, announced he would sit out the 2000 contest, saying
he would rather concentrate on persuading corporations to invest in
minority businesses. ``The time spent running for president is time
that cannot be spent doing something else,'' he said. ``I've got so
many issues I want to raise. I've got so many battles left to
fight.''
</P>
<P>
   That leaves Vice President Al Gore with only one rival for the
Democratic nomination, former Sen. Bill Bradley of New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   _ By RICHARD L. BERKE
</P>
<P>
   At Last, a Balloon Makes It
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Bertrand Piccard and Brian Jones became the first
balloonists to circle the world nonstop. They were greeted in
Geneva by a thunderous cheer and a trumpeter playing the
``Triumphal March'' from ``Aida.''
</P>
<P>
   Piccard, 41, a Swiss psychiatrist, and his British co-pilot,
Jones, 52, completed a 19-day trip around the world in their
Breitling Orbiter 3 balloon when they flew over an invisible finish
line at 9 degrees 27 minutes west longitude in Mauritania, then
touched down in the soft sands of southern Egypt.
</P>
<P>
   More than a score of pilots had tried to go around the world in
a balloon before. All failed.
</P>
<P>
   MIT Admits It's Tough on Women
</P>
<P>
   From Harvard to Stanford, top American universities are often
accused of discriminating against their female professors, and
usually respond with defensive denials. The Massachusetts Institute
of Technology took a different, more scientific approach: It
gathered the data, quantified the problem and verified its
existence.
</P>
<P>
   And now, the institute _ the most prestigious science and
technology school in the country _ has responded with an
extraordinary admission from its highest officials that, yes, women
on the faculty have been systematically, though unintentionally,
short-changed. It found pervasive evidence that women came up short
on everything from hiring and tenure to the allocation of critical
resources like research money and lab space.
</P>
<P>
   _ By CAREY GOLDBERG &QR;
</P>
<P>
   Cruise Line Takes a Plea
</P>
<P>
   Royal Caribbean Cruises pleaded guilty in federal court in Los
Angeles to three counts of making false statements to Coast Guard
inspectors in an attempt to conceal the illegal dumping of oily
waste water into the Pacific Ocean in 1994. Prosecutors believe the
unexpected admission reinforces United States jurisdiction over
foreign cruise ships. Royal Caribbean, the world's second-largest
cruise company, still faces potential dumping charges in New York
and Alaska. The industry is under congressional scrutiny on several
fronts, including whether to alter the tax-free status that saves
foreign ships plying U.S. waters billions of dollars a year.
</P>
<P>
   _ By DOUGLAS FRANTZ
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
