   A Japanese manager shocked the nation when he committed
hara-kiri in a protest of the corporate restructuring that is
starting to take place across the country. Moments before he
slashed his stomach with a 14-inch fish-slicing knife, Masaharu
Nonaka had been in heated talks with the president of Bridgestone
Corp., one of the world's largest tire makers.
</P>
<P>
   The case is extreme, but Nonaka's ritual suicide strikes a deep
chord in Japan, which is suffering from record levels of
unemployment and a recessionary economy.
</P>
<P>
   _ By SHERYL WuDUNN &QR;
</P>
<P>
   A Windfall in the Budget
</P>
<P>
   Deficits have given way to surpluses, but budget politics in
Washington go on. Both the House and the Senate adopted Republican
tax-and-spending plans, putting Congress on a collision course with
the Clinton administration over how to divide the huge fiscal
windfall.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans want to bolster Social Security and provide a big
tax cut. Democrats want to bolster Social Security and split the
rest of the money among Medicare, new spending and a much smaller
tax cut. With the pie as big as it is, there is probably room for
compromise.
</P>
<P>
   _ By RICHARD W. STEVENSON &QR;
</P>
<P>
   Possible Clue On Missing Atheist
</P>
<P>
   With a former employee of the missing atheist leader Madalyn
Murray O'Hair in custody, charged with weapons violations,
investigators were hoping for a long-awaited breakthrough in the
perplexing 1995 disappearance of the 77-year-old woman, her son,
her granddaughter and $500,000 in gold coins.
</P>
<P>
   David R. Waters, a convicted felon who also pled guilty in 1994
to theft from Ms. O'Hair's organization, American Atheists Inc.,
was arrested after an eight-hour search of his apartment in Austin,
Texas His lawyer told reporters that federal officials considered
Waters a suspect in the possible murder of the three missing
people.
</P>
<P>
   _ By RICK LYMAN &QR;
</P>
<P>
   Bright Lights, Wrong City
</P>
<P>
   Two buildings, a continent apart, with crowds peppered with
celebrities. But there the similarities ended. At the Dorothy
Chandler Pavilion in Los Angeles, film stars stepped smilingly in
for the Academy Awards ceremony. And at Police Headquarters in
Manhattan, former mayors, other politicians, union leaders, even a
few actors, gathered day after day to protest the shooting of
Amadou Diallo, the unarmed man who died in a hail of 41 police
bullets.
</P>
<P>
   But wait. Could that be Police Commissioner Howard Safir
mingling with the Oscar luminaries? The very man who had said he
would have to skip a Monday hearing on the Diallo affair because of
what an aide called ``important, long-scheduled meetings''?
</P>
<P>
   Yes indeed. And Safir had headed west on a Revlon jet, slept in
the swankest-of-the-swank Peninsula Hotel, all as a guest of a
Revlon pal. Once spotted, he hopped the red-eye home and made it to
the hearing after all. An ethics investigation is pending.
</P>
<P>
   _ By HUBERT B. HERRING
</P>
<P>
   Conviction for Kevorkian
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Jack Kevorkian was convicted of second-degree murder for
giving a lethal injection to a 52-year-old man with Lou Gehrig's
disease. Kevorkian, who defended himself at the trial in Pontiac,
Mich., could be sentenced to life in prison. It was the 70-year-old
doctor's first murder trial. In the past, he has been charged only
with assisted suicide. He was acquitted three times and a fourth
case resulted in a mistrial.
</P>
<P>
   White House Offers China Plan
</P>
<P>
   The White House thought it had a plan to improve relations with
China: Get Beijing into the World Trade Organization, something the
Chinese have sought for more than a decade. But the Chinese never
wanted to pay the price _ lower tariffs on imports, an end to huge
trade barriers and protection for state-owned industries.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the Chinese seem willing to play, and negotiations are
becoming furious in the run-up to Prime Minister Zhu Rongji's visit
to Washington on April 8. But in the White House, some are getting
cold feet. Amid charges of spying and human rights violations, some
wonder whether Congress will torpedo the whole deal.
</P>
<P>
   _ By DAVID E. SANGER
</P>
</TEXT>
