<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBAEAST28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cousy: `I feel sorry for Rick Pitino'
 &HT;    By Jeffrey Denberg
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Added to Rick Pitino's on-court problems with the
Celtics, team broadcasters Bob Cousy and Tommy Heinsohn remain on
the job despite the coach's efforts to fire them.
</P>
<P>
   So ask yourself if Cousy was crying crocodile tears when he
said, ``I feel sorry for Rick Pitino right now. Sometimes I think
he's going to have a nervous breakdown if he keeps going at that
pace.... He works 16 to 18 hours a day. He charts everything. There
are endless films to look at. Maybe he's trying to do too much.''
</P>
<P>
   With the Celtics slumping badly, Cousy continued, ``Hey, I
bought into a lot of it myself. They showed a big improvement last
year, and this year was going to be even better. They stole Paul
Pierce in the draft. Antoine Walker and (Ron) Mercer were a year
older. They picked up Kenny Anderson. But it hasn't happened. This
team has been a major disappointment.''
</P>
<P>
   Through the looking glass
</P>
<P>
   Miami coach Pat Riley, laughing, on Phil Jackson's claim that
this year's champion will be tainted because of the lockout: ``I
still think it's the effects of that windowpane (LSD) he took in
1970. What does he know? He's stumping for Bill Bradley. Jackson
should have no opinion about the NBA. He's not in it. He would love
it to be tainted because he's the only one who tasted victory in
the last (three) years. He doesn't want to give anyone any
credit.''
</P>
<P>
   Thank you call
</P>
<P>
   Stephon Marbury said he called Minnesota coach Flip Saunders but
denied saying he had made a mistake jumping to New Jersey. ``I
called and thanked him for everything he'd done for me as far as
being a better basketball player. ...I just did it out of respect.
...If he took it as something negative, I guess the pain is still
running deep down.''
</P>
<P>
   Noncontact defense
</P>
<P>
   Toronto coach Butch Carter had a simple strategy for beating the
Pistons last week. ``Just take it to the basket,'' he said, after
the Raptors overcame an 11-point deficit and won 103-101. ``They
won't take a charge.'' The Pistons took one charge the entire
night, while the Raptors made 13 layups or dunks. In the fourth
quarter, they scored 37 points and hit 13 of 16 shots, eight from
10 feet and in
</P>
<P>
   The shots will fall
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Ewing missed another big shot, and the Knicks lost at
Sacramento on Wednesday, so the critical calls to WFAN radio in New
York are even more vociferous. Ewing's response: ``I'm going to
keep taking those shots. They have to start going in sometime.''
</P>
<P>
   Pleading innocent
</P>
<P>
   Jack Nies whistled Christian Laettner for a Type 2 flagrant
foul, which calls for automatic ejection, against Jayson Williams
in the Pistons' game at New Jersey. ``Everyone in the whole arena
was surprised when all of a sudden Jack Nies made that call,''
Laettner said. ``I was surprised as anyone, but as you see, I just
ran off the court. You don't mess around with Jack Nies. He ... was
the only guy in arena who thought I should be thrown out.''
</P>
<P>
   Laettner was asked why he thought Nies had it in for him. ``I
don't know where it comes from,'' he said. ``His son (appears) on
MTV. Maybe that's it.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
