<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR SATURDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Saturday, March 27:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; KOSOVO  &LR; (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RDP (Brussels, Belgium) _ Serbian forces stepped up
attacks against ethnic Albanian civilians in Kosovo on Saturday as
NATO air operations rattled Belgrade, the Yugoslav capital, in the
heaviest attacks of the campaign, allied officials said. ``The
Serbs have been torching villages,'' the British Defense Minister,
George Robertson, said in London. ``There are reports that the
Serbs are bombing villages to the point of obliteration. There are
clear signs now that an all-out Serb offensive against the Albanian
population has started.'' By Craig R. Whitney. With photos and map.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-FORCE (Washington) _ Bill Clinton is a politician to his
core, a man of persuasion, not intimidation. He has always been
ambivalent about the use of force to accomplish his purposes, an
ambivalence that mirrors his still uneasy relationship with the
American military. By John M. Broder. With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MILOSEVIC (Undated) _ Profile of the Serbian leader:
Rarely can a historical turning point be established quite so
precisely as the one that occurred on April 24, 1987, when Slobodan
Milosevic, a veteran apparatchik best known for his organizational
skills, faced a crowd of enraged Serbs in a suburb of Pristina. As
they complained of being pushed back by police wielding batons, he
told them: ``No one will dare to beat you again.'' By Michael T.
Kaufman.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-BELGRADE (Belgrade, Yugoslavia) _ As the price of
gasoline rose more than seven times and a prominent Serbian
journalist was arrested Saturday for offending new censorship
rules, the citizens of Belgrade appeared considerably shaken after
the heaviest night of NATO bombing in and around the capital. By
Steven Erlanger. Eds: Correspondent was ordered to depart
Yugoslavia on Thursday but was allowed to reenter the country early
Saturday morning.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RUSSIA (Moscow) _ Anti-American reaction to the NATO
bombing grows in Russia. By Celestine Bohlen.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CLINTON (Washington) _ As United States and NATO aircraft
entered the fourth day of strikes on Serbian targets, President
Clinton said Saturday that allied forces must ``stay the course''
to prevent the war in Kosovo from spreading. By John M. Broder.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-TURKEY (Istanbul) _ More than 3,000 ethnic Albanians from
Kosovo have arrived in Turkey in recent days, and Turkey is
welcoming them. By Stephen Kinzer.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OTHER INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   YUKON-GUN-CONTROL (Whitehorse, Yukon Territory) _ A new gun
control statute meets stiff resistance in the Canadian northwest.
By Anthony DePalma. With photo and map.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-FLAG-ANTHEM (Tokyo) _ The Japanese Government is trying to
rehabilitate the flag of the rising sun and the national song of
praise for the emperor, giving them legal status despite criticism
that in World War II they were emblematic of Japanese militarism.
By Nicholas D. Kristof.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-POLICE (Beijing) _ China is expanding the size of its
special domestic police force, trained in riot control, reflecting
Beijing's preoccupation with internal stability. By Erik Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   U.N.-HUMAN-RIGHTS (Geneva) _ At the annual U.N. human rights
conference, the United States is coming under criticism over its
use of executions. By Elizabeth Olson.
</P>
<P>
   EMBASSY-BOMB-SURGERY (Nairobi, Kenya) _ American plastic
surgeons are helping repair the scars, physical and psychological,
of survivors of the bombing of the American embassy in Kenya. By
Ian Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   SWEDEN-WALLENBERGS (Stockholm) _ The Wallenbergs have released
documents to clarify the family's wartime history, and some
historians suggest that other details may emerge as more archives
are opened. By Alan Cowell.
</P>
<P>
   U.N.-DRUGS-SATELLITE (Undated) _ The U.N. program charged with
reducing illicit drugs is creating its own satellite monitoring
system to identify the cultivation of narcotics in the major source
countries. By Christopher S. Wren.
</P>
<P>
   CUBA-BASEBALL-POLITICS (Havana) _ Despite the excitement over
the Baltimore Orioles' exhibition game here and the veneer of
openness it conveys, American baseball comes to Cuba in a climate
of heightened political repression. By Mireya Navarro.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   DRUG-COMPANIES-ADS (Washington) _ The federal government has
repeatedly reprimanded drug companies in recent months after
finding that they had made false or misleading claims in television
commercials and magazine advertisements for a wide range of
prescription drugs. By Robert Pear.
</P>
<P>
   DRUG-COMPANIES-FDA (Undated) _ Two drug companies seeking to tap
the vast market of postmenopausal women at risk for breast cancer,
heart disease and bone loss have clashed with each other and run
afoul of the Food and Drug Administration over their marketing
practices, prompting a flurry of lawsuits, government warning
letters and accusations that inaccurate assertions could endanger
women's health. By Denise Grady.
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS (Washington) _ Beginning with an argument next week in an
obscure case about overtime pay for state probation officers in
Maine, the Supreme Court is setting out on an extended foray along
the border that separates federal authority from state
prerogatives. By Linda Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   PENSION-PROBLEMS (Undated) _ A quarter-century ago, Congress
created the Pension Benefit Guaranty Corp. to make sure that the 42
million workers with traditional pensions would get paid even if
their employer went bankrupt. How well that agency operates is now
being questioned in a series of audits by the agency's inspector
general and by a lawsuit charging that one of the pension agency's
contractors defrauded it. By David Cay Johnston.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL  &LR; (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-VIRUS (San Francisco) _ A rapidly spreading computer
virus forced several large corporations to shut down their e-mail
servers on Friday night as it rode the Internet on a global
rampage, several leading network security companies reported
Saturday. By Matt Richtel.
</P>
<P>
   GAY-MARRIAGE-MINISTER (Undated) _ A United Methodist Church
minister in Chicago, convicted of breaking church law by
officiating at the union of two gay men, has been suspended from
his duties. By Gustav Niebuhr.
</P>
<P>
   BLACK-BEACH-DISPUTE (Virginia Key, Fla.) _ As developers eye
this small key of largely palm and sand with intentions of turning
it into an upscale resort area, older black residents of Miami-Dade
are shaking their heads. By Rick Bragg.
</P>
<P>
   NAVAJO-ZOO (Window Rock, Ariz.) _ The Navajo's assertion of
tradition and the cultural reverence for animals have combined to
put the future of the 36-year-old Navajo Nation's zoo in doubt.
``It's a culture shock that we're experiencing,'' said Harry
Walters, a Navajo who is an anthropologist. By Catherine C.
Robbins.
</P>
<P>
   D-DAY-MEMORIAL (Bedford, Va.) _ Board members of the National
D-Day Memorial Foundation, which has its headquarters in this city
of 6,400, in the foothills of the Blue Ridge Mountains, were
disappointed when ``Saving Private Ryan'' didn't win the Academy
Award for best picture. They were hoping that an Oscar sweep for
the D-Day epic would help the foundation reach a $12 million
fund-raising goal for the construction of a major national
memorial, a rarity outside Washington. By Ian Zack.
</P>
<P>
   INMATE-APPEAL (Auburn, N.Y. _ In 1987, David Wong, an illegal
Chinese immigrant who was serving time for armed robbery, was
convicted of second-degree murder in the slaying of a prison inmate
and sentenced to 25 years to life in prison. Ordinarily, the case
of Wong would not attract much notice. But this story is different,
not only because interviews with prison employees, inmates and the
dead inmate's widow strongly suggest that Wong is innocent, but
also because Wong has found unconditional support from a group of
indefatigable strangers in New York City. By David Chen.
</P>
<P>
   GURU'S-WILL (White Plains, N.Y.) _ When Frederick P. Lenz III
swallowed 150 tablets of Valium and stepped off a dock into the bay
behind his Long Island home last year, he left behind a collection
of mansions, private jets and luxury cars valued at $18 million,
and a will that practically invited a lawsuit. By Debra West.
</P>
<P>
   POLICE-BRUTALITY-TRIAL (New York) _ More than a year and a half
after a Haitian immigrant named Abner Louima was reportedly
brutalized by police officers in Brooklyn, jury selection is to
begin Monday for the trial of four officers charged with attacking
him and of a sergeant accused of joining them in an attempted
cover-up. By Joseph P. Fried.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   RENAULT-NISSAN (Tokyo) _ In taking a stake in the troubled
Nissan Motor Co., Renault, the stodgy French car company that has
tried to become a formidable force in Europe, has embarked on a
risky business gamble to strengthen the global competitiveness of
both companies. By Stephanie Strom.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY &LR;  (``k'' code)
</P>
<P>
   DOWD-COLUMN (New York) _ Commentary by Maureen Dowd on police
brutality and Mayor Giuliani's response to the police shooting of
an unarmed immigrant.
</P>
<P>
   HERBERT-COLUMN (New York) _ Commentary by Bob Herbert: A woman
in Brooklyn was arrested and detained for eight hours for
forgetting to pay a ticket for driving with a broken taillight.
</P>
