<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBAWEST28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Admiral's aching, and so is his game
 &HT;    By Jeffrey Denberg
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The decline of San Antonio's David Robinson took
another strange twist. He turned in three weak efforts last week,
shooting a combined 7-for-32.
</P>
<P>
   He had probably the worst game of his career against Golden
State (three points, five rebounds) before being benched for the
last seven minutes of a seesaw game for 6-foot-7 Malik Rose.
</P>
<P>
   Against Portland, Arvydas Sabonis piled up a season-high 28
points against Robinson, who in the past had success against him.
</P>
<P>
   Then against Vancouver, Greg Popovich benched him again for the
final seven minutes of regulation after he missed 10 of his first
12 shots. Robinson played in overtime and helped save the game with
a 17-foot shot.
</P>
<P>
   Although he would not discuss his problems, Robinson apparently
has a sore ankle and trouble jumping.
</P>
<P>
   Teammate Avery Johnson said Robinson has always been prone to
hide his pain. ``He's a good teacher. He's taught me how to play
with injuries. The thing with Dave is, yes, some of it is his body.
And some of it is just trying to get his confidence back and find
his groove.''
</P>
<P>
   Out on the ledge
</P>
<P>
   Denver nearly blew a 29-point lead against Seattle, but
prevailed after the Sonics cut the gap to one point in the fourth
quarter. ``If we had lost after having that lead,'' Nuggets coach
Mike D'Antoni said, ``I'd have been up on a ledge somewhere, and no
one would have been able to talk me down.'' After general manager
Dan Issel read that quote the next day, he told D'Antoni, ``If we
had lost that game, nobody would have tried to talk you down.''
</P>
<P>
   A happier Pippen
</P>
<P>
   After complaining about his role in the Houston offense, Scottie
Pippen has recanted. ``I feel much better. I feel like I'm being
utilized, and I'm able to be a big part of the team's offense. It
was probably my fault more so than anything. But this has allowed
me to have more leadership and control of the games.''
</P>
<P>
   Feel free to shoot
</P>
<P>
   After Allen Iverson scored 41 points by taking 36 shots,
Shaquille O'Neal threw a thinly disguised barb at teammate Kobe
Bryant, who is equally unshy about firing away. ``Any shooter who
shoots the ball 36 times every night should be the leading scorer
in the league and should be an MVP candidate. I mean, I wish I shot
the ball 36 times.''
</P>
<P>
   Unhappy Clippers
</P>
<P>
   The Clippers waived James Robinson _ at his request _ after he
agreed to settle the last three years of his contract at $7.2
million. According to teammate Pooh Richardson, ``He told some of
the guys that it wasn't anything personal against them. He just
wanted out so bad that he'd do whatever possible to leave. He's
been in the league for six years and he felt that it was crucial at
this point of his career that he had a chance to prove that he
could still play.'' ... Rodney Rogers has reportedly told the
Clippers he won't be back. Lorenzen Wright has been unhappy since
camp and Portland wants him.
</P>
<P>
   Carlesimo mellows
</P>
<P>
   There is evidence P.J. Carlesimo has changed his ways since last
year's Latrell Sprewell choking incident in Oakland. ``He still
gets on people,'' Golden State guard Bimbo Coles said. ``As far as
that, he's the same person. But what's made him a better coach and
better for the players is, he takes in our input. It's not like
everything is his way. He asks us things about travel, about
practices, about how we want to play certain plays, which was
totally different last year. To me, it seems like he's made the
steps to become a better coach and a better players' coach, and
it's worked out.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
