</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHL-WESTNOTES28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Red Wings GM goes for broke
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ For Detroit to make some moves before the trading
deadline wasn't merely expected _ it was necessary to wake up a
slumbering two-time champion. But after general manager Ken Holland
traded two No. 1 draft picks, two No. 2s, a No. 3, other
conditional picks and two young players for four players ages 37
(Chris Chelios), 35 (Ulf Samuelsson), 32 (Wendel Clark) and 32
(Bill Ranford), the belief is that the Red Wings might have
mortgaged their future. Yes, Holland probably improved the team's
chances to win the Cup this year. But this team already had age at
its core _ Steve Yzerman (33), Brendan Shanahan (30), Larry Murphy
(38), Igor Larionov (38), Uwe Krupp (33 and possibly finished with
a back injury) and Doug Brown (34). Holland talks about a win-now
philosophy and said, ``We wanted to strongly pursue another
championship next year and the next couple of years,'' which is
admirable. But if the Wings fall short, they have a major
housecleaning facing them, with five fewer prospects in the system.
The deal that made the least sense was for the Rangers' Samuelsson,
who is injured, can't play for at least two more weeks and probably
won'tbe re-signed after the season. Holland gave up second- and
third-round picks just minutes before the trading deadline. Ranford
is a projected backup for goalie Chris Osgood next season if the
Wings lose Norm Maracle to the Thrashers in the expansion draft.
Clark gives the team a leader and a physical presence. But two
firsts for Chelios at this stage of his career? ``That was way out
of our range,'' said Philadelphia GM Bob Clarke, who also pursued
the defenseman.
</P>
<P>
   The New Math
</P>
<P>
   After buying out the remainder of Steve Duchesne's $11.25
million contract for $4.25 million before trading him to
Philadelphia, this is what the Los Angeles Kings were left with on
their accounting books: outlay of $7,451,219.30. Return on
investment: four goals ($1,862,804.80 each), 23 points ($323,966.05
each). ``I'm not sure if you'll see us too active in the free-agent
market in the future,'' Kings GM Dave Taylor said. ``You won't see
us enter into a four- or five-year contract and pay big dollars for
a player in their 30s anymore.'' Let's see if Taylor sticks with
that promise when Colorado's Theo Fleury becomes a free agent after
the season. ... Duchesne took a parting shot at Kings coach Larry
Robinson, whom the defenseman thinks tried to change his style of
play: ``I'm an offensive player. I've never been a very physical
player, but I try to stay in the way. It's great to have somebody
who knows exactly what type of player I am.''
</P>
<P>
   Etc.
</P>
<P>
   Chelios, who signed a two-year, $11 million deal with Detroit,
said he did not force the Black Hawks' hand. But when he demanded a
contract extension, he, in effect, forced Chicago to make a move.
GM Bob Murray could not justify a team missing the playoffs two
years in a row and giving a player, even Chelios, at least another
$3.7 million for one year. ... The 2000 second-round pick San Jose
gave up for Montreal's Vincent Damphousse escalates to a
first-rounder if the forward re-signs with the Sharks as a free
agent. ``For the price we paid, it's a good risk,'' Sharks GM Dean
Lombardi said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
