<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-27 14:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6449 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DOWD-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      03-27 0739
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOWD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: BROKEN BONES 
</HEADLINE>
  
refiling to fix coding (nk) 
 By MAUREEN DOWD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   My father shot a man to death once.
</P>
<P>
   He and another police detective were sitting in the dark in the
middle of the night, staking out a drugstore in downtown
Washington. They had been tipped off that there was going to be a
robbery.
</P>
<P>
   When the two policemen surprised the thief, he pulled a gun and
shot at them. My father shot back, aiming to wound but killing
instead.
</P>
<P>
   Like many tough Irish guys, my father scoffed at psychiatrists.
But he saw one then. It was hard for him to believe he'd taken a
life, even though he was in a life-and-death business. He spent
three months at home. He couldn't sleep. He had trouble swallowing.
``I feel,'' he told my mother, ``like my throat is full of broken
bones.''
</P>
<P>
   As a reporter, I always avoided police brutality stories. It was
not that I did not believe that police could abuse power in
sinister ways. It was just that I preferred not to dwell on it.
</P>
<P>
   But Mayor Giuliani is forcing me to dwell on it.
</P>
<P>
   I went to Police Headquarters last week to see the
demonstrations for justice in the death of Amadou Diallo, an
unarmed African immigrant who was ripped apart by a sheet of
bullets after four police officers mistakenly thought the peddler
with the broken English and a stutter might possibly maybe resemble
a rapist they were looking for, and might possibly maybe be
reaching for a gun.
</P>
<P>
   The Diallo demonstrations grew after Police Commissioner Howard
Safir, whose force is facing cascading investigations, took a
junket to the Oscars on a Revlon plane. They grew even after it was
reported Thursday that the four officers had been indicted by a
Bronx grand jury on second-degree murder charges.
</P>
<P>
   It would be easy to poke fun at the radical chic air of the
demonstrations. The arrests, with veteran activists walking
jauntily in to be booked by elaborately polite officers, could have
been scripted by Tom Wolfe. Wednesday was Rabbi and Labor day.
Thursday was Susan Sarandon day. Friday was Jesse Jackson day.
</P>
<P>
   People mingled in front of the State Supreme Court Building as
if they were at a cocktail party in a New Yorker cartoon. ``Hi, are
you getting arrested?'' a woman asked a man.
</P>
<P>
   A woman with a clipboard organized protesters from the City
University of New York. ``Is there anyone who hasn't been arrested
before?'' she called out chirpily.
</P>
<P>
   Young women, with the brio of Lakers cheerleaders, sang out,
``Hey, hey! Ho, ho! Giuliani's got to go!''
</P>
<P>
   Dick Gottfried, a Democratic state assemblyman from the Upper
West Side, boasted to Pete Grannis, a Democratic assemblyman from
the Upper East Side, ``My previous arrests were South Africa and
Soviet Jewry.'' Grannis tried to top him, murmuring that he'd been
``in Mississippi.''
</P>
<P>
   And then there is Al Sharpton, who organized the protests with
all those bobbing signs depicting the mayor with a little Hitler
mustache. It is so easy to dismiss the man who, in Tawana Brawley,
perpetrated one of the most damaging frauds in New York history.
</P>
<P>
   But just because the protests smacked of radical chic, and just
because the protesters didn't seem to have a precise goal in mind,
doesn't mean they were not important and right.
</P>
<P>
   It is one of those moments where you see the ugly worms crawling
under the gleaming rock. It is a moment for white, middle-class New
Yorkers to acknowledge that those who are not white or well off are
paying too high a price for the safer, shinier city that Giuliani
has given us.
</P>
<P>
   When something disgraceful happened to an innocent man, the
mayor's reaction was grudging, defensive and totally lacking in
human kindness. Instead of standing tall for the police, he should
have gotten on his knees and begged forgiveness from the Diallo
family.
</P>
<P>
   It is time for the mayor to acknowledge that sometimes there is
something even more important than how the police are feeling. He
has finally said the right things in this case. But it is time for
him to stop bristling and denying at every criticism, to see he has
more than a P.R. problem when nearly all the major black officials
in the city, and many white leaders, are willing to get arrested to
protest his Police Department.
</P>
<P>
   The only question about Rudolph Giuliani right now is whether he
can transcend himself, whether he feels broken bones in his throat.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-27-99 1421EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
