<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-27 14:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6450 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-FEATURE28-COX     03-27 0617
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-FEATURE28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    As others trade, Stars stand pat
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The second-most famous team headquartered in the
Dallas suburb of Valley Ranch had a relatively quiet week. The
belief was that a hockey team already carrying the name ``Stars''
on their jerseys didn't need another one.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been watching this team to see if what happened would
match our projections,'' general manager Bob Gainey said. ``There
have been some challenging times. But we've done quite well. That
kind of information allows you to go on and make your decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   In the days leading up to Tuesday's NHL trading deadline, the
decisions for Gainey were relatively easy. He would not trade
goalie Roman Turek, even if it increased the chances that the Stars
would have to expose the young backup or starter Ed Belfour in the
Thrashers' expansion draft. Gainey also decided he would not
significantly tamper with a roster that had built the league's best
record, despite a slight need for a defenseman and a speedy winger.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars made two minor acquisitions, picking up center Derek
Plante from Buffalo and re-acquiring Benoit Hogue from
payroll-trimming Tampa Bay. But for all intents and purposes, the
team that would make another run for the Stanley Cup was completed
last July, when owner Tom Hicks signed free agent Brett Hull.
Dallas had recorded the league's best record, 49-22-11, last
season. But after losing to Detroit in the Western Conference
finals four games to two and being shut out twice in the process,
the Stars' thinking was that Hull could make the difference.
</P>
<P>
   This will be the third year in a row that Dallas will set a
franchise record for points. But if the Stars fall short again,
Gainey is sure to get heat for not doing more. Detroit made four
high-profile deals, landing Chris Chelios and Wendel Clark.
Colorado acquired Dale Hunter, after getting Theo Fleury earlier.
Philadelphia, desperate for a spark, is renting Mark Recchi and
Steve Duchesne for the rest of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas had several offers for Turek. Tampa Bay offered four
players. Clark was on the block.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were never close to a deal,'' Gainey said. ``One of the
things teams try to do with trades is garner depth. Roman provides
that depth for us at the position that can be the linchpin of our
success in the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   Gainey still might trade one of the two goalies after the season
and before the June 25 expansion draft. He also might attempt to
work a deal with the Thrashers that would keep both in Dallas. What
he wasn't going to do was mess with the biggest advantage the Stars
have in the upcoming playoffs: goaltending. Entering the weekend,
Dallas had scored the second-most goals in the league to Detroit _
210 to 205 _ but had allowed 42 fewer than the Red Wings and had
the league's best goals-against average, 1.98.
</P>
<P>
   Further, despite the belief that Hull was forced on Gainey and
coach Ken Hitchcock by Hicks and concerns that the star would cause
problems with team chemistry, neither has happened. Hull is second
on the Stars in goals (28) and points (50), despite missing 21
games with injuries. Dallas has such a huge lead in the overall
point standings that Hitchcock will be able to rest some regulars
in the next few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think our team is a little better than we were last year,
but Detroit is better now, and so are some other teams,'' Gainey
said. ``We still have to beat the best teams to prove ourself.''
</P>
<P>
   He stopped short of saying the Stars have to win it. But if they
don't, he'll hear about it.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
