<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHL-EASTNOTES28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    No deals for Carolina, Florida
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Given that a playoff spot and the title of the weak
Southeastern Division is at stake, it was surprising that neither
Carolina nor Florida made a significant move before the trading
deadline. The Hurricanes, who have been in first place since Oct.
28, despite struggling in recent weeks, sought defensive help and
made pitches for Chicago's Chris Chelios (offering four players)
and L.A.'s Steve Duchesne, but GM Jim Rutherford backed off when
the asking prices were deemed to high. Referring to the Blackhawks'
move in getting two first-round picks from Detroit for Chelios,
Rutherford said, ``What they got for him pretty much answers any
questions about our position.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Hurricanes' decision to remain pat could be rationalized,
Florida's couldn't. The Panthers were expected to overtake Carolina
after trading for Pavel Bure. But Bure has missed several games
with injuries, and Florida hasn't been significantly better with
him (5-4-2) than without him (6-7-4), going into the weekend.
Playing nine of their last 13 at home, the Panthers opened that
stretch Wednesday with a 2-1 loss to the New York Rangers. The
atmosphere in the National Car Rental Center was so dead, goalie
Sean Burke said, ``Sometimes being at home isn't as big a deal as
you might think.'' New blood was needed to shake up the team and
the town.
</P>
<P>
   Open market
</P>
<P>
   Detroit made the highest profile moves, but no team was busier
prior to the trade deadline than Tampa Bay. GM-coach Jacques
Demers, on a mission to slash the budget by $8 million, made six
deals that included jettisoning Bill Ranford ($3.087 million),
Wendel Clark ($1.4 million) and Benoit Hogue ($1.2 million). The
hack-and-slash summary: Demers traded seven players, a sixth-round
pick and other conditional picks for only three players,
conditional picks and ``future considerations.'' He dumped
approximately $6 million in salary. The kick is that Demers said
after the deals there is now ``stability'' in the organization and
maintained the Lightning has ``a bright future.'' The following
night, Tampa lost to Nashville, and Demers berated his players.
Captain Cooked
</P>
<P>
   When the Canadiens dealt Vincent Damphousse to San Jose, that
made five captains in a row the team has traded. Previous
sacrifices: Guy Carbonneau, Mike Keane, Kirk Muller and Pierre
Turgeon. The next victim? Nobody knows. A team spokesman said the
team captain might vary from game to game for the remainder of the
season. That was a collective sigh you heard in the locker room.
</P>
<P>
   Etc.
</P>
<P>
   The NHL still favors Mario Lemieux's plan to purchase the
bankrupt Penguins. But Lemieux is seeking many of the same
financial concessions from the Civic Arena and local governments
that majority owner Roger Marino sought. ... Washington GM George
McPhee will draw high marks from players for fulfilling veteran
Dale Hunter's wish to be traded to a Stanley Cup contender
(Colorado, for a No. 2 pick). ``Right now I'm thrilled for him,''
McPhee said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
