<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-27 14:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6452 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-NHL-NOTES28-COX     03-27 0714
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHL-NOTES28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GM's inquire about possible deals
 &HT;    By Jeff Schutlz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ General manager Don Waddell can't make any trades yet,
but that didn't stop about 10 of the league's GMs from contacting
him before the trading deadline about committing to possible deals.
``They would ask me things like, `If we pick up this player for the
rest of the year, is he somebody you might be interested in during
the expansion draft?' '' Waddell said. ``But I'm not interested in
making any deals now. It's not in our best interest. What if I
told, say, Florida, that there's a certain guy we wanted, and then
they went out and made a trade for a goalie that we wanted
instead?'' From the Thrashers' standpoint, the most interesting
aspect of the predeadline deals involved backup goaltenders the
team is looking to pluck in the expansion draft _ particularly
Dallas' Roman Turek and Detroit's Norm Maracle. But Waddell said,
``We understand some deals can still be be made before the draft.''
The expansion draft is June 25. ... Eight months ago, team
officials were on the record about having sold out of the two
top-priced tickets ($70 and $65) and nearly sold out of the next
two levels ($55 and $50). Suddenly, the Thrashers aren't divulging
any details about season tickets, other than to say total sales
have exceeded the NHL mandate of 12,000. Why the sudden secrecy?
Because of sluggish sales of club seats at the new arena, the
Thrashers are trying to convert season-ticket holders to a section
with essentially the same view but with waitress service. Any
converts would open up a ticket slot at their current level. Turner
Sports, which owns the Thrashers and Hawks, has been running
several radio ads for club seats of late. ... How much interest is
there in center Patrik Stefan of the IHL's Long Beach Ice Dogs?
When the potential No. 1 pick in the draft played a game in
Kalamazoo, Mich., the other night, 43 scouts representing 20 NHL
teams attended.
</P>
<P>
   DECADE SCORECARD
</P>
