<P>
   TWO MINUTES: RON TUGNUTT
</P>
<P>
   Team, position: Ottawa, goalie.
</P>
<P>
   Update: Leads the NHL in goals-against average (1.72) and is
second in saves percentage (.930) and winning percentage (.662,
20-9-5).
</P>
<P>
   On success after struggles with Quebec, Edmonton and Montreal:
``Quebec gave me a chance to play. Unfortunately, they were going
through a rebuilding process. The Senators had already rebuilt by
the time I got here. I'm just in the right place at the right
time.''
</P>
<P>
   On key to turnaround: ``I have to credit (former Washington GM)
David Poile, who suggested I needed to go to the minors (with
Portland in 1995) to get some games under me and learn how to win
again. I figured I'd give it one year and if it didn't work out,
I'd move on and play in Europe. Fortunately, it worked out.''
</P>
<P>
   On Ottawa's decision to rotate him and Damian Rhodes in goal:
``We understand the situation here is unique, but it seems to be
working, and you don't want to rock the boat. We have two goalies
fresh every game. The thing is, neither one of us (has) a big
ego.''
</P>
<P>
   On his relationship with Rhodes (a potential expansion pick of
the Thrashers): ``We don't talk about a lot of things other than
hockey and golf. They're the only two things we have in common. We
get along, but we don't exactly go out to dinner. It's kind of a
strange relationship.''
</P>
