<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990327.0107 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-27 14:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6454 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDUC-TV-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      03-27 1131
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDUC-TV-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNCLE SAM IN TELEVISIONLAND: LESSONS NOT QUITE READY FOR PRIME
TIME 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 (bl)  
 By JAMES STERNGOLD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ If some adults doubt how difficult it is to
deliver educational messages to children through television, they
should have attended a recent conference here on creating positive
programming. Some children, ages 11 to 14, were asked if they
watched Jerry Springer. They all said yes. Asked if the show was
staged, these young viewers, wise to the ways of manipulation, said
yes again, with several adding that the staging increased the
thrills.
</P>
<P>
   Children have never been more cynical about television, harder
to reach or as resistant to traditional programming than now, with
the proliferation of cable channels and the Internet. Yet this
comes at a time when the federal government has started an oddly
earnest experiment, a counterpoint to this age of deregulation,
requiring the networks to devote at least three hours a week to
educational programming. The rules specify the kinds of messages
that must be delivered and the age group at which they are aimed.
</P>
<P>
   The rules, passed by the Federal Communications Commission and
in effect for two seasons now, have created a quandary for network
executives, who are eager to comply but don't want to build, as one
executive said, a three-hour black hole in schedules that are
already being watched less and less by children whose taste for
irreverent humor, violence and other forms of entertainment has
made educational moralizing unappealing.
</P>
<P>
   The question is whether the cod-liver oil of educational
programming can compete with the french fries of pure
entertainment. Can Scholastic's ``The Magic School Bus'' on Fox
attract someone from Jerry Springer? So far, the answer seems to be
not yet.
</P>
<P>
   In terms of volume, the law has clearly met its goal. Federal
Communications Commission Chairman William Kennard, who
participated in the conference on positive programming held by the
the Academy of Television Arts and Sciences this month, said in an
interview that virtually all the stations in the country were in
compliance, some even offering four hours a week of educational
fare. The shows range from ``The Magic School Bus,'' an animated
program that teaches science to children 6 to 9 years old through
flights of fancy, to ``Hang Time,'' ``One World'' and ``Saved by
the Bell,'' dramas for teen-agers on NBC that frequently focus on
morals and relationships.
</P>
<P>
   But few children or teen-agers are actually tuning in, experts
say. According to Nielsen Media Research, the highest-rated
educational show, ``Hang Time,'' which airs at 10:30 Saturday
morning, is watched by only 2.8 percent of the households with
televisions this season. Popular cartoons and pure entertainment
shows frequently pull in almost twice that.
</P>
<P>
   Some argue that the shows' construction, which begins with the
curriculum and ends with the story, is antithetical to the creative
process. A compelling story, they say, should be paramount.
</P>
<P>
   This structural awkwardness was evident at an NBC seminar
recently held at a hotel here. Various experts taught writers of
the network's educational programs, which are aimed at teen-agers,
how to build in important lessons and still be creative.
</P>
<P>
   ``Keep thinking out of the box!'' exhorted Robin Schwartz, NBC's
executive in charge of the programs. Dr. Drew Pinsky, who offers
sexual advice on MTV's ``Loveline,'' added, ``To produce material
for teens, there cannot be a whiff of adult management of the
message. It has to be real.''
</P>
<P>
   But then Karen Hill-Scott, a child development expert and an
adult who manages the messages on every one of the NBC educational
programs, showed a series of pie charts on last season's shows with
precise statistics on their treatment of the ``socio-emotional
domain'' and ``the cognitive domain.'' In the future, she said, the
writers had to develop more programs around anti-drug and
anti-smoking messages, among other themes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've done everything but show the lungs of the kid who
smokes,'' said Peter Engel, the executive producer of the NBC
Saturday programs. ``It's very, very difficult to do these shows.
You've got to do them in informational and educational ways, but if
they're not entertaining, nothing happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Advocates of the programming say that, on the plus side, a new
market is emerging for material that enlightens. ``I do measure the
results of the law by the fact that there's a generation of
programming that wouldn't exist without it,'' said Jeff Chester,
executive director of the Center for Media Education, based in
Washington. ``At the very least, the programs are benign. They
aren't violent or exploitive.''
</P>
<P>
   Most experts agree it is impossible to measure whether the law's
real goal _ better educated children _ is being met, except in the
most general sense. ``This is like exercise,'' said Rep. Edward
Markey, D-Mass., one of the law's primary backers. ``We all know
you should exercise, and in the same way, kids should watch
educational television. I know it's not harmful, and I'm positive
it's helpful.''
</P>
<P>
   Many network executives say that if ``not harmful'' is the best
that can be expected, the money might be better spent elsewhere,
opening the television schedule to shows that more children might
actually view.
</P>
<P>
   ``We certainly wouldn't be doing this much without the law,''
said CBS senior vice president Martin Franks. ``The rule has been a
wonderful success in terms of quantity.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``It's a little harder to judge whether it's been a
success in terms of quality. Because there's so much of this on the
air, the government has made it harder for a show to break through
the clutter. I'm not sure that's a great public policy outcome. You
might argue that we'd be better off funding scholarships with that
money.''
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps the biggest criticism of the federal rules is the
claim that television is best suited to conveying lessons
informally rather than through pie charts or government mandates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't buy that the lessons have to be so formal,'' said
Meryl Marshall, chairman of the Academy of Television Arts and
Sciences and a speaker at the conference. ``What this seminar has
grown out of is a strong desire by the membership itself to be
conscious of what we want to convey. People's focus is not on
regulation, but it is on values.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-27-99 1432EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
