</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-BUDGET-FINAL-NYT </SLUG>
  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Editors: The following items from The N.Y. Times Week in Review
for Sunday, March 28, moved Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   _ On the dress page:
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-SERBS-REVIEW (Belgrade) _ Slobodan Milosevic rose to
power on the issue of the minority Serbs in Kosovo, the province
from which Serbs derive their defining myths of nationalism,
victimization and endurance. Kosovo is the Serbs' Jerusalem, the
holy touchstone and center of their existence as a nation despite
all the defeats and travails of history. It is so deeply ingrained
in Serbian mythology that the West seems to have miscalculated
Milosevic's ability to abandon the issue even if he wanted to. By
Steven Erlanger. (`i' category).
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-KLA-REVIEW (Undated) _ In trying to bring the Serbs to
heel, NATO has unwittingly married itself to the Kosovo Liberation
Army, which is widely seen as a terrorist group. Although the KLA's
atrocities are dwarfed by those of Serb leader Slobodan Milosevic,
the fact that it has emerged to speak for Kosovo's Albanians, and
the fact that NATO is bombing Serb targets in Kosovo, reveals a
great deal about the moral ambiguities facing outsiders who wade
into the Balkans. By Chris Hedges. (`i' category)
</P>
<P>
   NY-POLICE-PROTESTS-REVIEW (New York) _ The protests and arrests
at police headquarters have gotten much media coverage. Less
attention has been given to off-stage huddles between the
protesters' lawyers and police officials, often to discuss ground
rules. The police politely explained that to get arrested for
disorderly conduct, the demonstrators would have to block BOTH
entrances. In turn, the demonstrators promised not to resist
arrest. Organizers have even provided police with the names of
those planning to be arrested _ a thoughtful act designed to
expedite warrant checks and the release of the conscientious
scofflaws. By Dan Barry. (`a' category)
</P>
<P>
   _ Also moving in the `a' category
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-CONDUCT-REVIEW (Washington) _ If the candidates are to
be believed, the 2000 presidential campaign will be a high-toned,
polite affair. But while candidates sense that people are repulsed
by the vitriolic discourse in Washington _ and pollsters warn that
attacks can boomerang _ no one believes that the days of dirty,
dark politics are over. In this first post-impeachment campaign,
the trick will be to deploy attack strategies without seeming to do
so. By Richard L Berke.
</P>
<P>
   SLAVERY-BOOKS-REVIEW (Undated) _ Slavery ended in the 1860s, but
it is only the 1990s that historians and others are writing freely
about the brutality and violence of slavery _ taboo topics that
have silenced families, black and white, for centuries. A
proliferating number of popular and scholarly books about slavery
are stripping away what is left of the velvety romance of benign
slaveholders presiding over docile slaves. And they are emphasizing
the slaves' efforts to escape or rebel. By Doreen Carvajal.
</P>
<P>
   B52-REVIEW (Undated) _ The most remarkable aircraft taking part
in NATO's strikes at Serbia is also the oldest: the B-52.
Thirty-seven years after the last of them rolled off the production
line, the B-52 remains the workhorse of the Air Force, old and slow
but still able to deliver a terrific punch anywhere in the world.
And, incredibly, the last of the 76 B-52s still flying are not
expected to retire until 2044, when they will be 82 years old.
</P>
<P>
   CAR-THEFT-REVIEW (Detroit) _ The end of the Cold War has led to
an arms race between the people who make cars and the people who
steal them. It has changed the auto theft industry by opening up a
huge new market for stolen cars. Thieves supplying this business
have become more sophisticated; so have the counter-measures
designed by automakers to stop them. By Keith Bradsher.
</P>
<P>
   WOMEN'S-MAGS-REVIEW (Undated) _ Changes in Glamour, echoed in
other women's magazines, is part of a larger retreat _ not a
backlash of men against women but of women against feminism _ that
vexes feminist theorists and cheers conservatives. By virtue of the
articles they choose to publish, youthful women's magazines like
Cosmopolitan and Glamour seem to argue that their reader doesn't
want or need feminism; that she doesn't care much about Washington
or affirmative action, and that she isn't angry about being cheated
out of day care. By Alex Kuczynski.
</P>
<P>
   EDUC-TV-REVIEW (Los Angeles) _ The federal government has
started an oddly earnest experiment, a counterpoint to this age of
deregulation, requiring TV networks to devote at least three hours
a week to educational programming. The rules have created a
quandary for network executives, who want to comply but don't want
to build a three-hour black hole in schedules that are already
being watched less and less by children whose taste for irreverent
humor, violence and other forms of entertainment has made
educational moralizing unappealing. By James Sterngold.
</P>
<P>
   PIZZA-CRISIS-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``When Washington is in crisis,
pizza sales soar,'' says Frank Meeks, owner of 59 Domino's Pizza
stores in the D.C. area. When the Lewinsky scandal broke, the White
House was ordering an unrivaled 900 pizzas a day. The Capitol set
its record _ 1,500 pies _ on Impeachment Saturday. As the bombing
of Serbia began, the Pentagon set its record: over 800 pies. By
Hubert Herring.
</P>
<P>
   SHAKESPEARE-HEADLINES-TEXT-REVIEW (Undated) _ How have the media
been recycling the Bard-isms in the midst of Shakespeare's
pop-culture renaissance? Let us count the ways, with selected
newspaper headlines, starting with last week's Oscar awards, at
which `Shakespeare in Love' won Best Picture.
</P>
<P>
   ARCHITECT-TEXT-REVIEW (Undated) _ Stephen Kliment, former editor
of Architectural Record, says he often can't figure out what
today's architects and other high-concept designers are talking
about. In his book `Writing for Design Professionals,' he pleads
for clarity in proposals, letters, brochures and articles.
</P>
<P>
   THISWEEK-REVIEW (Undated) _ A look at the Oscars and some other
highlights of the week.
</P>
<P>
   _ Also moving in the `i' category:
</P>
<P>
   OPEC-WHY-REVIEW (Vienna) _ OPEC and its oil embargoes had
considerable impact in the 1970s because a measure of anti-American
sentiment could be counted on. But in the '80s and '90s, divisions
among the Mideast oil producers (and alliances with the U.S. after
Iraq's invasion of Kuwait) became more important, even as new
non-OPEC oil production began in Alaska and the North Sea. Now a
new political factor has taken hold, uniting OPEC's members as
never before and overcoming much of their rivalries: the cost to
their countries of low oil prices. By Youssef Ibrahim.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; QUESTIONS OR RERUNS: (888) 346-9867 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PHOTOS AND GRAPHICS: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Phone: (888) 603-1036
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TECHNICAL PROBLEMS: &LR;  Peter Trigg
</P>
<P>
   Phone: (212) 499-3332.
</P>
