<DOCNO> NYT19990327.0113 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-27 14:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6459 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NUCLEAR28-COX     03-27 0735
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NUCLEAR28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By Dale Dempsey
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _This year the Pennsylvania power company AmerGen
purchased the nuclear reactor at Three Mile Island, which prompted,
well, some strange reactions.
</P>
<P>
   ``People say, 'You bought what?' '' said Ralph DeSantis of
AmerGen. ``We get that a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   AmerGen's investment in Three Mile Island, which only a few
years ago would have seemed as likely as buying up steam threshers,
is one of several signs that the nuclear power industry seeks to
make a comeback.
</P>
<P>
   Three Mile Island, which 20 years ago was the scene of the
nation's worst nuclear reactor accident, stopped the nuclear
industry cold in the United States. The disaster in Chernobyl in
the Ukraine underscored the trend.
</P>
<P>
   Since the partial meltdown of reactor No. 2 at Three Mile Island
on March 28, 1979, there have been no new nuclear plants planned or
built in the U.S. Many plants under construction at the time,
including the Zimmer power plant near Cincinnati in 1982, were
converted to coal.
</P>
<P>
   AmerGen is buying reactor No. 1 at TMI, which DeSantis points
out has continued to operate without incident for two decades.
</P>
<P>
   One of the reasons that nuclear power, long one of the favorite
targets of environmental groups, could see a resurgence is,
ironically, the environment.
</P>
<P>
   Industry officials point out that the United States cannot meet
the stringent clean air goals outlined in the Kyoto Agreement
without nuclear power, which does not emit the so-called
``greenhouse gases'' of traditional coal-powered plants.
</P>
<P>
   John Kane, vice president of the Nuclear Energy Institute, an
industry lobbying group, said nuclear energy will be the ``nation's
workhorse in helping to achieve air-quality goals.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration has included about $17 billion in the
most recent budget.
</P>
<P>
   Department of Energy Secretary Bill Richardson, in Miamisburg,
Ohio, last week, said that nuclear energy ``has a place'' in the
country's power picture.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government is moving toward an answer to one of the
major problems associated with nuclear plants, disposal of high
radiation spent fuel. Congress is considering a bill to have the
government take possession of all the old nuclear waste, now stored
in various spots around the country, and disposing of it at its
deep mountain burial site in Nevada.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has the 104 nuclear power plants, more than
any other country, but they supply less than 20 percent of the
country's electricity. France, with just 59 reactors, gets 78
percent of its power from nuclear plants.
</P>
<P>
   Industry officials say that safety in U.S. nuclear plants has
improved since Three Mile Island, which dramatically displayed
deficiencies in operator training and warning instruments.
</P>
<P>
   The Institute for Nuclear Power Operations, established by the
industry after TMI, reports that the number of ``significant
events'' or potential shutdowns at nuclear plants fell from a high
of 2.38 per unit in 1985 to just 0.10 per unit in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``The data prove it _ nuclear plants are safer and more reliable
than ever,'' said Joe Colvin, president of the Nuclear Energy
Institute.
</P>
<P>
   Others are not so sure the industry's safety record has
improved.
</P>
<P>
   A study of the industry by the Union of Concerned Scientists
found that five plants were shut down for more than a year to fix
safety problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``Apparently the industry and the Nuclear Regulatory Commission
have forgotten about Three Mile Island,'' said David Lochbaum of
the scientist group.
</P>
<P>
   The Union of Concerned Scientists recommend that the industry:
</P>
<P>
   _ Develop risk studies based on all information
</P>
<P>
   _ Respond more quickly to warning signs
</P>
<P>
   _ Communicate more openly with the public on safety matters
</P>
<P>
   Another concern is the aging of current nuclear plants.
</P>
<P>
   There have been 27 reactors closed after operating for an
average lifetime of 15 years, according the Safe Energy
Communication Council in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   The council reported that a national opinion survey found six
out of 10 voters opposed building new nuclear reactors.
</P>
<P>
   Anti-nuke groups may not be the only obstacle facing the
industry. Utility deregulation and low prices for oil and natural
gas may end up making nuclear power too expensive to compete.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
