<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TMI28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Remembering TMI two decades after the accident
 &HT;    By Dale Dempsey
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ In a matter of eight seconds in the predawn hours
of Wednesday, March 29, 1979, the nuclear power plant at Three Mile
Island in Pennsylvania went from normal operation to the brink of a
catastrophe.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty years later there is still intense debate over the health
and environmental impact of the United States' worst nuclear
accident. The accident, in which the plant's radioactive fuel rods
were exposed and more than one third melted, effectively halted the
growth of nuclear power in this country.
</P>
<P>
   While 104 existing plants continue to operate, there have been
no new plants built since 1979. And many plants under construction
at the time, including the Zimmer plant partially owned by Dayton
Power &AMP; Light, were converted to coal.
</P>
<P>
   However, things could be changing.
</P>
<P>
   With coal-fired plants under fire for not meeting strict federal
clean air standards, the nuclear power industry is showing signs of
being reborn. Some industry and government representatives believe
the nation cannot meet air standards to curb global warming without
nuclear power in the mix. In fact, TMI 1 _ not the unit involved in
the accident _ was recently sold to a Pennsylvania power company.
TMI 1 has operated without incident since shortly after the
accident.
</P>
<P>
   Nuclear power plants emit none of the so-called ``greenhouse
gases'' that spew from coal plants, but nuclear plants still
haven't successfully solved the problem of nuclear power, most
importantly disposing of the used, spent nuclear waste. The shadow
of Three Mile Island, and the even longer shadow of the accident at
Russia's Chernobyl plant, still hover over the industry. While
industry and government regulatory agencies like the Department of
Energy and the Nuclear Regulatory Commission downplay the damage
done at Three Mile Island, outside Harrisburg, Pa., there are some
researchers who think the health effects of the accident were much
worse.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty years is time enough for some hard-to-detect cancers to
start showing up. Researcher Steve Wing, an epidemiologist at the
University of North Carolina, thinks he sees statistical
indications that cancer deaths have increased in the areas downwind
from Three Mile Island.
</P>
<P>
   But to understand the issues, first it is necessary to revisit
what happened on Wednesday, March 28, 1979, and the investigations
that followed.
</P>
<P>
   At 4 a.m. on Day 1 of the accident, a pump supplying water to
TMI-2's steam generator stopped operating. Water serves two
purposes in a nuclear plant like the one designed by Babcock &AMP;
Wilcox at Three Mile Island: It supplies steam to the plant's
electric generator and cools off some of the intense heat produced
by the reactor.
</P>
<P>
   The plant's safety system shut down the steam generator. As the
reactor's coolant water temperature increased, a valve on top of a
containment tank opened as it was supposed to, releasing some of
the pressure. The valve was supposed to close 13 seconds later, but
in the first of a series of instrument failures and poor
communication between plant operators, it remained open for nearly
three hours.
</P>
<P>
   Operators in the control room believed the valve was shut and
did not pump needed coolant water into the reactor. A ``loss of
coolant accident'' was in progress. Eventually, nearly one-third of
the plant's coolant water escaped through the valve.
</P>
<P>
   At about 6 a.m. some of the casings around the reactor's fuel
rods ruptured, partially uncovering the rods and sending
radioactive gas into the coolant water. Eventually, one-third of
the rods would melt down. The reaction also produced a bubble of
hydrogen in the containment building, which produced great concern
of an explosion for several days after the accident.
</P>
<P>
   As radiation detection alarms went off all over the plant, the
incident was declared a general emergency at 7:20 a.m. Radiation
was released to the containment building and to the environment.
Estimates of how much radiation escaped into the air outside the
plant vary. Industry and government sources found that radiation
levels outside remained low throughout the accident. Critics
believe the releases could have been much higher downwind of the
plant.
</P>
<P>
   WKBO, a radio station in Harrisburg, reported the story of TMI-2
at 8:25 a.m. Miscommunication added to the crisis. While officials
were aware of low-level releases to the environment, public
relations people from Metropolitan Edison, the plant owner, were
telling reporters there had been no release. The report added to an
atmosphere of mistrust. Pennsylvania Gov. William Scranton, who in
the next three days would weigh whether to evacuate 600,000 people,
was also not quickly informed of the release.
</P>
<P>
   On Day 2 of the accident, some children under 2 and pregnant
women were told to leave the area downwind of the plant.
</P>
<P>
   On the afternoon of Day 2, radiation levels measuring 3,000
millirems per hour were recorded above the plant. (An average
X-ray, by comparison, measures 10 millirems.) Also, Met Ed released
water from showers, toilets and laundry facilities into the
Susquehanna River, some of it contaminated. Company officials did
not inform the reporters _ who by now numbered in the thousands _
of the release, adding to the level of mistrust.
</P>
<P>
   By early evening, Nuclear Regulatory Commission officials
received the results of an analysis that showed damage to the
reactor core was more substantial than anticipated. There was a
possibility of greater radiation releases.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Scranton eventually decided that no evacuation was needed,
but continued to advise pregnant women and preschool children to
stay more than five miles from the plant.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, March 31, Day 4 of the accident, concern about a
possible explosion of the hydrogen bubble reached its peak, but
officials later determined that not enough oxygen was being
generated to cause an explosion.
</P>
<P>
   After numerous operator mistakes and miscommunications, coolant
water was restored to the reactor core, bringing it under control.
Today, TMI-2 remains in cold, monitored storage while its sister
reactor continues to produce electricity.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, the worst nuclear accident in U.S. history has
been the subject of hundreds of studies, but some question their
validity.
</P>
<P>
   Industry officials concede that the accident was a result of
poor operator training and inadequate instruments _ faults they say
have since been addressed at the nation's nuclear plants.
</P>
<P>
   A class-action lawsuit by 2,000 people living downwind of Three
Mile Island was dismissed in 1996 in U.S. District Court, and is
currently being appealed. Judge Sylvia Rambo ruled that there was a
``paucity'' of evidence that the accident caused ill health
effects.
</P>
<P>
   University of North Carolina researcher Wing, at the request of
the litigants, re-examined data from a 1990 Columbia University
study that found no increased cancer rates after Three Mile Island.
</P>
<P>
   Writing in the January 1997 journal, Environmental Health
Perspectives , Wing found lung cancer incidence elevated 300-400
percent and leukemia rates up by 600-700 percent among those in the
direct path of the radiation plume released at Three Mile Island.
</P>
<P>
   The report touched off a lively debate on methodology and
statistics between the authors of the two major studies.
</P>
<P>
   Both Wing and the Columbia researchers, however, say further
health studies need to be done. The data used for both was
collected between 1981-85, too soon for some cancers to make an
appearance.
</P>
<P>
   Wing said the Columbia report errs in assuming too low an
exposure rate from the accident and not including enough cancers.
Industry officials say that more than a dozen health studies since
1979, including a Pennsylvania Health Department registry of 35,000
people living near the plant, show no ill effects.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think more attention needs to be paid to it,'' Wing said.
``I don't feel the book should be closed at all. There is something
to look for.''
</P>
<P>
   A 1991 book, Deadly Deceit by Dr. Jay M. Gould and Benjamin
Goldman, also claims that cancer and mortality rates in the areas
closest to Three Mile Island are higher than reported and suggest a
link to the accident.
</P>
<P>
   One of the strengths of Wing's study, he said, is that it looked
at rates both upwind and downwind of the accident, and the rates
downwind are higher.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what makes our re-analysis so interesting,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Wing said that in addition to collecting more health data, the
whole process of the nuclear regulatory agencies should be opened
up to encourage more community participation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would be the first to say that our study doesn't prove by
itself that there were high-level radiation exposures, but it is
part of a body of evidence that is consistent with high
exposures,'' Wing said. ``The cancer findings, along with studies
of animals, plants and chromosomal damage in Three Mile Island area
residents, all point to much higher radiation levels that
previously reported.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
