<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-FORCE-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON HAS GONE FROM A VOCAL DOVE TO A HESITANT HAWK 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ariz.) (See also: KOSOVO-RDP, KOSOVO-BELGRADE, KOSOVO-MILOSEVIC,
KOSOVO-RUSSIA, KOSOVO-CLINTON, KOSOVO-TURKEY) 
(rk) 
 By JOHN M. BRODER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Bill Clinton is a politician to his core, a man of
persuasion, not intimidation. He has always been ambivalent about
the use of force to accomplish his purposes, an ambivalence that
mirrors his still uneasy relationship with the American military.
</P>
<P>
   And when he is forced by events _ or by his own threats _ to use
American military might, as he did this week in Yugoslavia, he does
so only reluctantly, and tentatively. He sets limited ends and
applies limited means, doing everything he can to minimize the risk
to American military personnel.
</P>
<P>
   He uses stand-off weapons in remote-control combat, keeping
pilots tens of thousands of feet above their targets and missileers
hundreds of miles away from theirs.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton adopted this low-risk, high-technology approach to
warfare after President Bush's last military foray became his first
_ the dispatch of soldiers on a humanitarian mission to Somalia _
and ended in humiliation and bloodshed. The other times Clinton
deployed large numbers of ground troops, in Haiti and in Bosnia,
came only after he received assurances they would not engage in
combat.
</P>
<P>
   The history of the Clinton administration's use of power surely
reflects the evolution of military technology, but the thinking of
the commander in chief is an even stronger factor.
</P>
<P>
   Since entering office, Clinton has employed force or the threat
of force as a tool of foreign policy a dozen times. But he has
never articulated what could be called a ``Clinton Doctrine'' that
guides his foreign policy or that informs his decisions to use
force.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, reflecting the range of problems he is addressing,
Clinton has drawn on a dozen different rationales for using power
in the pursuit of peace. Critics say the wide-ranging aims amount
to no aims at all; the Clinton Doctrine, they say, is expediency
and an ingrained aversion to conflict.
</P>
<P>
   The closest the president has come to formulating a foreign
policy doctrine was in his first inaugural address, at a time when
he was criticizing Bush's reluctance to use force to halt the
ethnic slaughter in Bosnia and was promising a more muscular
approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``When our vital interests are challenged, or the will and
conscience of the international community is defied,'' the newly
elected Clinton said on Jan. 20, 1993, ``we will act _ with
peaceful diplomacy whenever possible, with force when necessary.''
</P>
<P>
   His words were a conscious echo of President Kennedy's vow in
his 1961 inaugural address to ``pay any price, bear any burden'' to
ensure the survival of liberty.
</P>
<P>
   But time and the tides of history have tempered Clinton's
resolution. He did not act with force in Bosnia until 30 months
later, after tens of thousands more civilians died, in part because
the Europeans were unwilling to intervene in the charnel of their
own backyard.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, 18 dead Army Rangers in Somalia in 1993 and Saddam
Hussein's continued defiance in Iraq have left the president
chastened.
</P>
<P>
   This week, in what could be heard as more apology than
explanation for his dispatch of American planes and missiles to
Yugoslavia, Clinton said somberly, in a speech to a federal
employees union: ``Now, I think if the American people don't know
anything else about me, they know that I don't like to use military
force, and I do everything I can to avoid it. But if we have to do
it, then that's part of the job, and I will do it.''
</P>
<P>
   And he has. The president launched cruise missile attacks on
Sudan and Afghanistan to punish suspected terrorists; he acted in
Bosnia and Kosovo to deter a dictator and stop genocide; he ordered
an invasion of Haiti to restore an elected leader to power; he
bombed Iraq numerous times to compel compliance with U.N. mandates
or in retaliation for suspected terrorist acts. In some cases, as
in the Balkans, the reasons included preventing wider war and
stemming the flow of refugees.
</P>
<P>
   While this may appear a grab bag of rationales, Sandy Berger,
the president's national security adviser, said in an interview on
Friday that they represent a consistent set devised over the last
six years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question we have confronted is whether military force can
be an instrument of American national interest in situations short
of all-out war,'' Berger said. ``The president has rejected the
idea that the choices in Kosovo are invading Serbia or watching the
Kosovars get slaughtered.''
</P>
<P>
   The president was willing to order U.S. forces into limited
action in this instance and in others, Berger said, after he was
satisfied that the national interest was at stake, that the mission
was achievable at an acceptable cost, that the goals are clear and
that all peaceful means have been exhausted.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he said, Clinton agonizes over these decisions and acts
only when the consequences of inaction are ``truly catastrophic.''
</P>
<P>
   The administration's restrained criteria for the use of force
replaced an earlier foreign policy formulation _ ``assertive
multilateralism'' _ that harnessed American decision making to that
of the United Nations and other international bodies.
</P>
<P>
   That approach had been ridiculed as wishy-washy and unbecoming
to the globe's sole superpower, and critics said Clinton would be
sacrificing American sovereignty to the bureaucrats and
blue-helmeted peacekeepers of the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the roots of Clinton's martial reticence lie in his
personal history, some in his tenuous political position and some
in the inherent instability in the world that he inherited in the
dust of the Cold War.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
