<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-27 14:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6463 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-FORCE-2TAKES-N     03-27 0887
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-FORCE-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
  
 WASHINGTON: Cold War.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Clinton says his instincts as a conciliator stem from his youth,
when he was forced to intercede to stop his alcoholic stepfather
from abusing his mother. He has said he wants to be remembered as
the ``repairer of the breach'' described in the book of Isaiah.
</P>
<P>
   As a young man, a bearded Bill Clinton avoided the draft and
organized protests against the Vietnam War. He wrote the commander
of his home-state ROTC unit that he loved his country but
``loathed'' the military.
</P>
<P>
   He further alienated the armed forces when, shortly after taking
office, he moved to end discrimination against gay people in the
military. He was rescued by a face-saving compromise engineered by
the chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, Gen. Colin Powell, but
lasting damage was done. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., a former Naval aviator and
prisoner-of-war in Vietnam, said that the mutual suspicion between
Clinton and the military has abated somewhat, ``but there's still
not a great deal of respect for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Military personnel are particularly galled by the apparent
double standard applied to sexual misconduct in the White House and
in the armed forces, McCain said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't like it,'' McCain said, ``but it doesn't affect
their day-to-day work.''
</P>
<P>
   Although White House aides emphatically deny it, the friction
with the Pentagon has in some ways shaped Clinton's deliberations
on the use of force and the way he has applied it.
</P>
<P>
   Particularly after the episode in Somalia, when the humanitarian
relief mission deteriorated into a firefight with armed bandits in
Mogadishu, Clinton has been reluctant of sending ground forces into
a hostile environment.
</P>
<P>
   He was prepared to dispatch 15,000 troops to Haiti to restore
President Jean-Bertrand Aristide to power forcibly, but the planned
invasion became a bloodless occupation after a last-minute deal was
brokered by Powell and former President Carter.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, his military operations have involved
high-technology, relatively risk-free strikes from afar. Since last
August, Clinton has rained ordnance on Sudan, Afghanistan, Iraq
and, now, Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   American peacekeepers remain in Bosnia, but they did not arrive
until the parties agreed to lay down their arms in 1995 and no
American serviceman or woman has been killed in combat there.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the beginning of 1993, Clinton was very affected by the
view that Americans don't care about foreign affairs,'' said
Michael Beschloss, a historian in Washington. ``He has been more
quiet about foreign policy than any president since Hoover, and
that makes it tougher when he needs to use force.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't talk to the American people about Haiti until 72
hours before the invasion was to begin,'' Beschloss said. ``It was
the same thing here. We haven't heard him talk about Kosovo
consistently, so when it happened the American people didn't
understand the frame of reference or the need to use force.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   One result has been public skepticism about the Balkan
operation. Polls show that Clinton's overall approval ratings have
remained high, but public support for his handling of foreign
policy has slipped since he ordered the airstrikes against Kosovo
and Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   Traditionally, presidential approval ratings benefit from a
``rally 'round the flag effect,'' a surge of public support that
typically accompanies foreign actions. For example, Clinton's
approval rating jumped 7 percentage points after the airstrike on
Baghdad in 1993, and rose by 9 percentage points after the
occupation of Haiti in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   But a CBS News poll, conducted after the president's speech to
the nation on Wednesday, showed a decline in support for his
handling of foreign affairs to 60 percent from 69 percent in
January. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nor can Clinton count on the unquestioning support of Congress
when he commits American forces to combat. When he ordered an
attack on Iraq last December just as the House was to vote on two
articles of impeachment against him, the Senate majority leader,
Trent Lott, and other leading Republicans openly questioned the
timing and Clinton's motives.
</P>
<P>
   That would have been shocking in an earlier day or under a
different president.
</P>
<P>
   It is that very climate that helps explain why Clinton chooses
to project power mostly from a safe distance. A major commitment of
ground forces _ with potentially large loss of life _ is difficult
to contemplate for a president who engenders such distrust, not
only among his adversaries, but among his allies as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clinton vacillates a lot,'' said a former senior military
officer who served at the National Security Council during
Clinton's first term, ``because of the political capital he doesn't
have and has never had.''
</P>
<P>
   In politics as in war, the side with the stronger army dictates
the terms of battle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Standard U.S. military doctrine says that you create the
conditions to force the battle to be fought on your terms,'' the
officer said, speaking on condition of anonymity. ``But Clinton has
never been good at dictating terms, either at home or abroad.
That's why there is no `Clinton Doctrine' as such. It's the
doctrine of the day, whatever you have to do right now to get by.''
</P>
</TEXT>
