<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-27 14:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6465 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-NFL-NOTES28-COX     03-27 0793
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFL-NOTES28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Redskins sale not a done deal
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   As NFL owners continue to scrutinize the heavily leveraged $800
million bid of Howard Milstein to purchase the Washington Redskins,
they are taking increasing note of the manner in which he has
operated the NHL's New York Islanders.
</P>
<P>
   It's clear they don't like what they have witnessed the past few
weeks. With the Isles doomed to a fifth consecutive season missing
the playoffs, the club has traded six players since March 9, paring
$6.45 million from the payroll. The result is a barely competitive
team that features six rookies and six other players with less than
100 games of NHL experience. General manager Mike Milbury recently
conceded the team ``doesn't have a plan'' for the future.
</P>
<P>
   No one should be surprised if Daniel Snyder, a partner to
Milstein and man viewed with more favor by the league, splits and
attempts to buy the Skins himself. The more likely scenario is that
the trustees for the estate of late owner Jack Kent Cooke put the
team back on the market and Phoenix businessman Sam Grossman lands
the franchise.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, an example of how awkward things are for current
Redskins management while the team's future is in limbo occurred at
Champ Bailey's workout in Athens last Wednesday. The session was
attended by current Redskins GM Charley Casserly and Vinny Cerrato,
the man who could replace him. Cerrato is former personnel director
with the 49ers and was hired as a consultant by Milstein to monitor
team activities.
</P>
<P>
   Helping hand
</P>
<P>
   Chris Chandler is taking an off-field role in improving the
Falcons' on-field outlook. The veteran quarterback reshuffled his
contract Friday, agreeing to take about $3 million of his $3.5
million salary for 1999 as a signing bonus. The nifty bit of
bookkeeping created more than $3 million in salary cap room for
Atlanta. It will enable the Falcons to sign guard Greg Bishop and
pursue more free agents. The team remains tempted by Cincinnati
free agent cornerback Ashley Ambrose.
</P>
<P>
   Go Ricky
</P>
<P>
   The most debated player in the draft continues to be Heisman
tailback Ricky Williams of Texas. New Orleans GM Billy Kuharich and
coach Mike Ditka last Tuesday raised their offer _ all six
selections in this year's draft and first- and third-round choices
in the 2000 draft _ for Williams. But the team most likely to
consider such a blockbuster swap, Indianapolis, suddenly is hot for
Williams as well. The Colts braintrust will attend the workouts of
only two players, Williams and Bailey. It now appears the Colts,
who own the No. 4 pick, feel that may be too high to take Southern
Cal linebacker Chris Claiborne, who had only an average workout
last week. The Colts granted agent Rocky Arceneaux permission to
seek a trade for incumbent tailback Marshall Faulk.
</P>
<P>
   Tip sheet
</P>
<P>
   Upset that league owners still have made no proposal to NFL
Coaches Association executive director Larry Kennan for improving
benefits, assistants for some teams want to escalate pressure.
Kennan, though, has calmed constituents and feels an offer will be
made at the May owners meetings in Atlanta. ... Florida linebacker
Jevon Kearse had a tremendous workout for scouts last week. At his
campus session, the 255-pounder clocked a 4.43 time in the 40 and
had a 40 1/2-inch vertical jump. ... Raiders owner Al Davis is
carrying a league-high $11 million in ``dead money,'' dollars that
count against the '99 salary cap for players no longer with the
team. ... Players whose draft stock is on the rise: C Damien Woody
(Boston College), OT Luke Pettigout (Notre Dame), DE Patrick Kerney
(Virginia), RB Shawn Bryson (Tennessee), OG Brandon Burlsworth
(Arkansas), SS Rich Coady (Texas A&AMP;M), LB Barry Gardner
(Northwestern), QB Shaun King (Tulane) and LB Mike Peterson
(Florida). ... If Ditka can't land Williams, he may attempt to deal
up a few spots and take UCLA quarterback Cade McNown.
</P>
<P>
   The remnants
</P>
<P>
   How one NFC personnel director rated the top players remaining
in the unrestricted free agent pool: LB Jamir Miller (Arizona),
Ambrose (Cincinnati), DE Derrick Alexander (Minnesota), OT Wayne
Gandy (St. Louis), CB Ryan McNeil (St. Louis), DT Jerry Ball
(Minnesota), LB Marvcus Patton (Washington), WR Sean Dawkins (New
Orleans), LB Anthony Davis (Kansas City) and QB Jeff George
(Oakland).
</P>
<P>
   The last word(s)
</P>
<P>
   San Diego rookie coach Mike Riley on how quarterback Ryan Leaf
will handle the addition of veteran Jim Harbaugh: ``It may be a
blow to him. There's still a bit of shell-shock from last year, but
I hope he'll realize this takes the microscope off him for a little
while.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
