<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-27 15:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6467 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-CLINTON-NYT &LR;      03-27 0537
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-CLINTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON SAYS NATO ALLIES NEED TO `STAY THE COURSE'
</HEADLINE>
   (See also: KOSOVO-RDP, KOSOVO-FORCE, KOSOVO-BELGRADE,
KOSOVO-MILOSEVIC, KOSOVO-RUSSIA, KOSOVO-TURKEY) 
(rk) 
 By   JOHN M. BRODER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As United States and NATO aircraft entered the
fourth day of strikes on Serbian targets, President Clinton said
Saturday that allied forces must ``stay the course'' to prevent the
war in Kosovo from spreading.
</P>
<P>
   In his weekly radio address, Clinton said that Serbian troops
have continued to attack civilians and burn villages in the
province of Kosovo, a region of Serbia with a large ethnic Albanian
population that seeks greater autonomy.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said the aim of the allied military operation is to halt
the repression in Kosovo and to keep the war from spreading.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must, and we will, continue until Serbia's leader, Slobodan
Milosevic, accepts peace or we have seriously damaged his capacity
to make war,'' Clinton said. Milosevic is the president of
Yugoslavia, of which Serbia is the major entity.
</P>
<P>
   As he did in an address to the nation Wednesday night announcing
the start of the air campaign, Clinton referred to the Balkans as a
``powder keg at the heart of Europe'' that has ignited wider war
before in this century.
</P>
<P>
   ``Americans have learned the hard way that our home is not that
far from Europe,'' the president said Saturday. ``Through two world
wars and a long Cold War, we saw that it was a short step from a
small brush fire to an inferno, especially in the tinderbox of the
Balkans. The time to put out a fire is before it spreads and burns
down the neighborhood.''
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslavia has been smoldering since it unraveled after the
collapse of communism in Eastern Europe. NATO and the United States
have intervened with force twice _ in Bosnia in 1995 and now in
Kosovo _ when the killing became intolerable and the Serbian
leadership refused to accept settlement terms dictated by the West.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said Saturday, as he has said several times this week,
that the United States acted now ``to prevent a wider war we would
have to confront later, only at far greater risk and cost.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that the American goal was a peaceful and united Europe,
but that achieving that end now requires the use of force.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes you have to fight in order to end the fighting,''
Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton praised the skill and courage of American forces engaged
in the conflict _ pilots, technicians, air traffic controllers and
mechanics. He said that all 19 members of NATO are contributing to
the effort, some with combat aircraft, others with bases, money or
support personnel.
</P>
<P>
   He noted that the ethnic Albanians of Kosovo had accepted a
peace agreement negotiated at Rambouillet, outside of Paris, two
weeks ago that would grant them autonomy but not independence.
Milosevic's refusal to sign the accord and his stepped-up campaign
of force in Kosovo were the triggers for this week's military
action.
</P>
<P>
   ``We asked these people of Kosovo to accept peace, and they
did,'' Clinton said. ``We promised them we would stick by them if
they did the right thing, and they did. We cannot let them down
now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-27-99 1505EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990327.0122 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-27 15:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6471 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-RUSSIA-2TAKES-     03-27 1260
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-RUSSIA-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AROUND THE U.S. EMBASSY IN MOSCOW, A NIP OF COLD WAR IS IN THE
AIR 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: KOSOVO-RDP, KOSOVO-FORCE, KOSOVO-BELGRADE,
KOSOVO-MILOSEVIC, KOSOVO-RUSSIA, KOSOVO-CLINTON, KOSOVO-TURKEY) 
(DW) 
 By CELESTINE BOHLEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Caught up in the belligerent hysteria that has filled
the sidewalks in front of the American Embassy here for the last
three days, Aleksei Yermakov could not have been happier.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look around, there are only young people,'' said Yermakov, a
40-year-old interpreter, grinning at the black-jacketed youths
shouting obscenities and throwing eggs, beer and paint at the
embassy's mustard yellow walls. ``Isn't it wonderful?''
</P>
<P>
   Yermakov came here on Wednesday night as NATO launched its first
bombs against Yugoslavia. By his account, things got off to a nasty
start.
</P>
<P>
   ``We climbed up on embassy cars, jumped on them, scratched
swastikas on them,'' he said gleefully. ``We went down to the gate
where the employees live. One came out to move his car. We
surrounded him, and he had to call for help.''
</P>
<P>
   Like many other protesters, Yermakov came to the U.S. Embassy to
show his support for the Serbs, seen here as Slavic Davids under
attack by an American Goliath. But those centuries-old sympathies
are only one reason for the sudden outbreak of a virulent
anti-American virus in Moscow last week.
</P>
<P>
   For many Russians, the issue was not so much the rediscovery of
an old Slavic brotherhood as the re-emergence of a familiar enemy:
Uncle Sam. If during the Cold War Soviet propaganda warned about
creeping American hegemony, today, as the American-led forces of
NATO launched wave after wave of missiles at Yugoslav targets, it
seemed to some here as though that hegemony had taken hold.
</P>
<P>
   Not only do many Russians see NATO's use of force as wrong,
misguided or criminal. They also view it as a reminder of their
powerlessness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Russia is a great country,'' said Yermakov, turning serious.
``The main thing is to respect ourselves. I look at the Serbs and I
am jealous. They have such faith in themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Andrei Manilov runs an ad hoc recruitment center for volunteers
signing up to fight for Serbia, set up under the auspices of the
political party headed by the ultranationalist Vladimir V.
Zhirinovsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``These men understand that today it's Serbia, tomorrow it could
be Russia,'' he said. ``NATO could decide to interfere anywhere _
in Chechnya, for example,'' he added, referring to the Russians'
own breakaway region in the Caucasus.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no hatred of the American people,'' chimed in a young
man, sitting at a table nearby, waiting to sign up volunteers. ``It
is the American government that wants to take over all of Europe.
They are bringing their own order to Yugoslavia by the use of
force.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want a government formed by Washington, and they are
doing it with military force,'' added the young man, who declined
to give his name. He was alluding to the leaders of Kosovo's ethnic
Albanian majority, who have signed a proposed peace accord for the
Serbian province.
</P>
<P>
   So far, said Manilov, about 350 people had signed up at the
Moscow volunteer center, where a row of military boots and other
gear were on display beneath a big television screen blaring the
latest news from Yugoslavia. He claimed that more than 10,000 had
signed up at recruitment centers around Russia, where they now
await visas to Yugoslavia and further orders.
</P>
<P>
   Andrei Gusev, 21, a disk jockey at a Moscow nightclub, came to
the center dressed in jeans and a camouflage jacket. ``What is
going on is out of control,'' he said. ``I don't understand how you
can bomb like this. It reminds me of Hitler. The Germans attacked
in the same way.''
</P>
<P>
   Such one-sided perceptions of the conflict are not so strange,
given the information about Kosovo available to the average
Russian, said a political analyst, Andrei Piontkovsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would join this hysteria too if I only watched Russian
television,'' he said. ``Then my perception would be of a small
Serbian nation attacked by an armada led by the most powerful
country in the world. Nobody here knows much about the atrocities
against Albanians.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But, of course, the main issue is the impression that has been
made very clearly that Russia is not playing in the superleague,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   There was a definite Cold War ring to the reaction in Moscow.
Communist Party chiefs fulminated against imperialistic aggression,
the foreign minister lectured the West on its lack of morality, and
at a news conference the chief of the General Staff, Anatoly
Kvashnin, took out his pointer and went to the map to show the
pattern of what he termed enemy strikes against Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   The only difference between this and the Cold War era is that
this time Russia is no longer a key player. Its military is not
involved in the conflict, and its diplomacy has yet to make an
impact on its outcome. The television reports of the all-night
vigils being kept at the Ministry of Defense seemed almost
poignant, a Sunset Boulevard performance by a former superpower.
</P>
<P>
   To make matters worse, for all the operational information
generated by the Russian general staff, much of it turned out to be
wrong _ like a statement attributed to Defense Minister Igor D.
Sergeyev that NATO was preparingto send in 22,000 ground troops.
</P>
<P>
   Delivering a rundown on the first night of NATO action, Kvashnin
noted at a news conference that the Russian military had
``preliminary information'' that two NATO fighter jets _ a Tornado
and an F-16 _ and several cruise missiles had been downed. ``For
some reason,'' he said ominously, ``nothing is being said about
this.''
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, the reason for NATO's silence was that the
downings _ also reported by Yugoslavia's state-controlled news
media _ had not taken place. To some, the general's fumbling
performance was a sign that Moscow's generals were going through
old, outdated motions, trying to puff up their role.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, there is nothing strange about the fact that the
general's speech was muffled and confused,'' said Pavel
Felgenhauer, a Russian journalist and defense analyst. ``I believe
they are all having a 24-hour party, celebrating the return of the
enemy. They are having a really good time. They are pretending that
they are more important than they really are.''
</P>
<P>
   In a television interview last week, Prime Minister Yevgeny M.
Primakov insisted that Russia was not being left on the sidelines,
noting that Prime Minister Tony Blair of Britain was waiting for
his call.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are turning to us, they are turning to us,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But others were drawing more ominous conclusions about the
political shift in Russia. ``The side effect of the strikes is the
long-awaited breakthrough of `new political thinking' in Russia,''
wrote Leonid Radzikhovsky, a columnist in the newspaper Segodnya.
``This something new is something old that was not completely
forgotten _ xenophobia, envy-hatred toward America, an inferiority
complex of a former empire.
</P>
<P>
   ``The concern is that the strikes will give, in the end, a real
and bloody justification for hatred of the `blood-stained West'
that has been accuumulating for a long time,'' he wrote, noting the
triumphant ``roar of delight'' from Russian generals and Communist
Party chiefs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the roar of winners,'' he added. ``It is a political and
psychological victory over the more important enemy _ over Russia,
its society, its people.''
</P>
<P>
   (MORE) &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   Krasnaya Zvezda, the Russian military's newspaper, ran a
front-page article pointing to the NATO strikes as proof of what
the newspaper said was Washington's illusion that it can still lay
claim to the role of ``world dictator.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is why it is like another sign from heaven for Russia,''
the commentator Vadim Markushin wrote. ``It is time to use our own
mind, time to look after ourselves, our economy and our security,
and the strengthening of our armed forces.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is time to understand at last that neither the West nor
anyone else can in principle be interested in a strong Russia,'' he
wrote, before making a pitch for a regathering of the old Soviet
empire, starting with Belarus and Ukraine, Russia's two Slavic
neighbors. ``We should speed up the creation of a union with
Belarus, come up with a clear intitiative in respect to a reunion
with Ukraine (let us not be afraid of this radicalism) and turn the
Community of Independent States into a community in the real, not
just formal, meaning of the word.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-27-99 1513EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990327.0124 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-27 15:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6473 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-TURKEY-ART-650     03-27 0831
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-TURKEY-ART-650&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN TURKEY, A WARM WELCOME FOR REFUGEES FROM KOSOVO
</HEADLINE>
   (See also: KOSOVO-RDP, KOSOVO-FORCE, KOSOVO-BELGRADE,
KOSOVO-MILOSEVIC, KOSOVO-RUSSIA, KOSOVO-CLINTON) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204.) 
(rk) 
 By STEPHEN KINZER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISTANBUL, Turkey _ At shabby Istanbul hotels where refugees from
the conflict in Kosovo are arriving by the hundreds, the men drink
tea and chain-smoke to keep the tears away.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to leave everything behind, including our parents and
our brothers and sisters,'' said one of them, a strapping auto
mechanic in his mid-20s, as he stood in a dim corridor. ``We had
neighbors who were murdered with knives. At any moment our parents
...''
</P>
<P>
   At this the man broke down into sobs, retreated into his room
and collapsed onto a bed. His wife, standing outside, began weeping
softly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pristina used to be such a nice place,'' she said, referring
to the capital of the Serbian province of Kosovo. ``Now every house
and every mosque is on fire. Serbian families write `S' on their
doors. If you don't have an `S,' the Serb gangs come to burn and
kill.''
</P>
<P>
   In this family, the husband refused to give his name, saying he
feared reprisals against relatives left behind. The woman, who gave
her first name as Lume, said she considered herself ``amazingly
lucky'' to have been able to escape.
</P>
<P>
   More than 3,000 ethnic Albanians from Kosovo have arrived in
Turkey in recent days. Most have melted into the large Albanian
community in Istanbul, and others like Lume and her family will
probably find refuge in private homes soon.
</P>
<P>
   Several million people in Istanbul are of Albanian extraction, a
legacy of the centuries when Albania was under Ottoman rule, and
many people here feel an instinctive solidarity with anyone who
comes from there.
</P>
<P>
   Although some countries have been reluctant to accept refugees
from the current wave of turmoil in Kosovo, Turkey has opened its
arms. Turks consider their country a logical haven for Kosovo's
ethnic Albanians, whom they see in part as Muslim victims of
Christian oppression. Headlines over newspaper stories reporting
their arrival declare ``They Have Nowhere Else'' and ``Emigration
or Death.''
</P>
<P>
   Turkish leaders have vowed to accept and provide for all
refugees from Kosovo who are able to make their way here. They have
strongly supported the bombing campaign by NATO, of which Turkey is
a member.
</P>
<P>
   ``The aim of the NATO operation is to break Yugoslavia's ability
to wage war,'' President Suleyman Demirel said.
</P>
<P>
   Refugees interviewed in Istanbul described harrowing 30-hour
trips in buses crammed with 80 or more people. Several said their
money and valuables had been stolen or extorted from them by police
officers who stopped them as they crossed Serbia. From Serbia, they
drove through Bulgaria to Turkey.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some buses were allowed only to take women and children,''
said a driver who, like other refugees, declined to give his name.
``Others were turned back altogether. Some have just disappeared.
The ones that make it are full of screaming children and people who
have driven through areas where homes are on fire and bombs are
going off.''
</P>
<P>
   Several refugees said they could not imagine returning home
until foreign troops were on the ground to protect them.
Yugoslavia's refusal to admit such a force set off the current wave
of bombing. There seems little prospect that the United States or
other outside countries will send ground troops to Kosovo as long
as Yugoslav units are there and ready to fight them.
</P>
<P>
   At a camp near Istanbul formerly used to shelter Bosnian
refugees, the Turkish authorities are preparing to house several
hundred families from Kosovo. It has not been necessary to use the
camp so far, however, because many families in Istanbul have
volunteered their hospitality.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been several waves of emigration from Albania to
Turkey over the years, so many of these refugees have relatives
here,'' said Nusret Kallura, who emigrated seven years ago and is
now helping to arrange shelter for new arrivals.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   As he spoke, he took calls on a cell phone from bus drivers,
disoriented refugees and others caught up in the exodus. He said he
expected that 800 to 1,000 refugees from Kosovo would arrive in
Turkey each day for at least the next week or so.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every group that arrives has new stories about the lawyer who
was killed with his two sons, or about the 22 teachers who were
shot, or some other atrocity,'' Kallura said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our people in Turkey are opening their hearts and homes. We
even have families who say they don't have relatives coming, but
they'll take people they don't know. All of us feel that if we or
our parents or grandparents hadn't left in time, this could be
happening to us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
