<DOCNO> NYT19990327.0125 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-27 15:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6483 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-RDP-ART-2TAKES     03-27 0867
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-RDP-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SERBS INTENSIFY ATTACKS ON KOSOVARS AS NATO AIR STRIKES CONTINUE 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic map is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
(See also: KOSOVO-FORCE, KOSOVO-BELGRADE, KOSOVO-MILOSEVIC,
KOSOVO-RUSSIA, KOSOVO-CLINTON, KOSOVO-TURKEY, KOSOVO-ASSESS,
KOSOVO-MACEDONIA) 
 (bl)  
 By CRAIG R. WHITNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRUSSELS, Belgium _ Serbian forces stepped up attacks against
ethnic Albanian civilians in Kosovo on Saturday as NATO air
operations rattled Belgrade, the Yugoslav capital, in the heaviest
attacks of the campaign, said allied officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Serbs have been torching villages,'' said British Defense
Minister George Robertson in London. ``There are reports that the
Serbs are bombing villages to the point of obliteration. There are
clear signs now that an all-out Serb offensive against the Albanian
population has started.''
</P>
<P>
   In Belgrade, for the first time, people heard large explosions
before air-raid sirens sounded, suggesting that Yugoslavia's
integrated air defense system has been damaged around the capital,
as NATO has asserted.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton said in his weekly radio address Saturday that
allied forces must ``stay the course'' to prevent the war in Kosovo
from spreading.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must, and we will, continue until Serbia's leader, Slobodan
Milosevic, accepts peace or we have seriously damaged his capacity
to make war,'' Clinton said. Milosevic is president of Yugoslavia,
which consists of the republics of Serbia and Montenegro.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday there were no visible signs that Milosevic was backing
off. All of Serbia's television channels played patriotic themes
Saturday and broadcast news coverage of NATO attacks and of
protests against them in Greece and Russia. Reports that at least
four NATO planes were shot down were later denied by NATO, but the
denials were not shown on television there.
</P>
<P>
   In Kosovo, Serbian troops continued their rampage against the
ethnic Albanians, burning homes and villages and rounding up
Albanian men. There were continued reports, still unconfirmed, of
forced marches, beatings and mass killings.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not happening because of NATO,'' Robertson said.
``This violence was going on before we began.''
</P>
<P>
   Only continued air strikes by the allies can halt the Serbian
offensive, Robertson said, adding, ``We are now targeting the
headquarters and command and control centers that are clearly
critical in carrying out these attacks.''
</P>
<P>
   The allies planned to continue bombing those targets and
anti-aircraft defenses throughout Yugoslavia on Saturday, officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   Air Commodore David Wilby of Britain said in a Brussels briefing
that in operations that ended before dawn Saturday, ``some of the
airplanes turned back because of the weather, but manned aircraft
did get through to their targets last night.'' In all, 249 allied
planes took to the air Friday, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bombs dropped from aircraft and warheads of cruise missiles
struck military targets around Belgrade, the southeastern Serbian
city of Nis, and six areas in and around Kosovo, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   NATO officials have given only sketchy accounts of damage from
its air raids because they say it will take time to analyze
photographs taken after the attacks. And without people on the
ground, they say, it is impossible to provide accurate estimates of
casualties.
</P>
<P>
   Robertson and other officials warned Milosevic on Saturday not
to try to retaliate by attacking international peacekeepers in
neighboring Bosnia or Macedonia. About 12,000 allied soldiers in
Macedonia are preparing for missions to enforce a peace agreement
in Kosovo if, as the allies hope, the bombing forces Milosevic to
accept one.
</P>
<P>
   He showed no sign of being ready to do that Saturday as the
Serbian offensive against ethnic Albanian positions in Kosovo
continued.
</P>
<P>
   ``While we have no confirmation, a campaign of killing, looting,
harassment and intimidation of ethnic Albanians is possible,''
Wilby said. Jamie Shea, the alliance's chief spokesman, said the
allies had received unconfirmed reports of large-scale Serbian
actions against thousands of civilians.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do know a large number of Albanian women and children were
pushed across the Albanian border without any men, which suggests
that ethnic cleansing is taking place,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The allies, he added, will do their best to see that Serbian
authorities who may be responsible for atrocities against civilians
will be prosecuted for them by the international criminal tribunal
in The Hague.
</P>
<P>
   With all international observers out of Kosovo for more than a
week, allied officials said they had no way of checking reports
from ethnic Albanian journalists and others of multiple atrocities
against civilians by Serbian army soldiers and Interior Ministry
policemen in the province.
</P>
<P>
   Officials here disputed Serbian news reports that two NATO
planes had been shot down Friday night. ``All NATO aircraft have
returned safely to their bases,'' Shea said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Belgrade television broadcast images showing the Yugoslav
capital almost deserted by shoppers Saturday after heavy overnight
missile raids aimed at military targets on the outskirts of the
city.
</P>
<P>
   Stinging chemical fumes wafted over parts of the city Saturday
after allied warplanes bombed a rocket fuel depot in the Ibarska
Magistrala area in the southern suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   Hashim Thaci, the leader of the ethnic Albanian delegation that
signed the peace agreement that Milosevic refused to accept in
Paris earlier this month, said that Serbian military and police
sweeps through Kosovo could only be stopped by sending in NATO
ground forces, an Austrian news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
   But U.S. and European officials at the alliance headquarters
here said Saturday that none of the alliance's 19 countries were
even considering such a step, and military officials at command
headquarters in Mons said that the alliance's political authorities
had not asked them to prepare for an invasion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no current plans for ground operations,'' said Wilby,
adding later, ``Currently, there are no plans for us to take on
ground operations in Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   French Defense Minister Alain Richard told the daily Le Figaro,
``Sending ground troops in is foreseen only in the context of
implementing a political agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   Gen. Sir Charles Guthrie, the chief of the British Defense
Staff, said in London that the bombing of army and police
headquarters last week had already significantly disrupted Serbia's
ability to continue the offensive in Kosovo. ``We know the Yugoslav
army has been badly rattled,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can assure you that the integrated air defense systems of
the Yugoslavs have been severely degraded,'' the general added.
``I'm not, certainly, saying that he has lost his ability to hit an
aircraft, but he's going to find it much harder.''
</P>
<P>
   NATO planes have shot down five of the most advanced
fighter-bomber aircraft in the Yugoslav arsenal, MiG-29s.
</P>
<P>
   Adding details to earlier accounts of a dogfight Friday
afternoon in which two NATO F-15s shot down two advanced MiG-29
Yugoslav planes over Bosnia, Wilby said the MiGs had apparently
intended to try to lure the NATO planes across the border into
Serbia to try to shoot them down.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our aircraft turned toward them in rule-book fashion and shot
them down,'' he said. The wreckage of one lies in a minefield in a
sector of Bosnia patrolled by Russian troops serving with the
alliance-led peacekeeping force, he said, and the other MiG went
down in an unknown location.
</P>
<P>
   The fate of the pilots was not known Saturday. If Russian
soldiers found a surviving pilot, Wilby said, he was sure they
would turn him over to allied authorities.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's continued participation in the Bosnia operation came
under question Saturday after Moscow threw out the alliance's
liaison officer in Moscow. Russian cooperation with the alliance
has been suspended since the allies began the air strikes.
</P>
<P>
   Though the allies kept attacking air defense targets Saturday,
releasing pictures of damage done to a surface-to-air missile site
in Jakovo outside Belgrade and of a Serbian airfield at Batajnica
showing a number of hangars destroyed, officials in Brussels said
that air power could offer no absolute protection to Albanian
civilians against the reported thuggery and repression now believed
to be under way.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the trigger for our action _ the desire to prevent a
humanitarian catastrophe,'' Shea said. ``As air operations evolve
in the coming hours, and coming days, we will be in a good position
to severely disrupt and hinder the Yugoslav army and Interior
Ministry police sweeps.''
</P>
<P>
   ``NATO's resolve to continue this operation until its objectives
are achieved remains absolute,'' he said, disputing any suggestion
that second thoughts expressed in Athens, Prague, Rome and some
other allied capitals had already numbered the operation's days.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
