<DOCNO> NYT19990327.0127 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-27 15:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6486 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-MACEDONIA-515&AMP;     03-27 0839
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MACEDONIA-515&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLEEING KOSOVARS TELL OF DEATH AND PILLAGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: KOSOVO-RDP, KOSOVO-FORCE, KOSOVO-BELGRADE,
KOSOVO-MILOSEVIC, KOSOVO-RUSSIA, KOSOVO-CLINTON, KOSOVO-TURKEY,
KOSOVO-ASSESS) 
(lb) 
 By CARLOTTA GALL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SKOPJE, Macedonia _ Accounts filtering out of Kosovo from
refugees and the few telephone calls that can be made into the
province from neighboring Macedonia tell of dozens of killings,
particularly of ethnic Albanian intellectuals, and burning of
houses, shops and markets in major towns.
</P>
<P>
   Fighting between the ethnic Albanians' Kosovo Liberation Army
and Serbian forces has also intensified, and has moved to at least
one town, Djakovica, in southern Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Albanians in the town have described the armed rebels as
occupying the new part of town, an area of modern high-rises, while
Serbian forces have control of the old town, an area of narrow
streets and small houses on the south side.
</P>
<P>
   Serbian forces have had tank positions on the edge of the old
town, from which they have shelled the area close to the border
with Albania. The rebel army has been active in the region under
the leadership of a commander known as Ramush.
</P>
<P>
   Taulant, a young ethnic Albanian working in Skopje, said he had
spoken to his cousin in Djakovica by telephone at midday on Friday.
The cousin, Genc, 40, a father of four, said Serbian forces had
shelled the old part of town and then moved in to burn houses and
shops. Taulant spoke on condition that only first names would be
used, so the police would not be able to trace his cousin.
</P>
<P>
   Genc went on foot on Friday to investigate whether his own house
in the old part of town had been affected. It was still standing
undamaged, but he said ``All the old part up to my house was on
fire,'' Taulant recounted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now they are starting to burn the small market,'' Taulant
said. ``From the way he described it, the houses were set on fire
by hand, and not from the shelling.'' Their telephone conversation
broke off abruptly when Genc said Serbian forces were shelling his
own neighborhood in the new part of town.
</P>
<P>
   Genc also told his cousin that the police were searching house
to house but had not yet come to his area and that he had not seen
any police in the streets. A local artist, Adi Shehu, had been
killed, Genc said, saying he had talked to the man's neighbors.
There was no way to confirm this account.
</P>
<P>
   Reports from elsewhere in Kosovo suggest that killing and
burning continue. Serbian forces have also unleashed a heavy
assault on rebel positions in northern Kosovo, reportedly with
devastating effect.
</P>
<P>
   ``The KLA is in a really bad situation in the north,'' said a
Western diplomat who is tracking developments from neighboring
Skopje. ``They have lost ground. Infantry can only hold out against
heavy armor for so long.''
</P>
<P>
   The most heavily contested area in northern Kosovo is around the
towns of Podujevo and Mitrovica and in the Cicavica mountains, 25
miles northwest of Pristina, where Serbian forces have conducted
the main thrust of their offensive against the Kosovo Liberation
Army over the last month.
</P>
<P>
   The Western diplomat also said there were credible reports
emerging of as many as 50 killings of ethnic Albanians in the town
of Mitrovica and in Pristina, the capital.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Ethnic Albanians in Skopje have managed to confirm the death of
the human-rights lawyer Bajram Kelmendi, speaking to someone in
Kosovo's capital, Pristina, who had actually seen the body.
</P>
<P>
   Kelmendi and his two sons were arrested and taken away by
uniformed police on Wednesday night, the first night of the NATO
bombing. His wife and the wife of the elder son told foreign
journalists on Thursday that five policemen burst in at around 1
a.m., threatened to shoot and ordered them to lie on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   The two women said the police demanded money, saying they would
kill the children if Kelmendi did not hand it over. Then, the women
related, they took the men off, telling Kastriut, the elder son,
30, to kiss his wife and children goodbye as he would not see them
again.
</P>
<P>
   The three bodies were found dumped on the road by a gas station
on the edge of Pristina on Friday, the New York-based group Human
Rights Watch has said.
</P>
<P>
   An unconfirmed report from an ethnic Albanian journalist in
Pristina said that a well-known surgeon from Djakovica, Izet Hima,
was also reported to have been found killed.
</P>
<P>
   Albanian state television said 30 people were reported dead in
the town of Orahovac, and more than 20 in Suva Reka.
</P>
<P>
   Telephone lines into and within Yugoslavia were heavily
overloaded or out of order Saturday, and it appeared that few calls
had reached Kosovo since Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   The few foreign journalists who have remained in Pristina or
managed to return since journalists from NATO member countries were
expelled on Thursday have been confined to their hotels or houses,
virtually unable to work.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
