<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-27 16:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6508 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCOTUS-2TAKES-NYT &LR;      03-27 1087
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGH COURT FACES MOMENT OF TRUTH IN FEDERALISM CASES  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Me., Fla., Ga. )   By LINDA GREENHOUSE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Beginning with an argument this week in an obscure
case about overtime pay for state probation officers in Maine, the
Supreme Court is setting out on an extended foray along the border
that separates federal authority from state prerogatives.
</P>
<P>
   Depending on how the court decides a series of cases extending
through the remainder of its current term and into the next, that
border could be redrawn. Already it is increasingly unstable and
ill-defined, the result in large part of the court's own recent
decisions, as a narrow majority has coalesced around a view of
federal authority more limited than the Supreme Court has held in
many years.
</P>
<P>
   Now, in the view of legal scholars who study the court's
federalism decisions and lawyers who handle cases in this area, the
court has reached a moment of truth, the point at which the
justices will have to distill the loose and sometimes extravagant
language of their recent decisions and show what they really mean
to do.
</P>
<P>
   These are not the high-profile federalism battles of recent
years, over such issues as congressional term limits or the Brady
gun-control law. This is day-to-day, bread-and-butter federalism,
the federalism not of theory but of practice.
</P>
<P>
   For example, in Alden vs. Maine, the case set for argument on
Wednesday, the question is whether state workers can go to state
court to sue a state for violations of federal labor law, in this
case the failure to pay time and a half for overtime. Since recent
Supreme Court precedents have barred suits of this type in federal
court when the defendant is a state, states would be immune from
labor-law suits filed by their employees, if the justices agree
with Maine's high court that the state courts are closed as well.
</P>
<P>
   Next month, the court will hear arguments in two cases, one on
whether states can be sued for patent infringement and the other on
whether they can be sued for for engaging in false advertising in
violation of federal law. For their next term, the Justices have
accepted a case on whether states can be sued by their employees
for violations of the federal law against age discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   More than a dozen federalism cases have been filed at the court
in recent months, with others moving quickly through the legal
pipeline. The individual cases, embedded in various strands of the
Supreme Court's elusive and highly technical federalism doctrines,
might not be of much general interest standing alone; occasional
skirmishes along the federal-state border are a staple of the
court's docket. But the whole in this instance is greater than the
sum of its parts, making it clear that profound issues of state
sovereignty and of the supremacy of federal law are at stake.
</P>
<P>
   The flood of new cases is the direct result of the court's
recent federalism initiatives, which sent powerful signals, both to
the states and to the lower courts charged with interpreting the
Supreme Court's work, that the rules of the game were changing.
</P>
<P>
   For example, a 1995 decision, United States vs. Lopez,
overturning the federal Gun-Free School Zones Act, was the first
time since the New Deal that the court found Congress to have
exceeded the bounds of its constitutional authority to regulate
interstate commerce. The legislative goal of keeping guns away from
schools did not fall within the limited authority the Commerce
Clause conferred on Congress, the court said.
</P>
<P>
   The next year, the court turned its attention to the 11th
Amendment, which gives the states immunity in federal court against
certain kinds of lawsuits. In Seminole Tribe vs. Florida, the court
expanded that immunity, overturning one of its own precedents in
order to rule that Congress had no authority under the Commerce
Clause to pass a law permitting states to be sued in federal court.
The decision struck down a law that permitted Indian tribes to sue
states to force negotiations over tribal casinos.
</P>
<P>
   Then in 1997, the court ruled that a provision of the Brady
gun-control law, requiring local sheriffs to perform background
checks on would-be gun purchasers, violated state sovereignty by
``commandeering'' state employees to do the federal government's
bidding.
</P>
<P>
   That decision, Printz vs. United States, was based on the 10th
Amendment, a provision the Supreme Court had ignored for most of
its history before its episodic revival over the last 25 years as
an occasional limit, of uncertain dimensions, on federal authority
over the states.
</P>
<P>
   As the legal system absorbed this string of decisions, the
federalism climate quickly began to change. States became vigorous
in asserting defenses to suits brought under federal law, and the
lower courts began to respond sympathetically, pushing the envelope
of state immunity even beyond what the court had found necessary.
As that dynamic of action and reaction begins to fill the court's
federalism docket once again, one question is whether the justices
like what they see.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a sense in which the justices have backed themselves
into a corner on federalism, and now their chickens are coming home
to roost,'' Thomas W. Merrill, a law professor and federalism
expert at Northwestern University, said recently. Merrill said that
the cases now before the court carry the logic of the earlier cases
to a kind of extreme that ``I can't help but think is going to make
the swing votes on the court a little queasy.''
</P>
<P>
   All the recent cases were decided by 5-4 votes, with a majority
comprised of Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist and Justices
Antonin Scalia, Clarence Thomas, Sandra Day O'Connor and Anthony M.
Kennedy. The dissenters were Justices John Paul Stevens, David H.
Souter, Ruth Bader Ginsburg and Stephen G. Breyer. Of the majority,
Kennedy is widely seen as the justice most likely to put the brakes
on a drive toward state sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
   The case to be argued on Wednesday, Alden vs. Maine, No. 98-436,
offers an interesting test. Maine, joined by 36 states that filed a
brief as friends of the court, is defending a 1998 ruling by the
Maine Supreme Judicial Court, which said that the state courts
cannot hear a suit by 65 state probation officers and juvenile case
workers. The plaintiffs say that under the Fair Labor Standards
Act, they are entitled to overtime pay that the state has refused
to provide.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  Under the Supreme Court's Seminole Tribe decision, it is clear
that the suit cannot be heard in federal court, where it was
originally filed. But Congress provided that Fair Labor Standards
Act suits can also be brought in state court. Maine's high court,
however, interpreted the Seminole Tribe ruling as a statement not
only about the jurisdiction of the federal courts, but about deeper
principles of state sovereign immunity that closed the state
courthouse doors as well.
</P>
<P>
   The 11th Amendment is phrased as a limit on ``the judicial power
of the United States'' and does not mention state courts; the
Supreme Court has never interpreted it as providing state-court
immunity. But Rehnquist's majority opinion in the Seminole Tribe
case did refer to the ``the background principle of state sovereign
immunity embodied in the 11th Amendment,'' a powerfully ambiguous
phrase which Maine has seized in its Supreme Court brief in the
Alden case.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since the 11th Amendment is simply the embodiment of the
background principle of state sovereign immunity,'' the state is
telling the court, ``there is no principled basis upon which to
distinguish congressional authorization of suits by private parties
against unconsenting states in state court from such suits in
federal court.''
</P>
<P>
   Maine's brief has borrowed phrases from the court's decision in
the Brady Act case, telling the justices that the federal
government should not be permitted to ``commandeer'' the state
courts for the administration of a federal statute.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration has joined the Maine state workers in
appealing the state court's immunity decision. The brief filed by
Solicitor General Seth P. Waxman tells the court that the decision
``is of profound concern to the United States'' and a direct threat
to the concept of the supremacy of federal law. ``Any interest the
state has in asserting immunity in this case must give way to the
overriding interest in the vindication of federal law,'' the
government's brief asserts.
</P>
<P>
   Another aspect of the Seminole Tribe decision is in dispute. The
ruling suggested that despite the new limitations on its authority
under the Commerce Clause, Congress retained the power to abrogate
the states' 11th Amendment immunity under its authority to pass
laws guaranteeing the individual rights protected by the 14th
Amendment.
</P>
<P>
   The U. S. Court of Appeals for the 11th Circuit in Atlanta
disagreed, finding 11th Amendment immunity for the states in suits
under the federal Age Discrimination in Employment Act. The
government's appeal of that ruling is United States vs. Kimel, No.
98-796. The other pending cases are College Savings Bank vs.
Florida, No. 98-149, and Florida vs. College Savings Bank, No.
98-531, raising immunity questions under federal patent and
trademark law.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
