<SLUG> BC-RENAULT-NISSAN-880(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN RENAULT-NISSAN DEAL, BIG RISKS AND BIG OPPORTUNITIES
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By STEPHANIE STROM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ In taking a stake in the troubled Nissan Motor Co.,
Renault, the stodgy French car company that has tried to become a
formidable force in Europe, has embarked on a risky business gamble
to strengthen the global competitiveness of both companies.
</P>
<P>
   The deal attempts to balance the differing needs of a Japanese
auto company and a Western one. While some American and European
companies have teamed up to better conquer world markets, some of
the smaller Japanese and European auto companies have largely sat
on the sidelines.
</P>
<P>
   The Japanese have been restrained by their culture and their
reluctance to fully embrace change. Renault, on the other hand, has
had a history of failed engagements and marriages.
</P>
<P>
   The alliance takes a step toward resolving Nissan's substantial
financial difficulties while allowing its management, which has
produced boring cars and sizable losses, to save face _ not an
insignificant issue in the culture of corporate Japan.
</P>
<P>
   And it seeks to insulate Renault from Nissan's financial woes
while giving it access to the Japanese company's advanced
engineering and technical skills. It also provides significant car
making capacity in important markets like the United States and
Mexico where Renault is not present.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope you will have great expectations for this alliance,''
said Yoshikazu Hanawa, Nissan's president.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the two companies seemed well aware that their new
partnership may raise as many challenges as it seeks to resolve.
``We know the problems confronting our companies will not work
themselves out through this alliance,'' said Louis Schweitzer,
Renault's chairman and chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, he said, both companies would use it as a tool to
overcome their respective hurdles. He predicted that the potential
synergy of the deal, including joint parts procurement, combined
sales and marketing operations and the exchange of models to round
out each company's product lines, would reduce costs on a combined
basis by $3.3 billion in the two years from 2000 to 2002 regardless
of the effect of cost-cutting measures.
</P>
<P>
   For Renault, the partnership represents a chance to vault into
the automotive big leagues at a time when the global auto business
is evolving into a handful of huge global players. If combined,
Renault and Nissan would be the world's fourth-largest car maker
after General Motors, Ford and Toyota, with 9.1 percent of the
global market.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, Renault has stepped into the big leagues by
buying stakes in American Motors, which owned Jeep, Mack Trucks and
Volvo of Sweden. Only the Mack truck deal a decade ago was
successful. The Volvo deal produced board room clashes before it
was officially consummated. Renault ended up selling American
Motors to Jeep in 1987 after a rocky relationship.
</P>
<P>
   For Nissan, the deal brings in much-needed new capital and gives
it access to the cost-cutting, product development and efficient
procurement know-how that have become Renault's claims to fame.
</P>
<P>
   Renault will pay 643 billion yen, or $5.4 billion at current
exchange rates, to buy new stock that will give it a 36.8 percent
stake in Nissan and to purchase a 22.5 percent stake in Nissan's
struggling truck subsidiary, the Nissan Diesel Motor Co. Schweitzer
said the deal to buy a portion of Nissan's stake in Nissan Diesel
came up only in the final stages of discussions, which started last
summer.
</P>
<P>
   Down the road, Nissan also has a right to buy some of the 44
percent stake in Renault owned by the French government and Renault
is likely to make Hanawa a board member.
</P>
<P>
   Renault has also agreed to refinance Nissan's short-term debt
for five years in exchange for warrants that it could use to raise
its Nissan ownership to 44 percent. That percentage would still be
less than is required to have control of the Japanese company.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Nissan recovers, we did not want it to be controlled by
another company,'' Schweitzer said. ``We did not think that would
be good for Nissan.''
</P>
<P>
   Renault will use $2 billion in cash and raise the rest from its
banks, Schweitzer said. He said Renault aimed to pay off the debts
it will incur as a result of the Nissan deal in three years.
</P>
<P>
   A portion of the money will be used to pare away some of
Nissan's 4.3 trillion yen, or $37 billion, in publicly disclosed
debts. The investment includes the transfer of Nissan's European
auto-financing operations to Renault, which in and of itself will
wipe 38 billion yen, or $322 million, off Nissan's balance sheet, a
Nissan spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   But the most interesting part of the deal involves three top
Renault executives _ Carlos Ghosn, Patrick Pelata and Thierry
Moulonguet _ who will resign from the French company and take
senior positions at Nissan, which has one of the most bureaucratic,
hierarchical cultures in corporate Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Questions about potential culture clashes cropped up repeatedly
at the two companies' press conference Saturday afternoon, which
one reporter compared to having sushi with Chardonnay.
</P>
<P>
   Hanawa, whose name became ``Anawa,'' in the voice of the French
interpreter, said he and Schweitzer had dined together on many
cuisines, all of which they had enjoyed.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But how well the patrician Japanese executive will enjoy the
scrutiny and advice of his new second-in-command, Ghosn, remains to
be seen.
</P>
<P>
   Ghosn (pronounced go-en), a well-liked Brazilian who currently
is second in command at Renault, will take responsibility for the
day-to-day operations of a company whose sales in Japan have been
slipping even as the deterioration in the overall car market seems
to be slowing.
</P>
<P>
   As chief operating officer, he will report to Hanawa, who will
use the title president in Japan and that of chief executive
officer when on the road.
</P>
<P>
   Pelata will become Nissan's executive vice president in charge
of product planning and strategy, a portfolio similar to that he
holds at Renault. He will take on the task of infusing Nissan's
cars with more flair and overhauling its costly production process.
</P>
<P>
   But the biggest task goes to Moulonguet, a hard-nosed,
no-nonsense financial expert who will become Nissan's deputy chief
financial officer. Although he officially reports to Tadahiro
Shirai, Nissan's chief financial officer, Moulonguet is expected to
focus on Nissan's costs and hack away its mountain of liabilities,
parts of which are not publicly reported thanks to lax Japanese
accounting rules.
</P>
<P>
   Ghosn, Pelata and Moulonguet, who will sit on Nissan's board,
will be Schweitzer's eyes and ears in Tokyo, and as such, will have
leading roles in trying to shape a recovery for Nissan.
</P>
<P>
   But Schweitzer cautioned repeatedly that they are not meant to
be a cure for Nissan's ills. ``The turnaround of Nissan will have
to be achieved by Nissan itself,'' he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Already, Nissan officials say, the company is considering fuller
disclosure of its myriad financial problems, in part to satisfy
changes in Japanese accounting rules and in part because there is a
growing belief that Nissan must openly confront its difficulties if
it is to overcome them.
</P>
<P>
   The Renault executives will also encourage Nissan to procure
parts on a global basis, rather than primarily from the satellite
of suppliers and affiliates here whose costs, and thus prices, are
higher than their non-Japanese competitors.
</P>
<P>
   Those relationships will be hard to eliminate, however, as
Nissan's fortunes are tangled up with the performance of its
affiliates because it has financial stakes in them.
</P>
<P>
   Schweitzer said the two companies were already prepared to start
several joint production and procurement projects. Renault will
begin manufacturing its cars in Nissan's plants in Mexico and
Southeast Asia, while Nissan will use Renault's factories in South
America.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-27-99 1623EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
