<DOCNO> NYT19990327.0134 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-27 16:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6515 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DRUG-COMPANIES-FDA-2T     03-27 1172
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRUG-COMPANIES-FDA-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAKERS OF WOMEN'S DRUGS CLASH WITH FDA ON MARKETING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ind.) (With DRUG-COMPANIES-ADS) 
(lb) 
 By DENISE GRADY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two drug companies seeking to tap the vast market of
postmenopausal women at risk for breast cancer, heart disease and
bone loss have clashed with each other and run afoul of the Food
and Drug Administration over their marketing practices, prompting a
flurry of lawsuits, government warning letters and accusations that
inaccurate assertions could endanger women's health.
</P>
<P>
   Caught in the middle are millions of American women who are
trying to determine whether there is any drug they can take after
menopause that does not bring on as many problems as it is supposed
to solve.
</P>
<P>
   One of the feuding companies is Zeneca, maker of tamoxifen,
which is prescribed to reduce the incidence of breast cancer in
high-risk postmenopausal women. Zeneca is a British company with
offices in Wilmington, Del.
</P>
<P>
   Tamoxifen, which also goes by the brand name Nolvadex, has been
in use for many years to treat breast cancer, and when it received
additional approval last spring for use in risk reduction, it
became the only drug approved in the United States to lower the
incidence of any form of cancer.
</P>
<P>
   The other combatant is Eli Lilly and Co., based in Indianapolis.
Lilly marketed the drug raloxifene last year under the brand name
Evista, to prevent the bone-thinning disease osteoporosis, also in
postmenopausal women. The disease is a major cause of broken bones
in elderly women, including fractures in the hips and spine that
can be crippling and even life-threatening.
</P>
<P>
   Zeneca, which filed suit against Lilly on Feb. 25 in U.S.
District Court in New York, wrote to thousands of doctors in the
United States and posted a letter on its Web site asserting that
Lilly's sales representatives had falsely told doctors that Evista
could prevent breast cancer and had created a widespread
misperception that Evista could be used in place of Nolvadex.
</P>
<P>
   Lilly countersued on March 19, denying the accusation and
demanding that Zeneca stop its comments about Lilly's sales force.
The case is scheduled to go to court in May.
</P>
<P>
   The FDA had already written to both companies in January,
accusing them of placing misleading advertisements in consumer
magazines and telling them to stop. Lilly was said to have implied
that Evista could prevent breast cancer and Zeneca was told it had
wrongly omitted mention of the risks of Nolvadex, which include
blood clots and a slight increase in the risk of uterine cancer.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for the drug agency said that it could seize a
product or obtain an injunction against ads that violate
regulations but that those measures were rarely taken. Both Zeneca
and Lilly said they had stopped using the offending ads and other
promotional materials.
</P>
<P>
   The warnings to Lilly and Zeneca are striking because the
companies are the first to jockey for position in an enormous and
potentially lucrative new market: cancer prevention.
</P>
<P>
   ``Breast cancer is not the most frequent problem facing women,
but it's the one that concerns them most,'' said Dr. Wulf Utian,
director of obstetrics and gynecology at the University Hospitals
of Cleveland, who has no connection to either company. Even though
far more women die of heart disease than breast cancer, women worry
more about the issue of which drugs or hormones might cause breast
cancer or prevent it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is very confusing for women, and also very confusing for
average practitioners,'' Utian said. ``There is a huge need for
additional studies.''
</P>
<P>
   The first treatment approved for problems associated with
menopause was estrogen, which is now available in a variety of
formulations. In addition to relieving hot flashes, insomnia and
other problems, estrogen has also been shown to prevent bone loss
and reduce the risk of heart disease and possibly Alzheimer's
disease.
</P>
<P>
   But estrogen has a downside: Many women are afraid to take it
because it may cause a slight increase in the risk of breast
cancer. And unless it is combined with another hormone,
progesterone, it can also increase the risk of uterine cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Evista, often described as a ``designer'' estrogen, is an
estrogenlike molecule developed with the hope of mimicking some of
estrogen's good points while avoiding its bad ones. It was approved
in late 1997 and marketed in 1998, earning $144 million for Lilly
in its first year, a spokeswoman for the company said.
</P>
<P>
   Evista reduces bone loss only about half as well as estrogen,
but its selling point was that studies indicated that it might not
increase the risk of breast or uterine cancer.
</P>
<P>
   The osteoporosis studies also suggested that Evista might
actually reduce the risk of breast cancer, but those findings were
considered inconclusive because the studies were relatively short,
they were not designed to evaluate breast cancer and they did not
include women at high risk for the disease. For that reason, the
FDA approved Evista only for osteoporosis.
</P>
<P>
   But once a drug is on the market, doctors are free to recommend
it for any condition, whether it has been approved for that use or
not, a widespread practice known as ``off-label'' prescribing.
</P>
<P>
   It is that freedom that Zeneca has accused Lilly of trying to
exploit. Mary Lynn Carver, a spokeswoman for Zeneca, said company
officials had noted that even before Evista was approved for
osteoporosis, Lilly had asked the FDA to consider data on breast
cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Wary of incursions onto its turf, Zeneca kept tabs on Evista,
Ms. Carver said, and Zeneca sales representatives routinely asked
doctors what Lilly representatives had been telling them in their
offices during the private ``detailing'' visits that are an
important source of drug information for many doctors. What the
Zeneca representatives heard led to the lawsuit, Ms. Carver said.
</P>
<P>
   Court documents filed by Zeneca state that Lilly sales
representatives had tried to mislead doctors into believing that
Evista had been proved to prevent breast cancer and could be
prescribed instead of Nolvadex for high-risk women.
</P>
<P>
   Angela Sekston, a spokeswoman for Lilly, said, ``We deny all
allegations of wrongdoing that have been put forth in Zeneca's
lawsuit.'' Lilly has filed a legal response as well as the
countersuit, she said. ``We want to stop Zeneca from making false
allegations about our sales force.'' In addition, she said, Lilly
is asking the court to force Zeneca ``to run corrective ads to take
back the statements they've already made.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if Lilly intended to stop making assertions about breast
cancer, she left the door open, saying: ``FDA does allow for
disclosure of data around a scientific meeting. It can be discussed
in meetings and peer-to-peer forums.'' Lilly researchers have
presented breast-cancer data from the osteoporosis studies at
several medical meetings.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Fran Visco, president of the National Breast Cancer Coalition,
an advocacy group in Washington, said, ``I have been to medical
conferences where doctors have gotten up and spoken of raloxifene
as a miracle drug.'' They seem to believe that it has been proved
to prevent breast cancer and ward off heart disease, she said,
adding, ``I don't know where it's coming from, but there certainly
is a lot of talk out there about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Outside the United States, beyond the reach of the FDA, Lilly
has promoted Evista to prevent breast cancer and heart disease. In
the February issue of a Canadian journal for pharmacists, an ad
said, ``Reduces the incidence of breast cancer'' and ``improves the
lipid profile.''
</P>
<P>
   Evista is currently being studied in women at high risk for
heart disease, but results are not expected for several years. To
determine whether the drug can reduce the risk of breast cancer, a
five-year nationwide study of 22,000 women is planned to begin this
spring, comparing Evista with tamoxifen.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Leslie Ford of the National Cancer Institute said, ``Only
through that trial, a head-to-head comparison, will we really have
the answer.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
