<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLICE-MAYOR-ASSESS-1000(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIULIANI MEETS WITH BLACK LEADERS, MAKING THE ROUTINE SEEM
MOMENTOUS
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Note language 8th graf, ``After the election ...) 
 (rk) 
 By DAN BARRY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Time and again, the Giuliani administration has
demonstrated the ability to make the routine seem unusual, and the
bizarre seem mundane.
</P>
<P>
   How else could a meeting between the mayor and the city's
highest-elected black official take on the significance of a
Botha-Mandela sit-down? How else could a mayor have refused to meet
that leader for more than a year?
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's session last week with C. Virginia
Fields, the Manhattan borough president, was viewed as so
extraordinary that the City Council speaker, Peter F. Vallone, who
arranged the meeting, somehow emerged as the great healer of City
Hall.
</P>
<P>
   Then came word that the mayor had agreed to meet with state
Comptroller H. Carl McCall, another black leader he had rebuffed
for years, and would soon be inviting other people of color to
Gracie Mansion for face-to-face chats.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly seven weeks after the Amadou Diallo shooting began
roiling race relations in the city, the administration decided that
the time had come to, as one aide put it, ``build bridges'' and let
the ``healing process'' continue. And so Giuliani was poised to be
congratulated for meeting elected city and state officials _
activities that might normally be considered an expected duty of
his office.
</P>
<P>
   So far, however, the praise has been muted by healthy
skepticism. ``How come now?'' asked Bill Lynch, the chief of staff
to former Mayor David N. Dinkins.
</P>
<P>
   He recalled that Giuliani had previously talked of improving
relations between the police and minorities _ immediately after the
brutalization of Abner Louima, allegedly by the police in the
summer of 1997, and just before his re-election.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the election he said, `The hell with this,' '' Lynch
said, reflecting the opinion of other black leaders in the city.
``And you say, `Trust him now?'''
</P>
<P>
   Some political observers say the lingering distrust reflects the
way the mayor's Mr. Outside persona has turned against him at
perhaps his most vulnerable moment in public office.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout his tenure, he refused to build the bridges now
hastily under construction to the city's black and Hispanic
neighborhoods; he gloried in every Police Department triumph and
belittled complaints against the force, and he exuded a
my-way-or-the-highway style of governance.
</P>
<P>
   Now, they say, the mayor's strengths hint of weakness. Last
month's shooting death of Diallo, an unarmed black man, by four
white police officers in a hail of 41 bullets raised questions
about race-tinged aggression within his beloved Police Department,
exposing his poor relations with minority leaders.
</P>
<P>
   The sudden outreach to black and Hispanic leaders _ on the heels
of his dismissive comments about their motives _ tests his
credibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem we're finding now is that Rudy's support among
elected officials was obviously thinner than he realized,'' said
Mitchell Moss, the director of the Taub Urban Research Center at
New York University. ``A mayor of New York has to be responsive to
everyone. And the Giuliani administration did not recognize that
you cannot govern the city and ignore'' black and Hispanic
residents.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is obviously a really tough one for the mayor to
empathize with,'' said John H. Mollenkopf, director of the Center
for Urban Research at the Graduate Center of the City University of
New York. ``It's tough not only because his heart is with the
police and the criminal-justice system, but it's tough because he
doesn't hang around in places where there are a lot of black and
Dominican and West Indian and Puerto Rican young men to get to
know.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps, his critics suggest, that is why Mr. Outside now seems
so alone.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Many analysts say the mayor at first acted as best he could,
given the social and political nightmare presented by the Diallo
shooting. Even though the four officers reportedly have been
indicted on charges of murder _ the grand jury's decision is
expected to be announced this week _ the city still has heard only
one side of what happened that night in the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   As mayor for all the city, as he and his aides like to put it,
Giuliani thought it best to urge calm, to defend what he considers
to be an exceptional Police Department, and to express sorrow for
the loss of a young street peddler from West Africa. ``The mayor is
being balanced,'' said a senior adviser, speaking on condition of
anonymity. ``He is doing exactly what you want a leader to do.''
</P>
<P>
   But each day demonstrated that the case symbolized so much more,
from the fear that many black and Hispanic residents harbor for the
Police Department to the simmering resentment they hold for
Giuliani. And the mayor reverted to the rigid style that had won
him a high job-approval rating and the acclaim of national
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   He dismissed the daily acts of civil disobedience staged by the
Rev. Al Sharpton outside Police Headquarters in lower Manhattan as
``silly'' and ``highly partisan''; he ridiculed the demand that the
officers be arrested _ something he rightly pointed out was not his
decision _ and generally ignored the larger statements being made.
His defense of the police seemed gradually to mute his expressions
of understanding.
</P>
<P>
   ``He really has a moral stance that there's a right and a wrong
here, and the police are generally doing the right thing, and he's
not going to back off from that just because it's politically
unpopular,'' Mollenkopf said. But in politics that approach can be
both refreshing and problematic, he added. ``It's clear that by
imposing higher standards in lots of areas, the mayor has gotten
the city to clean up its act. But moral absolutism is hard to
swallow in hard doses.''
</P>
<P>
   Former Gov. Mario Cuomo agreed. ``You pay a price for his kind
of constant pressure, his constant in-your-face,'' he said. ``It
gets things done, it's aggressive and it's strong. And people do
react to strength. There's also a downside to that. When you're in
people's faces, you irritate.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   By last week, it had become obvious to the mayor and his aides
that the Mr. Outside act had worn thin. Respected political and
civic leaders, including those previously allied with the
administration, were being arrested outside police headquarters.
His job-approval rating had plummeted. Suddenly, Ms. Fields and
McCall were welcome at Gracie Mansion.
</P>
<P>
   Raymond B. Harding, the leader of the state's Liberal Party and
one of the mayor's closest advisers, answered the question ``What
happened?'' by citing what he considered to be a ``confluence of
situations.''
</P>
<P>
   First, he said, the Democrats that dominate city politics
outside the mayor's office seized on the case with the aim of
crippling Giuliani politically. While talking of ``healing and
reconciliation'' at the daily protests, he said, they demanded that
he do the impossible and ensure the arrests of the four officers.
</P>
<P>
   Second, he said, resentment lingers over Giuliani's decision in
his first term to ``treat all New Yorkers as one.'' The mayor acted
on this promise by disbanding a network of advisers to ethnic
neighborhoods that had been established by previous
administrations. Leaders from those neighborhoods say the decision
ended their access to City Hall.
</P>
<P>
   Lastly, Harding said, ``people are not looking at his mayoral
actions but are focused on his rhetorical style.''
</P>
<P>
   In response, the term-limited mayor has changed his actions and
tempered his rhetorical style, just as speculation intensifies over
his possible candidacy for the U.S. Senate next year.
</P>
<P>
   After meeting with black and Hispanic members of the City
Council on Friday, for example, the mayor emerged from Gracie
Mansion to tell reporters how productive it had been. ``It might be
I made a mistake in not having more meetings like this,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Several black leaders, though, said they are skeptical of
Giuliani's recent epiphany. They said they hope to use the Diallo
incident both to change the city's police culture and to register
more minority voters throughout the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's playing to his base and trying to show them that
he is a rational guy, and that he is now meeting with some
blacks,'' Lynch said. ``But that's all he's doing.''
</P>
<P>
   But the mayor's aides assert that Giuliani is trying. To that
end, there was a late addition to Sunday's mayoral schedule: he
would be meeting with Priscilla A. Wooten, a black City Council
member, and other civic leaders at a diner in Brooklyn. And after
that meeting, there would be a press conference.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
