u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GAY-MARRIAGE-MINISTER     03-27 0723
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAY-MARRIAGE-MINISTER-550&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MINISTER IS SUSPENDED FOR OFFICIATING IN GAY CEREMONY
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Ill., Neb)   (rk) 
 By   GUSTAV NIEBUHR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A United Methodist Church minister in Chicago, convicted of
breaking church law by officiating at the union of two gay men, has
been suspended from his duties.
</P>
<P>
   The penalty for the Rev. Greg Dell, which is to take effect in
July, was handed down by a jury of 13 Methodist ministers shortly
before midnight on Friday in the suburban Chicago church where the
trial began on Thursday. Earlier Friday, the jury found Dell guilty
of disobeying his denomination's ``order and discipline'' by
performing the ceremony last year.
</P>
<P>
   In handing down the penalty, among the toughest options
available, the jury said the suspension would end when Dell
submitted a written pledge to his bishop promising not to officiate
at another same-sex union, as long as the rule against the unions
remained.
</P>
<P>
   But afterward, Dell, 53, said he would never sign such a
document, a stand reflecting his oft-repeated statement that he
would not stop officiating at same-sex unions, because to do so
would contradict his understanding of his responsibilities as a
pastor to all the people in his congregation.
</P>
<P>
   Dell's conviction is the first under a 1996 United Methodist
rule forbidding ministers to conduct same-sex ceremonies. As such,
it is a landmark within the denomination that, with 8.5 million
members, is the nation's second-largest Protestant denomination,
after the Southern Baptist Convention.
</P>
<P>
   The trial was closely watched by Methodists, whose generally
centrist church contains a strong liberal wing with many members
who openly dissent from the rule against same-sex unions.
</P>
<P>
   The struggle over the issue will likely shift to northern
California, where a Methodist bishop filed a formal complaint on
Tuesday against 69 ministers who jointly officiated at the union of
two women in Sacramento in January, in a show of defiance against
the prohibition of same-sex unions.
</P>
<P>
   The cases derive from a sentence _ ``Ceremonies that celebrate
homosexual unions shall not be conducted by our ministers and shall
not be conducted in our churches'' _ that was inserted into the
denomination's rule book, ``The Book of Discipline'' by the
Methodists' top policy-making body, the General Conference, three
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Because the sentence was placed in a section of the book
containing advisory statements on such subjects as the environment,
racism and the use of tobacco, some Methodists viewed it as not
legally binding. In March 1998, in the only other trial held on the
issue, a Nebraska pastor, the Rev. Jimmy Creech, was narrowly
acquitted of disobedience to church law after his lawyers argued
that the sentence was advisory.
</P>
<P>
   But on Aug. 8, 1998, the church's Judicial Council, its highest
court, ruled that the sentence was binding. Six weeks later, Dell
conducted the service, which had been planned for several months.
</P>
<P>
   In interviews, Dell, who is married with an adult son and has
served as a minister for three decades, said his church, Broadway
United Methodist Church in Chicago's Lakeview neighborhood, has a
congregation that is about 30 percent gay and lesbian. To deny
those members any service that he would render to heterosexual
congregants, he said, would be discriminatory.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The jury initially scheduled Dell's suspension to begin July 1.
But retired Bishop Jack Tuell, a trained lawyer who acted as the
judge, agreed to delay the suspension until July 5, to allow Dell
to perform a wedding on July 3.
</P>
<P>
   But the bishop denied a request from Dell's counsel that the
suspension be delayed until after Oct. 23, the date of another
wedding Dell had been scheduled to perform.
</P>
<P>
   In his remarks afterward, Dell called the sentence a product of
``moralistic rigidity'' within the church. He said he would likely
appeal it and his conviction to the church's regional
jurisdiction..
</P>
<P>
   But the Rev. Stephen C. Williams, an Illinois pastor who served
as prosecutor, said he was ``very proud of the way the jury
deliberated to make this decision.'' He added, however, he would
have preferred a promise from Dell not to perform any more same-sex
ceremonies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
