<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-FLAG-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAPAN WEIGHS FORMAL STATUS FOR ITS FLAG AND ANTHEM  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By NICHOLAS D. KRISTOF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ The Japanese government is trying to rehabilitate the
flag of the rising sun and the national song of praise for the
Emperor, giving them legal status despite criticism that in World
War II they were emblematic of Japanese militarism.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi is preparing legislation to make
them the national flag and national anthem, although it is unclear
when the bill might actually become law.
</P>
<P>
   The flag, or hinomaru, and the song, called Kimigayo, have been
widely used in the postwar period. The hinomaru flies above
government offices and is used at state banquets, and Kimigayo is
played at sumo matches and at Olympic medal ceremonies when
Japanese athletes win.
</P>
<P>
   So their legal adoption would not make much practical
difference, beyond perhaps standardizing their forms. The
dimensions of the flag's design _ a red sun in the center of a
white rectangle _ varies, and there are several version of the
song.
</P>
<P>
   But formalizing them has been controversial because of the
associations with the war, and until now Japanese governments have
shied away from giving them legal status.
</P>
<P>
   Obuchi and his Cabinet officials argue that the sensitivities
left over from the war have faded enough both within Japan and
abroad to allow the present situation to be formalized. Still, in
the last few days Obuchi has signaled that he may proceed
cautiously because of criticism at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to follow the trend of public opinion, and the opinion
of the mass media,'' Obuchi told Japanese television last week.
</P>
<P>
   The willingness to raise the issue attests to Japan's growing
self-confidence, its discontent with the ambiguities left by the
war, its frustration with the criticism that erupts whenever it
tries to assert pride in its past, and its diminishing concern with
taboos connected to history.
</P>
<P>
   Obuchi and other officials note that there is nothing
intrinsically militaristic about the flag or anthem; the roots of
both go back many centuries. Kimigayo has no rockets' red glare or
bombs bursting in air or other war images. It is an ode to the
Emperor, a prayer for him to reign ``until the pebbles of today
have merged into boulders whose sides are lined with moss.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The song is understood as a prayer for the peace and
longstanding prosperity of the nation, with the Emperor
personifying the integration of people and country,'' Obuchi told
Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Critics say that the war left the flag and song as inextricably
linked to brutality as the swastika in Germany. So Japanese
pacifists and some countries in Asia have expressed concern about
the idea of giving them legal status.
</P>
<P>
   ``They bear testimony to a militaristic past which proved to be
the bane of Asia and indeed of Japan itself,'' said the Singapore
Straits Times in an editorial. It added that ``Tokyo has rekindled
a divisive national issue that may have repercussions for its image
abroad.''
</P>
<P>
   The Japan Teachers Union, which traditionally has leaned left
and been hostile to the flag and song, adopted a resolution urging
the government to wait until a consensus has been reached, but it
did not rule out the move. The Asahi Shimbun, Japan's most
influential newspaper, took a similar editorial position, urging
the government to ``steadily win consent from the public'' before
pushing the new law.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ten years ago or 20 years ago, I would have opposed this,''
said Yasuaki Onuma, a Tokyo University law professor who has
organized programs for Japanese to help Korean and other victims of
World War II. ``But frankly speaking, whether we should have this
as a customary rule or as a statutory rule does not seem so
important.''
</P>
<P>
   Since 1989, the Education Ministry has called for the flag and
song to be used in school graduations, and that is usually where
disputes arise. Prime Minister Obuchi decided to push for the law
after a high school principal killed himself Feb. 28 after being
caught in the middle of a dispute about whether to include Kimigayo
at this year's commencement.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the legislation will not address another void left over
from history: officially, Japan has no head of state. The functions
of head of state are usually taken up by the emperor, but putting
that into law would require a constitutional amendment, and for
now, no one is even talking about it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
