<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-27 16:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6535 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-D-DAY-MEMORIAL-550&AMP;AD     03-27 0902
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-D-DAY-MEMORIAL-550&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOPES FOR A MEMORIAL EBB WITH `PRIVATE RYAN' LOSS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Va.)  (lb) 
 By IAN ZACK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEDFORD, Va. _ Bob Slaughter hasn't bought a movie ticket since
his wife dragged him to see ``The Sound of Music'' way back in
1965. ``I have no interest whatsoever in that stuff,'' Slaughter, a
74-year-old retiree, said.
</P>
<P>
   But Slaughter, a crusading D-Day veteran, still found himself
glued to his television set last Sunday night for the interminable
Academy Awards broadcast, during which he rooted _ in vain, it
turned out _ for the Steven Spielberg film ``Saving Private Ryan''
to take home Best Picture honors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I stayed up till 1 o'clock or 1:30,'' he said. ``I was
disappointed that picture didn't get it.''
</P>
<P>
   So were the other board members of the National D-Day Memorial
Foundation, of which Slaughter is chairman, at its headquarters in
this city of 6,400, in the foothills of the Blue Ridge Mountains.
</P>
<P>
   The foundation was hoping that an Oscar sweep for the D-Day epic
would help it reach a $12 million fund-raising goal for the
construction of a major national memorial, a rarity outside
Washington. Congress chose Bedford as the site for the sprawling
nine-acre D-Day memorial in 1996, a nod to the community's
sacrifice on June 6, 1944, when it lost more men per capita in the
Normandy invasion than any other place in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The project, though, has fallen behind schedule. The foundation
has raised more than $8 million, but about $3 million of that
exists only as pledges and, without enough cash on hand, the
memorial's planners have postponed construction.
</P>
<P>
   The dedication of a ceremonial granite victory arch at the base
of the memorial, which had been planned for the 55th anniversary of
D-Day in June, has been delayed. And the completion date for the
memorial of June 6, 2000, is now in doubt.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, World War II veterans are not getting any younger.
</P>
<P>
   ``These men are all so anxious to see it,'' said Lucille Hoback
Boggess, who serves on the Bedford County Board of Supervisors and
who lost two brothers, ages 30 and 24, on D-Day.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-five Bedford men, including Raymond and Bedford Hoback,
were members of A Company, 116th Regiment of the 29th Infantry
Division, a Virginia National Guard unit that was part of the
invasion's first wave. Nineteen Bedforders were killed in a hail of
bullets soon after they leaped off landing boats on the shores of
Normandy. Two more died later in a day of ferocious fighting. At
the time, Bedford's population was only 3,200.
</P>
<P>
   Today, only two of Bedford's men from A Company survive.
</P>
<P>
   Spielberg's film, which captured the carnage and chaos of the
D-Day landing like no other, has brought the memorial project
untold publicity. The foundation had hoped to catch a final
windfall from the Oscars, and in anticipation of an Academy Award
for the film, placed a full-page advertisement in USA Today on
Monday. The advertisement began, ``It took our generation's
greatest storyteller to tell their generation's greatest story,''
and included a phone number to call, (800) 351-DDAY.
</P>
<P>
   Three pages away, the American Battle Monuments Commission,
raising money to build the National World War II Monument on the
Mall in Washington, ran its own full-page advertisement, featuring
Tom Hanks, the film's star. ``I guess they had the same idea we
did,'' Slaughter said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The D-Day memorial foundation's staff of five, working out of an
old corner newspaper office just down the block from Granny Greer's
General Store in downtown Bedford, has attracted some wealthy
donors for the memorial, including Charles Schulz, the ``Peanuts''
comic strip creator and a World War II veteran, who gave $1 million
and agreed to serve as chairman of the fund-raising drive.
</P>
<P>
   For now, the highest hill in Bedford remains just that, with two
wooden poles marking the place in the red clay where the victory
arch is to be place.
</P>
<P>
   The memorial's design has all the grandeur of a Washington
memorial, made more impressive by the surrounding peaks of the Blue
Ridge.
</P>
<P>
   The green, white and black arch _ inscribed with the invasion's
code name Operation Overlord _ will rise 44 feet, 6 inches, for the
year, month and day of D-Day.
</P>
<P>
   Leading up to the arch will be two plazas that will depict
Allied soldiers in bronze. Several grim-faced soldiers will be
shown wading through water onto the beach, while others will be
shown scaling the German fortress on their way to reaching the
arch. A 33,000-square-foot education center is also planned.
</P>
<P>
   Foundation officials expect more than 200,000 visitors annually
at the site, a four-hour drive southwest of Washington, and private
developers already have bought up much of the surrounding land,
expecting a market for hotels and restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   William McIntosh, the foundation's vice president for education,
hopes the memorial will show that the nation's heart exists outside
the Capital Beltway.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this could serve as a model for other national memorials
outside of Washington, then that would be a valuable thing,'' he
said. ``Right now, the implication is you can't be in the nation
unless you're in Washington. But the nation can be in Montana, the
nation can be in Pennsylvania, the nation can be in Virginia.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-27-99 1653EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990327.0151 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-27 16:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6536 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SWEDEN-WALLENBERGS-NY     03-27 1169
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWEDEN-WALLENBERGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A WARTIME SWEDISH TALE, IN REVISION  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By ALAN COWELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   STOCKHOLM, Sweden _ The setting: wartime Stockholm; neutral
capital, nest of spies. The players: two brothers, scions of
Sweden's mightiest business dynasty, one dealing with Hitler's
Germany, the other with Churchill's Britain. The question: whose
side were they on?
</P>
<P>
   More than a half century later, when Europe has been hit with a
wave of self-questioning over its wartime morality, the answer
might seem just one more footnote to history. But the brothers were
Wallenbergs _ prominent among the power elite that runs this land
and leaders of a business whose tentacles stretch across Europe. So
the answer has implications for the future of that business and for
the country's view of its own neutrality.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jacob Wallenberg was accused of a number of things over the
last couple of years, so we have gone back and looked for
answers,'' said his 43-year-old great-nephew, also called Jacob
Wallenberg. He is the chairman of the family bank, SEB, and a
senior figure in Investor AB, the family's financial arm.
</P>
<P>
   ``All we are intending to do is answer those points,'' he said.
``It is a direct response to the discussion that has been prevalent
in Sweden.''
</P>
<P>
   The name Wallenberg often evokes a distant cousin of the
financial players. Raoul Wallenberg was a diplomat who saved many
Jews in Nazi-occupied Hungary and who disappeared in the Soviet
Union at the end of the war to meet a fate that has never been
explained.
</P>
<P>
   In that era, the brothers Jacob and Marcus were, among many
other things, the owners of the factories that supplied roller
bearings to Hitler's war machine until 1944. They also sold roller
bearings to England.
</P>
<P>
   Their wartime dealings with Robert Bosch GmbH, a German company
founded in 1886 that became a world leader in automotive
electronics, provoked an uproar immediately after the war over a
transaction involving an American subsidiary.
</P>
<P>
   But there is another story, known to historians for decades, yet
only now emerging with texture and detail from the Wallenberg
family archives. The family has been offering those details on the
Internet to try to deflect any suggestion that the family tree is
tainted with collaboration.
</P>
<P>
   It is the story of those two brothers, who were not simply doing
a neutral country's business with Germany and England. They used
their unique position to provide a clandestine, risky and
high-level link between conspirators seeking to overthrow Hitler _
among them Carl Goerdeler, the mayor of Leipzig _ and close
advisers to Churchill.
</P>
<P>
   Even as that story emerges, some historians suggest other
details may follow as more archives are opened. The family
business, which began with a Stockholm bank in 1856, has grown and
diversified and now accounts for about 40 percent of the Swedish
stock market.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Wallenbergs were very shrewd businessmen, and I don't
think there was any sentimentality in their dealings with
Goerdeler,'' said Klemens von Klemperer, a historian at Smith
University who published a major work in 1992, ``German Resistance
Against Hitler: The Search for Allies Abroad, 1938-1945'' (Oxford
University Press).
</P>
<P>
   It was not until two years ago, when researchers chanced upon
sealed envelopes that had been kept in a vault apart from the
family archives, that many of the details emerged, said Anders
Perlinge, the family's chief archivist. They bore instructions that
only Jacob or Marcus should open them.
</P>
<P>
   Their descendants approved opening the envelopes. Inside, the
researchers found remarkable correspondence that offered insights
into a triangular relationship between Goerdeler, the Wallenberg
brothers in Stockholm and, in London, Charles Hambro, a peacetime
banker and wartime spy close to Churchill and other officials.
</P>
<P>
   The letters trace a desperate effort by Goerdeler to contact
Churchill and to win his support for an effort to overthrow Hitler.
When the doomed attempt was made, on July 20, 1944, Goerdeler was
among those arrested and executed.
</P>
<P>
   He first came into contact with the Wallenbergs before the war
as an adviser to the Bosch company in Stuttgart, which had close
ties with the Wallenbergs' firm. After the outbreak of war, Sweden
appointed negotiators to address its trade with the belligerents
under requirements of international law dealing with neutral
powers.
</P>
<P>
   Jacob Wallenberg was named as a negotiator with Germany because
he spoke the language and had business ties there, said Ulf Olsson,
a historian at Goeteborg University, and Marcus was appointed
Britain, where he had similar connections.
</P>
<P>
   Their companies, particularly the SKF ball bearing plant, thus
became part of a web of deals in which Sweden traded iron ore and
other products for German coal, coke and chemicals in transactions
financed partly by looted Nazi gold, according to several recent
histories.
</P>
<P>
   Arne Ruth, former editor of the Dagens Nyheter daily newspaper,
which has campaigned in recent years for openness about Sweden's
dealings with the Third Reich, the brothers ``had a double
function.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They were privately defining their business interests in
relation to the Allies and the Germans,'' he said. ``And they were
also diplomats defining official Swedish policy.''
</P>
<P>
   At another level, however, the Wallenbergs were playing an even
more complex game, according to a new study of the affair by Gert
Nylander, who was for many years the chief Wallenberg family
archivist.
</P>
<P>
   According to his study, which draws on the recently discovered
documents, ``business'' meetings between Carl Goerdeler and Jacob
Wallenberg were known to both the Nazi regime and the Swedish
government. But the meetings _ in Berlin and Stockholm between 1939
and 1943 _ were also a forum for ``concrete efforts at establishing
contacts between the German opposition and the British government,
with the active participation of the Wallenbergs,'' the study said.
</P>
<P>
   German generals who opposed Hitler wanted several commitments
from Churchill, including that allied bombing raids would cease
during a coup attempt and that there would be a chance to negotiate
peace terms. Churchill made no promises but did not discourage the
plotters, the latest Swedish documents suggest.
</P>
<P>
   The documents have been posted on a Web site
(http://arkiv.wallenberg.org), published in German and Scandinavian
historical journals and translated into English.
</P>
<P>
   But they have not answered everyone's questions. When a Swedish
historians' commission published findings on their country's
dealings with the Nazis, Salomo Berlinger, a member representing
Sweden's Jews, said ``more research should be done'' into the role
played by Swedish wartime business establish ``whether it prolonged
or contributed to prolonging the war.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Johannes Tuchel, director of the German Resistance Memorial
Center in Berlin, ``The last word about the Wallenbergs has not
been spoken.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
