<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PINOCHET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PINOCHET FACES 33 NEW COUNTS IN EXTRADITION CASE
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By WARREN HOGE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ The Spanish judge whose extradition request has kept
Gen. Augusto Pinochet under house arrest in London for the past
five months sent British prosecutors 33 new charges of human rights
abuses against the former Chilean dictator on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The judge, Baltasar Garzon, said that all the new allegations
relate to a period beginning in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   That date became critical to Pinochet's future Wednesday when
England's highest court, the Law Lords, ruled that the decision on
whether to proceed with the extradition case could be based only on
crimes alleged to have occurred after that date.
</P>
<P>
   That was the year in which torture overseas became a crime
punishable in Britain.
</P>
<P>
   The effect of the ruling was to eliminate 27 of the 30 original
charges of crimes against humanity, and the court directed British
Home Secretary Jack Straw to reconsider his earlier approval of the
extradition request now that the case was substantially weaker.
</P>
<P>
   Pinochet, 83, was arrested in London in October on Garzon's
request that he stand trial in Madrid on charges of genocide,
conspiracy to murder, kidnapping, hostage taking and torture in
connection with the deaths or disappearances of 3,000 people from
1973 to 1990, when he ruled Chile.
</P>
<P>
   A Crown Prosecution Service spokeswoman confirmed that her
office had received new information from Garzon Saturday, but she
refused comment on whether it would figure in Straw's review.
</P>
<P>
   Neil Durkin, a spokesman for Amnesty International, which
supports the effort to try Pinochet in Madrid, said, ``It's still
too early to be sure what the legal position on the new cases is.''
</P>
<P>
   The High Court has scheduled a hearing for Monday to hear a plea
from Pinochet's lawyers that the extradition effort should be ended
and that he should be allowed to return to Chile.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
