<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-27 17:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6552 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYS-BUDGET-BATTLE-600     03-27 1133
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYS-BUDGET-BATTLE-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALBANY DEMOCRATS MOVE WARILY, WITH EYE ON PATAKI'S VETO KNIFE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By CLIFFORD J. LEVY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Gov. George Pataki of New York used his veto power over the
state budget last year for the first time, boldly slicing more than
$1 billion in spending, it so startled Democratic lawmakers that it
has left them with a kind of political post-traumatic stress.
Worried, even panicked, that the governor will again wipe away
their programs, the Democrats have all but brought this year's
talks to a standstill as they hunt for a way to fend him off.
</P>
<P>
   Some call for quickly reconciling with him by meeting many of
his demands. Others urge hostile tactics, with the Democratic
majority in the Assembly stalling his proposals until he backs
down.
</P>
<P>
   All the choices are nettlesome, which is why the Democrats have
fallen back on the quintessential Albany strategy: delay. And that
means that the state is almost certain to miss the April 1 deadline
for a new budget for the 15th year in a row.
</P>
<P>
   At the heart of the Democrats' anxiety is this realization:
Pataki was running for re-election last year, but he still did not
shy from erasing more than 1,000 politically popular items in the
budget approved by the Legislature, from aid for school
construction to AIDS and cultural grants. This year, after coasting
to another term with little apparent damage from the vetoes, he
will no doubt be even less hesitant about invoking this authority.
</P>
<P>
   ``The governor's vetoes last year were a great surprise,'' said
Assemblyman Clarence Norman Jr., D-Brooklyn. ``It really put us on
notice that in this year's negotiations, there must be some type of
fail-safe position and method of insuring that those things we put
in the budget, that they are held harmless from the governor's
potential vetoes.''
</P>
<P>
   Determined to bolster his credentials as a fiscal conservative
as he broadens his national profile, Pataki wants the budget to
grow at no more than the rate of inflation, about 2 percent. His
archrivals, the Assembly Democrats, are seeking far more _ a 4
percent increase by their reckoning, and 8 percent in the
disdainful estimation of Pataki, who has repeatedly termed that
level unacceptable.
</P>
<P>
   Before last year, Pataki and Assembly Speaker Sheldon Silver, a
Democrat, would ultimately have reached some back-room compromise,
joined by the state Senate Majority Leader Joseph Bruno, a
Republican. But in 1998, glasnost swept through Albany, and instead
of negotiating the budget in private with the governor, Silver and
Bruno turned the job over to legislative committees, which reached
an agreement without a direct role for Pataki.
</P>
<P>
   Because he was not involved in the horse-trading, and so not
bound by any promises, Pataki had more freedom to wield his veto
knife. It was a defining moment in his tenure, and in recent days
it has seemed as if he is spoiling for a replay.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will exercise that constitutional power if it comes to
that,'' he said Thursday, referring to new vetoes.
</P>
<P>
   Reacting to such threats, the Assembly Democrats are mulling
options. The most drastic would be to reject the conference
committees and seek a return of the days when the three leaders
negotiated the budget in private. Pataki and Bruno would oppose
that, and it would represent a public relations stain for the
Assembly Democrats, given that the committees are considered a sign
that the Capitol is adopting late-20th-century government customs.
</P>
<P>
   Short of that, the Democrats hope to persuade Pataki to advise
the conference committees about their work, so they can avoid
proposals that might incur vetoes. It is not clear, though, how
much Pataki will oblige.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Silver could give up trying to lure Pataki into the process, and
instead seek to forge an alliance with Bruno, who is a longtime
Pataki ally but could yet turn traitorous. If Bruno would agree to
override Pataki vetoes, the Assembly Democrats could probably
protect their proposals. Last year, Bruno opposed an override,
unwilling to embarrass the governor while he was seeking
re-election.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Bruno will not rule out an override, and as a result he has
become a pivotal figure in the budget fight _ courted by both
Pataki and Silver.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate Republicans are seeking more of an increase than
Pataki, less than the Assembly Democrats. If the governor also
finds that route unacceptable, Bruno could desert him. The senator
might conclude that he needs the extra spending to help his members
win re-election in 2000. After all, it is easier for Pataki to be
tightfisted because he does not face the voters again until 2002.
(Last year, even with the vetoes, Pataki pushed through an
election-year budget with a 7 percent increase.)
</P>
<P>
   Bruno has not shown his cards yet, preferring to try to mediate
between Pataki and Silver, who dislike each other and mostly talk
through Bruno.
</P>
<P>
   In the budget battle, Silver has fewer bargaining chits than the
governor. Still, Silver has already refused to allocate money for
charter schools, a key Pataki program, knowing that he can try to
exchange that for the governor's approval on Democratic spending
items.
</P>
<P>
   Silver has criticized the Republicans for the impasse, saying
that Pataki introduced his budget late and Bruno has made it
difficult to agree on the amount available to spend. For the
speaker, though, delay is a time-honored tactic.
</P>
<P>
   Legislative leaders long ago realized that the public blames the
governor more than lawmakers for late budgets, largely because he
is better known. So the Legislature has often tried to gain the
upper hand by refusing to act on the budget.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the Assembly Democrats are hoping that if the dispute
drags on, they can link the late budget to Pataki's recent national
travels, portraying him as neglecting his duties at home in favor
of Republican politics.
</P>
<P>
   That strategy has one obvious pitfall. In return for winning
Pataki's support for a salary increase for lawmakers, the
Legislature agreed in December to a new law that withholds
lawmakers' pay after April 1 until they approve a budget. Pataki,
though, gets paid.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats, who increasingly grumble about the law, vow not to
cave in to the governor. They continue to assail the Pataki budget,
saying that it calls for unconscionable reductions in health care,
education and other programs.
</P>
<P>
   What will break the impasse? Silver was asked that question
Thursday, and he did not seem to have a ready answer. But he
appeared in no hurry to hurry things up. Maybe what is needed, he
said, with the budget deadline fast approaching, is ``some exposure
to the public as to what the issues are.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
