u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLA-HIALEAH-POLITICS-     03-27 1128
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-HIALEAH-POLITICS-630&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SOUTH FLORIDA STRONGMAN PUSHES FOR SECESSION 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HIALEAH, Fla. _ This city's heart and soul are apparent along
Okeechobee Road, which forms one of its borders with Miami:
auto-repair shops with names like Torres Tires; travel agencies
where one can book a fare or send money to a relative in Cuba;
accountants' and lawyers' offices where speaking in Spanish is
taken for granted.
</P>
<P>
   Yet there is perhaps no clearer symbol of this city of 190,000
than its seven-term mayor, Raul Martinez. And Martinez has big
plans for Hialeah: He wants to make it its own county.
</P>
<P>
   Tired of having Hialeah pay high taxes in exchange for what he
says are Miami-Dade County's deficient services, Martinez is
seeking to build a political moat within Florida's largest urban
center.
</P>
<P>
   ``Go and speak with other mayors,'' he said in an interview.
``Everybody complains of the lack of services by the county.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time that I've said, `Mr. County Manager, tell me the
services you're providing us,' he says, `Well, we give you this and
we give you that,''' Martinez added. ``Well, no, they don't, and
then when I point that out, I'm right.''
</P>
<P>
   A charismatic administrator who supervises everything from
buying street lamps to filling potholes, Martinez is known within
Hialeah as a strongman who gets things done. And his efficiency
extends to his own position. Last year his formidable power was
further strengthened with a new city charter that also increased
his salary by $30,000, to $152,702 a year, making him the
highest-paid mayor in the county.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez, 50, has been mayor since 1981, except for three years
when he was suspended from office after a federal grand jury
indicted him on racketeering and extortion charges. He was
convicted in 1991, but the conviction was overturned on appeal. Two
retrials ended in hung juries.
</P>
<P>
   In January he persuaded the City Council to approve a $1.2
million settlement with him for legal fees as well as for the
salary and interest he was denied during his suspension.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez attributes his legal troubles, which stemmed from
accusations that he had traded zoning favors to developers in
exchange for money and land deals, to perjury by the opposing side,
unethical prosecutors and political rivals.
</P>
<P>
   Around Miami, Martinez's bid to make his city a county, which he
first outlined a year ago, is seen as a ploy to gain additional
power.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez counters that his motives are purely practical. With
its own police, water and sewer systems, Hialeah is already able to
meet many of its daily needs, he said. The remaining assets
required by a county, like a hospital, a jail and a courthouse, can
be bought or contracted for, he added, with the $80 million to $100
million that the city currently pays Miami-Dade in taxes every
year.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez's complaints about the county administration have been
echoed by other cities and unincorporated areas that rely on the
county for everyday services. With more than 2 million residents, a
population larger than that of 17 states, and an area bigger than
Rhode Island, Miami-Dade County has, over the years, ballooned into
a megalopolis.
</P>
<P>
   In the process, the county's staff has grown to about 28,000,
more than the estimated populations of 19 of Florida's 67 counties.
Along with this growth, Martinez and others say, has come increased
inefficiency and corruption. Cities like Miami Beach and Coral City
have complained that the county's resources are spread too thin to
provide the services they need to function. Opa Locka, just north
of Hialeah, has also spoken of secession.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our present structure needs some adjustment,'' said state Rep.
Willie Logan, a Democrat who represents Opa Locka. ``People are
feeling as if they don't have access to our government, because the
government is too far removed.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Many observers believe that Martinez's proposal also stems from
his bitter rivalry with Alex Penelas, the 37-year-old mayor of
Miami-Dade County and a fellow Cuban-American.
</P>
<P>
   As Democrats, both men break from the mold of most
Cuban-Americans here. The two first met in the late 1980s when
Penelas, a newcomer to politics, received the backing of Martinez
for a seat on Hialeah's City Council.
</P>
<P>
   Penelas was elected to the county leadership in 1996, while
Martinez remained in Hialeah, his career path narrowed by the
federal case against him. In the 1997 elections, Penelas backed
Martinez's opponent, Herman Echevarria. And while the county mayor
is sometimes cited as a possible future presidential hopeful, the
city mayor bemoans the fact that his legal troubles have thwarted
his ambition of becoming a congressman or an ambassador.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of Martinez's strategy is to hurt Penelas,'' said Dario
Moreno, a professor of political science at Florida International
University, ``and so far he has been winning the political battle.
He has gotten all of the attention. It's a very effective tool to
point out the shortcomings of the Penelas administration.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez denied that his intention was to push the county mayor
into the political shadows, but he spoke openly about his feelings
for Penelas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have different styles,'' he said. ``He deals with press
conferences, and I deal with facts and I deal with issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Penelas said that his opposition to Hialeah's bid for countyhood
rested on purely legal arguments.
</P>
<P>
   As for his rivalry with Martinez, he said, ``I happen to respect
and like Martinez tremendously; this is not an issue of rivalry of
any sort.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, Martinez set his quest for secession in
motion by asking two state legislators to file bills in the Florida
House and Senate. So far, the Senate bill has won support in the
first of several committees it must go through before being
submitted for a full vote. It calls for a special election in 2000
to let Hialeah residents decide on countyhood.
</P>
<P>
   Penelas argues that only Miami-Dade County, through a special
home rule law that allows it to define its borders, can authorize a
change in Hialeah's status.
</P>
<P>
   As long as the legal road to secession remains in dispute, few
believe that Hialeah will become a county any time soon. At most,
analysts say, the debate will serve to open a wedge of dissent that
may expose the perils of an urban sprawl that has quietly outpaced
political consensus.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the bill will get through the state
Legislature,'' said Marsha Matson, an instructor in political
science at the University of Miami and a critic of the county
administration. ``But it might in the future if the county does not
reform itself.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
