<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TITANIC-WRECKAGE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT RULING ALLOWS TRIPS TO THE TITANIC  
(DW) 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Newfoundland, France, New Guinea)   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The company salvaging the wreckage of the Titanic has exclusive
rights to the ship's artifacts but it cannot keep others from
visiting and photographing the wreckage, a federal appeals court
has ruled.
</P>
<P>
   The decision on Tuesday by a three-judge panel of the 4th U.S.
Court of Appeals, in Richmond, Va., overturned a federal district
judge's ruling last year that the company RMS Titanic, which won
the salvage rights in 1994, could ban anyone else from a 10-mile
radius of the wreckage.
</P>
<P>
   Deep Ocean Expeditions, an adventure tour company that wants to
run tours of the wreckage, appealed the lower court decision,
contending that a company's rights to wreckage under conventional
maritime salvage law does not extend to the water surrounding it.
</P>
<P>
   Deep Ocean can now go ahead with an expedition this summer, for
which passengers will pay about $35,000 to ride in mini-submarines
that can dive to depths of 12,500 feet.
</P>
<P>
   Alex Blanton, a lawyer for Deep Ocean, said the company was
pleased with the decision. ``All our client ever wanted to do was
visit the wreck site and take pictures, and the court upheld that
right,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Deep Ocean's owner, Mike McDowell, was leading a diving
expedition off New Guinea and was unavailable for comment.
</P>
<P>
   The appellate court did affirm the lower court's ruling that RMS
Titanic had exclusive rights to artifacts from the liner, and ``we
are pleased with that,'' said Bradford Stillman, a lawyer for the
company.
</P>
<P>
   The company realized that its request for photography rights was
``novel,'' Stillman said, but had hoped to bring in extra money to
pay for restoration and exhibition of the artifacts.
</P>
<P>
   The wreckage of the Titanic, which hit an iceberg in the North
Atlantic on her maiden voyage in April 1912, killing 1,503
passengers and crew members, was found 400 miles off Newfoundland
in 1985 by a team of French and American scientists. RMS Titanic
claimed salvage rights by being the first company to consistently
recover artifacts from the wreckage two years later. It has
profited from displaying thousands of artifacts at exhibitions
around the world.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-27-99 1747EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990327.0163 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-27 17:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6556 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INMATE-APPEAL-ART-2TA     03-27 1028
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INMATE-APPEAL-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAITH AND FRIENDSHIP FUEL 12-YEAR QUEST FOR NEW MURDER TRIAL
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., N.C.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204.) 
(rk) 
 By   DAVID W. CHEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUBURN, N.Y. _ On a snowy afternoon in March 1986, someone
fatally stabbed an inmate named Tyrone Julius at the Clinton
Correctional Facility in Dannemora. Sixteen months later, David
Wong, a Chinese illegal immigrant who was serving time for armed
robbery, was convicted of second-degree murder in Julius' death and
sentenced to 25 years to life in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Ordinarily, the case of Wong, prisoner No. 84-A-5320, would not
attract much notice. But this story is different, not only because
interviews with prison employees, inmates and Julius' widow
strongly suggest that Wong is innocent of murder, but also because
Wong has found unconditional support from a group of indefatigable
strangers in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   For the last decade, members of the David Wong Support Committee
have huddled every few weeks to fight for his release. They have
talked to Chinese government officials and college audiences around
the country. They have hired lawyers to handle his appeal. And they
have organized fund-raisers for his defense _ including a banquet
in Chinatown this month that drew 230 supporters and $8,000 in
donations.
</P>
<P>
   They have been so moved by Wong's case that at least eight
members have become lawyers to fight for people like Wong and
against a justice system that they believe is tilted against
immigrants and members of minority groups.
</P>
<P>
   What has ultimately sustained this long-running, long-distance
relationship, though, is not just philosophy or politics. It is
something simpler: an unexpected flowering of trust and friendship
through handwritten letters, late-night phone calls and occasional
prison visits, proving that the most intimate of connections can
sometimes emerge in the most trying of circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   ``As the years wear on, the political issues are still there,
but at another level it's really a human relationship, because
we're like a family now,'' said Patti Choy, 45, a career counselor
at the Fashion Institute of Technology in Manhattan and a member of
the committee. ``He knows our life; he knows all these little
things. And his letters? Just amazing. We sometimes can't get over
how we've all aged together.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, Wong's cause has taken on even more urgency. In weeks,
maybe days, a state Court of Appeals judge, George Bundy Smith, is
expected to decide whether to hear one last appeal for a new trial.
</P>
<P>
   If the answer is no, which seems likely, then the last resort is
a federal habeas corpus petition, said Gabor Rona, Wong's lawyer at
the Center for Constitutional Rights in Manhattan. In such a
petition, Wong would argue that his federal constitutional rights
had been violated and that he should be released. But such
petitions are rarely granted, so there is a gathering sense that
Wong's uphill battle may soon be over.
</P>
<P>
   But oddly enough, Wong's supporters are fretting more than the
soft-spoken, diminutive Wong is.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look at success or failure not in terms of whether my appeal
will succeed,'' Wong, 35, said during an interview at the Auburn
Correctional Facility, where he is now incarcerated. ``I think my
success is how much I and those wonderful people accomplish to make
the system a little bit better.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before, I didn't care about anybody, and nobody cared about
me,'' said Wong, who grew up poor in the rural Fujian province of
China and in Hong Kong before being smuggled to New York as a
teen-ager. ``But now, they have made me see the good side of human
nature.''
</P>
<P>
   One reason so many people believe Wong is that he did not reach
out to them initially. Instead, another inmate at Dannemora, Tse
Kin Cheung, wrote to people active in Asian-American affairs to say
that Wong, who barely speaks English, had been framed.
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, Yuri Kochiyama, a longtime civil rights advocate,
visited Wong in prison. He told her that yes, he had participated
in an armed robbery on Long Island in 1983. But no, he said, he did
not kill Julius; he had never even met him.
</P>
<P>
   Impressed, Mrs. Kochiyama established the David Wong Support
Committee. Eventually, the committee persuaded William M. Kunstler,
the famed civil rights lawyer, and the Center for Constitutional
Rights to take the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``David was just straightforward,'' said Mrs. Kochiyama, 77, who
acts as host for the committee's meetings at her Harlem apartment.
``We knew that he was a guy who had been unjustly treated, and that
he needed support.''
</P>
<P>
   He has received that support from a mostly Asian-American
assortment of more than 40 students, professionals and blue-collar
workers.
</P>
<P>
   Norman Wong, for instance, covered David Wong's murder trial as
a reporter for a Chinese-language newspaper in New York City.
Angered by the verdict, he quit journalism and eventually became a
lawyer specializing in asylum cases. (Norman Wong is not related to
David Wong.)
</P>
<P>
   For Wayne Lum, a postal clerk, the case has been so inspiring
that he occasionally shepherds his wife and three children to the
meetings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see this as a defining element in my life,'' Lum said.
``Before, it's like, you go to work, you have dinner, watch a
little TV, go to sleep. But now, I'm committed to these justice
issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Those emotions crested at the recent Chinatown banquet, which
featured speeches, music, a raffle. But the highlight, no doubt,
was a recording of Wong's voice, reiterating his innocence.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   About 4 p.m. on March 12, 1986, someone used a five- or six-inch
blade to stab Julius, 32, a recent arrival at the state prison in
Dannemora who had been convicted of second-degree murder in
Manhattan. The nape wound was so severe that Julius did not finish
his step, and he collapsed. He died 11 days later.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 70 to 100 inmates in the prison yard who hovered over
Julius, only Wong and Cheung were searched. Investigators found no
weapon and no blood on either man.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Wong's trial began in July 1987 in Clinton County Court, and
hinged on the testimony of Richard LaPierre, a prison guard who had
spotted Wong near the scene through his binoculars, from a tower
more than 100 yards away, and Peter DellFava, an inmate with a long
record of forgery, grand larceny and other crimes. A week later, an
all-white jury convicted Wong.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent interview, however, a former prison employee said
the consensus among employees and inmates was that Wong ``did not
do it.'' And a guard who works at Dannemora now and was in the yard
that day said the scene was too hectic, with many similarly dressed
inmates milling about, to discern what had happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``My personal self, I could not pin that incident on that guy,''
said the guard, speaking on the condition of anonymity. ``I was
surprised, because he got along with people and he was never a
problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Several former inmates were more blunt: They said they had seen
who killed Julius, and the killer was not Wong.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Ballinger, who was released from prison in 1996 after
serving time for burglary, said Julius was attacked by two Hispanic
men from New York City in retaliation for an earlier scuffle at
Rikers Island.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was payback time,'' said Ballinger, who now lives in North
Carolina. ``It was so quick and smooth that the average person
wouldn't have noticed it. They were standing there, laughing.''
</P>
<P>
   At the time of the stabbing, though, few people vouched for Wong
because they were worried about prison grudges, said Cheung, who
now lives in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
   ``A C.O. told me that they got the wrong guy,'' said Cheung,
referring to a corrections officer. ``A lot of inmates knew it,
too. But anybody who snitches, they can get killed.''
</P>
<P>
   In New York City, Sharon Julius, Julius' widow, said she, too,
had heard that her husband was killed because of an altercation at
Rikers Island. A friend of her husband even warned her that his
killer had not been caught, and that she should exercise caution in
pursuing a wrongful-death lawsuit against the state, she said.
</P>
<P>
   A year or so after her husband's death, she said, she received
an anonymous letter and two threatening phone calls from men who
told her to stop investigating the incident _ or else. She
complied, fearful for the safety of her three children.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always assumed that the real killers were still out
there,'' said Mrs. Julius, who had never even heard of Wong _ much
less been informed that anyone had been convicted _ before a
reporter contacted her. ``Whoever really did it, I'd really like to
know. I want to see justice served. Absolutely.''
</P>
<P>
   To prosecutors in Clinton County the record has always been
clear, however. Since his conviction, Wong has lost every major
appeal, District Attorney Penelope D. Clute said. And even the
county judge, Charles H. Lewis, described Wong as ``coldblooded''
as the trial ended.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Rona says, Wong's defense in a case so dependent on the
credibility of witnesses was compromised by several factors. He
listed the following:
</P>
<P>
   Wong's original lawyers failed to interview potential witnesses
like Ballinger. The jury did not know that prosecutors had
recommended parole for DellFava And there were weaknesses in
LaPierre's testimony, including his acknowledgment that he did not
see the stabbing or the weapon.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Rona said, Wong did not have a translator who could
speak his native Fuzhou dialect. Jo-An Ting, a secretary who had
never worked as a translator before, spoke Mandarin _ a dialect
that Wong could barely speak.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was nervous to do the job; I was not a professional,'' Mrs.
Ting said.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, Chinese who have recently immigrated to the
United States have shunned Wong, wary, perhaps, of associating with
an illegal immigrant convicted of a crime.
</P>
<P>
   Even Wong's closest blood relative here _ a niece who lives in
Binghamton _ has visited him in prison only once.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, committee members have had to overcome language
problems, since Wong's English is uneven and few committee members
can speak Chinese.
</P>
<P>
   But that has not prevented supporters and Wong from developing
siblinglike bonds.
</P>
<P>
   Joannie C. Chang, one of several students-turned-lawyers, has
mailed care packages to Wong stocked with Chinese goods like wheat
gluten and grass jelly.
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago, she drove seven or eight hours from Manhattan
to remote Clinton County, in northern New York about 10 miles from
the Canadian border, in an attempt to persuade Mrs. Ting to
acknowledge formally that she had botched the translation.
</P>
<P>
   And while she now lives in San Francisco, Ms. Chang still
corresponds with Wong. Once, after she excitedly mentioned her
participation in an approaching fund-raiser for AIDS patients, Wong
mailed her a small donation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was so touched by that,'' said Ms. Chang, 30. ``It makes you
admire him even more.''
</P>
<P>
   Maggie Ho and Ricky Sin personalized their connection in another
way, visiting Wong's family during a trip to Hong Kong in 1996. His
mother, they said, had been despondent about her only son, but came
alive when she discovered that others cared about him, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was extremely emotional for everyone; our eyes were really
watery,'' said Ms. Ho, 31, a social worker who now lives in
Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   Should Wong's appeal prevail, he would be deported to Hong Kong
or China. Should it fail, he would be eligible for parole on Jan.
15, 2017.
</P>
<P>
   But he is not circling that date just yet. Instead, he is
looking forward to April 10, when as many as 20 committee members
plan to make the six-hour drive to Auburn to help celebrate his
36th birthday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
