<DOCNO> NYT19990327.0169 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-27 17:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6570 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POLICE-BRUTALITY-TRIA     03-27 1044
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLICE-BRUTALITY-TRIAL-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JURY SELECTION TO BEGIN IN POLICE BEATING CASE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By JOSEPH P. FRIED   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ More than a year and a half after a Haitian immigrant
named Abner Louima was reportedly brutalized by police officers in
Brooklyn, jury selection is to begin Monday for the trial of four
officers charged with attacking him and of a sergeant accused of
joining them in an attempted cover-up.
</P>
<P>
   As many as 600 prospective jurors are to arrive in U.S. District
Court in Brooklyn to begin the jury-selection process in the
racially and politically charged case, even as the city's attention
is focused on a similarly explosive case involving a more recent
encounter between a black man and white police officers: the
killing in the Bronx last month of an unarmed West African
immigrant, Amadou Diallo, by four officers who fired 41 bullets at
him. Those four officers were reportedly indicted Thursday on
second-degree murder charges.
</P>
<P>
   As with the Diallo case, Louima's confrontation with the police
in August 1997 _ in which prosecutors say he was tortured in a
bathroom at the 70th Precinct station house in Flatbush after being
beaten in a police car _ led to mass public protests and charges
that Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's administration had set a tone that
fostered police brutality and abuse against members of minority
groups.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani was swift in terming the accusations in the Louima case
``shocking to any decent human being'' and in declaring that if
they were proved, the officers involved should receive
``substantial terms of imprisonment.''
</P>
<P>
   A final flurry of pretrial papers filed in the Louima case last
week shows that the evidence is expected to include clashing
testimony by medical experts over how Louima received the most
severe of the injuries he suffered on the morning of Aug. 9, 1997,
when he was arrested in a brawl outside a Haitian nightclub on
Flatbush Avenue. Louima's injuries included a perforated rectum and
a damaged bladder that kept him hospitalized for two months.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors say the injuries were inflicted when one of the four
70th Precinct officers who arrested Louima, Justin Volpe, rammed a
stick into his rectum and then his mouth while he was handcuffed in
a bathroom in the station house. Another of the officers, Charles
Schwarz, held him down, prosecutors say.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the two officers have denied that their clients
committed these acts, though the lawyers have not said in their
court arguments how Louima, who is 32, married and the father of
two young children, might have suffered his injuries.
</P>
<P>
   But in one of the papers filed last week, a prosecutor suggested
that he anticipated that Volpe's lawyer, Marvyn Kornberg, might
argue at the trial that Louima received his injuries in an act of
sodomy before his encounter with the police.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutor, Alan Vinegrad, chief of the criminal division in
the U.S. attorney's office in Brooklyn, said in a letter to defense
lawyers and to the trial judge, Eugene Nickerson, that he intended
to call a medical expert who ``will testify that, in his opinion,
the injuries to Abner Louima's rectum and bladder were caused by a
blunt object being forcefully inserted into his rectum while he was
either in a prone or bent-over position.''
</P>
<P>
   The expert ``will further testify that the injuries were not
caused by a penis,'' Vinegrad said, and that they did occur ``at a
time consistent with the government's theory.''
</P>
<P>
   In his own papers last week, Kornberg said he would call three
medical experts who were expected to testify that the internal
injuries ``are inconsistent with forcible insertion of a blunt
object in his rectum.'' The papers do not say whether the experts
will state how they think Louima was hurt, or what Kornberg may
offer as a possible cause.
</P>
<P>
   Kornberg declined to provide this information to a reporter,
saying ``I will not comment on what I will argue,'' or on any other
aspect of the trial. Vinegrad similarly said he would not discuss
the trial. ``We intend to present our evidence in the courtroom and
not before,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But when he announced the indictment of Volpe and the other
officers 13 months ago, Zachary Carter, the U.S. attorney in
Brooklyn, said that Louima's injuries had resulted from an assault
of ``singular depravity'' by police officers.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, in a civil suit that Louima's lawyers filed for him
against the officers, the city and other parties, the lawyers
termed Louima a victim of ``one of the most shameful, vicious and
cruel acts of police brutality in the history of New York City.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Volpe, 26, and Schwarz, 33, Officers Thomas
Bruder, 32, and Thomas Wiese, 35, are to be tried. They are not
accused of torturing Louima with the stick, but of joining Volpe
and Schwarz in beating him in a police car before they arrived at
the station. The sergeant to be tried, Michael Bellomo, 37, is not
charged in either assault but with trying to cover up the alleged
beating in the police car.
</P>
<P>
   Volpe is also charged with beating a second Haitian immigrant,
Patrick Antoine, near the nightclub, and the sergeant is accused of
joining Volpe in arresting Antoine on false charges.
</P>
<P>
   All the defendants say the charges against them are untrue.
Their lawyers have rejected any implications that the officers
harbor racist attitudes, pointing out that Volpe's girlfriend and
Wiese's fiancee are black.
</P>
<P>
   Volpe and Schwarz could face sentences of up to life in prison
if convicted of the charge of violating Louima's civil rights by
sexually assaulting him with a stick, and Bruder, Wiese and Bellomo
could face up to 10 years in prison if convicted of the charges
against them. The officers and sergeant have been suspended with
pay and are free on $100,000 bonds pending the outcome of the
trial.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from the medical testimony, prosecution evidence is
expected to include Louima's testimony and testimony by Officer
Eric Turetzky, who reportedly told investigators he saw Louima with
his pants around his ankles being taken by Volpe away from the
bathroom area to the cell area of the station house.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Kornberg has indicated that he will challenge Turetzky's
account, and will seek to call Louima's credibility into question
by highlighting such matters as his retraction of a statement that
the officers who attacked him said, ``This is Giuliani time, not
Dinkins time'' (a reference to David Dinkins, who preceded Giuliani
as mayor).
</P>
<P>
   Jury selection is expected to take about three weeks, involving
a questionnaire of more than 40 pages and courtroom interviews that
will seek to determine things like the potential jurors' knowledge
and opinions of the Louima case and their views about police
treatment of minority-group members generally.
</P>
<P>
   Prospective jurors in federal court in Brooklyn are not drawn
only from that borough, but also come from Queens, Staten Island
and Long Island. As a result, the pool of prospective jurors at the
courthouse generally has fewer blacks than the pool of potential
jurors in state and local courts in Brooklyn, which are drawn only
from that borough.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Heinemann, the federal court's clerk, declined to make
public figures that he said had been gathered several years ago for
``internal use'' involving the racial makeup of jurors at the his
courthouse.
</P>
<P>
   The defense lawyers sought to have the trial moved out of New
York City, or at least postponed, on the ground that the intensive
news coverage of the Diallo and Louima cases had so inflamed public
sentiment that impartial jurors would be impossible to find.
Nickerson rejected the request, though he said he would reconsider
if the selection process bore out the lawyers' claim.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
