<SLUG> BC-NY-POLICE-GIULIANI-NYT </SLUG>
  
 McCALL SEES CONCILIATORY TONE IN MEETING WITH GIULIANI  
 (bl)  
 By ROBERT D. McFADDEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ New York Comptroller H. Carl McCall, the state's
highest-ranking black elected leader, met privately with Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani at Gracie Mansion for more than an hour Saturday
and came away with the impression that the mayor had begun to
regret his longstanding lack of dialogues with minority leaders.
</P>
<P>
   The 75-minute meeting over bagels, lox and fruit was the first
between McCall and the mayor since Nov. 30, 1994, a drought that
reflected tensions between the Republican mayor and the Democratic
comptroller, and Giuliani's general absence of rapport with black
and Hispanic elected and civic leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani, who in recent days has softened his caustic tone and
begun a series of meetings with minority leaders in response to
mounting criticism of his administration's aggressive police
policies and to protests in the Amadou Diallo case, did not comment
immediately on his meeting with McCall, one of more than 1,000
people voluntarily arrested in the protests.
</P>
<P>
   But the comptroller, while declining to go into detail about
what they had discussed or whether they had agreed upon anything,
called the meeting cordial, frank and wide-ranging. He said the
mayor had apparently learned much from his recent talks with
minority leaders and seemed to regret not having held such talks
before.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has found them to be very, very useful and productive,''
McCall said. ``He has indicated that he really did make a mistake
in terms of not having that kind of dialogue earlier. He's learned
a lot from it.''
</P>
<P>
   The comptroller suggested that he, too, regretted the long
silence between them.
</P>
<P>
   ``As you know,'' he said, ``I haven't had the opportunity to
meet with the mayor for four and a half years. We had a very frank
discussion about a wide-ranging set of issues, from the present
crisis with the Police Department to education to welfare reform.
They are the kinds of things that I had wished the mayor and I had
been conferring on and having dialogue over the last number of
years.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about whether they had discussed current issues in the
city _ strained relationships between the police and minority
groups and the indictment of four Street Crime Unit officers in the
killing of Diallo _ McCall said he and the mayor did not discuss
the Diallo case specifically, and agreed only to continue their
talks, though no date for further discussions was set.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting itself, rather than what was said, was significant,
he suggested. ``It was important to establish a working
relationship with the chief executive of the city,'' McCall said.
``I've been trying to do that for a long time. The priority for me
was to see that the mayor was interested in having this kind of
dialogue.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani met with 10 members of the City Council's Black and
Latino Caucus at Gracie Mansion on Friday night, and afterward,
sounding almost contrite, called it the ``beginning of an important
dialogue.'' He added: ``I wish we'd had this meeting earlier. It
might be I made a mistake in not being more open to meetings like
this.''
</P>
<P>
   There was no protest outside Police Headquarters on Saturday _
they have been held only on weekdays since March 9 _ but more than
200 supporters and allies of the Rev. Al Sharpton rallied at his
National Action Network headquarters on 125th Street and vowed to
continue their campaign of civil disobedience for what they call
justice in the Diallo case and reforms in the Police Department.
</P>
<P>
   A day after Police Commissioner Howard Safir announced major
changes in the Street Crime Unit _ adding 50 minority members to
the overwhelmingly white unit and putting its plainclothes members
into uniform _ Sharpton said the moves were not enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want Safir to know that we're not talking about costume
changes,'' Sharpton told a cheering crowd. ``We want to deal with
the function and not the uniform. We don't want to be beaten by
blacks and Latinos. We want the beating to stop.''
</P>
<P>
   Sharpton also expressed skepticism about Giuliani's willingness
to meet with minority leaders, calling it a ploy to divide them and
dilute their fight against police brutality. He insisted that
alliances that had been built in the protest campaign would be
preserved.
</P>
<P>
   Others attending the meeting included Manhattan Borough
President C. Virginia Fields; Rep. Jose Serrano, a Democrat-Liberal
of the Bronx, and Norman Siegel, executive director of the New York
Civil Liberties Union.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Fields, who met Giuliani on Wednesday for the first time in
15 months, said that the coalition of black and Hispanic leaders
and their allies in civil liberties, labor and religious groups
would remain united in their approach to Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going through that door with the same message,'' she
said, ``and the message is: we must use our influence wherever we
sit, because we need change in this city and this country.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
