<SLUG> BC-YUGOSLAVIA-SURGERIES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICAN LEAVES YUGOSLAVIA AFTER HELPING WITH SURGERIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARY SANCHEZ  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OVERLAND PARK, Kan. _ It's a quiet night here in Zagreb. The
Croatian people are delighted that America is bombing Serbia:
``They're finally getting a taste of what they dealt us.''
</P>
<P>
   The writing is an e-mail Overland Park anesthesiologist Robert
Reid sent his wife Friday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   To Annette Reid, the message is assurance that her husband had
escaped a war zone and made it to safe territory.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Reid is part of an American medical team who escaped into
Croatia after being trapped in Belgrade when NATO began bombing
Serbia. Reid was helping with children's heart operations in a
Serbian hospital.
</P>
<P>
   NATO hopes the American-led air strikes will stop the slaughter
of Kosovo's ethnic Albanian majority by Serbian forces.
</P>
<P>
   Reid was expected to return to Kansas City this weekend,
provided that a German airline will fly its routes in Croatian
airspace.
</P>
<P>
   At home with their two young children, Reid's wife has been
glued to CNN broadcasts, worried for her husband's safety.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see the people trashing the embassies and you just wonder,
what would they do with a couple of Americans if they found them?''
Annette Reid said.
</P>
<P>
   The fear is not unfounded.
</P>
<P>
   In his e-mails, Reid said he wasn't concerned about the bombing
while he was working in a Belgrade hospital as part of the Memphis,
Tenn.-based International Children's Heart Foundation. But he was
alarmed at the ``rapidly escalating'' hatred of Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Many Serbians blame the United States for the NATO bombing.
</P>
<P>
   The e-mail continues: Women were screaming at me, ``How can you
kill children?'' They have no idea what their own troops have been
doing to the Kosovo people.
</P>
<P>
   In an e-mail sent Thursday to his wife, Reid said all outside
news had been blocked and the Serbian people were only hearing
``gross propaganda.'' He said they were being told no military
sites were being hit by the air strikes, but 10 civilian sites had
been targets. Also, the news said the United States planned to bomb
elementary schools next.
</P>
<P>
   Reid and the rest of the medical team fled Belgrade with the
help of both Serbian and Croatian people.
</P>
<P>
   A Platte County nurse who was part of the same team arrived home
late Thursday night. Marilyn Maddox left Belgrade by bus before the
bombing began.
</P>
<P>
   The medical team has an ongoing relationship with the Mother and
Child Health Care Institute, the Belgrade hospital. Reid had worked
there before.
</P>
<P>
   The foundation works in Croatia and Serbia, as well as many
other countries. The eight-person team came to Belgrade after being
invited by the Ministry of Health, said Lisa Estes, executive
director of the Children's Foundation in Memphis.
</P>
<P>
   Early Friday, the Minister of Internal Affairs in Belgrade
arranged for a car to take the medical team to the Serbian-Croatian
border. A Serbian doctor from the hospital also accompanied the
group in another car, Estes said.
</P>
<P>
   Croatian doctors that the foundation works with met the team at
the border, Estes said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were deeply concerned,'' Estes said. ``Our communication
with them was sporadic because it was very hard to get through on
telephone lines.''
</P>
<P>
   For Reid, this was not the first time he has fled a country he
was giving medical help to through the foundation.
</P>
<P>
   In September, Palestinian officials drove him from that country
when a conflict broke out with Israel.
</P>
<P>
   At home with their children, 6-year-old Ellen and 4-year-old
Eric, Annette Reid said she was only a little surprised her husband
decided to stay in the country after the bombings began.
</P>
<P>
   ``They wanted to get as much done as they could because those
people wait and wait for months to get the operations.''
</P>
<P>
   Without the heart operations, considered routine in America, the
children will die, said Maddox, who fled Belgrade on Tuesday.
Maddox and a New York doctor decided to leave when peace
negotiations broke down.
</P>
<P>
   Maddox and the doctor got the last two seats on a double-decker
bus that took them to an airport in a neighboring country.
</P>
<P>
   The trip normally takes about five hours, but theirs took 10,
including four hours spent stopped at the border. Their passports
were temporarily confiscated and Maddox's luggage was searched.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't talk much on the bus,'' Maddox said. ``We didn't
want to draw any attention to ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Maddox said the team hoped to perform at least 18 surgeries. But
it was behind because the cases were more complicated than
expected.
</P>
<P>
   For a while, she was particularly concerned about one infant.
</P>
<P>
   The baby was on the operating table when air raid sirens blew
and the hospital's electricity went out, possibly as part of a
blackout so it would not be hit by bombs.
</P>
<P>
   The baby was on a bypass machine, meaning its blood had been
drained from the heart so repairs could be made.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if they had a backup generator or some sort of
battery,'' she said. ``I guess that baby might have died.''
</P>
<P>
   But in an e-mail sent to his wife Wednesday, Reid said the
infant was doing fine.
</P>
<P>
   Reid wrote: Our 14-day-old Jatene Switch was doing well. I'm
quite happy about that case.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
