<HEADER>
A6599 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TERMINATION-LAWSUIT-K     03-27 0836
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TERMINATION-LAWSUIT-KAN </SLUG>
  
 Woman wins lawsuit against Kansas  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DONALD BRADLEY  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Caryn McCue Woltkamp has won her fight
against those she calls the ``good ol' boys'' at the Kansas
Department of Human Resources.
</P>
<P>
   The department paid $510,000 this month to Woltkamp, who claimed
in a federal lawsuit that high-ranking officials conspired against
her and eventually fired her after she accused her immediate boss
of sexual harassment. She said he repeatedly asked her for sex,
groped her in the office and pleaded to take nude pictures of her.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the Human Resources Department's duty is to protect
state employees from sexual harassment.
</P>
<P>
   Woltkamp, 37, prevailed in a 1996 jury trial in U.S. District
Court, and the verdict was later upheld on appeal. Attorneys
representing the department recently decided against asking the
U.S. Supreme Court to consider the case.
</P>
<P>
   The jury originally awarded Woltkamp $300,000. Legal fees and
interest pushed the amount to $510,000.
</P>
<P>
   The court judgment ends a six-year struggle that took Woltkamp _
a single mother at the beginning _ from investigating unemployment
claims in Topeka, Kan., to waiting tables in Peculiar, Mo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad I did it, but I'm glad it's finally over,'' Woltkamp
said. ``They took a part of me that I don't think I'll ever get
back.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kansas attorney general's office said Thursday that the
state disagreed with the original verdict and still maintains its
innocence. The judgment was paid because the state had run out of
legal options, said Assistant Attorney General John Cassidy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Courts tend to defer to juries' decisions,'' Cassidy said.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Ybarra, the boss Woltkamp accused of sexual harassment,
is still employed at the Human Resources Department. A department
spokeswoman said he was working in a supervisory role and earning
$49,774.
</P>
<P>
   Ybarra answered his telephone at the department Thursday but
declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Timothy Monsees, Woltkamp's attorney, said, ``This is a man who
cost the taxpayers of Kansas well over a half-million dollars, and
he still has his job.''
</P>
<P>
   Monsees said his office worked about 1,500 hours on the case and
he presumed the state's attorneys billed a similar number.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even at $100 an hour, that's another $150,000 in legal fees he
cost the state of Kansas,'' Monsees said.
</P>
<P>
   Woltkamp _ McCue at the time _ took an entry-level job at the
Human Resources Department in 1979 shortly after graduating from
high school. Supervisors praised her work as she climbed the
bureaucratic ladder to the post of special investigator.
</P>
<P>
   Ybarra became her boss in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   Woltkamp said in her lawsuit that the sexual harassment began
almost immediately.
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, she filed a complaint with the Equal Employment
Opportunity Commission, a precursory step to a federal lawsuit. In
January 1993, the EEOC gave Woltkamp permission to sue.
</P>
<P>
   Department officials soon began to lobby her not to file,
Woltkamp later claimed in court. They told her that her job status
would be looked upon more favorably if she let the matter drop.
</P>
<P>
   She agreed. But after the 90-day filing deadline passed, she was
fired. The termination letter told Woltkamp that she was fired for
``deficiencies in work performance.''
</P>
<P>
   She found herself unemployed with a 15-year-old daughter.
</P>
<P>
   Her unlawful-termination lawsuit alleged her firing was
retaliation for filing the sexual harassment complaint. Defendants
included the department, Ybarra and three other officials.
</P>
<P>
   Defendant William Medlock, a senior manager in the department,
testified that A.J. Kotich, the department's chief legal counsel,
told him to stop investigating Woltkamp's complaint because it was
being taken care of.
</P>
<P>
   Kotich was Ybarra's brother-in-law. He still holds the legal
counsel position.
</P>
<P>
   Early in the litigation, Monsees said the defendants ``tried to
protect one of their own at the expense of a woman.''
</P>
<P>
   Two defendants were fired in unrelated sexual harassment cases
before Woltkamp's lawsuit went to trial. Medlock was fired in
November 1995. Hobart Hayes, an Equal Employment Opportunity
Commission officer, was fired in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Woltkamp has since married and lives in Raymore, Mo. She
recently quit her job waiting tables at a Peculiar diner.
</P>
<P>
   Her daughter is 18 now, a senior at Raymore-Peculiar High
School. Woltkamp's work difficulties and subsequent legal struggle
have lasted half the teen-ager's life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to keep most of it from her, but it's changed both of
us,'' Woltkamp said. ``I'm not as trusting as I used to be. And she
will probably never be as trusting as I was before this all
started.''
</P>
<P>
   She said she wants to begin a career but is unsure what field it
would be in.
</P>
<P>
   It won't be politics or government.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a time when that's what I wanted my future to be,''
she said. ``Now, I'm just so glad to be away from all that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
