<SLUG> BC-HALLMARK-PRODUCT-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HALLMARK CARDS THIS WEEKEND BEGINS ITS BIGGEST PRODUCT ROLLOUT
EVER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JENNIFER MANN  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Hallmark Cards Inc. this weekend begins its
biggest product rollout ever by giving away 24 million cards from
its new low-priced Warm Wishes line.
</P>
<P>
   To back the giveaway blitz, Hallmark is spending $50 million to
tell the story of Warm Wishes, a line of 1,040 cards selling for 99
cents, designed for more casual relationships such as neighbors,
co-workers and acquaintances.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, Hallmark will give away 36 million Warm Wishes cards
in the rollout, which will run through August. The line will be
sold at 20,000 retailers that sell Hallmark products.
</P>
<P>
   ``Consumers told us they wanted to be able to use cards for more
occasions but at a lower cost,'' said Hallmark spokeswoman Linda
Odell.
</P>
<P>
   Odell said she didn't know how much revenue Hallmark hoped to
generate from the new card line.
</P>
<P>
   But Hallmark conducted a seven-month test in Las Vegas beginning
late last year. It found that greeting card sales overall increased
12 percent during the test and that ``Hallmark claimed a
significant portion of this category sales growth,'' according to
information from the company.
</P>
<P>
   E. Gray Glass III, an analyst who follows Hallmark, said the
company was unveiling the new line to stay competitive.
</P>
<P>
   ``They see a niche market,'' Glass said. ``Or it may be that
they're responding to something already in the marketplace.''
</P>
<P>
   Glass said his sense is that Hallmark is performing well
relative to the competition. For instance, Hallmark says its 1998
sales were $3.9 billion, up 5 percent from 1997. American
Greetings, on the other hand, had a sales increase of 0.3 percent
for 1998.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
