<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2K-NOVELTIES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESSES CASH IN ON WORRY WITH YEAR 2000 NOVELTIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FINN BULLERS and DAVID HAYES  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Several area businesses have found a whole
new way to fight the year 2000 bug. They're embracing it, and
making money in the clinch.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the strange case of Stan Chrzanowski, local ad guy
turned entrepreneur. Late last year, Chrzanowski said enough was
enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``People around me, friends, everyone, had been talking about
Y2K to the degree that it got crazy,'' he said. ``People were
really talking about buying guns and stockpiling food and bottled
water.''
</P>
<P>
   Chrzanowski's response? A spoof package ``that covers every
aspect of everyone's fear.''
</P>
<P>
   The locally produced Y2K Survival Kit includes a small divining
rod to ferret out water when the supply lines are cut. (Note: It
doesn't work. We tried.)
</P>
<P>
   And a compass to find ``your way to the nearest wilderness.
Start your version of a new human race.''
</P>
<P>
   Also in the kit, a mini-squirt gun to ``ward off those critters
that will want to confiscate your supply of bonbons, Twinkies or
paper clips,'' and a bag of sunflower seeds to either plant a crop
or to throw on the floor to annoy your cubicle mates at work.
</P>
<P>
   With a $14.95 price tag, the oddball product has the makings of
a hit.
</P>
<P>
   Chrzanowski, president and creative director of West Creative in
Kansas City, said the company sold more than 2,000 of the kits in
five weeks _ selling out of its first production run. The kit is
assembled by workers at a vocational center in Liberty, Mo. Area
Boy Scout troops are making the twig-sized divining rods.
</P>
<P>
   ``Marketing this product is half the battle _ and fun,''
Chrzanowski said. ``We just received an order for 500 from a
company on the West Coast. They're using it as a giveaway to their
clients _ a humorous relief.''
</P>
<P>
   The kit is available at gift stores, Borders and other local
shops, or on the Net at www.y2ksurvivalkit.net.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most companies take a year or two years to get started, but
this had to happen fast,'' Chrzanowski said. ``We had a time
deadline. Come January 1, I don't think we'll sell any. Unless I
come up with a `we survived Y2K kit.' &UR; ''
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere in Kansas City, they're up to their ears in chocolate
Easter bunnies now, but after Mother's Day, business slows down at
Annedore's Fine Chocolates.
</P>
<P>
   So owner Nancy Hatch and her employees have hatched a plan to
bolster business and boost the spirits of stressed Y2K programmers.
Annedore's will create a foil-lined box with peanut butter bugs
crawling on chocolate Y's, 2s and K's. They'll be ready after
Mother's Day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Y2K is an issue that's a great mystery to many,'' Hatch said.
``And the more we speak out (about Y2K), the more calmness will
come about.''
</P>
<P>
   Nothing _ save for a dozen long-stemmed roses, we have learned
from experience _ soothes anxiety better than chocolate.
</P>
<P>
   Up until this point, we've been bugged by a bug we've never
seen. Now, a Lawrence company is promoting a mischievous-looking
spider that is trademarked as the official Y2K Bug.
</P>
<P>
   At 8 inches tall, the royal blue and black creature is a pudgy,
six-legged Beanie Baby-like novelty gift being marketed as a
computer good-luck charm. It's manufactured by Image Makers of
Calabasas, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the insipid little creature that has the nation in its
grip,'' said Todd Brabender with Spread the News public relations
of Lawrence, Kan. The creature sells for $7.95 at stores such as
Hallmark, Sears, Osco and Walgreens.
</P>
<P>
   Joining a growing crowd of Y2K novelties, this creature has
something going for it others don't. A percentage of each sale will
go to a Youth 2 Knowledge (Y2K) Computer Fund to help young people
learn about computers.
</P>
<P>
   Checks of $1,000 to $3,000 will be written to a number of
national charities, Brabender said. If your group is deserving,
contact Brabender at (785) 842-8909, or write him at 2620 Cranley
St., Lawrence, KS 66046.
</P>
<P>
   Other evidence is surfacing in the Kansas City area that
marketing departments have gotten the memo: Y2K is a nifty way to
bolster market share.
</P>
<P>
   At Barnes and Noble, a table bears the sign: ``The Year of
Living Dangerously...Be prepared for the Year 2000. Find out what
you can do to protect your money, your home, your job and your well
being.''
</P>
<P>
   Scattered about the table are a couple of dozen Y2K books _ from
Y2K for Dummies to shock-Y2K writer Michael Hyatt's Y2K, the Day
the World Shut Down.
</P>
<P>
   Our favorite? It's a tossup between Pooh and the Millennium, and
Millenniumopoly, which replaces the traditional Baltic Avenue with
the Plague, and Park Place with the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   At a SuperTarget store, you can buy a 13-inch Panasonic TV//VCR
combo that, as the box says, is ``Year 2000 ready.''
</P>
<P>
   And here's the kicker.
</P>
<P>
   Electronics giant Sanyo had posted bright yellow ``This product
is Y2K compliant'' signs on its Web site to alert customers that
its plastic cutting board, with no moving parts, and a bread warmer
are ready for the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The claim, which since has been yanked from the Web site,
sparked a round of laughter at the company's expense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somehow we don't think a product designed `for easy cutting of
fresh bread, bagels, fruits, vegetables, meats, etc., into straight
slices' is going to give up the ghost come New Year's Eve,'' wrote
Declan McCullagh at www.y2kculture.com.
</P>
<P>
   The Wall Street Journal, The Times of London and Jay Leno chimed
in with funny jabs. In the end, ``the humor of the situation was
not lost on us,'' a company spokesman said. ``It may seem that our
efforts were a bit overzealous.''
</P>
<P>
   So much for cutting-edge technology.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
