<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAXPAYERS OWE SEN. KIT BOND A DEBT OF THANKS FOR BATTLE WITH IRS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: Sen. Kit Bond of Missouri has been fighting a mostly
thankless but important battle with the Internal Revenue Service
and deserves a good deal more credit than he's getting for his
efforts.
</P>
<P>
   This is especially so in light of the fact that he seems to have
won the battle.
</P>
<P>
   It began after Bond learned the IRS was implementing a provision
of last year's IRS reform legislation in a manner Bond claimed was
contrary to the law's intent to protect taxpayers. As Senate Small
Business Committee chairman, Bond had been getting inquiries from
constituents concerned about IRS notices informing them that
third-party contacts might be necessary as part of an audit.
</P>
<P>
   What disturbed Bond was that a law meant to help taxpayers was
apparently being used to intimidate them. The provision in question
had been designed to ensure taxpayers full opportunity to
accommodate the IRS before examiners began contacting third
parties. Moreover, if third-party contacts did become necessary,
the law was supposed to give taxpayers a chance to minimize the
potential damage to their reputation these contacts might cause.
</P>
<P>
   As Bond noted in a letter to the IRS commissioner, third-party
contacts are especially hazardous to small-business operators
because they can ``chill relationships'' with suppliers, employees
and customers fearful of becoming involved themselves as part of
the audit.
</P>
<P>
   Bond said the law was not being used as intended. Its intent, he
said, was to notify taxpayers of IRS third-party contact plans
``only in those exceptional cases in which the IRS cannot first
obtain all the necessary information directly from the taxpayer.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Then, and only then,'' Bond wrote, ``the notice is to provide
sufficient information about whom the IRS needs to contact for the
taxpayer to mitigate the damage to personal and business
relationships.''
</P>
<P>
   Bond said the IRS violated the spirit of the law by sending out
blanket notices of its plan for third-party contacts as an
intimidating first resort rather than a last resort to prepare
taxpayers for this disagreeable eventuality.
</P>
<P>
   After Bond's initial complaint, the IRS further irked the
senator by not going as far as Bond thought was needed to fix the
problem. He then followed up with another sharply worded letter to
the IRS commissioner demanding full relief.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the process, Bond's office kept sending out news
releases trying to draw media attention to his crusade, but the
media mostly yawned. Bond persevered, though, and the IRS this week
announced plans to stop warning all those chosen for an audit that
third parties might be contacted as part of their examination.
</P>
<P>
   Bond became a footnote in this effort to protect taxpayers but
deserves much more credit than he's gotten. To be sure, those
audited by the IRS are a minuscule part of the citizenry, so it's
not a policy matter that affects the masses.
</P>
<P>
   Bond's willingness to stand up for taxpayers, however, has
meaning far beyond those being audited. By taking his watchdog
obligation seriously, Bond reminded powerful regulators in all
agencies that at least one person on Capitol Hill is willing to
take on even small fights for big causes on behalf of average
Americans.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
