<DOCNO> NYT19990327.0182 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-27 18:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6607 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ADAMS-BUSH28-COX     03-27 1556
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ADAMS-BUSH28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Like father, like son in the White House
 &HT;    By Ken Herman
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ He was born in New England to a dad who became
president and a mom with a penchant for speaking her mind.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, he picked up an Ivy League degree, passable
fluency in a second language and a stint as an adviser in his dad's
presidential administration.
</P>
<P>
   His father survived eight years as vice president and was
elected president but got the ballot-box boot after one term.
</P>
<P>
   And, like Gov. George W. Bush _ with whom he shares all of the
above _ John Quincy Adams went after his dad's old job. He got it,
and, history tells us, he blew it.
</P>
<P>
   Though neither Adams ranks near the top among U.S. presidents,
they remain in the books as the only father-and-son chief
executives in U.S. history, a record the Bushes would tie if George
W. wins in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   It would not take much to outshine John Quincy Adams, who,
according to Grolier Encyclopedia, ``was not one of the greatest
presidents.''
</P>
<P>
   Adams historian Paul C. Nagle offers a simpler assessment of how
Congress dealt with President John Quincy Adams.
</P>
<P>
   ``They bludgeoned him,'' said Nagle, formerly of the University
of Kentucky and University of Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   But John Quincy Adams (the sixth president and the son of John
Adams, who was the second president) became a revered ex-president.
During a post-congressional career that began two years after he
left the presidency 1829 and continued until his death in 1848,
Adams became a leading anti-slavery voice.
</P>
<P>
   He resurfaced in the public psyche two years ago when, portrayed
by Anthony Hopkins, Adams was given silver-screen hero treatment in
the movie ``Amistad'' for his defense of Africans who rebelled
aboard a Spanish slave ship.
</P>
<P>
   The anti-slavery fervor sparked him to lead a long, eventually
unsuccessful effort to keep Texas, a slave state, out of the union.
</P>
<P>
   ``The answer is, no, I haven't read anything about him,'' the
current governor of Texas said when asked whether he knows much
about the man whose feat he may match. Bush said that about the
only thing he knows is that Adams waged a long battle against
making Texas a state.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike former President Bush, the son of a Connecticut senator,
the elder John Adams was not born to power and privilege. He was a
Massachusetts farmer caught up in revolutionary fever.
</P>
<P>
   ``But he always seemed to feel sort of inferior to the
wealthier, the merchant class of Boston,'' said Nagle, whose most
recent Adams book was a 1997 biography of John Quincy Adams.
``They, in turn, sort of looked down on this rotund gentleman who
was prone to lose his temper, as were all the Adamses.''
</P>
<P>
   The elder Adams played politics well enough to rise to the top
with a win in the presidential race of 1796 over runner-up Thomas
Jefferson.
</P>
<P>
   His wife, Abigail Adams, was an outspoken woman, like Barbara
Bush, ``sort of a cult figure,'' Nagle said. In 1776, while her
husband was working on independence for the colonies, Abigail Adams
offered this gender-specific nudge: ``In the new code of laws which
I suppose it will be necessary for you to make, I desire you would
remember the ladies and be more generous and favorable to them than
your ancestors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do not put such unlimited power into the hands of the
husbands. Remember all men would be tyrants if they could. If
particular care and attention is not paid to the ladies, we are
determined to foment a rebellion and will not hold ourselves bound
by any laws in which we have no voice or representation.''
</P>
<P>
   History does not record Adams' response. The nation responded by
not allowing women to vote until 1920.
</P>
<P>
   Like the elder Bush, the elder Adams decided he wanted to be
president. Also like Bush, he failed in his first effort and
settled for two terms as vice president. Under the original
constitution, that was his consolation prize for finishing second
to George Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Very quickly, Adams was very unimpressed with the job. As the
No. 2 man to Washington, he set an enduring tone for what it would
mean to be the No. 2 man in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``My country has in its wisdom contrived for me the most
insignificant office that ever the invention of man contrived or
his imagination conceived,'' Adams complained to his wife.
</P>
<P>
   In 1796, he became the first incumbent vice president elected to
the presidency. The most recent to accomplish that rare promotion
was the elder Bush, who in 1988 became the first to do it since
Martin Van Buren in 1836.
</P>
<P>
   Like the elder Bush, the elder Adams was dumped after one term,
losing to nemesis Jefferson, who was his vice president despite
being a political foe.
</P>
<P>
   Adams and Jefferson were linked in life and death.
</P>
<P>
   On his deathbed, Adams' last words were ``Thomas Jefferson
survives.''
</P>
<P>
   Wrong. A few hours earlier, Jefferson had died at Monticello.
</P>
<P>
   In one of the enduring coincidences of American history, the two
men who helped give birth to the nation died on the same day, July
4, 1826, exactly 50 years after they signed the Declaration of
Independence.
</P>
<P>
   But John Adams lived long enough to achieve revenge on Jefferson
and the bluer bloods of American politics. According to Nagle, by
the time Adams lost to Jefferson in 1800, a family plot had already
been hatched.
</P>
<P>
   ``He and John Quincy Adams both felt that somehow the good name
of Adams had to be polished up, that there had to be some kind of
vengeance against the New England crowd that didn't support
Adams,'' Nagle said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was political vengeance,'' he said. ``Plus the fact that
both sides of the family had to struggle against alcoholism. They
wanted to see some member of the family succeed.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who said he stopped drinking alcohol at age 40 because it
was getting in the way, had nothing on the Adamses. Two of John
Quincy Adams' brothers, as well as two of his sons, died of
alcoholism, according to Nagle.
</P>
<P>
   And like Bush, who claims he grew up wanting to be baseball
great Willie Mays, John Quincy Adams did not grow up wanting to be
president. The job didn't exist until he was 22.
</P>
<P>
   Though he was not born into wealth and position, John Quincy
Adams did benefit from a family that saw public service as a worthy
goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having a father that was in a position to become president
gave him opportunities that no other young man, or very few young
men, in the new republic had,'' said Celeste Walker, associate
editor for the Adams Papers at the Massachusetts Historical
Society, who has spent 25 years reviewing the 250,000 pages of
letters, diaries and public papers left by three generations of the
Adams family.
</P>
<P>
   Nagle said the evidence is ``overpowering'' that he was raised
to lead the new nation.
</P>
<P>
   At age 24, Adams got these not-so-subtle words of encouragement
from dad. ``If you do not rise to the head, not only of your
profession but of your country, it will be owing to your own
laziness, slovenliness and obstinacy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That,'' Nagle said, ``is pressure.''
</P>
<P>
   After a successful career as an overseas ambassador, where he
made good use of the fluency he developed in French, the younger
Adams was summoned home by his dad to begin preparing for an
eventual presidential race he did not covet.
</P>
<P>
   ``He disliked politics intensely,'' Nagle said. ``He wanted to
be a scientist. He wanted to be a poet.''
</P>
<P>
   He almost got his wish.
</P>
<P>
   The election of 1824 was the most inconclusive in American
history. Andrew Jackson had the most popular votes, but nobody
earned an Electoral College majority. The election went to the
House of Representatives, which, after Henry Clay threw his support
to Adams, made him president.
</P>
<P>
   In his inaugural address, Adams told Americans he was ``less
possessed of your confidence in advance than any of my
predecessors.''
</P>
<P>
   As president, he never made up the confidence deficit. He got
nowhere with grandiose plans for interstate roads and a national
observatory. In 1828, like dad, he became a one-termer, losing to
Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   But two years later, Adams began a successful career as a
Massachusetts congressman. Grolier's ``The American Presidency,''
noting Adams pre- and post-presidential successes, labels his
presidential years ``a strange interlude.''
</P>
<P>
   Adams died at his desk in the U.S. House on Feb. 23, 1848.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the last of earth. I am content,'' were his last
words.
</P>
<P>
   But he had failed on one score. After dedicating years to
keeping Texas out of the union because it would be another slave
state, his efforts failed on Feb. 19, 1846, when Texas President
Anson Jones turned control over to James Pinckney Henderson, the
first governor of the newest state.
</P>
<P>
   One hundred fifty-three years later, that state has produced the
candidate closest to being able to complete another father-and-son
presidential duo.
</P>
<P>
   After 25 years of studying the first family that did it,
historian Nagle is convinced the Adamses would approve.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they'd see it as charming,'' he said. ``I know I do,
being the father of sons. Sons tend to want to do something
different than their father. Of our three boys, not one of them
wanted to pursue history. One of them decided to flunk history in
college.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
