<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-ADVANCE28-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Out of provisionals, Waltrip qualifies
</P>
<P>
   By Al Levine
</P>
<P>
   STAFF WRITER
</P>
<P>
   Fort Worth, Texas _ Thunderstorms threaten today's running of
the Winston Cup Primestar 500 at Texas Motor Speedway. But as far
as Darrell Waltrip is concerned, there isn't a black cloud in the
sky, only silver linings.
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, ol' D.W. made the race. Without a provisional.
</P>
<P>
   After he flat-out qualified under extreme pressure and in such
dramatic fashion, Waltrip ran whooping and screaming through the
garage area, fists held high, nearly in tears.
</P>
<P>
   Facing elimination from the 43-car field with his race engine in
after the qualifying motor had blown earlier in the day, Waltrip
turned in a lap of 186.554 mph during requalifying. He'll start
32nd in today's race.
</P>
<P>
   He pushed his No. 66 Ford faster than he wanted. ``Scared myself
to death. Kind of liking jumping off the high dive; ain't never
done it before, hope I make. But I held my nose.''
</P>
<P>
   Only once in his past 20 races has Waltrip started closer to the
front. Last year, he used champions' provisionals to make the field
in 20 of 33 races. He'd already used up his first allotment of
provisionals this season and was facing being shut out of a race
for the first time since November, 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, he looked up and said ``Thank you, Lord.''
</P>
<P>
   I felt our whole year was riding on this weekend,'' Waltrip
said. ``If we miss this show, we miss out on the points. And after
last week, (when) we had a real bad race, another bad finish or no
run at all here and we'd have been history. It's a breath of fresh
air and we needed it badly.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week at Darlington, NASCAR black-flagged him for driving
too slow. So Waltrip's qualifying run, though it's more than three
mph slower than pole-sitter Kenny Irwin's lap of 190.154, was huge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe I felt that good since I won the Daytona
500,'' Waltrip said. ``It was a feeling of relief.''
</P>
<P>
   He suggested perhaps that the champions' provisionals may have
made him lazy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been very prepared for (today) for a long time and quite
frankly I'm glad it came,'' Waltrip said. ``It's a test.
Everything's a test. As long as I had provisionals to fall back on
I don't think I ever stepped up to the plate. I don't think my team
ever stepped up to the plate. I don't think we ever realized that
we were taking that and abusing it because we could. When you got
to the track and you weren't that good, you said, `it doesn't
matter, we can get a provisional, anyway.' So we'd work on the car
and play along and about Sunday we'd be OK or decent.''
</P>
<P>
   The qualifying certainly lifted his spirits.
</P>
<P>
   ``People in the garage probably got more faith in me than I've
got in myself right now,'' Waltrip said. ``I've been dragging
around, kind of having pity parties and feeling sorry for myself.
Last Sunday, I was embarrassed. So we came here on kind of a low
already.''
</P>
<P>
   But he's not low anymore.
</P>
<P>
   PRIMESTAR 500
</P>
<P>
   -- When: 2 p.m. today
</P>
<P>
   -- Where: Texas Motor Speedway
</P>
<P>
   -- TV: CBS.
</P>
<P>
   -- Defending champion: Mark Martin.
</P>
<P>
   -- Comment: The much-maligned Texas Motor Speedway has undergone
a major makeover that has made it a fast track, with pole-sitter
Kenny Irwin surpassing 190 mph. The driver who handles the new
pavement best will win the race.
</P>
