<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: THE FATHER BEHIND RIPKEN'S STREAK 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By DAVE ANDERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   When his father was in his early years as a manager in the
Baltimore Orioles farm system, Cal Ripken Jr. was too young to
wonder how baseball should be played.
</P>
<P>
   ``After school was out,'' he has often said, ``my mother would
pack up my sister and my two brothers and me and we'd go wherever
my father was managing that year.''
</P>
<P>
   They went to minor-league towns in South Dakota, Washington
state, Florida, upstate New York and Texas, and then in 1972, not
long before Cal Jr.'s 12th birthday, they drove to North Carolina
where Cal Sr., his cap perched on his already-gray crew cut, was
managing at Asheville. That's when Cal Jr. began to care about
baseball. And to learn.
</P>
<P>
   Before the games, Cal Jr. would take batting practice, shag
flies and take grounders. Not that his father the manager was
tutoring his skills.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they were little,'' Cal Sr. once said, ``I showed all
four of my kids how to catch a ground ball and how to catch a fly
ball. Other than that, I just let them play, like kids are supposed
to. I didn't talk hitting with Cal until his junior year in high
school.''
</P>
<P>
   But in Asheville little Cal didn't want to just play baseball.
He wanted to think baseball.
</P>
<P>
   During the games, other kids went to the hot-dog stand or
wandered around the ball park to see what mischief they could get
into, but little Cal Jr. watched what those minor-league pitchers
were throwing as intently as if he were the next hitter. When the
game was over, he sat with his father the manager and asked
questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why did you steal in the third inning?'' he might say. ``Why
did you take that pitcher out in the seventh?''
</P>
<P>
   His father the manager, who had been a career minor-league
catcher in the Orioles' farm system, would explain his reasoning
and his son would remember. For two more seasons, the Ripken kids
spent the summer in Asheville. More questions from little Cal, more
explanations from his father the manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the time I was ready to play, I knew the proper way to do
things,'' Cal Jr. has said. ``Nobody had to tell me what the Oriole
cutoff play was.''
</P>
<P>
   He not only knew what was known in the Baltimore organization as
``the Oriole way,'' a training manual his father helped write, but
he also would develop into The Oriole, the future Hall of Fame
shortstop who would play in a record 2,632 consecutive games before
he finally decided to sit down last Sept. 20 at Camden Yards before
the Orioles' last home game of the season.
</P>
<P>
   And when Cal Sr. died Thursday at 63, he deserved to be
remembered not only as the father behind Cal Jr. the ballplayer,
but also the father behind his son's streak.
</P>
<P>
   ``My bedtime stories,'' the Oriole shortstop has said, ``were
about foul tips splintering up my dad's fingers as a catcher,
taping them together, spitting a little tobacco juice on them and
saying to the umpire, `Let's play.' Hearing those stories, it was
like my dad would have had to break his back to stay out of the
lineup.''
</P>
<P>
   And one day when Cal. Jr. was 16, after a snowstorm blocked the
road around their Aberdeen, Md. home, his father rigged a plow to
an old tractor. But the battery was dead. When his father tried to
hand-crank the tractor, the engine backfired. The crank flew,
opening a deep gash in Cal Sr.'s forehead. Blood flowed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's go to the hospital,'' young Cal said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just go on in the house,'' his father said.
</P>
<P>
   Cal Jr. remembered his father wiping off the blood with an oily
rag, going into the house to put two butterfly bandages on the
gash, then returning to start the tractor and plow the snow off the
road. And whenever Cal Jr. told that story, he had the same punch
line.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's my dad,'' he would say.
</P>
<P>
   In 1976 his dad finally made the big leagues, as an Oriole
coach. After Earl Weaver resigned as manager after the 1982 season,
Cal Sr. hoped to succeed him. Joe Altobelli got the job instead,
but with Cal Jr. established at shortstop, Cal Sr. remained loyal
to the Orioles organization and remained as the third-base coach.
</P>
<P>
   When Weaver departed after a second term, Cal Sr. finally was
named the Oriole manager for the 1987 season. Until then, only
Connie Mack and Yogi Berra had managed a big-league team with one
son on it. But with young Billy Ripken now at second base alongside
his older brother, Cal Sr. was the first to manage two sons.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that my dad was in the Oriole clubhouse with me,''
Cal Jr. once said, ``has helped me.''
</P>
<P>
   But what helped Cal Ripken Jr. just as much, if not more, were
all those questions and explanations after all those games in
Asheville. And all that snow that prompted his father to hand-crank
the tractor.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
