<HEADER>
A6618 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POLICE-TRIAL-CAST-NYT     03-27 0676
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLICE-TRIAL-CAST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CENTRAL FIGURES IN LONG-AWAITED COURTROOM BATTLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (With POLICE-BRUTALITY-TRIAL) 
(lb) 
 By JOSEPH P. FRIED   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A veteran judge is to begin working with prosecutors
and defense lawyers on Monday in U.S. District Court in Brooklyn on
jury selection for the trial of four police officers from the 70th
Precinct charged with attacking Abner Louima and of a sergeant
accused of trying to cover up part of the assault.
</P>
<P>
   The Judge
</P>
<P>
   EUGENE NICKERSON: On the federal bench since 1977, Nickerson,
80, served as Nassau County executive from 1962 to 1970, the first
Democrat elected to that post. Affable and courtly, he is also
known by lawyers for a steely toughness. The judge's major rulings
include two that struck down as unconstitutional the military's ban
on homosexual activity and the ``don't ask, don't tell'' policy for
homosexuals in the military. An appeals court reversed the rulings.
In 1996, he rejected the argument that the Mafia boss Vincent
Gigante was mentally unfit to stand trial, setting the stage for
his conviction in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The Prosecutors
</P>
<P>
   LORETTA LYNCH: Chief assistant U.S. attorney for the Eastern
District of New York, Ms. Lynch, 39, was previously head of the
office's Long Island section. She joined the office in 1990 after
six years in private practice and was the chief prosecutor in
trials involving charges of public corruption in Brookhaven.
</P>
<P>
   ALAN VINEGRAD: Vinegrad, 39, is chief of the criminal division
in the U.S. attorney's office, which he joined in 1990 after
several years in private practice. He was one of the prosecutors in
the highly publicized 1997 trial in which two black men were
convicted of violating the civil rights of a Hasidic Jew fatally
stabbed in violence in Crown Heights, Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   KENNETH THOMPSON: Thompson, 32, joined the U.S. attorney's
office four years ago after working as a lawyer with the Treasury
Department, where he helped investigate the initial 1993 raid by
federal agents on the Branch Davidian compound in Waco, Texas. His
mother is a retired New York City police officer, and he considered
becoming an officer himself.
</P>
<P>
   Chief Defense Lawyers
</P>
<P>
   MARVYN KORNBERG: Kornberg, 64, who represents Officer Justin
Volpe, exploded into prominence in 1985 by exposing police
brutality _ the torture of prisoners, including a client, with an
electric stun gun at a Queens station house. More recently he has
been prominent in defending police officers, and is the lawyer for
Sean Carroll, one of the officers reportedly charged with murder in
the killing of Amadou Diallo.
</P>
<P>
   STEPHEN WORTH: Worth, 47, represents Officer Charles Schwarz. A
former assistant district attorney in Brooklyn, he has defended
officers in trouble for two decades, and since last May his firm _
Worth, Longworth, Bamundo &AMP; London _ has had a contract with the
Patrolmen's Benevolent Association to represent officers. He is a
lawyer for Edward McMellon, another officer reportedly charged in
the Diallo killing.
</P>
<P>
   STUART LONDON: Representing Officer Thomas Bruder, London, 44,
is a partner of Worth and a former assistant district attorney in
the Bronx, where he supervised a unit that investigated police
misconduct. More recently he has often defended officers, including
Francis Livoti, convicted last year on charges stemming from the
choking death of a man in the Bronx, and (with Worth) McMellon.
</P>
<P>
   JOSEPH TACOPINA: Tacopina, 32, represents Officer Thomas Wiese.
He is a former assistant district attorney in Brooklyn who, in
private practice, has represented defendants charged with
white-collar crimes as well as police officers.
</P>
<P>
   JOHN PATTEN: Patten, 58, who represents Sgt. Michael Bellomo,
prosecuted police officers charged with perjury when he was an
assistant district attorney in Manhattan. A large part of his
longtime private practice has involved defending police officers
against charges ranging from assaulting suspects to selling
confidential information to mobsters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
