<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-27 19:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6619 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT     03-27 0960
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: AT DUKE, THERE ARE TOP PLAYERS AND TEAM LEADERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By WILLIAM C. RHODEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ Elton Brand had just received the latest
in a series of awards that have tumbled over him like a waterfall.
On Monday, Brand, Duke's outstanding sophomore forward, was awarded
the Oscar Robertson Trophy by the U.S. Basketball Writers
Association as the nation's top player. Wednesday, he was named the
winner of the Atlanta Tip-Off Club's Naismith Award. And here he
was Friday being named player of the year by The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   Now, reporters surrounded Mike Krzyzewski, asking the Duke coach
to describe Brand's greatness. One reporter prefaced his remarks by
saying Brand was Duke's leader. Krzyzewski snapped: ``Trajan
Langdon is our leader. Elton Brand is our best player.''
</P>
<P>
   The coach's statement spoke volumes about a battle between an
emerging player and a master coach attempting to prepare the player
for coming battles, battles for which the player may not be
prepared. Ever so discreetly, the coach has thrown down the
gauntlet. If Brand is great, what does that make Grant Hill?
Krzyzewski knows he and his team exist in an era in which the news
media make kings and queens out of frogs _ not because they really
are kings and queens, but because we need someone to dethrone.
</P>
<P>
   For the last 18 months, Krzyzewski has stayed on top of Brand.
As recently as December, he put the 6-foot-8-inch standout player
on the bench. The coach said he wasn't working hard enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a growing player,'' Krzyzewski said. ``He's not an end
product. Early on in the season, he kind of looked at it that he
was already there because of all the publicity. He can become an
outstanding player. He's not a great player now. He can become it,
if he knows he's not that now.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, there is speculation that Brand will leave Duke to go to
the National Basketball Association, becoming the first player to
leave the Durham, N.C., university as an underclassman.
</P>
<P>
   These are impossible times for anyone who believes young players
should stay in college to learn and absorb. Many of us make the
annual case against young players turning professional. The reality
is that in this climate where everyone seems to be making grabs for
the money, arguing values over cash is difficult. Telling players
on the threshold of riches to wait on the Lord is difficult at
best, hypocritical at worst.
</P>
<P>
   On a more pragmatic level, Krzyzewski knows that Brand holds the
key to preserving a sensational, legacy-setting season. He also
knows that all it takes is for Brand to have an off night and
William Avery to get in foul trouble and Duke is under glass. The
Blue Devils will be an army without a general.
</P>
<P>
   That is why Krzyzewski drew a sharp, immediate distinction
between best player and team leader. The leader single-handedly
bails the team out of jams, then carries the team to higher
heights. That's what Grant Hill did throughout his career at Duke.
</P>
<P>
   In Duke's early-season loss to Cincinnati in November, Brand was
bounced around and held to 12 points and 7 rebounds. The next game
against Michigan State, Brand had only 3 rebounds. THREE. Three
games later, Brand was benched.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you feel you've already finished your journey, you don't
continue to travel,'' Krzyzewski said. ``He needs to continue to
travel. That's what we're trying to impress on him.''
</P>
<P>
   And this approach presents issues Brand must answer: Does he
want to go through another college season? Does he want to risk
being benched next season if, in the coaches' determination, he is
lazy and undeserving. Does he want to be labeled? And how much
money does Brand lose in that scenario? Brand would be a better
player if he waits, but who cares?
</P>
<P>
   There are two measurements at work: can you get the money, and
can you play?
</P>
<P>
   Money is the overriding issue. Not how good, not how mature.
This is the way of the world. Last week in Knoxville, Tenn., a
distraught Ron Artest said that he would love to return to St.
John's for another run at the Final Four. But he said he was not
going to allow a game to affect his personal life.
</P>
<P>
   Everybody is ready for a couple million dollars. On the surface.
</P>
<P>
   Is Brand? ``I know I'm not prepared to go pro and play against
L.J.'' _ the Knicks' Larry Johnson _ ``the Barkleys and the
Malones,'' Brand said recently. ``They're big and strong, and they
know the game right now.''
</P>
<P>
   This has been a phenomenal season for Brand. He has reached
double figures in points and rebounds 17 times, is shooting 62
percent from the field and has blocked 83 shots.
</P>
<P>
   Off the court, Brand is a solid character, easygoing and quick
to smile. He was raised by his mother and a strong extended family
in Peekskill, N.Y. He learned to play the physical game of
basketball on the playgrounds, where fouls are never called and
nobody plays zone defense. He was the biggest player at Peekskill
High, so he often found things too easy. He admits that as a
schoolboy, ``Maybe I was lazy, but when you're 6-7 and &QC; 6-3 guys are
guarding you, it's hard to get up for that.
</P>
<P>
   ``One day,'' he added, ``I'll be prepared.''
</P>
<P>
   Brand is of one of three NBA-caliber players on Duke's team.
Scouts say William Avery might be an NBA franchise player. They all
agree that Corey Maggette, the freshman forward, has NBA stuff.
They say that Brand is unstoppable at this level. In the NBA, they
say he will be a good player, though maybe not an All-Star.
</P>
<P>
   For a competitor like Krzyzewski, Brand might represent the
greatest challenge in a season without flaw. If Brand leaves, he
will be about the only thing the Blue Devils will have lost all
season. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
