u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SKATING-WORLDS-520&AMP;AD     03-27 0898
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKATING-WORLDS-520&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUTYRSKAYA DETHRONES KWAN AS RUSSIANS COMPLETE SWEEP
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By   CHRISTOPHER CLAREY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HELSINKI _ Michelle Kwan will soon reassume control of her own
destiny as she sorts through what many 18-year-old Americans sort
through when winter turns to spring: university acceptance letters.
</P>
<P>
   But when Kwan took the ice for the free-skate program Saturday
in the Hartwall arena, her options were limited.
</P>
<P>
   Mariya Butyrskaya, a Muscovite, had already clinched the gold
medal and a four-event Russian sweep at these world figure skating
championships.
</P>
<P>
   Kwan, the defending champion and last competitor in the final
group, was in the uncommon position of skating for second place.
She would succeed in winning the silver, but by her own lofty
standards, her overall performance in Helsinki cannot be considered
a success. For the second time in her career she was displaced as
the world champion on European ice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just really proud of myself,'' Kwan said of her free
skate. ``It's been a rough week or me: a lot of ups and downs.''
</P>
<P>
   Kwan did not fall Saturday, as she had in Friday's short
program: a gaffe that left her fourth in the standings. But in her
free program she did step out of her opening triple lutz and did
downgrade a double axel to a single axel.
</P>
<P>
   Though she completed six triple jumps cleanly, she was not the
most complete skater the last two days in Helsinki, and a severe
cold, which cut into her practice time, did not help her cause or
confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cold probably hit me harder mentally than physically,''
Kwan said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we came here, we saw that Michelle was not in such good
shape,'' said Yelena Tchaikovskaya, Butyrskaya's coach. ``I never
see Michelle fall in practice, but here in practice there were many
mistakes. She even fell after jumps, and I think this is news for
us.''
</P>
<P>
   Good news as it turned out for Butyrskaya, a two-time European
champion who landed seven clean triple jumps. At the age of 26
years 272 days, the Muscovite is the oldest women's world champion
in history, and a mature counterpoint to the teen-agers _ Kwan,
Tara Lipinski, Oksana Baiul _ who have been hoarding much of the
gold of late.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I skate like a woman on the ice,'' Butyrskaya said.
``I can do all the jumps. I have learned to cope with my nerves,
and today I proved I am the best skater in the world. The age
doesn't matter.''
</P>
<P>
   Butyrskaya also became the first Russian to win the women's
world title. In 1993, Oksana Baiul became the first Soviet-born
women's champion, but by then the Soviet Union already had split
apart and Baiul was representing Ukraine.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have gotten near this step by step,'' Butyrskaya said. ``A
couple years ago, Irina Slutskaya became the first Russian to win
the European title. Then I won, and now we are not going to let
that title get away anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Russia had already swept the four disciplines at the last three
European championships. Now it is the first to run the table at the
world championships since ice dancing joined the marquee in 1952.
Yelena Berezhnaya and Anton Sikharulidze won the pairs event;
Aleksei Yagudin the men's, and Anjelika Krylova and Oleg
Ovsyannikov finished first in the dance.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   That success comes despite Russia's top skaters and coaches
leaving in droves for the surer ice and better conditions that
currently prevail in the United States and Europe.
</P>
<P>
   But Butyrskaya and the women's bronze medalist, Julia Soldatova,
17, remain based in Moscow. Both are being guided by Tchaikovskaya,
one of Russia's most respected coaches. Tchaikovskaya began working
with Butyrskaya after she fell apart in the short program at the
1997 European championships.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me it was very interesting why this fantastic woman and
skater cannot perform in competition,'' Tchaikovskaya said. ``Maria
now knows she's a very strong skater and believes she can do this.
The reason she did very well this year is psychological.''
</P>
<P>
   A girl half Butyrskaya's age also did well in Helsinki. Sarah
Hughes, a 13-year-old with braces on her teeth from Great Neck,
N.Y, finished a surprising seventh after skating a clean free
program with six triple jumps that earned her marks ranging from
5.2 to 5.6 for technical merit and from 5.3 to 5.7 for
presentation.
</P>
<P>
   At 13, Hughes would normally be too young to compete here, but
she earned the right by winning a silver medal in the last world
junior championships.
</P>
<P>
   A younger 13-year-old, Naomi Nari Nam, of Irvine, Calif., was
not old enough to skate at the world juniors, and though Nam
finished second to Kwan at the U.S. national championships, she
could not compete here because of the age requirements.
</P>
<P>
   That allowed Hughes to take one of the three American spots in
Helsinki.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wanted to skate well because I wanted them to know that
13-year-olds do belong here, and that age doesn't matter,'' Hughes
said.
</P>
<P>
   It remains unclear whether this was Kwan's world-championship
farewell. She has applied to six universities, including Stanford,
Harvard, UCLA and Cal-Berkeley, and if she elects to start school
full time in the fall, the impact on her skating career could be
profound.
</P>
<P>
   ``Michelle has some decisions to make,'' said her coach, Frank
Carroll.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
