u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-POLICE-PROTESTERS-     03-27 0891
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-POLICE-PROTESTERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VARIED COALITION PLANS NEXT STEP IN PRESSURING NYC POLICE 
</HEADLINE>
  (also see NY-POLICE-PROTESTS-REVIEW) 
 (bl)  
 By JONATHAN P. HICKS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ With the reported indictment of the police officers
who killed Amadou Diallo, the wide array of politicians, business
leaders, clergymen and others who had been demanding the
indictments in daily protests have turned their attention to
broader goals.
</P>
<P>
   While the Rev. Al Sharpton contends that the demonstrations and
arrests at Police Headquarters will continue, other protest leaders
have renewed their calls for a requirement that police officers
live within New York City and for the creation of an independent
civilian commission to oversee complaints of police misconduct.
</P>
<P>
   Those are some of the recommendations that have emerged from
discussions among a diverse group of black and Hispanic elected
officials, clergy members, labor leaders and business executives.
</P>
<P>
   The group, which includes former Mayor David Dinkins, Sharpton
and Dennis Rivera, the president of 1199, the National Health and
Human Service Employees Union, met Saturday to develop legislative
strategies in the aftermath of the indictments.
</P>
<P>
   The four white officers, members of the Street Crime Unit, were
reportedly indicted Thursday by a Bronx grand jury in the killing
of Diallo, the unarmed African immigrant who in February was cut
down in a fusillade of 41 shots at his Bronx apartment building.
</P>
<P>
   The group is calling for a renewed emphasis within the Police
Department to hire more black, Hispanic and Asian officers and to
enhance its psychological review of new officers.
</P>
<P>
   The most controversial demand is certain to be the call for an
independent panel with broad powers to subpoena police officers and
records. The mayor, who has long contended that such investigations
would be best handled within the Police Department, has said
outside monitors could interfere with internal departmental
investigations.
</P>
<P>
   For the last several weeks, the reaction to the Diallo shooting
has brought together an uncommon assembly of protesters at Police
Headquarters complaining about what they consider abusive treatment
of minority New Yorkers by officers. While the demonstrations and
arrests were organized by Sharpton, they came to involve public
figures who rarely if ever take part in such events.
</P>
<P>
   Sharpton, whose National Action Network has been at the core of
planning the daily demonstrations, has not been alone in organizing
the protests. For nearly a year, a group of black business leaders
has also been holding strategy sessions. Participants said they had
been outraged by the case of Abner Louima, the Haitian immigrant
whom prosecutors say was brutalized in a Brooklyn precinct station
house in 1997. The trial of four officers and a police sergeant in
the Louima case begins Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Among the participants in the strategy sessions were J. Bruce
Llewellyn, chairman of the Philadelphia Coca-Cola Bottling Co.;
Loida Nicolas Lewis, chairwoman and chief executive of TLC Beatrice
International Holdings Inc., and two who were arrested last week in
protests blocking the entrance to Police Headquarters: Earl Graves,
the publisher of Black Enterprise magazine, and Ed Lewis, the
publisher of Essence magazine. Graves, who sits on the corporate
boards of Daimler Chrysler and the parent company of American
Airlines, said he felt compelled to participate in the sessions and
in the arrests because ``We are simply saying `enough is enough.'
''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the meetings of the business executives occurred in
Lewis' offices at Essence. The publisher said he decided to become
involved after the incident with Louima.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems to me that what happened to Diallo is a continuation
of this outrageous police behavior,'' Lewis said. ``We're still
looking at the trampling of our civil liberties in the name of
crime reduction.'' In addition, Lewis said, he felt it was
important for news organizations and the public to realize that
``there are people who are just as concerned about this as Reverend
Sharpton is.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, while there may be broad agreement on many of the
legislative goals, there is great disagreement about strategy. For
example, Sharpton and Dinkins have asked that black and Hispanic
legislators wait to meet with Mayor Rudolph Giuliani until after
Saturday's meeting, which was expected to produce specific
recommendations.
</P>
<P>
   But Giuliani, who has generally avoided requests by black
politicians to meet with him, has had discussions in the last few
days with 10 members of the City Council's Black and Latino Caucus
and Manhattan Borough President C. Virginia Fields. He met Saturday
with state Comptroller H. Carl McCall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt that it was important not to give the mayor an
opportunity to say that he had reached out to us but that we
declined because of some political gamesmanship,'' said City
Councilman Philip Reed, who represents much of East Harlem. ``We
work in the same building. We pass by him all the time. It seems
ridiculous to treat this like it's the Kosovo talks.''
</P>
<P>
   But several other Council members viewed the situation
differently, saying it was vital to meet with the mayor only after
the leaders had clearly defined a set of goals Saturday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
