<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIPSYTE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: AGE OF REFORM HAS SHORT LIFESPAN IN COLLEGE ATHLETICS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ROBERT LIPSYTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   You can hold your breath. Sports is entering an Age of Reform.
Which will be over soon.
</P>
<P>
   The sheer range of current controversies is breathtaking; from a
racket beloved for its corruption, boxing, to a quasi-religious
concept once promoted as a moral equivalent to war, the Olympics,
the very notion of sports as Fair-Shake City is under attack.
Somewhere between the palaces of Las Vegas and the palaces of
Lausanne are the groves of academe, which came alive this month
during the annual celebration of the most liberal of arts,
basketball.
</P>
<P>
   We don't need to belabor Olympics and boxing. Having just
admitted synchronized diving, the Games deserve a breather.
However, since I had forgotten that the Olympics enjoyed nonprofit
status (just so I could deduct my annual donations?), maybe we
should at least keep an open eye. Having to subsidize as well as
bribe Olympic officials seems excessive.
</P>
<P>
   Boxing, on the other hand, is supposed to be crooked, which is
why Don King was created, supposedly during a story conference at
HBO. The two killings in his resume were probably the idea of the
network's imaginative president of sports, Seth Abraham, to keep
fighters and managers in line. King's hair is no joke; in the final
phase of his creation, there was so much juice in the room it was a
wonder that no one was electrocuted.
</P>
<P>
   The white suburbanites who promoted the new boxing (while their
hipper brothers were helping to get hip-hop mainstream) wanted the
sport to have a faux outlaw edge. They wanted it to appear crooked
and dangerous rather than merely greedy, in which case they would
have had to establish a trade group like the Motion Picture
Association of America and a Jack Valenti to lobby for
protectionism against foreign fighters like Lennox Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   College basketball, which wraps up tomorrow, is where we should
concentrate our concern. Its television revenues are a mainstay of
the National Collegiate Athletic Association, which puts that
organization in a difficult position on reform. The NCAA was
originally formed because athletic directors and coaches knew they
could not trust each other. Given enough slack, even the Ivies
would have brought in herds of giraffes stuffed them in school
uniforms and pointed them at the hoop.
</P>
<P>
   Knowing their membership so well, the NCAA eventually instituted
minimal standards, most recently the so-called Proposition 16,
which required a relatively low level of test scores and high
school course completion for college athletic eligibility.
</P>
<P>
   A protest movement, led by such race card dealers as Temple
coach John Chaney and former Georgetown coach John Thompson called
such standards discriminatory; black athletes from traditionally
under-funded and under-serviced schools would suffer because of
their substandard educations. Recently, a federal judge struck down
the NCAA rules.
</P>
<P>
   Such standards may very well be discriminatory. It is one of the
basic concepts that underlie affirmative action. At the same time,
there has always been something cynical about the application of
social engineering to basketball competition, especially since the
college selection process now begins earlier and earlier in a young
athlete's career. The diversion of youngsters, especially black
youngsters, from education begins even before they learn to read.
</P>
<P>
   These days, with sneaker companies providing the links among the
Amateur Athletic Union, the high schools, colleges and pros,
youngsters are identified and tracked before they reach middle
school. As one leading youth coach, Gerard Papa of the Flames of
Brooklyn (one of Stephon Marbury's early stages), points out, it's
no coincidence that AAU groupings are now by grade rather than age;
marked players are often a year or two older than their teammates,
sometimes because they've allowed themselves to be left back _
redshirted, in a sense, in junior high _ so they have more time to
physically develop. With their eyes on the prize _ a college deal
and a shot at the pros _ learning to read their own contracts may
be a distraction.
</P>
<P>
   For all its talk of reforming a sport that pays its bills, the
NCAA may have been relieved by the judge's decision. It can now
claim to be constrained from a cleanup. Of course. Why would
colleges want to become involved in something as potentially messy
and costly as education?
</P>
<P>
   This is why there is something to be said for the dropping of
pretense. The most competitive colleges could treat their teams as
corporations and factories once treated their teams in the old AAU
_ as morale and publicity-building adjuncts. Players would not have
to go to class and could dicker for long-term benefits and better
cars. It's too early to teach hypocrisy, as the NCAA schools do
now; that's better left for the graduate and professional schools
where the sports lawyers, doctors, executives and journalists come
from.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, the Olympics, boxing and the NCAA will follow the
lead of such popular sports organizations as Major League Baseball,
the National Football League and the National Hockey League. No
major surgery, just nip-and-tuck reform. Baseball reconfigured its
strike zone without a mention of how that affects all history.
Football reinstated instant replay and said nothing about seasons
of suspect decisions.
</P>
<P>
   And hockey, bless its dented skull, installed harder glass
partitions around its arenas without penalizing the goons who are
paid to run opponents into them. The NHL, however, does have a
policy against concussions. They could give you headaches. Should
be banned.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
