<HEADER>
A6629 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GORE-NH-NYT &LR;      03-27 0844
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-NH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE BEGINS TO PRESS THE FLESH WITH NEW HAMPSHIRE VOTERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHUA, N.H. _ Al Gore quacked like a duck in a baby's face. He
empathized with a woman about caring for her ailing elderly mother.
He hammed it up in a home video. He donned a pullover sweater and
slacks, strolled into several living rooms and stopped by a front
porch, where he hugged a woman with lung cancer.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president, who has spent years assembling the nuts and
bolts of his all-but-announced presidential candidacy, moved this
weekend to the ``retail'' phase of his campaign _ the vital process
of selling himself house by house, voter by voter in this
first-in-the-nation primary state. His aim was to demonstrate that
he is worthy of being president by showing he can mix it up with
real people _ and that he is a real person too.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first living room conversation of the year 2000
campaign that I've had the privilege to engage in,'' he told about
70 people Saturday in the parlor of Martin Gross, a prominent
Concord lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like to formally ask for your support,'' he said,
after officially visiting the state 15 times over the last six
years and handing out $90 million in federal grants. ``I'd like to
be your president starting in the year 2001.''
</P>
<P>
   Before his motorcade left the neighborhood, he stopped and
talked with Joan Tibbetts, 58, who has lung cancer and was
complaining about people on welfare. She was sitting on her porch
with her retarded daughter, Kiersten. Gore said he was sorry, that
his sister had died of cancer and, in a Clinton-like gesture, he
embraced them both.
</P>
<P>
   Unabashed pressing the flesh is what retail politics is about,
even for an incumbent vice president. Despite the security bubble
that envelops Gore and the media horde that surrounds him, his
aides want him to connect more with voters and yet establish
himself as presidential. ``We want to keep something special about
his aura, but we don't want that to be a barrier,'' said Ron Klain,
Gore's chief of staff.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, whose campaign created a whirl of up-close-and-personal
moments for him this weekend across the Granite State, said this
could make the difference between whether he wins or loses the
election 20 months from now.
</P>
<P>
   In response to two days of questions, he said his chief mission
was to keep the economy thriving and that he would not let Social
Security ``unravel.'' He said he favored an overhaul of the
campaign finance system and would not take contributions from
political action committees. He condemned President Clinton's
extramarital affair and his lying about it, but asserted, ``He is
my friend.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of those who attended his events were Democrats, and many
were already committed to him. Nonetheless, they said they were
thrilled that he was stepping out to meet them. ``He has a nice
firm handshake,'' Guthrie Speers, 72, a retired Presbyterian
minister, said admiringly as the vice president personally greeted
every one of the 340 people attending a Democratic dinner in
Conway.
</P>
<P>
   His advisers said that the weekend was a chance for Gore to move
out from being Clinton's shadow and to try to erase some of the
damage he recently inflicted on himself for saying he ``took the
initiative in creating the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   But he repeatedly demonstrated his fondness for casting his
accomplishments with a definitive air. The 3,000 town meetings he
conducted during his 16 years in Congress, he said, was ``an
all-time record.'' He said he ``personally negotiated'' with the
Big Three automakers ``to create a new kind of automobile that
would have three times the fuel efficiency.''
</P>
<P>
   Although he has a commanding lead in polls over former New
Jersey Sen. Bill Bradley, his only rival for the Democratic
nomination, Gore is fighting early concerns about his electability
in the general election next year against Texas Gov. George W. Bush
and Elizabeth Dole.
</P>
<P>
   Gore clearly knew his task.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want your support, I'd like you to vote for me,'' he said
over and over. But it was not all easy for the famously stiff Gore,
who, according to surveys, is lodged in voters' minds as dull and
earnest. A recent Washington Post survey even asked voters if Gore
was ``very boring'' (22 percent said yes) or ``somewhat boring''
(34 percent).
</P>
<P>
   Can he ever shake the reputation for being wooden? ``Oh no,'' he
told an interviewer for the New England Cable Network. ``I'm old
enough to believe I'll never be rid of that. But I think the older
I get, the easier time I have expressing myself in public the way I
do with my friends.''
</P>
<P>
   After that particular interview, the reporter, Alison King,
asked Gore to wish her father, Jackson, a happy birthday in a home
video. The vice president took the microphone, draped an arm over
Ms. King, interviewed her about her father and called it a wrap
with a jolly sign-off: ``Jackson, there you have it! Live, from
Carroll County, N.H., a preview of your birthday.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-27-99 1915EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
