<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-27 19:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6630 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT     03-27 0861
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: UCONN FANS HAPPY TO SAIL UNCHARTED WATERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (kd) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ The fan from Connecticut wanted to know
how to pass the time, waiting for Saturday's game with Ohio State.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why not go to practice on Friday?'' somebody suggested.
</P>
<P>
   ``They let you go to practice?''
</P>
<P>
   Rookies. What are you going to do? Duke fans, with their
congenital sense of entitlement, know precisely when to strut into
the Final Four practice, last weekend in March, just about every
year.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut was the new kid on the block, making its first
appearance in the Final Four late Saturday afternoon against Ohio
State.
</P>
<P>
   Waiting in the wings were Michigan State and Duke, which has
been here eight times in the past 14 seasons.
</P>
<P>
   The Connecticut fans _ the long-suffering Connecticut fans, I
might add _ were officially just happy to be here. At least, that
was their position as they made their trek down from the Northeast,
like so many belated snowbirds.
</P>
<P>
   The fans could even watch practice, such as it was _ layup lines
and foul-shot drills, the real stuff being conducted elsewhere,
behind closed doors.
</P>
<P>
   Their Connecticut euphoria was partially due to having escaped
Gonzaga last Saturday in the regional final in Phoenix. Nothing
against the appealing Mighty Zags from Washington State, but a
regional loss to Gonzaga would have been the worst thing that ever
happened to the state of Connecticut _ or maybe second to the New
England Patriots' feasting their greedy eyes on some prime real
estate in Hartford.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, that crisis was averted, and Connecticut was officially
in the Final Four. Never again would anybody question the coaching
wisdom of Jim Calhoun, at least until 5:42 p.m. Saturday, that is
to say, tip-off time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're excited, we are happy to be here,'' Calhoun proclaimed
on Friday. ``Since we left Phoenix, there has been a lot of
exuberance, a lot of joy, a lot of happiness, and a lot of
tape-watching.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kids are getting ready for this moment,'' Calhoun added.
``They have the chance to do something special.''
</P>
<P>
   Notice that Calhoun did not say they were ``just'' happy to be
here. It's all right for Connecticut fans to feel that way, and
many of them did. For my dose of Connecticut madness, I talk with a
family of Connecticut boosters, who have been buying season tickets
for several decades, who have suffered those depressing Wednesday
losses in the Big East tournament, and then suffered equally
depressing first-round losses in the vagabond National Invitation
Tournament in some empty gym in New England.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut was well past that under Jim Calhoun. Each Big East
championship, each run to the regionals, raised the stakes. Now
Connecticut was at the Final Four. Was there some resident sourpuss
in my friend's family that might feel a Final Four was not enough?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's OK,'' my friend pronounced. ``It's nice to be here.''
</P>
<P>
   That is a nice attitude to have. They don't feel that way in
Kentucky, where I have some history. Back there, I am told, the
locals are downright unhappy because Tubby Smith's lads lost to
Michigan State in a regional final. Kentucky people expect to be at
the Final Four every year, and were, for that matter, for the past
three seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Duke, on the other hand, had inexplicably missed three straight
Final Fours, which did not take away from their hauteur, you
understand. Coach Mike Krzyzewski was asked on Friday if he had any
friendly collegial advice to give to his three fellow coaches, none
of whom had ever been to the Final Four as participants.
</P>
<P>
   No, Coach K said with not much more than a smirk on his face. He
wasn't joking. He had no advice to offer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never had the advantage of good looks or intelligence,''
Coach K said. ``So if I have an advantage of experience, I won't
talk about it.''
</P>
<P>
   By his refusal to discuss it, Coach K was suggesting that there
is indeed some tried-and-true way to approach the Final Four. Or
maybe he was just messing with our minds.
</P>
<P>
   The Connecticut basketball people seemed to have a grip on the
Final Four.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, when we arrived here, everybody said we've never
been to a Final Four before,'' said Richard Hamilton, the lithe
gunner. ``One thing we try to do, it's just another game. We don't
want to just be in the Final Four, we want to win as many games as
possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Khalid El-Amin, the personification of self-confidence, said:
``You may not have this experience again, so you definitely have to
make the most of it. You know, we couldn't come here to play one
game, we came to play two games.''
</P>
<P>
   Calhoun applauded this approach. Never again does he have to
deal with questions about why he never got to the Final Four, and
what a blessing that must be. And Calhoun was not yet in a spot
like Tubby Smith, who has to explain to Kentucky fans what he has
done for them lately.
</P>
<P>
   It was a nice little interlude. The Ohio State game would come
soon enough. Heightened expectations. Duke knew all about it, in
its genes. Connecticut was about to find out.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-27-99 1916EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
