<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-27 19:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6632 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-TRAILBLAZERS-TRAV     03-27 0735
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-TRAILBLAZERS-TRAVAILS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOUNG TRAIL BLAZERS SACRIFICE FOR SUCCESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MIKE WISE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   After his team was quickly knocked out in the first round of the
playoffs by the Los Angeles Lakers last season, Rasheed Wallace of
the Portland Trail Blazers met with his coach, Mike Dunleavy, and
asked if Dunleavy wanted him to come off the bench next season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever it takes to make us better, I'm willing to do it,''
Wallace said.
</P>
<P>
   One sacrifice by a young player led to another. And another.
Until it became routine for the Trail Blazers. Their roster is
devoid of All-Stars, championship rings and thirty-something
leadership. But they do have incredible depth and chemistry and, at
22-5, the National Basketball Association's best record.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once Rasheed said he would go to the bench, it gave Mike a lot
of flexibility,'' said Bob Whitsitt, the Trail Blazers' president
and general manager. ``That wasn't a 35-year-old veteran realizing
he wasn't a starter anymore; that was a 24-year-old kid who loves
to play. The feeling was, if he could sacrifice. . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``And then when players like Greg Anthony and Jim Jackson _ a
guy who had started his whole life in the league _ were OK with
coming off the bench, it effectively sent a big message to the
locker room.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether it's rooted in unselfishness, talent or both, Portland's
emergence this season has been almost startling. The Trail Blazers
have been to the playoffs 16 consecutive seasons, currently the
league's longest streak, and after 27 games last season they were
17-10. But they have not been a legitimate title contender since
Clyde Drexler, Buck Williams and Terry Porter were fixtures in the
early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Some of their success can be attributed to fresher legs during a
frenzied, truncated season. They have one of the league's younger
teams, averaging 27 years in age. Only Anthony, the Lithuanian
center Arvydas Sabonis and Stacey Augmon are 30 or older. Jermaine
O'Neal turned 20 three months ago.
</P>
<P>
   But their depth rivals that of the Lakers. It gives the Blazers
the ability to match up against anyone, including the two-time
Western Conference champion, the Utah Jazz. Portland has split two
games with the Jazz this season after winning seven of their eight
prior meetings.
</P>
<P>
   Other reasons for the quick start: power forward Brian Grant is
tipping the ball to himself like Dennis Rodman used to, and point
guard Damon Stoudamire no longer runs around without purpose in the
half-court offense. And whether starting or subbing, Walt Williams
represents instant offense.
</P>
<P>
   The package is impressive, especially given the preseason
scouting report. If there had been a vote for the NBA playoff team
most likely to combust, the Blazers might have been that team: nine
players who had started at different times during their careers,
fighting for minutes. And some with unsavory reputations as
teammates.
</P>
<P>
   Wherever he played _ Dallas, New Jersey, Philadelphia or Golden
State _ Jackson never seemed to fit in. Anthony shot too much for a
point guard. And along with the off-season acquisitions, there were
holdovers like the notorious Isaiah Rider and the unpredictable
Wallace.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think sometimes that rap is a little overused,'' Whitsitt
said. ``I don't think it's bad to have guys walking that emotional
line. It's when you cross the line that you get into trouble.
They're playing at such a high level now that they're learning how
to play in the flow of the game and downshift a little bit at the
same time.''
</P>
<P>
   Rider, who leads the team in scoring at 15.6 points a game,
still strays from the program sometimes. He was caught on camera
last Sunday night at the Rose Garden, dancing on the sideline and
trying to ignite the crowd during a timeout. The Blazers trailed
Philadelphia by 2 points, but ended up winning.
</P>
<P>
   And when Dunleavy yanked Stoudamire and inserted Anthony to
guard the 76ers' Allen Iverson for the entire fourth quarter of
Portland's 91-75 victory, Stoudamire was not peachy about the
coach's decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sitting out the fourth quarter is difficult, I don't care if
you've won 45 games in a row,'' Stoudamire said last week. ``It
hurt. It definitely hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   But for the most part, they have been selfless. One victory at a
time, the skittish young Blazers are maturing into a team that
could last into June. &QL; 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
