<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NBA NOTEBOOK: JOHN STARKS, CHRIS MILLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MIKE WISE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Starks Gets Out of the Rough
</P>
<P>
   From the Now-It-Can-Be-Told file: John Starks, a golf addict who
was criticized for taking his clubs to Indianapolis during the
second round of the playoffs last season, had already teed it up
the day before the New York Knicks defeated the Miami Heat in Game
5 of their first-round series.
</P>
<P>
   ``I played all day and then came out the next day and had a
great game,'' he said. ``I didn't think it was a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks did. Starks was included in the trade for Latrell
Sprewell at the request of the Golden State Warriors. But that was
not the first time the Knicks had shopped him during the off
season. For all his passion on the floor, the team's management
believed he had lost some of his desire for the game.
</P>
<P>
   Knicks Coach Jeff Van Gundy and at least two teammates were
critical of Starks' sudden obsession with golf, and they were upset
that he brought his clubs on the road the day before the Knicks
were eliminated by the Pacers in the second round.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those are excuses people like to make,'' Starks said last
week. ``Michael Jordan went out and played 36 holes and won a
championship the next night.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``Golf is not a strenuous sport. When you go out,
party all night long, drinking and doing those kind of things, then
you come back and try to play, that's hard on you. Much harder than
going out, getting in a golf cart, riding up to the ball, stepping
out, hitting the ball and going back to the cart. If you go out
there and walk the course, that's different.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't lost my competitive edge. I still want to win at all
costs. That's what drives me to go out there and play the way I
do.''
</P>
<P>
   And drive the ball off the tee, too. Starks has already played
27 holes at the pristine Olympic Country Club in San Francisco,
whose members include Warriors coach P.J. Carlesimo.
</P>
<P>
   ``You got a coach who likes golf, so it makes it a lot easier,''
Starks said, cackling.
</P>
<P>
   Mills Bemoans Lost Chance
</P>
<P>
   Chris Mills played only one season in New York, contributing as
a role player last year. But like other former Knicks who catch
their old team on television when they can, he mourns the break-up
of a team he thought had title potential in Michael Jordan's
absence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think guys like John, myself, I think Oak for sure, are
missed now,'' Mills said, referring to John Starks and Charles
Oakley. ``Especially when Mike retired, I thought we could have
done it right then and there. Maybe it still could be the year for
them, but there's just a different-looking team.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked to elaborate, Mills said: ``When I watch them on DirecTV,
I don't know, they just don't seem the same. That hard play. That
heart.
</P>
<P>
   ``I looked at it, before I was even there, as, `Damn, the
Knicks.' You know when you were playing against them, you go to the
middle and you know they're going to crush you, they're going to
play their behinds off, they're going to dive, they're going to do
whatever it took. I don't really see that now. I see guys looking
more for self, than to play as a team.''
</P>
<P>
   Mills, who is Starks' teammate now at Golden State, added that
Starks' emotion was severely missed by the Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was part of what the Knicks were about _ a guy who had
energy and heat and heart,'' Mills said. ``John has tremendous
heart.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, the fire just isn't there for the Knicks team I was used
to watching the last four or five years.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
