</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRAWBERRY PUSHES TO GET IN PLAYING SHAPE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By CHARLIE NOBLES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEARWATER, Fla. _ From the moment Darryl Strawberry came onto
the field at Jack Russell Stadium on Saturday, he attracted the
most fan attention among the Yankees. Never mind that Bernie
Williams made this trip, as did Derek Jeter and Paul O'Neill.
</P>
<P>
   Easy to spot with bulging muscles on a 6-foot-6-inch frame,
Strawberry went from one screaming group of fans to another,
signing autographs. He smiled easily and often, the picture of
accommodation and grace.
</P>
<P>
   It was hard for anyone to tell that maybe, just maybe,
Strawberry shouldn't have even been here. It was, after all, a
beautiful, cloudless day.
</P>
<P>
   ``My doctor specifically told me to stay out of the sun,'' the
outfielder said. ``I hope I'm not doing anything that will turn out
to be bad for me.''
</P>
<P>
   The no-sun advisory came because Strawberry, 28, had received
chemotherapy only a day before, as part of his sixth-month fight to
overcome colon cancer.
</P>
<P>
   He was bucking other odds for the first time by playing just a
day after the treatment. The chemotherapy ``kind of wears you
out,'' Strawberry said after batting practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel a little sluggish, but you try to fight through it,''
he added.
</P>
<P>
   He acknowledged that the chemotherapy sometimes gives him a
headache. He has undergone two treatments in a once-a-week schedule
that is to last four weeks. Then he will take a two-week break and
his progress will be assessed.
</P>
<P>
   Strawberry could have used another day off to get his stamina
back, he said, but he is determined to get ready for regular season
as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
   And that includes logging playing time in left field, which he
did for four innings Saturday against Philadelphia. He had one
fielding chance, a fly ball that he fielded cleanly.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Joe Torre, who is recovering from prostate cancer
surgery, told him in a telephone conversation last week that Chili
Davis, a switch-hitter, is the team's first option at designated
hitter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want him to play some outfield,'' Torre said of Strawberry
on Friday. ``Not that he has to prove that he can play it all the
time, but he has to be able to stay out for a time just in case he
has to. And the physical part isn't there yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Torre reiterated to Strawberry that the Yankees want him to ease
back into playing shape, not rush back.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not the most important thing that he breaks camp with
us,'' Torre said, ``because I don't want him to break down a week
later. We're looking long term here. Whether that means he's going
to have to stay down here and play Triple-A, we don't know at this
point in time.''
</P>
<P>
   Strawberry's left-field competition includes Ricky Ledee and
Shane Spencer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't worry about it; I just play,'' Strawberry said.
``Baseball's just fun to me and I go out and play.''
</P>
<P>
   In Saturday's game against the Phillies, he hit a sharp ground
ball to first base that drove in a run, then walked twice.
</P>
<P>
   Strawberry's status is one of the few decisions left to be made
before the Yankees leave Florida for the regular season. Another
decision involves the left-handed pitcher Andy Pettitte, who has
been battling elbow tightness since early in camp.
</P>
<P>
   Whether Pettitte makes the opening-day roster may depend on how
well he performs on Sunday. After confining his work to
soft-tossing Saturday, he will pitch in a game at the team's minor
league complex.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees could use a lift from Pettitte because Hideki Irabu
continued his shaky spring Saturday. He came in having given up
seven earned runs in 102/3 innings. And he was hit hard by the
Phillies, giving up nine hits and four runs in his first four
innings.
</P>
<P>
   At least the staff ace Roger Clemens looks as if he's ready for
the season. He threw 106 pitches in allowing no hits against the
Houston Astros late Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``As I tried to increase my velocity, that happened,'' Clemens
said. ``My velocity was better and my change of speeds was better.
I'm also happy with my stamina. When I wanted to reach back and
work a little harder, I could.''
</P>
<P>
   Don Zimmer, the Yankees' interim manager, can understand why
Clemens, at 36, shows no signs of slowing down. When Zimmer went to
leave long after Friday's game, he said, Clemens was still working
on his fitness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not many pitchers can stay up with him conditioning-wise,''
Zimmer said. ``If I had to make a choice right now, I'd take him to
win the Cy Young award again.''
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE PITCH
</P>
<P>
   _ Outfielder Chad Curtis has a policy of signing autographs for
children but not adults, figuring this is where he should put his
energy. When he declined an adult's request Saturday, the man
criticized Curtis. ``He said, `I paid for a ticket just like the
kids,''' Curtis said. ``I said, `Nowhere on the ticket does it say
that you're entitled to an autograph, whether you're a kid or an
adult.' I didn't want the guy to be bitter, so I tried to make him
understand my position.''
</P>
<P>
   _ The Yankees have started giving their regulars a periodic day
off. Saturday was first baseman Tino Martinez's.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
