<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-NOTES28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Drivers like Texas track's makeover
 &HT;    By Al Levine
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ No runs, no drips, no errors. The Texas
Motor Speedway makeover received a thumbs-up from the stock car
racing community this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   For a track that's only three years old, the place certainly has
a history. Two years ago, heavy rains caused a water seepage
problem on the track and drivers could not control their cars on
the wet surface.
</P>
<P>
   General manager Eddie Gossage answered the complaints last year
by handing out T-shirts that read ``Shut Up And Drive,'' which
really irritated the drivers. The reconstruction seems to have
worked better than the T-shirts.
</P>
<P>
   ``They made the best of a bad situation,'' said Dale Jarrett,
driver of the No. 88 Ford. ``I think those problems are remedied
now and we have a much better race track to race on.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Turn 1 is a lot easer to get into,'' points leader Jeff Burton
said. ``Before, it was very difficult to drive the car down in
there and hit where you needed to hit. It's just a better race
track. They made it more raceable. It's too fast right now because
of the new pavement but as time goes on that'll get wore off.''
</P>
<P>
   Gossage is pleased with the changes. ``That's why we spent $3.2
million last year, to hopefully hear them say good things about the
speedway,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Pretty good odds
</P>
<P>
   Multi-car team owner Jack Roush went into the weekend with nine
chances to get his 200th career win: he had two cars in Saturday's
Coca-Cola 300 Busch race here, two entries in the Craftsmans Truck
series race in Phoenix later in the day and five cars in today's
Winston Cup Primestar 500.
</P>
<P>
   His lineup today: Mark Martin (starting sixth), Jeff Burton
(20th), Johnny Benson (24th), Chad Little (37th, on a provisional)
and Kevin Lepage (40th, on a provisional).
</P>
<P>
   Still, Roush isn't anticipating a celebration even though Burton
and Martin have won the first two Cup races held here. ``I'm not
counting on it,'' Roush said. ``We've been extraordinarily lucky at
Texas in not having things happen beyond our control that would
stop us from winning. I don't expect the string to continue, but
we'll try.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Roush's news release, his career victories include
119 road racing wins, 39 Winston Cup, 34 Busch and seven truck
victories. However, the NASCAR record book credits him with only 34
Cup victories.
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett supports fund
</P>
<P>
   Dale Jarett renewed an arrangment Saturday with the Susan G.
Komen Breast Cancer Foundation which benefits every time he
finishes in the top three or takes a pole.
</P>
<P>
   His sponsor, Ford Credit, will contribute $10,000 for every
Jarrett win, $7,500 for each second place and $5,000 for thirds and
the pole. The Foundation received $175,000 from Jarrett's finishes
last year.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
