<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-MORA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORA BIDS FOR A SPOT ON METS AS UNDERDOG 
</HEADLINE>
  (kd) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT ST. LUCIE, Fla. _ Melvin Mora wanted a shot at top-level
play somewhere so badly he went half way around the world before
last season and ended up in Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   In retrospect, Mora _ who is making a strong bid for the final
spot on the Mets' opening day roster _ was asked Saturday morning,
was the move to Asia a mistake?
</P>
<P>
   ``Big,'' the Venezuelan native said.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, in a strange, roundabout way, going to the chaotic
baseball world of Taiwan, instead of the more established leagues
in Japan, has actually helped the little-known 27-year-old utility
man. Indeed, he might finally make his first major-league club this
spring.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever happens come opening day, Mora has already accomplished
something he was not able to do in six seasons in the Houston
Astros organization from 1992-97: get invited to a big-league camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``And there is no question about it,'' Mets General Manager
Steve Phillips said recently. ``Melvin's opened everyone's eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   A .404 batting average in 47 at-bats this spring hasn't hurt.
Neither has the ability to play just about everywhere but pitcher,
catcher and first base. Mora began his career as a center fielder.
But his ability to re-invent himself into an adequate second
baseman is one of the reasons why Mets Assistant General Manager
Jim Duquette thinks that Mora has a shot at being a major leaguer
some day, if not with the Mets on opening day. That, and Mora's
hard work at improving his offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's always had the tools,'' said Duquette. ``It's just that
his bat has held him back. That, and his ability to be an effective
infielder. And he's improved on both.''
</P>
<P>
   It was Duquette who recommended Mora to Phillips last summer,
after Mora had fled Taiwanese baseball after just a month and a
half. And it was Duquette _ along with Mets Coach Cookie Rojas who
had seen Mora play in Venezuela this winter _ who convinced
Phillips to extend a nonroster invitation to Mora this spring.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Mora had the chance he always wanted. And he has made
the most of it so far. ``If it was me making the decision,'' Mora
said, ``I'd put my name there as the first one. But it's not my
decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Mora is apparently fighting with Mike Kinkade and Craig
Paquette, who also bat right-handed and can play a multitude of
positions, for the final spot on the 25-man roster. ``And it seems
to change every day,'' Duquette said.
</P>
<P>
   Early on, Kinkade appeared to be in front. Recently, though,
Paquette gained ground, while seemingly out of nowhere, Mora has
come along to make it a three-man race. Only three, because this
morning, the 36-year-old Mariano Duncan asked for _ and was granted
_ his release.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not over for me,'' Mora said of the Mets' seven
exhibitions remaining. ``I've got seven more games and I don't want
to stop.''
</P>
<P>
   It is obvious that Mora is having the time of his life. It has
just been a long time in coming.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a guy that came out of the infamous Astros academy in
Valencia,'' Duquette said of the Venezuelan city that Mora comes
from. ``And he was overshadowed by other prospects like Bobby
Abreu, Richard Hidalgo, Oscar Henriquez, Carlos Guillen, Freddy
Garcia and Manny Barrios. All of them were considered better than
Melvin, who was considered a solid utility player that you would
like to have on your club.''
</P>
<P>
   As far as the Astros were concerned, however, Mora was the type
of utility player that they wanted to have on one of their minor
league clubs. He hit .298 at Class AA Jackson in 1995 and .286 at
Class AAA Tucson in 1996. But after hitting .257 at Class AAA New
Orleans in 1997, the Astros again did not invite Mora to camp the
following spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``And that's when I said I'm done,'' Mora said. ``I didn't want
to go to AAA again.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead he went to Taiwan for $50,000 up front. It didn't take
much longer for Mora. who was delayed from leaving for a couple of
weeks because of passport problems, to want to come back (and pass
up another guaranteed $50,000).
</P>
<P>
   When Mora finally made it back to the United States last season,
he contacted Edgardo Alfonzo's brother Edgar, who is a coach with
the Mets' Class A affiliate in St. Lucie. Through Alfonzo, Mora got
in contact with Duquette, who offered Mora the only position he had
available: a utility role with St. Lucie. But, true to his word,
Duquette made sure that Mora was promoted to Class AAA Norfolk when
a roster spot opened up.
</P>
<P>
   Mora was considered a long shot when camp began this spring. But
all he wanted was to be at camp.
</P>
<P>
   And, as Duquette said, ``He's done the rest.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
