<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-27 19:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6639 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-ROONEY-NYT &LR;      03-27 1085
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-ROONEY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A GIANT WHO DIDN'T RUN AND DIDN'T BLOCK, BUT ALWAYS KNEW WHO
COULD  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By MIKE FREEMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tim Rooney is leaving professional football after almost 30
years. His retirement announcement was made quietly by the Giants
last week, amid the din of college basketball. But not even March
Madness can obscure what has been one of the truly great football
careers.
</P>
<P>
   One of the defining moments in Rooney's professional life was
the Pittsburgh Steelers' draft in 1974. Tim, a nephew of the
Steelers owner Art Rooney, had been hired several years earlier to
upgrade the team's pro personnel department under the direction of
Coach Chuck Noll.
</P>
<P>
   The Steelers quickly discovered that Rooney's judgment was
highly valuable, and he soon became involved in almost every aspect
of the personnel department, especially the draft. Then came the
1974 Steelers' draft, considered one of the best of all time. With
their first-round pick, the Steelers took wide receiver Lynn Swann,
and with their second, linebacker Jack Lambert. Pittsburgh had no
third-round selection, but with two fourth-round picks it selected
wide receiver John Stallworth and defensive back Jim Allen. In the
fifth round, Pittsburgh took center Mike Webster.
</P>
<P>
   So in that one draft, the Steelers picked two Hall of Famers in
Lambert and Webster, and two others who should be in the Hall in
Swann and Stallworth. ``Of course you look back on that draft and
you can't believe how it turned out,'' said Rooney, who has three
Super Bowl rings from his days in Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   After leaving Pittsburgh in 1979 for more authority as the
player personnel director of the Lions, he eventually caught the
eye George Young, then the general manager of the Giants. Rooney
came to New York in 1985 as director of pro personnel, the title he
kept for 14 years.
</P>
<P>
   Rooney became known as one of the hardest-working and best
prepared workers in the Giants' organization. ``Hiring him was one
of the smartest things I ever did,'' Young said recently. ``I
leaned on him a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Rooney will not discuss the key decisions he was involved in
with the Giants, or which players he wanted or did not want, but
it's no secret he was right most of the time.
</P>
<P>
   He was in favor of signing the free-agent running back Ottis
Anderson in 1986 when others questioned if he could still play. In
the mid-1990s, he was against Coach Dan Reeves' bringing in former
Denver players like Mike Croel, Mark Jackson and Michael Brooks,
all mostly busts. He was also against signing an aging Chris
Spielman in 1996 _ that, too, proved to be a wise decision.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, when the Steelers gave up on wide receiver Chris
Calloway, Rooney urged Young to sign him, and Calloway gave the
Giants six good years. Rooney scouted the former Dallas guard Ron
Stone, then a little-known backup, and when the Giants signed him
to a multiyear contract in 1996, the Cowboys, much of the National
Football League and members of the news media snickered. But Stone
has become a productive player.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, Rooney's personnel decisions helped the Giants win two
sets of Super Bowl rings.
</P>
<P>
   Giants General Manager Ernie Accorsi offered Rooney a two-year
contract extension this month, but after listening to Accorsi's
offer, Rooney went home, spoke to his wife, Mary Ann, punched some
retirement numbers into his calculator, and came to the conclusion
that at age 57, now was the right time to leave, even though he was
two years away from collecting a full pension.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every weekend beginning in July, for most of my life, I've
been around football,'' said Rooney, who will leave officially at
the end of May. ``It's been rewarding and fun, but now I really
want to take control of my life and do what I want to do, which
will include lots of traveling and sailing.''
</P>
<P>
   Rooney's successor has not yet been chosen, but will most likely
come from within the organization.
</P>
<P>
   Milstein Has Backers
 &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  While the NFL continues to study the bid for the Washington
Redskins from the real estate developer Howard Milstein, it is
clear he has some support. The league has received more than a
dozen letters from members of the House and Senate, pleading to
allow Milstein and the businessman Daniel M. Snyder to purchase the
team, with some threatening to launch an investigation if the
league vetoes the bid. Members of the Washington news media have
also called for approval.
</P>
<P>
   What his supporters do not know, according to a number of NFL
owners, is that Milstein himself is mostly to blame for not getting
immediate approval.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, Milstein has come off as arrogant in his dealings
with a significant number of the owners. He tried to repair his
image at the owners' meetings in Arizona two weeks ago, but based
on interviews with several owners this week, those efforts may have
come too late.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, problems still exist with the bid, mainly because
there is not enough cash in the offer. Much of Milstein's wealth,
these owners maintain, is in his real estate holdings, which are
financed by banks. Some traditional owners, whose wealth comes
mostly from the teams themselves, frown upon such leveraged
purchases of teams.
</P>
<P>
   The chances of Milstein's bid being approved are still about 50
percent, several owners said. The league will hold a special
meeting next month in Atlanta to reach a decision.
</P>
<P>
   One thing seems certain: If Milstein does get the team, Charley
Casserly, one of the NFL's more respected personnel men, will be
out as the Redskins' general manager. According to one owner,
Milstein's representatives have talked openly about firing
Casserly.
</P>
<P>
   If that happens, Casserly would almost certainly land with
another team, or join the league office. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Big Blue on Broadway?
 &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  There are rumors that the Giants have been exploring the
possibility of playing in Manhattan, although the Giants deny any
such interest and pointing to their lease with the Meadowlands that
runs well into the next century. ... More people are becoming
sports agents than ever before. More than 300 prospective agents
took a qualifying exam administered by the NFL players association
recently, with some 290 passing. There is concern among some agents
that increased competition will lead to more cheating. ... The
former Giants linebacker Corey Miller, whose neck injury ended his
career with New York, has been medically cleared to play again by
at least one other NFL team.
</P>
</TEXT>
