<HEADLINE>
CUBA'S BEST PLAYERS ARE FLASHY WITHOUT BEING FLAMBOYANT 
</HEADLINE>
  (also see BBO-ORIOLES-CUBA) 
 (bl)  
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HAVANA _ Omar Linares is the best-known member of the Cuban
national team that will play the Baltimore Orioles on Sunday, and
deservedly so. But Yobal Duenas may be the one player the Orioles
want to watch and remember.
</P>
<P>
   The Orioles and officials of other clubs who have come to Cuba
for a firsthand look at the talent here may want to get a good look
at Duenas, because they may not see him when the Cubans go to
Baltimore for the second game of the home-and-home series, if there
is a game in Baltimore. Speculation has arisen that the Cubans will
pull out of the second game because they don't want to risk
defections.
</P>
<P>
   Another speculated scenario, though, has them taking an older
team to Baltimore for the May 3 game on the theory that the older
players will be less attractive to major league teams and less
likely to defect.
</P>
<P>
   Duenas is a good-fielding second baseman who is in his mid-20s,
24 or 26, depending on the source of the information. ``He is one
of our best prospects,'' said Ismael Martinez, a coach for the
Industriales team of Havana. ``He has all the tools to be a great
baseball player.''
</P>
<P>
   Duenas won the Cuban League batting championship by hitting .418
in the recently concluded season, and equally as impressively he
had a .499 on-base percentage and a .626 slugging percentage.
</P>
<P>
   Those numbers would get any scout's attention. Linares has
attracted attention with a talent that has made him the best Cuban
player in the past two decades, if not the best in history.
</P>
<P>
   Linares is 31, which is considered old here for a player though
not old by American major league standards, but he has had his
chances to change addresses when he has played in the United States
with the national team and has chosen not to. While virtually all
of the Cubans who have defected have been pitchers, Linares, a
third baseman, would have been a sought-after international free
agent if he had desired to become one.
</P>
<P>
   ``Linares is the best example of a baseball player we have here
in Cuba,'' said Antonio Scull, whose two-run eighth-inning home run
Friday night gave Industriales a 3-2 victory over Santiago de Cuba
in the first game of the championship series of the Cuban League
playoffs. ``He is a modest player who gives everything on the
field. He is a player who could be playing in the big leagues, but
he decided to stay here in Cuba.''
</P>
<P>
   Cubans, Scull added in Spanish, in which all of the players
spoke, admire Linares because he opted to stay at home.
</P>
<P>
   Linares, on the other hand, is slipping as a hitter. Limited by
injuries to 87 at-bats this season _ Duenas, by comparison, had 337
_ Linares hit .287, sending his career average under .370. He has
won five batting titles with averages ranging from .409 to .446 but
none since 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, he is still widely respected among his peers.
``He's absolutely the best player we have here in Cuba,'' said Ivan
Correa, the catcher for Industriales.
</P>
<P>
   Linares also appears to be past his injuries. ``Omar seemed to
be in good shape the last few times we saw him,'' Martinez said of
the right-handed hitter.''
</P>
<P>
   German Mesa and Orestes Kindelan will not be joining Linares and
Duenas in the Cuban infield for the game at Estadio
Latinoamericano. Mesa, the slick-fielding shortstop, and Kindelan,
Santiago's slugging first baseman, are in the final playoff series
and will not be on the team, even though no playoff game is
scheduled for Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like to play, but this is a decision that has been
made,'' said Kindelan, whose 438 career home runs make him Cuba's
Hank Aaron. ``It's going to be a great opportunity for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he would go to Baltimore, the 34-year-old Kindelan
said, ``There I am surely going to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Linares, Kindelan has played in the United States. He very
much made his presence felt in 1996 in Atlanta, breaking the
Olympics home run record by swatting nine in nine games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I can play in the big leagues,'' the right-handed
hitter said. ``The pitchers throw a little harder, but they have to
throw it over the plate. I think I could hit it.''
</P>
<P>
   But he expressed no regrets at not trying to stay in the United
States. ``I feel fine because I'm in the company of my family and
my people,'' he said, standing outside the visitors' dugout 40
minutes before the start of the first game of the final series.
Money is very important, but it's not the only thing. For us,
family and friends are just as important.''
</P>
<P>
   Loidel Chappeli, a 27-year-old left-handed hitter, is expected
to be the Cubans' first baseman in Kindelan's absence. His
statistics this season were not as good as Kindelan's.
</P>
<P>
   With Mesa missing at shortstop, Danel Castro, 22, is the leading
choice to play there. No one, however, can replace Mesa, at least
not defensively. Allowed to return to the league this season after
having been one of several players suspended _ El Duque, the
Yankees' Orlando Hernandez, was another _ Mesa demonstrated his
talent in the series opener Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   In the first inning, Mesa flew through the air to snare a
leadoff line drive between short and third. Then in the sixth, he
teamed with second baseman Juan Padilla on as neatly an executed
play as any major league combo could pull off.
</P>
<P>
   Padilla went far to his right to field a leadoff grounder and,
knowing he could not throw out the runner, flipped the ball to
Mesa, who had come toward second. Pivoting as if he were completing
a double play, Mesa fired the ball to first for the out.
</P>
<P>
   But the Orioles won't see Mesa either here or in Baltimore. As
part of his return to active status, Mesa cannot play out of the
country. The players had been suspended because they were suspected
of harboring ideas of defection.
</P>
<P>
   Others in the Cuban starting lineup are expected to be catcher
Juan Manrique and outfielders Oscar Machado, Jose Estrada and Luis
Ulacia. The Cubans have not disclosed their starting lineup nor
their starting pitcher. However, players and coaches said the best
pitchers were Pedro Lazo, Jose Contreras and Jose Ibar, all
right-handers.
</P>
<P>
   They said Lazo and Contreras throw fastballs at speeds faster
than 90 miles an hour while Lazo also has a good slider and
Contreras a good curveball. Ibar's strength is more off-speed
pitches.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
