<SLUG> BC-BBO-ORIOLES-CUBA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ORIOLES TRY TO RALLY FROM A DOWN SEASON 
</HEADLINE>
   (also see BBO-CUBA)  
 (bl)  
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HAVANA _ Chris Hoiles succinctly summed up the Baltimore
Orioles' 1998 season. ``It pretty much goes to show you can't buy a
World Series,'' Hoiles, the team's erstwhile catcher, said. Not
even for $72 million.
</P>
<P>
   The Orioles play a historic game on Sunday, meeting the Cuban
national team on its home ground. They made history last year, too,
amassing the largest baseball payroll ever. But they got nothing
for it except a losing record.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody keeps talking about the money,'' Harold Baines,
their veteran designated hitter, said. ``Talk about wins and
losses, not how much a player makes. Whether you have the highest
payroll or the lowest payroll, you still got to go out there and
perform.''
</P>
<P>
   The Orioles performed so badly that they finished 35 games
behind the Yankees. Injuries to three of their five starting
pitchers _ Mike Mussina, Jimmy Key and Scott Kamieniecki _ in a
10-day span in May set the tone for their lost season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year was one of the most frustrating years for me
personally and for everyone on the team,'' shortstop Mike Bordick
said. ``Even though we had some key injuries, I still think we had
the talent to do a lot better than we did. There was a lot of
frustration. We just couldn't get it rolling. You'd think with the
talent we had we could've regrouped a little bit better. We didn't
get it done.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite their distance from the Yankees, measured in
metaphorical miles, the Orioles momentarily threatened to get into
the race for the wild-card spot in August. But a team meeting the
day after a poor effort in Chicago produced an ugly confrontation
between the Manager Ray Miller and the second baseman, Roberto
Alomar, and a couple of losses grew into a 10-game losing streak
that put an exclamation point on the team's awful season.
</P>
<P>
   Miller rejected the idea that his near fight with Alomar
affected the other players. ``You have a meeting, you're teed off
and you air everybody out,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The manager said the pitching injuries were the primary problem,
but he suggested the unusually high number of potential free
agents, 14, might also have contributed to the team's demise.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think it was that much of a problem in the clubhouse,
but I think it is mentally for people,'' Miller said. ``Fourteen
free agents at the same time. If one's talking to the general
manager, the other 13 are wondering, `Why isn't he talking to
me?'''
</P>
<P>
   Uncertainty in the front office was another element he cited.
Pat Gillick, the general manager, was on his way to retirement,
Miller said, and his assistant, Kevin Malone, wasn't sure if he
would be back.
</P>
<P>
   ``During a lot of the time that the rough things were going
on,'' Miller said, ``they were out scouting. I don't think there
was anything intentional. There just wasn't a whole lot of planning
going on for now.''
</P>
<P>
   The free agency theory receives mixed reactions. B.J. Surhoff,
one of the free agents, said his status did not affect him and he
doubted that the others were affected.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone wants to talk about a lot of different things other
than how we actually performed,'' Surhoff, the veteran left
fielder, said. ``I just don't think we played very well.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Rafael Palmeiro, who is now with the Texas
Rangers, said free agency ``was probably a distraction for some of
the players,'' adding: ``Some guys use it as a motivating factor.
Other guys don't play well under it.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Flanagan, the team's pitching coach last year and one of
its broadcasters this season, said he thought the bulk of potential
free agents could have been a factor. ``It's human nature when you
don't have a contract and you're in your free-agent year, the
tendency is to play for some numbers because it is your chance,''
he said. ``Maybe the focus, although unintentional, has become a
little bit more on the individual.''
</P>
<P>
   Because they let some of the free agents go and lost others they
wanted, the Orioles had to scramble to fill spots. They added
Albert Belle for his bat; Will Clark to replace Palmeiro at first
base; Delino DeShields to replace Alomar, who went to Cleveland,
and Charles Johnson to catch and improve the performance of the
pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   The Orioles may not have the No. 1 payroll this season, but they
will be up there with the Yankees and the Los Angeles Dodgers. The
question is whether the players feel any residual stigma lingering
from their high-priced failure last year.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Erickson, the starter for the game in Havana, said they
don't. ``The players don't care about the payrolls,'' he said.
``It's something for other people to talk about.''
</P>
<P>
   Center fielder Brady Anderson said he did not think so either.
``I understand that the team with the highest payroll in baseball,
you'd expect to win more games than you lose,'' he said. ``But the
effort we had was there. The results just weren't very good.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoiles said last year was last year; it's gone and forgotten.
But is it?
</P>
<P>
   ``The guys who were on the team last year and went through that
whole process realize that we have something to prove this year,''
Bordick said. ``You can have that little chip on your shoulder,
whether it would be proving people wrong or proving to yourself
that you can do something right. Hopefully, we can use that to push
in the right direction and have some success.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
