<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BASEBALL NOTEBOOK: JIM ABBOTT, RICK HELLING 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Overcoming Another Obstacle
</P>
<P>
   Ever since he led the United States to an 8-3 victory over the
Cuban national team in Havana in 1987, Jim Abbott has been the most
popular foreign player among Cuban fans.
</P>
<P>
   Everybody has to cheer for Abbott, an incredibly courageous man
who has been a major-league pitcher despite a birth defect that
left him with only one hand. And the cheering will grow louder this
year because he has overcome another obstacle _ a sudden loss of
his pitching ability.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't feel like there's any finality to it; it's an ongoing
process,'' the 31-year-old left-hander said of his impressive
comeback. ``I'm enjoying playing again. I'm just going out there
having fun, trying not to make it as complicated as I used to.''
</P>
<P>
   A member of the Milwaukee Brewers' starting rotation, Abbott is
back after an anguished period in which he staggered to a 2-18
record with the Angels in 1996, was released and did not play in
1997, and then made a belated start to the 1998 season in the minor
leagues in his comeback attempt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a bad year in '96,'' he said. ``I just didn't pitch
well. I became tentative, didn't throw quality pitches. I came back
to spring training the following year trying to make the team and
put all that behind me and I couldn't do it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a tough time for me. I didn't know what I wanted. I
didn't know if I could do well in the big leagues any more. It took
me a while to figure out what I wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   In baseball terms, Abbott said, if he was not dead, ``I was in
serious resuscitation.'' Last year, he related, he realized he
missed playing. ``I was healthy and young enough and wanted to give
it a shot,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Chicago White Sox gave Abbott a chance, and he responded
positively. After stops at four minor league outposts from May 31
to Sept. 3, he started for the White Sox five times and won five
times.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a different pitcher than I was a couple years ago,''
Abbott said. ``I'm not as afraid to take a chance. I may throw an
off-speed pitch where I would never have done that before.''
</P>
<P>
   Playing in the National League, Abbott has found something else
that is different. He has to hit, not an easy feat for a one-handed
batter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always kind of adapted,'' he said. ``I just try to make
contact. This spring I've tried to learn to be more aggressive.''
</P>
<P>
   His education, it seems, never ends.
</P>
<P>
   A Confidence Booster
</P>
<P>
   Rick Helling never heard of Billy Loes, the Brooklyn Dodgers
pitcher of the early 1950s who said he did not want to win 20 games
because then he would be expected to do it every year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't really worry about what other people expect,'' said
Helling, a 20-game winner for the Texas Rangers last year. ``I
don't think you can expect anyone to win 20 games. Last year we had
four 20-game winners.''
</P>
<P>
   Helling pointed out that neither Greg Maddux nor Randy Johnson
were among them. ``Those are guys who are aces and guys you would
expect to do things like that year in and year out, but they didn't
do it,'' he said. ``It's not easy to do.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``I played on a good team,'' he said. ``I kept most of
the games close and ended up winning most of them. This year I
might pitch better and win less games. I was just fortunate last
year that we won most of the games I pitched.''
</P>
<P>
   Helling said the most important benefit he gained from his good
performance was an infusion of self-confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Greg Maddux told me this winter you don't win 20 games by
accident,'' the 28-year-old right-hander said. ``You can't be lucky
and win 20 games. That gives me the confidence to know I belong
here and it's possible for me to do it again. If it ever happens
again, who knows? But if I'm struggling or get off to a bad start,
I know in the back of my mind that last year wasn't just a one-year
fluke.''
</P>
<P>
   Beware of Scorpions
</P>
<P>
   Comforting sign in the Anaheim Angels' clubhouse in Tempe,
Ariz., on the wall next to the door the players' exit for their
workouts: ``Check and look in all shoes, bags and gloves for
scorpions!''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
