<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-27 19:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6643 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKW-PURDUE-DUKE-NYT &LR;      03-27 1005
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-PURDUE-DUKE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PURDUE TRANSFERS ADD TO DUKE'S INCENTIVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By BILL PENNINGTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JOSE, Calif. _ Michele VanGorp and Nicole Erickson came to
Purdue in 1995 hoping to lead the school to its first national
championship in women's basketball.
</P>
<P>
   Purdue is one game from that goal. VanGorp and Erickson, now
star players at Duke, stand in the way.
</P>
<P>
   The most intriguing subplot of Sunday night's Purdue-Duke
championship game of the National Collegiate Athletic Association
women's tournament is VanGorp and Erickson, who transferred from
Purdue to Duke in 1997, matched against their former teammates.
</P>
<P>
   The duo transferred after Purdue abruptly fired coach Lin Dunn.
VanGorp, who had 20 points in Duke's 81-69 semifinal victory Friday
night against Georgia, has remained angry about the dismissal,
though she said she has no ill feelings toward her old teammates.
Some of those who stayed at Purdue have acknowledged that they also
considered transferring and have watched VanGorp and Erickson with
a keen and fond eye.
</P>
<P>
   So it's safe to say that this will be a story line copiously
examined as the teams prepare for Sunday night's game. Even if the
principals involved might wish otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday night, just minutes after Purdue defeated Louisiana
Tech, 77-63, to advance to the championship game, senior Stephanie
White-McCarty, who played with VanGorp and Erickson, was asked her
emotions facing her former teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not just playing against those two,'' White-McCarty
said. ``We have to play against all their players. So I'm
approaching it like any other game.''
</P>
<P>
   The motivation might be more pronounced for VanGorp, who has
been the most outspoken about Purdue's decision to change coaches.
She has said Purdue officials never gave her an adequate answer for
Dunn's dismissal.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no reason for it,'' VanGorp said on the eve of
Friday's game.
</P>
<P>
   The VanGorp-Erickson saga comes against the backdrop of a bigger
story involving the Duke women's team _ their presence in the
championship game at all.
</P>
<P>
   Duke, a bit player in the sport until recent seasons, has made a
captivating charge through the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   In the final weekend of a tournament traditionally dominated by
a few powerhouse programs, underdog Duke has stolen the spotlight
with a tough-talking coach, a savvy, scrappy, senior-dominated team
and a certain aplomb in a season branded as madness.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not surprised by this,'' said Duke Coach Gail
Goestenkors after Friday's victory, which allowed her team to keep
serve in its figurative Final Four match with the Duke men's team.
``These aren't upsets to us. We expect to win the national
championship.''
</P>
<P>
   Duke will no doubt be considered the underdog again Sunday, but
it has flourished in the role.
</P>
<P>
   Tonight, reminded that her team was considered the least
talented of the four teams in the women's Final Four, Goestenkors
smiled.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't have to be athletic to be a great player,'' she
said. ``We have smart, poised players who know how to play
together.''
</P>
<P>
   Duke used the same formula to dismantle Georgia that was so
effective in its stunning upset of three-time defending national
champion Tennessee in Monday's East Regional final. There was
dependable inside play by the 6-foot-6-inch VanGorp and there was
the lively play of a trio of nimble guards, Georgia Schweitzer,
Peppi Browne, and Erickson, who led all scorers with 22 points.
</P>
<P>
   And Duke won with an infectious enthusiasm and a weaving,
pass-happy, team-oriented offense that involved every player on the
floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``They spread you out and kill you slowly,'' said Georgia Coach
Andy Landers. ``You find yourself yo-yoing defensively from a
talented inside post player and a talented bunch of perimeter
shooters. You choose your poison.''
</P>
<P>
   While Duke presented its offensive attack exactly as planned,
the Blue Devils also effectively slowed Georgia's star twin guards,
Kelly and Coco Miller.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly Miller came into Sunday night's game averaging 27.5 points
per game in the tournament but sank just 5 of 13 shots against Duke
to score 13 points. Her sister led Georgia with 18 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew we had to focus on the twins,'' Duke's Erickson said.
``We saw on film that they liked to go to their left and then
shoot, so we tried to force them to their right. And we bumped them
around a little.''
</P>
<P>
   Interestingly, the Millers, who are 5-10, were supposed to be
the physical presence that thwarted and wore down Erickson, who is
5-6.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't happen that way. Erickson came out shooting, making
her first shot as she led Duke to a 40-34 halftime lead.
</P>
<P>
   VanGorp started slowly, hampered by a smothering Georgia
double-team. But she closed the first half by scoring eight of
Duke's last 12 points. At the start of the second half, she hit a
three-point corner jumper and another pull-up jumper, leading Duke
to a 13-point lead.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia's pressure defense, led by the Millers, rattled Duke
briefly, cutting the Blue Devil lead to seven points at the
midpoint of the second half. But Duke, which has three starters who
shoot better than 80 percent from the foul line, made 8 of 11 free
throws in the final eight minutes to help protect the lead.
</P>
<P>
   Erickson also hit two 3-point shots in the final minutes to ruin
any Georgia comeback hopes.
</P>
<P>
   Purdue, which has not lost since Nov. 22, took an early
advantage against Louisiana Tech, led by 18 first-half points by
guard Ukari Figgs.
</P>
<P>
   Figgs, who teams with White-McCarty in what is considered the
best backcourt in women's college basketball, made three of her
first four three-point shots as Purdue took a 40-27 halftime lead.
</P>
<P>
   Louisiana Tech mounted a comeback that cut Purdue's lead to
58-55 midway through the second half, but led by Figgs, Purdue
scored 14 unanswered points.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have anything to prove to anybody,'' Figgs said
afterward. ``We're No.1 and we're here to win a championship.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
