<SLUG> BC-OUTDOORS-NY-TROUT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OUTDOORS: MILD WINTER AUGURS WELL FOR TROUT SEASON 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By NELSON BRYANT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Even if you have made no preparations for the April 1 opening of
the trout fishing season in New York state, there is still time to
get some of your gear in order, an endeavor that should heighten
your anticipation of the pleasures that lie ahead.
</P>
<P>
   And if the weather doesn't turn around between now and Thursday,
stream conditions in much of the state will be close to ideal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a fairly mild winter,'' said Wayne Elliott,
fisheries manager for the state's Department of Environmental
Conservation's Region 3, which includes Westchester, Putnam,
Dutchess, Rockland, Orange, Sullivan and Ulster counties, adding
that many of the streams were open most of the time. ``As far as I
can remember, every snowstorm that we got this winter shifted over
to rain before it was done.''
</P>
<P>
   Stocking of trout, mostly browns, is under way in Hudson Valley
streams, Elliott said. In discussing the Amawalk, which he
described as ``a delightful wild trout stream,'' he noted that in
Region 3 and the state generally, stream trout fishing is limited
to lures or flies. The intent of the regulations, he said, is to
minimize mortality among fish that are released. Amawalk
regulations allow one to keep three trout of 12 inches or more in
length.
</P>
<P>
   A substantial infusion of 2-year-old brown trout _ fish from 12
to 15 inches _ are being released in many Region 3 streams this
year, Elliott said, about 10,500 of them. About 1,000 of those
fish, all tagged, are going into Esopus Creek. These spaghetti-type
tags are inserted under the dorsal fin. It is important, he said,
that anglers who catch any of these tagged fish return the tags to
the state's DEC. Anglers who wish to release such fish could simply
leave the tag implanted, note its number and report the date and
place of catch to the department.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Pierce, a DEC fisheries biologist whose duties include
watching over the Amawalk and the East and West branches of the
Croton River, is pleased with the success of a special no-kill
section of the West Branch, which was instituted a few years ago.
About a mile of the stream, between Croton Falls reservoir and the
stream's confluence with the East Branch of the Croton, is
involved. Anglers who fish this section with lure or fly have a
better than usual chance of encountering good numbers of wild brown
trout, some of them over 15 inches long.
</P>
<P>
   The East Branch continues to remain open to fishing with flies
or lures year-round _ from the East Branch reservoir to the
diverting reservoir _ and there is a daily limit of one trout, 14
or more inches in length.
</P>
<P>
   In the Catskills, the Beaverkill and the Willowemoc are in great
shape, said Ed Van Put, a wildlife technician with the DEC and a
master fly fisherman.
</P>
<P>
   Save for lingering snow and cold in early March, Van Put said:
``It was an easy mild winter. The streams beds haven't been scoured
by any significant floods or ice jams, and the trout should be
prospering.''
</P>
<P>
   As one might expect at this time of year, Long Island's three
major trout streams, the Connetquot, Nissequogue and Carman's
River, are eminently fishable. On the Carman's, more than two miles
of which are in Suffolk County's Southaven Park, it's fly fishing
only on the stream itself, with one stretch set aside for catch and
release, but lures and bait may be used on the pond and lake at the
downstream end. The daily limit, where allowed, is three trout,
nine inches or more in length. The daily fee is $2, and one may
fish from sunrise to sunset, seven days a week. The telephone
number is (516) 854-1414.
</P>
<P>
   On the Connetquot, in a state park of the same name in Oakdale,
a catch-and-release fly-fishing season is under way. The regular
season, also limited to fly fishing, begins Thursday. Starting that
day, there will be three daily sessions _ 7 to 11 a.m., noon to 4
p.m. and 4 p.m. to sunset _ and two trout of any size may be kept.
There are 30 beats, or fishing sites, and the fee is $15 a session.
There is no Monday angling. Reservations can be made by calling
(516) 581-1005. There is a bonus for angler-birders who visit this
stream: its ospreys have returned from warmer climes and are
nesting, said the park manager, Gil Bergen.
</P>
<P>
   On the Nissequogue, which is in Caleb Smith State Park in
Smithtown, there are eight river beats and five pond beats. One may
keep two fish daily, nine inches or more in length. It's fly
fishing only and there are two four-hour sessions daily save for
holidays and weekends, when there is a third session that starts at
4 p.m. ends at sundown. The fee is $15 a session. The number for
information and reservations is (516) 265-1054. Fishing is closed
on Mondays unless it is a holiday.
</P>
<P>
   A state fishing license is also needed to fish these three
streams.
</P>
<P>
   At the very least, if you are a fly fisherman, you should make
sure that you have a good supply of nymphs, wet flies and streamers
to take with you opening day. It might also be wise to bring along
a dozen or so small dries, perhaps No. 20 or 22 Adams, because if
the day is sunny and warm, there will be a hatch of tiny aquatic
insects on some pools.
</P>
<P>
   You should also test or inspect your waders for leaks. One
oft-suggested approach to this is to don your waders and slip into
a water-filled tub. This technique is dubious. Visual scrutiny _
including going into a dark room and running a flashlight around
the interior of the waders _ is best. Circle the flaws with a
marking pen so you can tell where to put the patches.
</P>
<P>
   If this is all too much, you can simply haul your waders out of
the cellar at the last minute, put them on, wade in and wait for
the worst. If there is a big leak, you are done for the day unless
you choose to retreat to your vehicle and apply a patch then and
there. In some instances, particularly if the day is cold and
nasty, this might be a welcome diversion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
