<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MAIN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO TARGETS SERB GROUND UNITS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER AND AND LOUISE D. PALMER AND  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Serb troops, defying NATO's four-day aerial siege,
stepped up their deadly attacks Saturday on ethnic Albanian
civilians in Kosovo, increasing pressure on the Clinton
administration and US allies to consider launching a ground war to
halt the atrocities.
</P>
<P>
   With all signs indicating that the NATO offensive has yet to
slow the slaughter in Kosovo, allied forces targeted Serb tanks and
troops in the separatist province and focused a new wave of missile
attacks on Belgrade, the Yugoslav capital.
</P>
<P>
   A NATO official warned that ``dark things are happening'' in
Kosovo, including reports of Serb forces murdering members of the
ethnic Albanian leadership, rounding up and killing military-age
men, and bombing and burning villages.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslavia said Saturday night that it had downed a NATO plane,
and a Dutch official said he had similar reports. If true, it would
be the first allied plane to be shot down since the offensive
began.
</P>
<P>
   The developments came amid growing pleas from ethnic Albanians
in Kosovo for NATO troops to fight Serb security forces on the
ground, and US officials confronted the public's enduring
reluctance since the Vietnam War to commit US soldiers to foreign
wars.
</P>
<P>
   ``We welcome the strikes, but we demand that NATO ground troops
come into Kosovo as quickly as possible,'' said a spokesman for the
Kosovo Liberation Army, which is fighting for autonomy for ethnic
Albanians who represent about 90 percent of the province's
population.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton said last week he had no plans to send combat
troops to Kosovo, and officials at the White House and Pentagon
Saturday reiterated his position.
</P>
<P>
   In his weekly radio address, Clinton called for NATO ``to stay
the course'' in order ``to defuse a powder keg at the heart of
Europe.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton made no reference to the potential for US involvement in
a ground war. But in a letter to congressional leaders that was
released Friday night, he said he had dispatched 100 Marines to
defend the US Embassy in neighboring Macedonia, and he raised the
possibility of sending an unspecified number of additional troops
to conduct operations such as combat search and rescue,
intelligence support, surveillance and reconnaissance in the
region.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sound military planning may also call for sending a limited
number of additional US military personnel to Macedonia in support
of ongoing operations,'' Clinton said in the letter.
</P>
<P>
   Although he expressed confidence Saturday in the outcome of the
NATO operation, he reported no progress in curbing the alleged Serb
war crimes. In fact, Clinton said, ``Serb troops have continued
attacks on unarmed men, women, and children.''
</P>
<P>
   In London, British Defense Secretary George Robertson provided a
bleaker assessment. ``There are clear signs now that an all-out
Serbian offensive against the Kosovo Albanian people has started
and violence is widespread,'' Robertson said. ``The Serbs are
bombarding villages to the point of obliteration.''
</P>
<P>
   Amid the brutality, thousands of Kosavars continued to flee to
neighboring countries. More than 250,000 people already have been
displaced, and the State Department Saturday projected that more
than 500,000 could be driven from their homes in the conflict.
Human rights groups reported that a Kosovo political nerve center
was burned down, as was a food warehouse operated by the Mother
Teresa organization.
</P>
<P>
   NATO Secretary General Javier Solana, in forgoing ground troops,
ordered allied military forces to expand their attack by targeting
the Serb operation in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The strategy could place NATO pilots at greater risk of attack
by Serb antiaircraft units because the jets and helicopters will be
required to fly closer to the ground to hit tanks, artillery, and
mobile command posts.
</P>
<P>
   But the decision to begin the assault, dubbed Phase Two of
Operation Allied Force, was seen as an indication that NATO leaders
are confident that the first stage of the attack crippled much of
Yugoslavia's air defense system and command and control facilities.
</P>
<P>
   In Aviano, Italy, US combat pilots, speaking to reporters for
the first time since the operation began, expressed surprise at the
minimal opposition they have encountered. ``We have not seen
anywhere near the amount of aircraft weaponry employed that we
thought we would see,'' said one Navy pilot, who was not permitted
to identify himself.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton signed off Saturday on the second phase of the operation
after meeting at the White House with his foreign policy advisers
and speaking with British, French, and German leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Solana gave the order to the supreme allied commander, US Army
General Wesley Clark. ``I have taken this decision with the support
of all allied governments, which are determined to bring a halt to
violence in Kosovo and prevent further humanitarian catastrophe,''
Solana said.
</P>
<P>
   NATO officials said warplanes and cruise missiles will continue
to strike military targets throughout Yugoslavia as part of the
effort to force Milosevic to accept a peace agreement that grants
autonomy to the ethnic Albanians in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   In massive raids Friday night and early Saturday, NATO aircraft
flew 249 sorties, and Tomahawk cruise missiles were seen soaring
across the Belgrade skyline before they detonated. Serbian state
radio reported that NATO missiles and bombs destroyed a military
barracks, a munitions dump, and a telecommunications site. New
attacks began late Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time since the strikes began, Serbian television
also reported that nonmilitary targets were hit, including a
factory and a pharmaceutical plant on the outskirts of Belgrade.
NATO officials denied those reports.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic called the NATO military action the worst threat to
world peace since 1945. He issued the statement after Russian
President Boris N. Yeltsin sent him a message of support and the
Russian foreign minister, Igor Ivanov, decried the NATO siege as
``a dark chapter in history.''
</P>
<P>
   Russian leaders have said their military will not enter the
conflict. But tensions remained high, as the Communist-dominated
parliament Saturday advised Yeltsin to formally cut ties with NATO.
Also, angry Russians protested in Moscow for a third day to express
solidarity with the Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   Crowds also demonstrated outside embassies in Berlin, Rome,
Athens, Vienna, and London. Some protesters clashed with police.
Others hurled objects at the embassies of NATO nations. And some
burned US flags and shouted anti-American slogans.
</P>
<P>
   Disagreement over the NATO mission also festered among US
political leaders. Delivering the Republican weekly radio address,
Senator John Ashcroft of Missouri said the Clinton administration
had yet to articulate a clear plan for the mission.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our duty obligates us to demand a clearly focused mission for
our soldiers,'' Ashcroft said. ``They deserve the complete
commitment of every American they serve and the certain leadership
of the commander-in-chief they obey.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, in his radio speech, said maintaining peace in Europe
is a vital US interest. ``Through two World Wars and a long Cold
War, we saw that it was a short step from a small brushfire to an
inferno, especially in the tinderbox of the Balkans.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
