<DOCNO> NYT19990327.0207 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-27 19:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6646 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-ETHNIC-CLEASIN     03-27 1056
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-ETHNIC-CLEASING-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SERBS' `ETHNIC CLEANSING' CALLED MORE AGGRESSIVE IN KOSOVO THAN IN
BOSNIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (editors: this has been added to Page 1 of The New York Times)  
 (bl)  
 By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The brutality against ethnic Albanian civilians by
Serb forces represents a ``broad-based ethnic cleansing campaign
across Kosovo'' that is far swifter and more sweeping than similar
efforts by Serbian forces during the war in Bosnia, a senior
Clinton administration official said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The administration had been caught off-guard by the scale of the
operations being carried out in Kosovo by Serbian security police,
the Yugoslav army and paramilitaries, the official said. Although
prepared for a large-scale military effort by the Serbs against the
ethnic Albanian guerrillas of the Kosovo Liberation Army, the
administration was not anticipating sweeping operations against
civilians.
</P>
<P>
   ``The brutal and evil nature is shocking,'' he said. ``Even for
hardened people, it's terrible.''
</P>
<P>
   The administration now knew of summary executions of men, and
the forced eviction of thousands of women, children and elderly men
by bus into northern Albania late Saturday, the official said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got the military sweeping across, fighting the Kosovo
Liberation Army and then burning shops and villages,'' the official
said. ``There is a great human tragedy unfolding. I don't want to
tell you all of Kosovo is aflame, but bad stuff is going on, and a
lot of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Pristina, the capital of Kosovo, was awash Saturday night in
leaflets apparently distributed by the Serbian authorities
encouraging ethnic Albanians to leave Kosovo via Macedonia, the
official said. Yugoslav army tanks have been patrolling the streets
of Pristina for the last several days in an attempt to intimidate
the urban population, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The administration was still short of hard evidence because
foreign monitors left Kosovo last weekend, Western journalists were
forced out and telephone lines have been cut. The official insisted
that cloud cover over Kosovo in the last few days had stymied
efforts to get clear satellite and other aerial images of the
humanitarian disaster.
</P>
<P>
   But enough anecdotal evidence had been gathered from all over
Kosovo _ a hilly, mostly rural area about the size of Connecticut _
to convince administration officials of the scale of Milosevic's
brutality.
</P>
<P>
   By way of comparison, the official cited landmark incidents in
the Bosnian war _ the massacre at Srebrenica and the use of
concentration camps for Muslim men of fighting age _ and said that
what was happening now in Kosovo was broader and faster-paced, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   By quickening the pace tonight of the air campaign against
Milosevic, the administration was ``doing everything we can'' to
try and curb the effects of what he described as Milosevic's
``brutal rampage.''
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials ordered the air campaign to begin when
Milosevic refused to sign a peace deal and then stepped up his
campaign of violence against Kosovo's Albanians. The administration
had ``no choice,'' even though it turned out that it encouraged
Milosevic to further accelerate the brutality, the official said.
</P>
<P>
   The Yugoslav leader would have tried to accomplish the same
ethnic cleansing even without the NATO attacks, the official said.
``It would have happened slower with no penalties for him,'' the
official said, who added that the conflict between NATO and
Milosevic was now developing into ``an awful test of wills.''
</P>
<P>
   Human rights workers and officials of the Organization for
Security and Co-operation in Europe, who have been trying to
collect evidence of the past few days atrocities, described a mass
execution near Velika Krusa, just north of Prizren in southern
Kosovo; the burning of large sections of Pec, a major town west of
Pristina; and the use of civilians as ``human shields'' in an
attempt to deter NATO attacks on Serbian military installations.
</P>
<P>
   There were numerous accounts of men missing, of whole villages
burned and homes torched. About 20,000 refugees who had huddled on
the Kosovo side of the border were now being bused into northern
Albania, administration officials said. Military-aged men were
noticeably missing in the retinue, they said.
</P>
<P>
   The bodies of about 35 men, women and children were found around
Velika Krusa on Saturday, according to a military official with the
Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe. This official
said he had been told by a commander of the Kosovo Liberation Army
in Kosovo, who spoke by satellite phone, that the bodies were found
shot and mutilated near a rail line. Thirteen other bodies of two
families were found nearby and the bodies of two elderly men burned
in their homes were also found, this official said.
</P>
<P>
   The guerrilla commander had also described seeing many other
bodies, maybe as many as several hundred, in the area but his men
had been unable to approach them because of fighting between Serbs
and the guerillas in the area, this official recounted.
</P>
<P>
   This official, a key liaison between the OSCE and the ethnic
Albanian guerrillas, said he was confident that the information he
received Saturday from the local guerrilla commander was credible.
This was in part because he had been able to double check it with
other sources in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   According to several accounts, a large swath of Pec, a pretty
town with well established residential areas, was on fire Saturday
night. An ethnic Albanian living in Washington, who asked not to be
identified, said he spoke tonight to a relative in Pec who
described seeing burning houses from his window and hearing steady
shelling from the direction of Serb military positions. The
relative said that he saw about 200 civilian men being marched down
the main road of the city to an unknown destination. The men were
flanked by Serbian policemen, he said.
</P>
<P>
   A report issued Saturday by the human rights office of the
Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe said repeated
reports were being received of ethnic Albanians being detained as
``human shields.'' The organization said that the reports could not
be verified but appeared credible.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Part of the agency's statement said: ``The reports that Albanian
civilians are being detained as ``human shields'' _ i.e., placed
strategically at military or other installations in an effort to
deter NATO bombing _ remain persistent but so far are proving
impossible to verify. In the past 24 hours further reporting of the
large-scale round-up of up to 20,000 people at Cirez (still
unconfirmed) describes this as a `human shield' operation.''
</P>
<P>
   Human rights officials working for the organization, which is
based in Vienna, said they had rarely encountered such frustrations
in trying to determine developments on the ground. Telephone
contact with Kosovo was almost impossible, they said.
</P>
<P>
   One worker, who asked not to be identified, said that most often
telephones in Kosovo that used to be answered by well-known
contacts of the organization were ringing but not being answered.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is unclear whether communications have been deliberately
disrupted, whether the individuals concerned are in hiding, or
whether something more sinister has happened to them: the general
experience when trying to contact people is that telephones appear
to be be ringing but go unanswered,'' Saturday's report said.
</P>
<P>
   A man reached by phone in Pristina on Saturday, Adem Demaci, a
prominent political activist who has campaigned for decades for
Kosovo's independence, described sitting in his apartment in the
dark Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last night we had about 60 shellings of restaurants and shops
in Pristina,'' Demaci said in describing a Serbian sweep through
the capital. ``The restaurants are all closed, the proprietors have
all gone away and the shops robbed.''
</P>
<P>
   Demaci said that six bodies, shot and then burned, had been
found in a street of the Pristina suburb of Kosovo Polje on Friday
night. ``There have been many killings in Pristina and people are
in great fear,'' he said. The streets were virtually deserted,
DeMaci said. Only three or four bakeries were operating.
</P>
<P>
   The OSCE human rights report said Saturday that many
Albanian-owned businesses had been set on fire by police,
paramilitaries or Serb civilians, creating the specter of a food
shortage. It voiced concern that civilians are also beginning to
run out of food because they cannot venture out.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
