<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-27 19:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6648 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-KOSOVO-NATO-NYT &LR;      03-27 0624
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-KOSOVO-NATO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: INVENTING NATO'S NEW ROLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: KOSOVO-RDP, KOSOVO-FORCE, KOSOVO-BELGRADE,
KOSOVO-MILOSEVIC, KOSOVO-RUSSIA, KOSOVO-CLINTON, KOSOVO-TURKEY,
KOSOVO-ASSESS, KOSOVO-MACEDONIA) 
 (bl)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Sunday, March 28:
</P>
<P>
   The air campaign against Yugoslavia is doing what years of
abstract debate could not. It is beginning to define the role for
the NATO alliance to play in post-Cold War Europe. Four days of
bombing is not enough to resolve this issue fully. But the early
indications are that the members of the expanded alliance are
capable of a unified response to threats to Continental security
and stability.
</P>
<P>
   Despite NATO's recent expansion to 19 members, the alliance
summoned the political unity required for decisive action to meet a
dangerous military crisis less than 100 miles from the borders of
NATO Europe. It acted with U.S. military leadership but with broad
combat participation from European members.
</P>
<P>
   In line with this unity, most NATO members have contributed in
some way. Britain, Canada, France, Germany, Italy and six other
countries in Europe have sent pilots to raid Yugoslav targets.
Others have provided air bases.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, there have been uneven spots in the European
support. Italy, despite its military cooperation, and Greece have
voiced some reservations. But the larger pattern has been that of
NATO giving unanimous political approval to the operation. It was a
demonstration of the kind of policy coordination that some of the
same countries have not been able to summon over non-European
issues like Iraq and Iran.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. planes, ships and missiles have been the largest single
component in the attacks. But NATO's European members have shown an
encouraging new assertiveness that makes it reasonable to imagine
Europe at last taking on broader responsibility for security
issues. Despite the historical sympathies several governments have
felt for Serbia, most have been able to recognize that they have an
interest in Balkan security and in halting the Serbian atrocities
that have driven Kosovo Albanians to seek refuge in other European
countries.
</P>
<P>
   The most striking change has taken place in Germany, which for
decades after World War II understandably and correctly shunned any
military activism beyond German frontiers. But Germans have now
spent more than half a century proving to themselves and their
neighbors that they have become responsible and conscientious
Europeans.
</P>
<P>
   Today's German leadership, including German military commanders
and the new socialist-led government of Chancellor Gerhard
Schroeder grew up after the war, and Germany is now ready to take
its proper place as one of NATO's leading members. European NATO
members cannot assume as much responsibility as they should for
Continental security without a strong and confident German
contribution.
</P>
<P>
   One note of caution must be sounded even as the U.S.-led air
strikes go forward. In regard to NATO's future, this operation must
be regarded as a deliberate, real-time testing of principles and
methods, rather than as a tactical model for all future crises. The
very fluidity of the situation in Yugoslavia supports the point.
NATO will face more difficulties this week. Slobodan Milosevic not
only continues to resist the international peace plan, but he seems
intent on intensifying his violence against the people of Kosovo
with paramilitary troops that cannot easily be stopped by air
power.
</P>
<P>
   If the alliance can preserve the unity and resolve it showed
last week, it should be able to pick apart and pressure Milosevic's
forces over time, and ultimately prevail.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
