<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-REVLON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL OBSERVER: IS IT TIME FOR RON PERELMAN? 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By FLOYD NORRIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sometimes a company gets attention it would just as soon pass
up. Last week Revlon Inc., the cosmetics company controlled by
Ronald Perelman, got a double dose. Rumors of an impending takeover
put the company at the top of the business section just as the
generosity of its president, George Fellows, put it on the front
page.
</P>
<P>
   Fellows provided transportation so that Howard Safir, the New
York City police commissioner, could attend the Academy Awards.
Company spokesmen firmly denied any impropriety in the police
furor, but Perelman, who has controlled Revlon since 1985, was
silent on the takeover rumors that sent the company's stock
soaring.
</P>
<P>
   If he does sell Revlon, Perelman would make a good profit, but
the gain would be nowhere near as great as it would have been had
Revlon been sold a year ago, before its stock fell sharply amid
excess inventories and talk that the company needed new products.
</P>
<P>
   Both pieces of publicity had unpleasant sides for Perelman, who
declined to be interviewed. The Safir trip reminded people of the
tycoon's willingness to do favors for the powerful, as in the offer
of a job to Monica Lewinsky before she became famous. And the
Revlon rumors focused attention on the problems of Revlon and other
companies in Perelman's corporate stable.
</P>
<P>
   Those problems have been growing for a couple of years. They
have not led to Perelman's eviction from the billionaires' club,
but they have damaged the wealth of those who invested in his
companies, and they have raised the issue of whether his reputation
for brilliance may have been overdone.
</P>
<P>
   Revlon seemed to be on a run a few years ago, with its Colorstay
makeup being touted as age-defying and growing Asian sales. But
then competitors brought out their own new products, Asian markets
trembled and Revlon announced layoffs. Suddenly, investors started
focusing on the $1.7 billion in long-term debt on the company's
books and the stock price fell as low as $12, half the price at the
company's 1986 initial public offering. Now it is back above $22,
thanks to the rumors.
</P>
<P>
   In one way, Revlon's performance is typical. Each of the four
companies that Perelman has taken public in the 1990s has been a
loser for investors who bought at the offering and held on. An
investment of $4,000, spread evenly among the four, would now be
worth about $2,600. That is not good during a bull market.
</P>
<P>
   That calculation seems unfair to Howard Gittis, Perelman's top
aide. ``If you buy when he does, and come out when he does, you do
fine,'' he says. That is true, and is shown by the performance of
such companies as New World Communications, the broadcaster that
was sold to Rupert Murdoch's News Corp. in 1997. Investors who
bought the stock at the same time as Perelman did very well. It is
those who bought stock when Perelman's companies went public who
have done poorly.
</P>
<P>
   Why? In the case of Coleman Co., the camping-equipment maker,
Perelman got hoodwinked. He agreed to sell the company for more
than $30 a share to Sunbeam, then run by Albert ``Chainsaw Al''
Dunlap.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, most of the payment was to be in Sunbeam stock,
which cratered amid questions about the company's accounting that
led to Dunlap's ouster. Coleman shares are now worth less than they
sold for in the 1991 offering. ``It's hard to protect yourself
against false financial statements,'' said Gittis.
</P>
<P>
   At Consolidated Cigars, the biggest cigar company in the nation
and the maker of such brands as El Producto and Muriel, Perelman
rode the cigar boom up and then back down. In 1996, investors were
sold stock at $23 a share, more than 14 times what Perelman had
paid. A few months ago the entire company was sold to a French
tobacco company, for $17.85 a share. Perelman made a big profit,
while public investors lost money.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was Marvel Entertainment, the comic-book company that
diversified into sports trading cards under Perelman's tutelage.
Both businesses soared as adults became active collectors, but
overleveraged Marvel went broke after the fads ended. An investor
who bought stock when Marvel went public in 1991, and held on, now
has some odd pieces of paper that give him or her the right to buy
securities in the successor company to Marvel. A $1,000 investment
is worth about $2.
</P>
<P>
   There can be no takeover of Revlon without Perelman's approval.
If he sells now, he will get plenty of money. But if he holds on,
he has a chance to revive both the company's fortunes and his own
reputation as a businessman and investor.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
