<HEADER>
A6651 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OBIT-PETROV-NYT &LR;      03-27 0465
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-PETROV-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VLADIMIR PETROV, 83, SOVIET PRISON CAMP SURVIVOR AND PROFESSOR  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Russia, Germany, Italy, Conn., Md., Va., Mass., Calif.,
Minn.)   By CARMEL McCOUBREY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Vladimir Petrov, who survived six years in a Soviet prison camp
and later became a professor of international affairs at George
Washington University, died on March 17 in his home in Kensington,
Md., a suburb of Washington. He was 83.
</P>
<P>
   The cause of his death was brain cancer, his family said.
</P>
<P>
   Petrov recounted his experiences in the camp and in World War II
in two memoirs, ``Soviet Gold'' (1949) and ``My Retreat From
Russia'' (1950), that were praised as brisk adventure stories as
well as important early sources of information about the Soviet
labor camps.
</P>
<P>
   Born in 1915 in what is now Krasnodar, Russia, he was a
19-year-old engineering student in Leningrad when he was arrested
and accused of espionage, which he dismissed in his books as having
been concocted by a woman in the secret police whose advances he
had spurned.
</P>
<P>
   He was sent to a labor camp in northeastern Siberia, in the
Kolyma River gold basin, traveling for 47 days in a sealed train
car with 60 other men. There were 500,000 inmates, and one year, he
said, as many as 70,000 died. Conditions were so bad, he wrote,
that ``few political prisoners ever live out their terms.''
</P>
<P>
   He was released in 1941, just before the Nazi invasion, and
bribed and finagled his way back to Krasnodar. Petrov's antipathy
for the Soviet system led him, as the war went on, to join a
German-sponsored movement to recruit a Russian force for a
last-ditch stand against the now-advancing Communists. As the Nazis
retreated, so did he.
</P>
<P>
   He made his way to Austria, where he was imprisoned briefly in a
Nazi camp. He escaped after a week, writing that after his
experiences in Soviet incarceration, ``it was as easy as breaking
out of kindergarten.'' Then he fled to American-occupied Italy.
</P>
<P>
   In 1947 he moved to the United States, and spent much of the
next two decades teaching Slavic languages at Yale. In 1965 he
received a doctorate in political science from Yale and joined the
Institute for Sino-Soviet Affairs at George Washington University.
He became professor emeritus in 1985.
</P>
<P>
   Petrov's marriage to Mirtala Kardinalowska ended in divorce. He
is survived by his wife, Jean; a son from his first marriage,
George, of Minneapolis; five daughters from his second marriage _
Susanna Petrov of Boston, Lili Robins of Stafford, Va., Anne Petrov
of Paris, Jane Petrov-Aronsohn of Washington and Carol Petrov of
Kensington; three sons also from his second marriage _ Vladimir of
Los Angeles, Alexander of Rockville, Md., and Andrew, of
Kensington, and six grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-27-99 1933EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990327.0213 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-27 19:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6658 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-REFUGEES-BOS &LR;      03-27 1506
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-REFUGEES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLEEING REFUGEES RECOUNT HORROR THEY LEFT BEHIND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT AND KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROJZAYE, Yugoslavia _ Beaten and terrified, ethnic Albanians
fleeing across the border to Montenegro on Saturday described a
systematic campaign of terror by Serbian forces in Kosovo,
including executions, looting, random machine-gun fire in the
streets, and all-night grenade attacks on Albanian villages.
</P>
<P>
   The Albanian Muslims reaching here said they had packed into
cars and fled for their lives from the city of Pec, the ancient
seat of the Serbian Orthodox Church and the most coveted city in
Kosovo for Serb forces.
</P>
<P>
   Their accounts indicated that the Serbs' ``ethnic-cleansing''
campaign has taken on a chilling ferocity as the fourth straight
night of NATO bombing continued to pound the Serbian forces of
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   A bruised and shaken couple, Fatima and Redjeb Djanbaya, arrived
in Rojzaye just two hours after being forced from their home and
driving through the smoldering ruins of their hometown of Pec.
Redjeb, a businessman, sat in the red Opal they used to escape,
beaten, frightened and unable to speak. His wife said four Serbian
paramilitary in green fatigues had opened fire on their home in the
center of Pec at noon and shattered the front windows before
bursting in.
</P>
<P>
   The couple was told they were going to die. The paramilitaries
stripped off Fatima's rings, bracelet, and necklace, forced Redjeb
to drink whiskey _ a sin for Muslims, clubbed him with a rifle
butt, and then, inexplicably, allowed them to flee _ Fatima with no
shoes.
</P>
<P>
   About 80 miles to the southeast, an ethnic Albanian who gave his
name only as Remzi crossed the border from Kosovo at Blace,
Macedonia, after making the most harrowing journey of his life. He
pulled the maroon Volkswagen Passat carrying his wife and three
children to the roadside and wept.
</P>
<P>
   ``Catastrophe,'' he said, over and over. Over his shoulder, less
than a mile away, several homes in an Albanian village were ablaze,
the orange flames leaping in the fading light of dusk.
</P>
<P>
   Remzi, who refused to give his last name, saying he feared for
relatives he left behind, was one of hundreds who crossed the
border into Macedonia Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike most of the refugees spilling out of Kosovo, Remzi is a
man of substance. He said he paid Serb paramilitary police
``thousands of deutsche marks'' at four separate checkpoints to
make it the 60 or so miles from his home to the border.
</P>
<P>
   He had watched from a distance, he said, as his lawyer, Bajram
Kelmendi, and Kelmendi's two sons were summarily executed by Serb
police three days ago. On Saturday, human rights groups reported
that the body of Kelmendi, a prominent civil rights lawyer, had
been dumped outside Pristina, the capital of Kosovo. ``They threw
their bodies on the side of the road,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Remzi's story and those like it were cited Saturday by officials
from NATO countries as reason why the attacks against Serb forces
operating in Kosovo needed to be stepped up.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Serbs have been torching villages, separating men and boys
from their families and shooting them in cold blood,'' George
Robertson, the British defense secretary, said at a news conference
in London. In Washington, officials said there was increasing
evidence that the Serbs were summarily executing ethnic Albanians,
apparently in retaliation for the NATO airstrikes and because there
was no international presence in Kosovo to deter or document the
killings.
</P>
<P>
   Corroborating reports of atrocities remained difficult because
international observers and news organizations have been expelled
from Kosovo or left for their own safety. But after previous
massacres by Serb forces, few international observers doubt their
willingness to perpetrate such acts.
</P>
<P>
   Fernando del Mundo, a spokesman for the United Nations High
Commissioner for Refugees, said his organization has not been able
to confirm reports of mass executions. He also said his
organization had heard, but had not been able to confirm, widely
reported allegations that up to 20,000 refugees were being forced
to march through central Kosovo by Serb troops. Del Mundo was
skeptical of the report, saying the alleged area was not heavily
populated.
</P>
<P>
   The details recounted by the refugees from Pec and elsewhere,
however, had a consistency that lent them a terrifying ring of
truth.
</P>
<P>
   Fatima Djanbaya remembered that one of the men who burst through
her door barked, ``We've come to kill you. We have orders.''
</P>
<P>
   The Serbs held a pistol to Redjeb's head and forced him to sit
at the kitchen table, she said. They ordered Fatima to lie face
down on the floor, then opened a bottle of whiskey they were
carrying and ordered Redjeb to drink, a calculated insult to his
Islamic faith. Then they smashed the side of his jaw with the butt
of a rifle and beat him.
</P>
<P>
   The Djanbayas begged for their lives and offered the Serbs
anything they wanted to spare them, she said. The paramilitaries
then stripped her of her jewelry, including her wedding ring.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kosovo belongs to Serbs, you should all leave. Or you will
die,'' the soldiers said.
</P>
<P>
   Fatima ran out in her stocking feet, and Redjeb, nearly
unconscious, stumbled out behind her. They made it to their car and
drove as fast as they could, passing the smoking ruins of ethnic
Albanian neighborhoods of Pec.
</P>
<P>
   ``Half of the city was burning,'' she said. ``We saw as we
drove, and we cried. I still cannot believe I am alive.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We will never see our home again. We left everything,'' she
said, describing the ordeal in a relative's home in Rojzaye.
</P>
<P>
   This Montenegrin town is set in the rugged canyons of the
Morache River valley, where some 4,000 ethnic Albanian refugees
have arrived since last summer. Legions more have massed across the
border in recent weeks but have been turned back by Yugoslav border
patrols and Montenegrin police. Only those with money to bribe
border guards have been able to cross. Most end up fleeing instead
to neighboring Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   But those who managed to make it here in recent weeks gave
chilling accounts of events in Pec as the buildup to the NATO
attack ignited attacks against Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   One large family, named Delajaj, found itself pulled apart by
the war. On Saturday, 16 family members, including 11 children,
packed into two compact cars, a Volkswagen Golf and a Honda Accord,
and fled, leaving others behind.
</P>
<P>
   Merita Delajaj, 22, said they decided to escape after a long
night during which Serbian paramilitaries surrounded the extended
family's cluster of homes. In Saturday's pre-dawn darkness, machine
gun fire shattered the windows of a house that faced the road,
where five male relatives, including her husband, were staying to
protect it from looters. She said she and 10 female relatives,
along with 15 children, huddled in the corner of another house as
the machine-gun fire rattled outside.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were very afraid. We just tried to cover the children, and
pray we wouldn't be killed,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When NATO started the bombing, the Serbs attacked us very
hard. They came house to house and are pushing the Albanians out.
They are killing those who stay behind,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   When they fled Saturday morning, with only two cars and limited
amounts of money to bribe the border guards, heart-wrenching
decisions had to be made. Parents had to choose which children to
send across the border, and which to keep behind. Merita left with
her two children, but her husband stayed behind. ``We just came
with the clothes we had. We took nothing. We ran to save the
children,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   At one point she was overwhelmed and sobbed uncontrollably. She
left the room as her two children, a 3-year old boy and a
6-year-old girl, looked on. When she came back, she said, ``It is
my husband. I don't know if he is alive or dead.''
</P>
<P>
   Phone connections to Kosovo have been badly disrupted, so
families spend hours dialing over and over the numbers of their
homes. Some described the ominous experience of hearing Serbian
voices answer.
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear just how many have fled, but some refugees said at
least half of the 100,000 ethnic Albanians living in and around Pec
had fled.
</P>
<P>
   The bloodletting has pitted neighbor against neighbor. ``These
were our friends, our neighbors,'' said Adel Radonchic, as she and
her husband described the Serbian paramilitary troops, some of whom
they have known all their lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't blame them for this. We blame Milosevic. He is the
only one who can be blamed,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Just before nightfall, 73-year-old Darnoli Abdula walked through
the border checkpoint. He said he had walked for two hours from his
village, Gajre, after Serb troops forced him to leave at gunpoint.
</P>
<P>
   ``The army burned my house,'' he said. ``The whole time I walk
here, I see nobody. I just see fire. All the houses on fire.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
