<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-U.N.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.N. PANEL URGES NEW INSPECTIONS IN IRAQ 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JUDITH MILLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ The 20-member panel reviewing Iraq's
disarmament record has concluded that because of Iraq's
unwillingness to reveal information, the United Nations needs to
continue to monitor, inspect and investigate Iraq's weapons
programs, diplomats said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The 27-page report is written in diplomatically opaque language
that reflects the numerous compromises among the divergent
political interests of its members. But at least three people who
have seen it said Washington and its allies consider it essentially
an endorsement of the Special Commission, whose inspections of
weapons programs have so infuriated Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
   ``In spite of well-known, difficult circumstances,'' the report
concludes, the commission and the international nuclear monitoring
agency ``have been effective in uncovering and destroying many
elements of Iraq's proscribed weapons programs in accordance with
the mandate provided by the Security Council.''
</P>
<P>
   The panel met Saturday to approve the document, a copy of which
was shown to The New York Times. The draft has been intensely
debated in secret sessions for more than a week by its panelists _
who come from the United States, Britain and other nations that
have strongly backed the special commission, and from Russia and
China, which have argued that the commission has outlived its
usefulness and that sanctions against Iraq must be lifted.
</P>
<P>
   Celso Amorim, the Brazilian representative to the United
Nations, who is chairman of this panel and two others that focus on
Iraq, is expected to give the document to U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan and the Security Council on Sunday or Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The report recommends some changes in the nature and structure
of the inspectors' group and the commission that oversees the
group's activities. It recommends, for example, that the commission
meet four times a year instead of twice and that it more closely
monitor the inspectors' activities.
</P>
<P>
   But the document contends that a future inspection system, what
the document calls ``reinforced ongoing monitoring and
verification,'' must be both ``comprehensive and intrusive,'' which
Iraq has strongly resisted in the past.
</P>
<P>
   Effective inspection, the report concludes, depends on ``full
and free access'' to suspect sites, and it stresses that
international inspectors must be given unimpeded access to all such
sites, including those at military facilities. ``Indeed,'' the
report states, ``the reinforced ongoing monitoring and verification
would be, if anything, more intensive than the one so far
practiced.''
</P>
<P>
   To achieve that, the panel recommends that more inspectors be
hired to monitor Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   According to several people familiar with the panel's
deliberations, the Russian and Chinese representatives pressed hard
at first for the report to conclude that Iraq had answered the most
important questions about its past weapons program, and that
therefore there were no ``disarmament issues'' that required
continuing investigation.
</P>
<P>
   But the report concludes the opposite. In virtually every major
weapons category, there are still outstanding ``disarmament
issues'' that merit further investigation, the document states,
particularly in Iraq's reporting on its biological weapons program,
where ``critical gaps'' remain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Iraq possesses the capability and knowledge base thorough
which biological warfare agents could be produced quickly and in
volume,'' the report warns.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
