u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKW-LADYFINAL-ADVANCE     03-27 0466
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-LADYFINAL-ADVANCE28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New faces in women's final
 &HT;    By Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JOSE, Calif. _ For a Final Four that has been missing a lot
of familiar names, tonight's national championship game featuring
Duke and Purdue offers plenty of interesting subplots.
</P>
<P>
   There are the two Duke seniors, guard Nicole Erickson and center
Michele VanGorp, going up against their old school, which they left
after a former coach was dismissed in the wake of recruiting
violations.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's current Purdue coach Carolyn Peck, who is coaching
her last collegiate game before moving on to a job in the WNBA this
summer.
</P>
<P>
   And most importantly, the winner will become a national champion
for the first time, a feat that deserves notice in a sport that in
the '90s has been dominated by Tennessee and Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone new is going to win the national championship,'' Duke
coach Gail Goestenkors said. ``The sport is ready for a new
national champion. How could it get any more exciting than that?''
</P>
<P>
   Top-ranked Purdue (33-1), which has won 31 consecutive games,
has been installed as a slight favorite to become the first Big 10
women's team to win a national crown, and that's just fine with
Duke.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pressure is all on Purdue,'' VanGorp said. ``They're the
ones who have been ranked No. 1, who have to uphold their standing.
We're the underdogs and we're trying to come in and topple the big
dog.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Boilermakers, who have upset Tennessee this season, have
succeeded because they don't overlook any foe.
</P>
<P>
   ``The record doesn't matter at this point,'' Peck said. ``We've
got to go out and play the game for 40 minutes, maybe 40-plus
minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   Duke (28-6), which beat Georgia 81-69 in the national semifinals
on Friday, is finishing the season where it started. After an
embarrassing 104-74 loss to UConn in San Jose in November, the Blue
Devils overcame a rash of preseason injuries to reel off 16
consecutive wins, capture the regular-season ACC title and upset
Tennessee in the Elite Eight.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a national championship on our minds,'' Erickson said.
``I think having the seniors we have on our team and the
competition we've faced all year has really prepared us for this.''
</P>
<P>
   The game will be the last for Purdue's dynamic senior guard duo
of Stephanie White-McCarty and Ukari Figgs, who stuck around when
then-coach Lin Dunn was fired in 1996. Despite several transfers,
the Boilermakers are enjoying the greatest season ever by a women's
Big 10 team.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're glad they decided to stay here,'' Purdue forward Katie
Douglas said of White-McCarty and Figgs, ``because I know we
wouldn't be here without them.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
