</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FREEWAY-MISTAKE-3takes-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FREEWAY INTERCHANGE MISSING TWO IMPORTANT LEGS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY LEE CONDON  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Thousands of L.A. drivers pay every day for a
mistake the state transportation agency made 32 years ago _ the
failure to connect the 5 and 134 freeways in all four directions.
</P>
<P>
   The result is that motorists traveling between two of
California's busiest freeways must detour onto streets in
neighboring Burbank, causing bottlenecks and bedlam for motorists
and neighbors alike.
</P>
<P>
   At the dawn of Los Angeles freeway construction, engineers
predicted Burbank and nearby Glendale would never grow large enough
or generate enough traffic to justify the cost of building ramps
from the 5 south to the 134 west and from the 134 east to the 5
north.
</P>
<P>
   They were wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Since the interchange opened in 1967, pass-through traffic grew
109 percent to an average of 441,000 cars and trucks a day _ making
it the 16th busiest freeway connection in the state. And Burbank
and Glendale are hubs of the entertainment industry, home to major
studios and drawing in thousands of new commuters a day.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a major freeway interchange that's missing two important
legs. It seems obvious that it would be done,'' said Burbank City
Manager Robert ``Bud'' Ovrom.
</P>
<P>
   This detour junction was built for $8.2 million in 1967. Adding
connectors would cost an estimated $80 million _ a fraction of the
$400 million to correct the bottleneck at the 101-405 freeway
interchange a few miles to the west.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the state Department of Transportation stopped
building incomplete junctions, the top transport agency official in
Los Angeles says there are no plans to add ramps to the 5-134
interchange.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have it on our priorities list,'' said Bob Sassaman,
acting director for the agency's District 7.
</P>
<P>
   The transport agency wants to focus on such projects as building
car-pool lanes, the 710 Freeway extension to Pasadena, north of
L.A., and adding sound walls, Sassaman said. ``The missing moves
are not as important to us. There are a lot more projects people
want us to do first,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Some motorists may think the incomplete interchange is
ridiculous, but in the 1950s and 1960s the design likely made
sense, Sassaman said. Planners assumed drivers on the 5 south could
take the 170 Freeway south to the 134 Freeway, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They likely anticipated that this was a minor move and
wouldn't be needed. When it was done I'm sure it made sense,''
Sassaman said.
</P>
<P>
   Unable to budge the state agency, the city of Burbank, Los
Angeles and Glendale have joined in a $50,000 study they hope will
prove the need for ramps.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's crazy. It's incomprehensible to me how they could build
that intercharge the way they did,'' said Frank Barneburg, chairman
of the Burbank Transportation Commission.
</P>
<P>
   The study has won support from key politicians and business
leaders.
</P>
<P>
   David Fleming, a prominent civic leader in L.A's San Fernando
Valley and vice chairman for the California Transportation
Commission, said he never uses the freeway when he travels into
Burbank because he does not want to have to get off and then back
on the freeway.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously people expect a freeway interchange to go in all
directions. Now you're stuck with half a system,'' he said.
Although the project may be daunting and expensive, Fleming said
Burbank should push forward.
</P>
<P>
   State Assemblyman Scott Wildman, D-Burbank, said he will push
the agency to reconsider building ramps, if even just for equity
between Los Angeles and other areas of the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Los Angeles has gotten the short end of the stick. You
look at the Bay Area and you can see where the money has gone,''
Wildman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have soundwalls on their freeways to protect cows from
hearing too much noise. Then you have people in Toluca Lake (in the
San Fernando Valley) who have been waiting for years for
soundwalls.''
</P>
<P>
   Momentum also is mounting in the Burbank and Glendale business
communities for construction of the ramps.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it would be a benefit to all the businesses located in
this part of Burbank,'' said Dan Millman, general manager of the
Media City Center, located off the Olive Avenue exit of the 5.
``The current route is cumbersome at best.''
</P>
<P>
   Millman said the detour is confusing to his shoppers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a large number of people who call us every day asking
for directions. They get lost and they want to know exactly what
streets to take to get here. I think there's many people who use
routes through the city rather than getting on the freeway.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It would absolutely take traffic off of Alameda Street and
Riverside Drive,'' Ovrom said. ``We have a big investment in the
Media City Mall, and I think it would increase people's willingness
to go there.''
</P>
<P>
   Ken Green, a spokesman for Disney, said the company contributed
to the cost of doing the study as part of its involvement in a
transporation coalition with the other studios and the cities of
Burbank, Glendale and Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   (SECOND TAKE FOLLOWS)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-27-99 1943EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
