<DOCNO> NYT19990327.0221 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-27 19:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6668 &Cx1f; ttc-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FREEWAY-MISTAKE-2ndta     03-27 0822
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FREEWAY-MISTAKE-2ndtake-LADN </SLUG>
 
LOS ANGELES: and Los Angeles. 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients)
<TEXT>
<P>
   Green said company officials have not yet decided whether they
support contruction of the new ramps, but agreed to help the cities
in their effort to see if adding the missing ramps back was a good
idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``We like the other studios see ourselves as a member of the
local community. It's appropriate for us to have a study that may
have an impact on improving traffic here.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the transport agency's engineer who led the design of the
134-5 interchange some 40 years ago believes the connectors must be
built because of population growth in the area.
</P>
<P>
   ``Times have changed. All of these freeways are carrying much
more traffic than what they were designed for,'' said Jess
Reynolds, who supervised a design team on several interchange
projects in L.A.'s San Fernando Valley. ``This would be the time to
take a look at some of these missing links. Maybe if it's justified
it can be done.''
</P>
<P>
   The interchange borders Burbank and Los Angeles, which has
thrown in its support for the connectors as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have a freeway to freeway interchange it should
provide for all moves,'' said Robert Takasaki, a senior
transportation engineer for the Los Angeles Department of
Transportation.
</P>
<P>
   Burbank's study so far indicates the new connections at a cost
of $80 million are possible but difficult to build.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Yamarone, principal traffic engineer for Burbank, said
engineers and consultants expect preliminarily to recommend against
building the ramps because of the great cost.
</P>
<P>
   ``The amount of traffic that would be using it just didn't
justify the impact and the cost,'' Yamarone said.
</P>
<P>
   If the next phase of the study shows that city streets are being
flooded by freeway traffic, Yamarone said he thinks city staff
would change its recommendation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We definitely would revive the ramp idea,'' Yamarone said.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless, the Burbank City Council has been pushing for the
connectors for more than a decade and has lined up political
support elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if that recommendation will be well-received. One
of the purposes of the study was to get Caltrans (the state
transport agency) to agree not to hold us to current standards,''
Burbank Councilman Ted McConkey said. ``I don't think we're going
to give up.''
</P>
<P>
   Yamarone said part of the problem is that the agency has strict
standards for how new ramps could be built.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd have to have much broader ramps than the ones we were
trying to make work,'' Yamarone said. ``We knew we'd never be able
to get an exception.''
</P>
<P>
   So far the city believes that to build the connectors, only a
group of horse stables would have to be taken. But pieces of
Griffith Park and the Los Angeles River also could be affected,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   During the interchange's construction in the 1960s, the effect
on Griffith Park was among the reasons the transport agency chose
not to build the connectors.
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds said a connector from the 134 east to the 5 north would
have meant taking an even bigger chunk of Griffith Park away than
was stripped away just to build the freeway.
</P>
<P>
   ``They felt it could be handled by the city streets,'' Reynolds
said, who retired from the agency in 1972. ``We didn't anticipate
that movement would have that much traffic.''
</P>
<P>
   Now Reynolds said he and the designers were wrong.
</P>
<P>
   The failure to build the connectors is a result of several
critical errors in judgment: First, engineers relied largely on
projections about future land use and development growth.
</P>
<P>
   The predictions, from the Los Angeles County Regional Planning
Department, did not contemplate the tremendous growth in the San
Fernando Valley in the last 40 years.
</P>
<P>
   The population of Burbank and Glendale rose from 234,559 in 1967
to 301,608 today, according county figures.
</P>
<P>
   And those statistics don't count the thousands of people drawn
to the two cities each day for work in the movie and television
studios. Jobs in Burbank alone grew from 75,000 in 1970 to 105,000.
</P>
<P>
   Making matters more urgent, in studies done for studio expansion
projects traffic engineers have found the 5 and 134 freeways have
reached overcapacity.
</P>
<P>
   Just ask Stan Freitag, a set builder who travels the surface
street link between the 5 south and the 134 west.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've gone through this way every day for the last nine years.
I don't understand the logic. All of a sudden you're dealing with
people crossing the street and stopping at stoplights,'' Freitag
said.
</P>
<P>
   Pressure to save money played a part in the interchange's
deficient design.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the transport agency was building for the future,
there was pressure to save money, so the designers were encouraged
to eliminate any links that they didn't think would be heavily
used, Reynolds said.
</P>
<P>
   (THIRD TAKE FOLLOWS)
</P>
</TEXT>
