<HEADER>
A6667 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AT-HOME-REAL-2TAKES-N     03-27 0872
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT-HOME-REAL-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW RULE ON LEAD DRAWS FIRE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JAY ROMANO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Beginning June 1, the federal government will require
contractors and others involved with renovation of painted surfaces
in pre-1978 residential buildings to notify both occupants and
owners of the hazards of lead-based paint.
</P>
<P>
   The regulation, which critics say will impose burdensome and
impractical requirements on owners and co-op boards, has been
mandated by the federal Environmental Protection Agency in its
``Pre-Renovation Lead Information Rule,'' which was issued on June
1, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The rule attracted a modest amount of attention when first
proposed in 1994, with about 30 official ``comments'' submitted by
trade organizations and advocacy groups nationwide. But lawyers for
co-ops and condominiums and representatives of multifamily property
owners now say that compliance will be difficult in many situations
and virtually impossible in others.
</P>
<P>
   Dayton Eckerson, a lawyer for the EPA, said that the agency was
aware of the difficulties in complying with the new regulation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The vagaries of different areas of the country can make what
seems to be a pretty straightforward rule end up looking pretty
complicated,'' he said. ``And we are going to have to come out with
some specific guidance for specific situations.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Eckerson said, the agency intends to issue written
clarifications on the new rule with the next six to eight weeks.
</P>
<P>
   One of the more vocal critics of the regulation is Dan
Margulies, executive director of the Community Housing Improvement
Program, a Manhattan-based trade association of apartment building
owners.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an insane requirement,'' he said. ``It is
inconceivable that this rule can be complied with in the real
world.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the new regulation, Margulies explained, whenever a
contractor expects to disturb more than two square feet of painted
surface in a house or apartment _ for example, by sanding, scraping
or otherwise preparing a painted surface for repair _ the
contractor must provide information about lead-based paint hazards
to the owner and occupants of the premises. If the work is in a
common area of a multiple dwelling, he said, the contractor must
provide lead-hazard notices to the property owner and, it seems, to
occupants of all apartments.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just think about how many times this notice requirement would
be triggered in a 100-unit building,'' Margulies said. ``Every
paint-patching episode, every ceiling-leak repair would require a
new notice.''
</P>
<P>
   And the notice requirements themselves, he said, are daunting.
For example, Margulies said, for a covered repair in a common area
the contractor must inform the property owner and building
residents about the nature and extent of the proposed renovations,
including start and end dates for the work to be performed. And the
contractor must also make the EPA's official lead-hazard pamphlet,
``Protect Your Family From Lead In Your Home,'' available at a
central location in the building.
</P>
<P>
   The notification of the owner must be performed by hand
delivering a copy of the notice and obtaining an acknowledgment of
the receipt, or by mailing the notice to the owner a week prior to
the start of the work. Notification of the residents, Margulies
said, can be made by slipping the notice under the door of each
apartment.
</P>
<P>
   If the notice is made by mail or by slipping it under the door,
the contractor must prepare a certification indicating how and when
the notice has been provided. The contractor must then keep the
signed acknowledgments and certifications on file for three years
following completion of the work.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a well-maintained building you're doing constant
maintenance,'' Margulies said. ``You'll have contractors sending
notices to tenants on a weekly basis. And then, if the scope of a
particular project changes, or the start date gets pushed back a
few days, the contractor has to start all over and send out a whole
new set of notices.''
</P>
<P>
   At very least, he said, the additional expense involved in
complying with the rule will be passed along by the contractors to
building owners. And while it may at first appear that only
contractors are required to comply with the new rule, he said, it
is likely that many property owners and co-op and condominium
boards will also have to comply with the rule as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``In most multiple dwellings, building employees end up doing
this kind of routine maintenance,'' he said. ``And that will make
the owner responsible for complying with the law.''
</P>
<P>
   Errol Brett, a Manhattan real estate lawyer, said that it is
essential for boards to make sure that the law is being followed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We live in a litigious society,'' Brett said. ``And since
board members can be held accountable for the acts of others, they
have to be absolutely sure that there is strict compliance with the
new rule.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the penalties for violation of the rule are significant _
up to one year in prison and up to $25,000 a day in fines _ the
only way a board can truly be certain that the rule is being
followed is to assume the responsibility for following it.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``It's better to be safe than sorry,'' Brett said, adding that
at the very least boards should include specific language in
renovation contracts requiring the contractor to provide proof to
the board that the required notices have been provided.
</P>
<P>
   But as a practical matter, he said, boards may have an even more
compelling reason for providing the notices.
</P>
<P>
   ``I represent a condominium in Queens with 1,100 apartments,''
Brett said. ``That means that if I have to make it possible for
every contractor the condominium hires to comply with the law, I
have to give each contractor the name and address of every unit
owner in the building. And there are a lot of companies out there
who would pay those contractors a lot of money to get those names
for their mailing lists.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, he said, while co-op apartments are legally owned by
the co-op corporation individual units are frequently sublet by
shareholders. Under the new regulation, he explained, it is unclear
who should be notified and how the notification should be made.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Brett said, he was not sure whether a board has the
right to provide lists of names and addresses of unit owners
without first obtaining their approval.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Cholst, a Manhattan co-op lawyer, said that another
problem with the new rule was its ambiguity. For example, he said,
while the rule contains an exemption for minor repairs _ those that
disturb less than two square feet of painted surface _ it is
unclear what must be done when a one-square-foot repair
unexpectedly expands to three-square feet.
</P>
<P>
   Another problem, he said, is that in one place the rule requires
notification of the occupants of ``each affected unit'' when a
common area renovation is being performed, yet in another it refers
broadly to ``each unit of the multifamily housing.''
</P>
<P>
   The former wording, he said, would seem to make it necessary to
notify only those on, say, a floor where a particular renovation is
being made. The latter phraseology, on the other hand, implies that
all occupants must be notified no matter where work is being done.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would appear to be an absurd interpretation,'' he said.
``But the phraseology is so ambiguous, and the potential fines and
penalties are so high, it probably pays to notify everyone for
almost everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Another puzzling element of the regulation, Cholst said, is that
while every occupant might have to be notified for a relatively
minor repair conducted in a common area, only the occupant and
owner of a particular apartment must be notified when repairs _ and
even significant renovations _ are being performed inside the
apartment.
</P>
<P>
   Accordingly, Cholst said, he intends to suggest to buildings
that he represents that whenever board approval is necessary for a
renovation in a shareholder's apartment, such approval be made
contingent upon the shareholder's acknowledging receipt of the
required notice from the contractor and perhaps even notifying
other unit owners of the work being performed.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to impose a huge burden on boards and managing
agents and shareholders,'' he said. ``But it's always better to err
on the side of caution.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
