<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-27 19:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6670 &Cx1f; ttc-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FREEWAY-MISTAKE-3rdta     03-27 0629
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FREEWAY-MISTAKE-3rdtake-LADN </SLUG>
 
LOS ANGELES: Reynolds said. 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients)
<TEXT>
<P>
   The trade-off is that some Los Angeles commutes are longer than
necessary, exacting a cost in wasted time on the road. In Los
Angeles during 1996, a trip that should take 20 minutes actually
took slightly more than 30 during rush hour, and the average
Angeleno spent 76 hours in traffic delays, costing $1,205 each
year, according to a University of Texas study.
</P>
<P>
   ``We only designed for 20 years into the future,'' said Mel
Hodges, chief officer of project studies for the agency. ``That
freeway was designed in the 50s.''
</P>
<P>
   Hodges explained that the 5 and the 134 come together at an
angle, so the thinking at the time was that people coming south on
the 5 would not need to go west on the 134 because they could have
taken the 170 south as a more direct route to the 134.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have no need to come back in the opposite direction,''
Hodges said.
</P>
<P>
   However, the agency also neglected to connect the 170 south to
the 101 west, requiring drivers to exit the 170 and take city
streets to the 101 entrance.
</P>
<P>
   Key to the agency's resistance to the 134-5 interchange is that
engineers say other, more heavily traveled interchanges are in need
of improvement.
</P>
<P>
   The peak rush-hour traffic at the intersection of the 101 and
405 freeways is 24,000 cars, while the 5-134 junction handles
14,000 cars.
</P>
<P>
   However, agency's numbers don't include drivers making the
connection by using Burbank surface streets.
</P>
<P>
   By the agency's estimation, those streets are not heavily
traveled either.
</P>
<P>
   About 9,500 cars a day exit at the 134's Victory Boulevard exit,
but only 2,500 make the link to the 5 north at the Western Avenue
onramp. Agency officials say that if a connector to from the 134
east to the 5 north was needed, those counts would be much higher.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't even see that move making even a dent in circulation
of city streets. If there was a big need for it there would be a
lot of people leaving Victory and Western,'' said Nick Jones, an
associate transportation engineer for the transport agency.
</P>
<P>
   Burbank leaders insist the missing link causes major traffic
problems.
</P>
<P>
   Councilman Bob Kramer said city officials see fixing the missing
link problem as part of an overall strategy to imporve traffic flow
on the freeways and city streets.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see it as a way to eliminate cut-through traffic in our
city. There's no question people use Hollywood Way and Buena Vista
Street to get from the 5 to the 134 quite a bit.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent years Burbank has put in speed bumps, chokers and
narrow surface streets to encourage commuters to get on the
highways rather than clogging up residential streets.
</P>
<P>
   From the start, the transport agency designed freeways for a
principal use: Long, regional trips and commuting.
</P>
<P>
   Ovrom said that people today are using the freeways for shorter
trips, many of them within the San Fernando Valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole system was designed to be spokes leading from the
suburbs into Los Angeles. Today that has all changed. Most of the
movement now is suburb to suburb traffic,'' Orvom said.
</P>
<P>
   The agency has not changed its philosophy. Sassaman said that
suburb to suburb traffic can be handled by surface streets and that
freeways were never meant to provide for motorists making short
trips.
</P>
<P>
   ``The freeway is set up for regional trips, not for local
trips,'' Sassaman said.
</P>
<P>
   Jeanne Armstong, director of development for the city of
Glendale, said her city wants the new ramps, in part because of
Glendale's retail war with Burbank.
</P>
<P>
   ``We certainly don't want people getting off the freeway in
Burbank,'' Armstrong said. ``We want them to come straight to
Glendale.''
</P>
</TEXT>
