<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHICAGO-REAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW LUXURY TOWERS ARE SPROUTING IN CHICAGO 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ROBERT SHAROFF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ After a decade-long drought in new construction,
downtown Chicago is suddenly awash in new luxury apartment towers.
About half a dozen towers are currently rising on the Near North
and South Sides, several in neighborhoods not previously known as
high-end residential enclaves.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, luxury housing in Chicago tended to be concentrated
in the Gold Coast, a neighborhood a mile north of the Loop and
consisting of Lake Shore Drive and three streets to the west. But
none of the new buildings are in this area.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, several are either on or just off Michigan Avenue,
while the rest are in neighborhoods that for most of this century
have been industrial and commercial areas.
</P>
<P>
   How is luxury defined in Chicago? The most common definition is
a purchase price of more than $300 per square foot.
</P>
<P>
   Informally, however, brokers and developers say that a luxury
apartment starts at about $1 million. All of the new buildings
contain at least some apartments at that price level.
</P>
<P>
   ``There used to be a real difference between what you got for
$300,000 and what you got for $700,000,'' said James Kinney,
president of Rubloff Residential Properties, a leading downtown
brokerage. ``Now, to get that same `wow factor' you're talking at
least a million dollars.''
</P>
<P>
   This is relatively new ground in Chicago. Five years ago,
according to data from the local multiple listing service, there
were 33 sales of $1 million or more downtown. In the last 14
months, however, there have been 122 sales, with an additional 56
$1 million-plus units currently under contract.
</P>
<P>
   Why the run-up in prices at a time when inflation remains at
historic lows? ``There's just a lot more money in Chicago today
then there was at the beginning of the decade,'' said Diane Swonk,
deputy chief economist at Bank One Corporation here. ``The economy
has been booming and it doesn't take many years of 20 percent
returns on assets to create a lot of disposable income.''
</P>
<P>
   If the numbers in the demand side of the equation are up, the
numbers on the supply side are down. ``This is the tightest market
for luxury sales I can remember,'' said Joan Armstrong, a broker
with Koenig &AMP; Strey who has specialized in Gold Coast real estate
for more than 20 years. ``There is very little to show people. If
they're nice apartments, they're gone in a week, often for more
than the asking price.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the new buildings under construction, the most notable are
Park Tower, the Bristol and Riverview, with Park Tower in
particular perceived as a premier luxury address.
</P>
<P>
   Park Tower, on the west side of Water Tower Square at Michigan
and Chicago Avenues, is a joint venture of Hyatt Corp. and LR
Development. The architect is Lucien Lagrange, principal of Lucien
Lagrange and Associates, a firm noted locally for innovative
residential work.
</P>
<P>
   The building, a streamlined 67-story Art Deco affair clad in
cream-colored stone, will open in the summer of 2000. The first 20
floors will be occupied by the 203-room Park Hyatt Hotel. The rest
will consist of 115 condominium units, including eight full-floor
penthouses. Condominium prices range from $617,000 to $3.5 million,
with an average of more than $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   According to Bruce Abrams, president of LR Development, all of
the penthouses have been sold and all but five of the remaining
units are spoken for.
</P>
<P>
   ``We researched the market and found that people wanted the
service and amenities that go with a hotel, but not the traffic and
congestion,'' he said. The solution, he added, was to have two
entrances _ one for the hotel on Chicago Avenue and another for the
condominium around the corner on Water Tower Square. Tenants also
will be able to order room service from the hotel and will have
access to the hotel's lavish health club.
</P>
<P>
   The building is extravagantly scaled, with apartments up to
10,000 square feet and with ceiling heights up to 15 feet. All of
the units face east and have clear views of Lake Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted the same feel you get in some of the classic Lake
Shore Drive apartment buildings from the '20s and '30s,'' said
Lagrange, the architect. ``The wasted space is really what makes
those old apartments special _ the galleries and vestibules and
hallways and niches. These aren't spaces that you eat or sleep in,
but there's something comfortable about them and also very
elegant.''
</P>
<P>
   Lagrange is personally designing several of the apartments in
the building and says the dominant style is ``more Beaux-Arts than
Bauhaus. People want columns and moldings. It's very classical,
very traditional.''
</P>
<P>
   Several blocks away, at the corner of Rush Street and Delaware
Place, is the Bristol, a 41-story International Style tower being
developed by Golub &AMP; Company. The architectural firm is Solomon
Cordwell Buenz Associates, based in Chicago. The building's 189
units range in price from $275,000 to $1.4 million. According to
Golub president Michael Newman, about 35 percent of the units have
been sold so far. The building will be completed by the end of the
year.
</P>
<P>
   Both the Bristol and Park Tower are within easy walking distance
of the Gold Coast. The third building, Riverview, has a more
adventurous location. That bulding is part of an emerging
neighborhood along the north bank of the Chicago River where it
meets Lake Michigan. For most of Chicago's history, this land _
within shouting distance of the Loop _ has been occupied by
warehouses and factories.
</P>
<P>
   It is now being developed into a mixed-use neighborhood that
includes residential, hotel and entertainment facilities as well as
a pedestrian promenade along the river. Riverview, which is being
developed by MCL Companies, will ultimately consist of three towers
with a total of about 400 units and about 30 town houses. The
architect is Gregory De Stefano of De Stefano and Partners, based
in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   The first phase, which will open late in 2000, consists of a
98-apartment tower and nine town houses. The tower units start at
about $285,000 and go up to $2 million while the town houses, which
face the river, start at $1.1 million and go up to $2.1 million.
According to Daniel McLean, president of MCL, 35 tower units and
four town houses have been sold. ``The site is spectacular _ you're
surrounded by water on three sides,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   What do you get for a $1 million today? ``Over 3,000 square feet
of space, fancy kitchens with granite countertops, hardwood floors
throughout, marble bathrooms, nine-foot ceilings and great views of
the lake and downtown,'' said McLean.
</P>
<P>
   The new luxury buyers, say developers, are a different crowd
than in the past in that suburbanites make up a much bigger part of
the mix. ``In the '80s, maybe 10 to 15 percent of the downtown
buyers were suburbanites,'' said McLean. ``Today, it's 40 or 50
percent. Many are empty nesters in their early 50s with high
incomes. They want to be downtown where there's lots to do.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're getting a surprising number of suburbanites _ probably
35 percent _ who are either moving to the city or are buying a
second residence downtown,'' said Newman.
</P>
<P>
   One such buyer is Harvey Kinzelberg, who, with his wife, Mary
Ann, recently purchased a 4,000-square-foot penthouse at Park
Tower. Kinzelberg, 54, is the founder of Sequel Capital Corp., an
industrial leasing firm based in suburban Deerfield.
</P>
<P>
   Kinzelberg, who currently lives in Glencoe, a tony North Shore
suburb, says he is ready for a change. ``The children are grown and
we want to experience the city _ the restaurants, the museums, the
wonderful architecture. The city's vibrant and exciting. It's time
for us to have some fun.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
