<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KINGS LOOK TO THE FUTURE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The time hasn't yet arrived, but it is drawing
near.
</P>
<P>
   In the coming days, barring a miraculous, season-saving
turnaround, the Kings officially will start thinking about next
season.
</P>
<P>
   Their version of the white flag of surrender will be a move to
recall some of their top prospects from the minors, giving several
players a taste of the NHL and giving Kings management what it
hopes will be an eye-pleasing glimpse of the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our playoff hopes are dim,'' general manager Dave Taylor
acknowledged. ``We could win eight or nine games (of the 11
remaining) and still not get in, the way Calgary is playing.''
</P>
<P>
   Consequently, it probably won't be long until the recalls begin.
The Kings, who begin a five-game trip today in Colorado, are
permitted four, and may begin to use them this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to the East Coast,'' Taylor said, referring to
Tuesday night's game in Boston against the Bruins. ``We'll see
where we stand.''
</P>
<P>
   Taylor said he has four players in mind to recall.
</P>
<P>
   Winger Jason Podollan, acquired this week in the deal that sent
Yanic Perreault to Toronto, probably will be promoted from the Long
Beach Ice Dogs of the IHL. The Kings also probably will recall
winger Pavel Rosa. And from Springfield of the AHL, the Kings
probably will recall winger Josh Green, who began the season in the
NHL, along with center Eric Belanger. A back injury, however, might
prevent Belanger from playing.
</P>
<P>
   For the moment, the Kings continue to cling to playoff hopes as
they prepare for their five-game swing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mathematically, we're still there,'' coach Larry Robinson
said. ``But time is ticking.''
</P>
<P>
   It has been a tumultuous week for the Kings, the $4.25-million
divorce settlement with Steve Duchesne the most notable event.
After the Kings shipped the disappointing defenseman to
Philadelphia on Tuesday, Taylor indicated that the experience
probably would make the team more fiscally conservative in the
future.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor indicated that Kings management has reached the
conclusion that building a consistent winning team, rather than
stocking the roster with stars, is the surest way to make the
franchise successful at the box office.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still question whether a star would do it,'' Taylor said.
`` A winning team would do it. A star and a winning team would
definitely do it.... Even going to Anaheim, they have two of the
best players in the game (Paul Kariya and Teemu Selanne), and they
still have empty seats there. That's what's alarming about this
game. It's hard for a family to afford to go to a game. We have to
bring the sanity back.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Taylor doesn't dispute that the Kings desperately need a
high-scoring forward. Adding one and staying within a budget is the
complicated part. Ideally, improvements in the team would come from
the pool of players drafted the last few years. But the Kings'
prospects are still in their developmental stages, and Taylor did
not rule out signing a free agent this summer. He did say, however,
that the Kings will be very careful before they do so.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll have to find ways to improve the team,'' Taylor said.
``We'll have to be creative and we'll have to take chances with
free agents, college free agents.... You're guaranteed to be
spending money now. Is it guaranteed to help the team? That's the
question. We can only control our (own spending). We have our plan.
Developing players is going to be really important to us. But we
have to find ways to improve ourselves in the short-term.''
</P>
</TEXT>
