<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-AIR-ATTACK-525&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLITICS AND GEOGRAPHY LIMIT NATO AIR ATTACK 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS: This is a late add to page 1 of the New York Times.)  
(lh) 
 By ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ By moving to widen the attack against Yugoslavia's
military targets, NATO is still trying to cut off the head of
Belgrade's war machine rather than dismember it piece by piece.
</P>
<P>
   NATO officials in Brussels, Belgium, announced Saturday that
allied fighter-bombers were shifting to a second phase to intensify
attacks on the Yugoslav tanks, troops and artillery that are
gouging a brutal offensive through Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   But senior Clinton administration officials challenged that
claim Saturday, accusing NATO diplomats of raising expectations
that allied fighter-bombers might not be able to deliver _ right
away or ever.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslavia's heavy weaponry has been on NATO's target list from
the start, Pentagon officials said. But the top priority of the
campaign's first phase was knocking out Serbian air defenses to
prevent the downing of any NATO planes, a precaution that may have
failed Saturday night if reports from Serbia are proven true that a
radar-evading F-117 stealth fighter was shot down.
</P>
<P>
   Under the broader campaign announced Saturday, NATO air forces
will attack a larger proportion of strategic military targets _
like command posts, headquarters, ammunition depots and airfields _
in a concentrated swath of Yugoslavia south of Belgrade, below the
44th parallel. The closer targeting had not begun by Saturday
evening, in part because the weather over Yugoslavia was
unsuitable, and in part, NATO officials said, because Yugoslav air
defense systems made it unsafe.
</P>
<P>
   But if NATO officials were to attack heavy weaponry in earnest,
commanders would be ordering aloft A-10 Warthogs, armed with
Maverick anti-tank missiles, and perhaps armor-busting attack
helicopters. They are not, administration officials say, fearing
that Army helicopters smack too much of ground forces, which have
been ruled out for now, and that the slow-moving, low-flying A-10s
would be too vulnerable to shoulder-fired ground-to-air missiles.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all very duplicitous of them,'' a senior Pentagon
official said of the NATO pronouncements. ``The phasing is more for
the political side, not the military. They should be characterizing
this as a significant gut check for the alliance.''
</P>
<P>
   NATO officials say they had little choice. The horrifying
reports of atrocities from Kosovo built up immense political
pressure to do something about the reported massacres. But
political leaders here and in Europe were not willing to risk using
the best anti-tank and anti-troop aircraft, these officials say.
</P>
<P>
   So for now, American and other allied officials say, ground
attack planes like F-16s and F-15Es will do the best they can at
least to scatter Serbian forces, if not actually destroy them.
</P>
<P>
   ``As the attack becomes more pervasive and intense, the Serbs
will have to disperse their forces,'' a Western military attache
said. ``Greater dispersal means less activity by their military.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, allied air power is severely limited by the region's
notoriously bad weather, hilly terrain, menacing ground-to-air
missiles and a lack of spotters on the ground to help pinpoint and
bomb Yugoslavia's heavy weapons.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``When you think of attacking fielded forces, what comes to mind
is troops in the open,'' said an Air Force general with experience
in the Balkans. ``That's not what we're going to be doing. First,
we'll have to locate them, and then precisely target them.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You go after their barracks and their headquarters,'' the
general continued. ``You go after where they work and live, and if
they're not there, at least you know where they won't be.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Air is going to be good to isolate these guys and separate
them from their leadership their ability to communicate with
them,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Bad weather is one important hindrance to the NATO pilots. Cloud
cover prevents them from identifying their targets and using
laser-guided bombs to hit them. This places a greater reliance on
unmanned cruise missiles, which are effective mainly against fixed
targets.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, many manned aircraft were forced to turn back because
of bad weather en route to or over their targets. NATO briefers
refused to say how many planes had aborted their missions.
</P>
<P>
   To hit ground targets with precision, allied warplanes would
typically have to drop to about 10,000 feet, from the 20,000 feet
or more at which they fly now. The pilots would have to visually
identify targets, which in hilly terrain can be very difficult.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the situation in Iraq and in Bosnia, the NATO pilots
would not have spotters on the ground or in the air to pinpoint the
target.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the Serbs are not maneuvering, then it's not a difficult
target to attack,'' an Air Force general said. ``Without someone on
the ground, especially if the Serbs are in close proximity to
friendly forces or civilians, the complexity goes up immensely.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
