<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOHNSON TRIES TO FIND RIGHT BATTING ORDER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   JUPITER, Fla. _ The Dodgers' eight position players are set, but
their positions in the batting order are still being finagled.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Davey Johnson said he ``likes the feel'' of
switch-hitting center fielder Devon White hitting fourth, giving a
lefty presence to the middle of the lineup. It would also split up
Gary Sheffield and Raul Mondesi.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm kind of fooling around, trying to find a fit,'' Johnson
said Saturday. ``With (Todd Hundley) being inconsistent in the
lineup, I'm trying to figure out how to best protect certain people
in the lineup.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the reasons the Dodgers were excited to acquire Hundley
was his left-handed bat in what had become a right-handed lineup.
But his unavailability most of the spring left the Dodgers with
only right-handers in the middle of the lineup.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm putting an end to that,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   So a week ago Johnson inserted White as the cleanup hitter,
giving the Dodgers a lefty bat among the righties. In the last
three seasons, White has hit .280 when he bats fourth.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the uncertainty around Hundley, I've had kind of a look
at Mondi,'' Johnson said. ``Mondi is a guy who hits a lot of
doubles. It's good to get somebody ahead of him who can run. Then
if they put Sheff on base, you've got a switch-hitter behind him
and you know that works.''
</P>
<P>
   White, who spent part of his time hitting fifth when he was with
the Florida Marlins, had no preference where he batted in the
order.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to hit 30 homers,'' said White, who hit 22
homers last season with Arizona. ``If I get a ball I can drive,
I'll drive it. My job is to get on base, score runs and drive some
runs in. Batting (fourth), you're in a situation where you get
better pitches, so you swing at better pitches.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson continues to flirt with the notion of batting shortstop
Mark Grudzielanek second. But Grudzielanek has proved to be a
better offensive player batting seventh than second. In his past
three years, he has hit .255 with a .304 on-base percentage from
the No. 2 spot. He has hit .301 with a .322 on-base percentage from
the seventh spot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Grudzielanek wants to hit down there (No. 2), but he doesn't
get on base enough,'' Johnson said. ``I told him `You've got to
show me you can walk more.' I look at on-base percentage. Heck, I
wake up in the middle of the night to look at on-base percentage.''
</P>
<P>
   As it looks now, Eric Young will bat leadoff, perhaps followed
by Grudzielanek, Sheffield, White, Mondesi, Eric Karros, Hundley
and Adrian Beltre. Johnson could have the same option if
left-handed hitting catcher Rick Wilkins is in the lineup.
</P>
<P>
   No hits, no satisfaction: Right-hander Chan Ho Park pitched six
innings and didn't allow a hit against the St. Louis Cardinals, but
he certainly wasn't proclaiming himself fit for the regular season
yet. Park walked five, throwing 95 pitches.
</P>
<P>
   ``No-hitter, but so what?'' Park said. ``It's spring training.
Too many walks. Five, six walks, you can't do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Park was particularly upset after walking two Cardinals in the
first inning. One of those walks was to Mark McGwire, prompting a
lusty ``Boo'' from the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was cutting it off too much. The ball was running on him,''
Johnson said. ``He was all hacked off. He was fighting himself a
little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   Balks, walks and chalk: Though Johnson hasn't officially named a
starting rotation, he said it would remain consistent with the
Grapefruit League rotation. That would mean Kevin Brown in the
April 5 opener followed by Park, Ismael Valdes, Carlos Perez and
Darren Dreifort. Since the Dodgers play 17 straight days to start
the season, nobody is scheduled to be bumped a day in the rotation.
. . . In an attempt to get at-bats for catcher Angel Pena and
middle infielder Juan Castro, Johnson sent both of them to the
Dodgers' Triple-A game against the Cardinals. ``I want them to get
about eight (at-bats) in the next few days. I have to make sure
they're getting some playing time, and I'm limited here,'' Johnson
said. He added that neither was demoted.
</P>
</TEXT>
