<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-27 20:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6691 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-TPC28-COX     03-27 0711
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-TPC28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Duval escapes with lead as Sawgrass mauls field
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PONTE VEDRA BEACH, Fla. _ Welcome to the TPC, which should stand
for Terribly Punishing Conditions or something moderately
unprintable.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, it's just The Players Championship, which Saturday
went from tough to torture chamber, and there is no hope (or rain)
in sight.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, the best field in golf is paid handsomely for putting
up with greens that putt like the floor at the Pauley Pavilion _
$900,000 is the first-prize loot _ but even those who have seen
shenanigans like this before at the TPC at Sawgrass were reaching
for the record books.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody went unscathed. Second-round leader Joe Ozaki disappeared
with an 81. England's Nick Faldo tied his worst-ever score in the
United States with an 83. Bob Friend, who aced the eighth hole
Friday and stood at 1-under par, is 14-over in this morning's
newspaper fine print after an 87.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like playing Augusta and the U.S. Open on the same day,
and I'll have none of that,'' said Scotland's Colin Montgomerie,
who stood at 1-under 215 after a 73 and felt fortunate to be there.
``It's probably the most demanding conditions we play ... but there
were a lot worse than me today.''
</P>
<P>
   Were it not for local knowledge, even Jacksonville-native David
Duval might have blown off the leaderboard. As it was, Duval held
onto his cap and his game decently enough to secure the 54-hole
lead at 4-under 212 _ the highest three-round score by a leader
since the tournament moved to Sawgrass in 1982. With a bogey at the
18th hole, Duval shot a 74 for a one-stroke lead over Phil
Mickelson (71 on Saturday) and Skip Kendall (70).
</P>
<P>
   With conditions the way they are and likely to worsen as the
greens get firmer and the wind continues to blow balls off line,
anyone within at least six shots of the lead is in contention.
</P>
<P>
   Three-shots back at 1-under 215 are Montgomerie, Nick Price (74)
and Scott Hoch (73). Four shots behind at even-par 216 are a group
that includes Tiger Woods (75), Mark O'Meara (71) and Payne Stewart
(74).
</P>
<P>
   The lowest scores on the board were 70s by Steve Stricker, Scott
Gump and Kendall. Six players broke par. Seventy-three shot over
par _ 14 of them 80 or better. Of the 27 players who started the
third round under par, six remain in red numbers. By late
afternoon, hitting a sprinkler became a decent option. At least, it
wasn't as hard as the greens
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw something today I've never seen before,'' Mickelson
said. ``On the first green I had a putt hit a spike mark and come
backwards. The spike marks were so firm, they could careen a ball
off line. That's when I knew it was going to be long day.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When Phil and I walked out on the first green, you could
almost see your reflection in it,'' Montgomerie said. ``It was
ridiculous.''
</P>
<P>
   The victims were everywhere you looked. Atlanta's Billy Andrade
made 10 bogeys during an 81. Sea Island's Davis Love III quadrupled
the 17th and went from 3-under to 1-over, but is still not out of
it, starting today at 2-over. Columbus' Larry Mize is even a stroke
better after a commendable 73.
</P>
<P>
   Wind-burned and weary, Duval could not have been happier than to
awaken today in his Jacksonville Beach house as the tournament
leader, regardless that his once five-shot lead had blown away in
the wind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know where to start,'' he said. ``I'm beat. It was
tough out there today and I think it was reflective on the scores.
We just got kicked around. ... If we had to do this every week, I
don't think a whole lot of people would play golf.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods, who was muttering obscenities to himself that were
evident to lip-readers, swiped at a mound so hard that he recoiled
5 yards. He almost flew the ball in the hole at the 15th and then
struggled to make bogey after scooting balls back and forth over
the putting surface.
</P>
<P>
   ``Club selection was impossible,'' Woods said. ``The greens (cut
to 1/10 of an inch Thursday) are almost impossible to play. Some of
the pins are in spots where you just can't hold them, they're so
burned out. But five shots is not too hard to make up.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
