<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PADRES EYE ANGELS' NEVIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. -- Phil Nevin had three hits Saturday in the
Angels' 4-2 loss to the Seattle Mariners at Tempe Diablo Stadium,
raising his average to .378 (14 for 37). Those numbers might be
just good enough to send him packing.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Walbeck (broken bone in right hand and currently visiting
his ailing mother) will return to the team Wednesday and might be
ready by opening day. Todd Greene continues to show his shoulder is
healthy enough to catch. Charlie O'Brien is the most experienced
catcher on the staff. All that makes Nevin expendable.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels have been interested in shortstop/utility player Andy
Sheets of the Padres, who have lost catcher Carlos Hernandez for
the season.
</P>
<P>
   Nevin has heard the same thing, so Saturday morning he met with
manager Terry Collins.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to let him know I've heard all this stuff, Nevin
said. ``I said `What's the deal? It's bothering me.' He said the
only thing you can do is what you do on the field. I've been traded
twice in my career. It's not something that would crush me.
</P>
<P>
   Nevin says he likes being in Anaheim and would prefer to stay.
However, the Padres would have plenty of playing time for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point in my career I need to play, said Nevin, 28.
``If it means going to San Diego and I'm going to be playing ... If
I'm going to get a lot more at-bats there than here, I'm sure it
would be good for me. If not, obviously I'd like to stay here.
</P>
<P>
   Nevin started at catcher on Friday in the Angels' game against
the Padres. And it was no coincidence. The Padres wanted -- and got
-- a good look at the former College Player of the Year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I've shown this spring I'm more than adequate
defensively and I can bring something to the table offensively if
I'm in there all the time, he said. ``I think people realize that.
I just wish people around here realized that.
</P>
<P>
   It is the policy of Angels management not to discuss potential
trades.
</P>
<P>
   It's only spring training, Mo Vaughn says. Just wait.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn, who has hit 40 or more homers in a season twice in his
career (the Angels record is 39), has had 50 at-bats this spring.
His home run total, however, is equal to that of Andy Stankiewicz.
</P>
<P>
   Zero.
</P>
<P>
   Mo knows, but isn't concerned. His priority Saturday was getting
dressed and out of the clubhouse in time to watch UConn in the NCAA
Tournament. Vaughn is a Connecticut native and has a friend on the
UConn coaching staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always hit at least one, Vaughn said of his spring
training history. ``But I don't worry about it either. It's been an
adjustment, but the adjustment has been out here (Arizona), not
with this team. I'll hit one before I leave.
</P>
<P>
   It's been more than a month since spring training began, and
everyone -- from players, to coaches to front office personnel --
is ready to go home.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last week in camp is the toughest for the players, Angels
manager Terry Collins said. ``You'll see the next few days guys
will have their bags packed, their cars loaded and ready to go.
I've got a list as long as my arm of guys wanting to go to Lake
Elsinore.
</P>
<P>
   Half the team will break camp on March 30 and play in Lake
Elsinore on March 31. The other half of the team will remain in
Arizona to play one last Cactus League game on March 31.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the Angels regulars will go to Lake Elsinore, including
Vaughn, Jim Edmonds, Garret Anderson, Darin Erstad, Todd Greene and
Troy Percival. Mark Petkovsek will start on the mound.
</P>
<P>
   Starting pitcher Tim Belcher made 98 pitches in six innings
Saturday, allowing three runs and five hits.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what I wanted to do, said Belcher, who will be the
Angels' opening day starter on April 6 vs. Cleveland. ``I wanted to
get up to 90 or 100 pitches so my next time out (April 1 at minor
league camp) I can cut back to about 50 or 60 pitches.
</P>
<P>
   Greene caught five innings Saturday but no Mariners baserunner
tried to run on him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Belcher mixes up his looks real well, and he's quick to the
plate, Greene said. ``But I don't feel bad about (no Mariners
trying to steal).
</P>
<P>
   Collins said it's possible Greene will be the Angels' opening
day catcher.
</P>
<P>
   Left fielder Darin Erstad was scratched from Saturday's game
because of a bruised right heel. ... The Angels travel to Tucson
today to play the Colorado Rockies. Ken Hill will start for Anaheim
against Colorado's Brian Bohanon.
</P>
</TEXT>
