<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-27 21:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6698 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-ASSESS-1STLD-W     03-27 1100
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-ASSESS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DO BOMBS FAIL EVEN AS THEY FALL? 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS to update; grafs 15-19 contain changes.)  (See also: KOSOVO-RDP, KOSOVO-FORCE, KOSOVO-BELGRADE,
KOSOVO-MILOSEVIC, KOSOVO-RUSSIA, KOSOVO-CLINTON, KOSOVO-TURKEY,
KOSOVO-MACEDONIA) 
(DW) 
 By R.W. APPLE Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Reports of multiplying atrocities filtering out of Kosovo, bad
enough news on purely humanitarian grounds, convey a still bleaker
message for allied policy makers trying to stem the bloodshed.
</P>
<P>
   Unconfirmed accounts reaching Central European capitals _ taken
as fact or something close to it by allied officials, despite a
lack of confirming details _ indicate strongly that three days of
bombing raids have so far utterly failed to achieve even the modest
goals set by NATO and spelled out on Wednesday by President
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   As one European diplomat said, ``we have to confront the
possibility that the air campaign, by forcing the independent
observers and Western journalists out of Kosovo, has given the
Serbs a sense that they can do whatever they like without anyone
being able to prove that they did it.''
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, unless the tide turns soon, an exit strategy for
Clinton and other leaders may be harder than ever to develop. That
has long been a major fear of some of his congressional critics.
</P>
<P>
   When the idea of bombing was first considered, some officials in
Washington suggested that it could be used to force Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosevic to accept the NATO peacekeeping force
in Kosovo that he adamantly opposes.
</P>
<P>
   Inclusion of the peacekeeper element in the proposed peace
settlement negotiated at Rambouillet, France, caused him to reject
the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton came to believe that it would be tactically wiser to
set goals for the airstrikes that might be more readily achieved.
So he said last week that the purpose of the bombing was to bolster
NATO's credibility, to deter Milosevic ``from continuing and
escalating his attacks'' in Kosovo and, if needed, to severely
damage his war-making machinery.
</P>
<P>
   NATO has succeeded in sending the message that it takes the
atrocities against ethnic Albanians seriously. But Milosevic has
not been deterred by the bombs and cruise missiles that the allies
have flung at him, and if his conventional war-making capacity has
been hurt, the ability of his paramilitary forces to spread havoc
in Kosovo remains strong.
</P>
<P>
   NATO's supreme commander, Gen. Wesley K. Clark, an American,
acknowledged on Friday that allied airstrikes could not in the
short term protect the ethnic Albanians from attacks by the Serbian
paramilitaries, and other officials said they wondered whether that
could ever be done without the introduction of ground forces.
</P>
<P>
   All the allies are opposed to sending in troops unless they are
invited by the Milosevic government; one NATO staff study
reportedly indicated that it would require a huge deployment,
perhaps 150,000 to 200,000 troops, to do the job.
</P>
<P>
   George Robertson, the British defense minister, conceded
Saturday in London that what he called ``an all-out Serb offensive
against the Albanian population'' had begun, and said he had
reports that ``the Serbs are bombing villages to the point of
obliteration.'' But he insisted: ``This is not happening because of
NATO. This violence was going on before we began.''
</P>
<P>
   The mood of apprehension in this region was heightened by the
intrusion of Serbian warplanes into Bosnian airspace _ MIG fighters
on Friday, helicopters Saturday. From the beginning, the countries
that border on Yugoslavia have worried about the Kosovo trouble's
spilling across their borders, and of course the Clinton
administration is particularly concerned about anything that
threatens to disrupt the hard-won peace settlement in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   Macedonia, which borders Kosovo on the south, is especially
vulnerable to the unrest. It could be flooded with refugees, and
its fragile multi-ethnic balance could be upset. At present, about
a quarter of its population of 2.2 million is made up of ethnic
Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   ``We get nervous in Hungary,'' an official in Budapest said,
``because one of our main cities, Seged, is just a few kilometers
from the northern border of Yugoslavia. But if shivers run down our
spines, think of the tremors they feel in Macedonia.''
</P>
<P>
   Late Saturday, the Western alliance responded to the reported
torching of villages and alleged massacres by switching tactics,
saying that low-flying planes would now go after Yugoslav tanks,
artillery and even ground troops.
</P>
<P>
   What was unclear is whether NATO had succeeded in its evident
intention to weaken the Serbs' radar and anti-aircraft defenses.
</P>
<P>
   At the start of the airstrikes, senior military officers said it
could take a week or more to finish the first phase. But Saturday's
announcement came just four days into the air campaign.
</P>
<P>
   If the slaughter in Kosovo continues, the ``ethnic cleansing''
could be largely complete in a short period. NATO might even lose
public support for its campaign, whose goals are difficult to
achieve, because of the dispersal of the paramilitary forces and
their supplies, and because the terrain and small-scale targets
require pilots to fly at dangerously low altitudes.
</P>
<P>
   Already, Greece and Italy have suggested that it might be time
for diplomacy, rather than bombs. Javier Solana, the NATO Secretary
General, has worked hard to preserve a semblance of unanimity in
the alliance, but he himself has said the airstrikes should last
for a matter of days rather than weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Yet there seems to be little strategic room for an early bombing
pause. That would only convince Milosevic that he had won, allied
officials say.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the apparent softening of resolve in some European
capitals suggests that the prospect of more or less open-ended
strikes by NATO warplanes is slim. If the bombing campaign does not
stop Milosevic, some administration officials have been saying, the
answer is more bombing. From the European perspective, at least,
that may swiftly begin to ring a little hollow.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic's accelerated campaign in Kosovo calls into question
another possible endgame.
</P>
<P>
   Some American officials have suggested that, failing an
agreement by the Serbian leader to return to the bargaining table,
the best thing to do would be to announce that his military
capacity had been degraded and call off the raids. But that would
not sound very convincing if the Serbs were still on their bloody
rampage in Kosovo, which is what the whole policy was meant to
stop.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-27-99 2113EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
