<SLUG> BC-CAR-DONNIE-ALLISON-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DONNIE ALLISON JOINS ALABAMA'S GANG OF COACHES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY D. BOGGS 
c.1999 Special to the Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Paul ``Bear'' Bryant and Gene Stallings,
make room for ``coach'' Donnie Allison.
</P>
<P>
   Allison, the 59-year-old veteran of NASCAR's famed ``Alabama
Gang'' and a 10-time winner as a driver, is coaching Ricky Craven
on the SBIII Motorsports team that fields the No. 58 Hollywood
Video Ford Taurus.
</P>
<P>
   A ``coach?'' In stock-car racing?
</P>
<P>
   It's all about communication.
</P>
<P>
   ``A percentage of what we talk about might just be talk,''
Craven said, ``but every now and then he comes up with something
real important.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Allison: ``Driving a car hasn't changed since I drove.
Ricky and I talk about different things that I used to feel at
different racetracks, and he still feels that. And I overcame
problems at different racetracks, and it seems to help him. It's
not a coach as much as it is somebody to talk to that's been there,
that's done the same thing he's doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Allison can even help on tracks where he never raced, including
Texas Motor Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can look at a car and pretty much determine where our
problem spots are. I guess watching a lot of cars and driving them
myself, it's an ability I have. I can't answer why I got it. I
don't know. But I do have it, and it's really not only helped
Ricky, but other guys I've helped.''
</P>
<P>
   Those other guys include Joe Nemechek, Bobby Hamilton, Davey
Allison and Hut Stricklin. Allison said he ``jumped at the chance''
to help Craven's team.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want to race. I want to race,'' Allison said.
</P>
<P>
   Money has nothing to do with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hell, no. I like to win,'' he said. ``The money is nice and
you can make a lot of money, but anyone who drives for the money,
they don't do well.''
</P>
<P>
   But how can an Alabaman like Allison and a New Englander like
Craven understand each other?
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a little dialogue problem there,'' Craven said with a
smile, ``but we'll overcome it.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
