<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-BUDDY-BAKER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUDDY BAKER SPEAKS FOR THE REGULAR FOLKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVID A. MARKIEWICZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _Racing, it has been said, is all about common
people doing uncommon things.
</P>
<P>
   So, who better to bring NASCAR to the nation than Buddy Baker, a
self-described common man who has done some very uncommon things _
like driving winning race cars at 200 mph?
</P>
<P>
   As a racing analyst for CBS Sports, Baker, a member of the
International Motorsports Hall of Fame, will again provide analysis
for the telecast of today's Primestar 500 at Texas Motor Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a sport that identifies with the regular folk,''
observed Baker's broadcast partner, Ken Squier. ``And Buddy's never
lost his common touch. He understands what people want to know, and
he's able to communicate that to them in a way that's easily
understood. He has a bit of that Will Rogers touch.''
</P>
<P>
   That Baker can so ably put viewers inside a car, or inside a
driver's head, is a tribute to his racing experience and his love
of motorsports. It isn't, he admits, because of innate broadcasting
abilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a passion for the sport, and you first have to have a
love for what you do,'' Baker said this week while trolling the
pits, preparing for today's race. ``That's really helped me along
in this job. It's certainly not my voice, or any of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, Baker's voice fits. A folksy Southern drawl, it reflects
NASCAR's roots. What's more, his down-home manner softens what is a
coldly technical and, at times, brutal sport. Baker's knowledge and
enthusiasm have earned him professional praise, while his frequent
``Buddyisms'' _ country-charming turns of phrases _ have set him
apart as a broadcast booth original.
</P>
<P>
   Son of a legendary driver, Buck Baker, Buddy stood out as a
racer long before he stood out as a broadcaster. With 17 wins on
superspeedways, (11th all-time) including a career-capping victory
at the Daytona 500 in 1980, he was selected one of NASCAR's 50
greatest drivers.
</P>
<P>
   Known for his love of speed, Baker was the first driver in the
world to break the 200 mph barrier on a closed course. He achieved
that feat in 1970 in a Dodge Daytona. He also won 40 Winston Cup
poles, ranking him 10th all-time.
</P>
<P>
   As a driver, Baker was renowned for his preparation. He tries to
be equally ready as an announcer.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't go out unprepared anymore,'' Baker said. ``The
people watching are far more sophisticated about what's going on
today. A mistake in front of 30 million people _ that's a big
mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   Baker's plan: ``You have to learn the players first off, and
remember that you did this for 32 years. You say, `OK, what's he
thinking, what's he feeling in this situation?'
</P>
<P>
   ``I know. I've been there, done that.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though he never thought about a broadcasting career when he
was driving, Baker now says, ``I'm just as passionate about doing
well up in the booth as I was in the car.''
</P>
<P>
   He's still comfortable in the driver's seat, however.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every now and then, I test a little bit in different race
cars, just so I know that I know what I'm doing,'' Baker says,
``and to keep up with the current race cars.''
</P>
<P>
   Baker calls NASCAR a ``family,'' and he has occasionally taken
on the role of mentor to younger drivers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'll come up and say, `I'm having trouble in Turn 1. The
car's slipping and gettin' in the corner,' '' Baker said. ``And
I'll know what it takes to make a suggestion that might help them.
Then, when they come up and say that that really helped, you know
how good that makes you feel?''
</P>
<P>
   Squier said Baker has done a lot to make others feel good, both
on and off the track. Last year, at a small race in Vermont, Baker
took time to visit with each of the 100-plus driving crews.
</P>
<P>
   ``He went and talked to every single one,'' Squier said. ``He so
impressed every driver there. They'd never known anybody who'd won
major races.''
</P>
<P>
   Baker's sensitivity was evident again last week, Squier noted,
when he was told that a 35-year-old man with spina bifida whom
Baker had befriended had died.
</P>
<P>
   ``He cried,'' Squier said. ``Buddy was a tiger as a driver, but
he's a pussycat as a person.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
