<HEADER>
A6701 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-NASCAR-HNS &LR;      03-27 0786
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Martin primed to keep Texas Motor Speedway streak alive
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By TERRY BLOUNT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
FORT WORTH _ If you are looking for a clear favorite to place a
wager on for the Primestar 500, Mark Martin is your man.
</P>
<P>
   Since Texas Motor Speedway opened, Martin has owned the place.
Not literally, of course, but the driver of the Valvoline Taurus
seems to know what the other drivers haven't figured out about the
1.5-mile D-shaped oval.
</P>
<P>
   More than 200,000 people will attend today's Winston Cup race at
the ultramodern facility where Martin has found Victory Lane three
times in the three seasons TMS has been open.
</P>
<P>
   Martin's victory in the rain-shortened Coca-Cola 300 on Saturday
kept his string going in Texas, which started when he won the
inaugural Busch Grand National race at TMS in 1997. He returned to
Texas last year and won the Winston Cup event. The 40-year-old
Arkansas native is the only driver to qualify in the top 10 in all
three Cup races held at TMS.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we have a great chance to win here again,'' said
Martin, who will start on the outside of row 3 today. ``I've been
lucky enough to win three times here, and I would love to make it
four (today).''
</P>
<P>
   Owner Jack Roush fears the odds may catch up with his team, even
though it had a 1-2 finish last year with Martin and Chad Little
and another 1-2 finish Saturday with Martin and Jeff Burton, who
won the first Cup race at TMS.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been extraordinarily lucky in Texas,'' Roush said. ``We
haven't had things happen beyond our control that would have
stopped us from winning, but I don't expect that string to
continue.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Gordon hopes his string of bad luck doesn't continue at
TMS, one of only three Winston Cup tracks where Gordon has failed
to win. He hasn't come close at Texas, finishing 30th in 1997 and
31st in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been a tough place for us,'' said Gordon, who will
start behind Martin on the outside of row 4. ``We've had bad things
happen here, but with the changes in the track, I don't see why we
can't have a good race.''
</P>
<P>
   All of the drivers feel differently about the track than they
did the first two years here. Finally, TMS has a racing surface to
match the finest facility in motor sports. That seems to be the
conclusion of the Winston Cup drivers heading into today's race.
</P>
<P>
   TMS officials spent $3.2 million on the racing surface since
last year's event to try to ensure a peaceful weekend without
driver complaints.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the proof is in the effort,'' TMS general manager
Eddie Gossage said. ``We addressed what they asked us to address.''
</P>
<P>
   Gossage and everyone involved at TMS can live without all the
negative things people remember about the first two NASCAR events
at the speedway.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, things began with a monsoon-like two-day storm that
made mud pits out of almost half of the parking area, causing a
massive traffic jam for the 185,000 fans.
</P>
<P>
   And then came the unexpected driver complaints about the new
racing surface. The dual-banking setup left the drivers saying TMS
was a one-groove track that was too tight entering turn 1 and too
dangerous coming out of turn 4.
</P>
<P>
   Their fears became a reality on the first lap on the inaugural
Winston Cup race at TMS when 13 cars were involved in a crash on
the first turn.
</P>
<P>
   TMS officials spent $500,000 to make changes to the track, along
with paving most the grass areas of the parking lot that had been
made unusable from the downpours.
</P>
<P>
   When the 1998 race weekend came around, everyone hoped the
problems were in the past, but the track controversy had just
begun. The drivers continued to complain about the tight entrance
and exit to the frontstretch, but they also said a dip had
developed between turns 3 and 4.
</P>
<P>
   T-shirts were being sold at TMS that read ``Shut Up and Drive.''
That caused friction between Gossage and the drivers, and even more
friction between Gossage and NASCAR president Bill France Jr.
</P>
<P>
   A bad situation became worse when a drainage problem on the
track caused water to seep to the surface in turn 1. France had
seen enough and warned TMS officials that NASCAR would not be back
unless corrections were made.
</P>
<P>
   Smith and Gossage didn't hesitate on the decision to rebuild the
racing surface. The 24-hour-a-day project was completed in six
weeks, and the results have passed the test of the drivers this
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``The track is the best it has ever been,'' said Kenny Irwin,
who is on the pole for today's race at 190.154 mph in the Texaco
Ford. ``It's still a one-groove track, (but) it's more comfortable
getting around here that it used to be.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
