<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FIGHTER-BOX-0328-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    F-117A NIGHTHAWK
 &HT;    With KOSOVO-STRIKES-0328.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By RICK CHRISTIE 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   F-117A: THE FIRST STEALTH FIGHTER
</P>
<P>
   Overall Mission: The F-117A Nighthawk is the first aircraft
designed with stealth capabilities.
</P>
<P>
   Current Mission: The current NATO air campaign against Serb
military targets in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Features: The F-117A's unique design as a single-seat fighter
makes it exceptional in combat. Its navigation and attack systems
is set up in a state-of-the-art digital avionics suite that reduces
pilot workload. Detailed planning for missions into heavily
defended areas can be programmed into an automated mission planning
system.
</P>
<P>
   History: The first F-117A was delivered in 1982, and the last in
1990. Only 31 months after the U.S. Air Force decided to develop
the aircraft, the first flight came in 1981. The lone F-117A unit,
the 4450th Tactical Group (now the 49th Fighter Wing, Hollman Air
Force Base, N.M.) began operating in October 1983. The Aeronautical
Systems Center, Wright-Patterson Air Force Base near Dayton, Ohio,
combined the stealth technology during the development and
production process.
</P>
<P>
   Characteristics:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Primary function: Fighter/attack
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Contractor: Lockheed Aeronautical Systems Co.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Power Plant: Two General Electric F404 engines
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Length: 65 feet, 11 inches
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Height: 12 feet, 5 inches
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Weight: 52,500 pounds
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Wingspan: 43 feet, 4 inches
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Speed: High subsonic
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Range: Unlimited with air refueling
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Armament: Internal weapons carriage
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Unit cost: $45 million
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Crew: One
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Date Deployed: 1982
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Inventory: 54 active
</P>
<P>
   Source: Air Combat Command, Office of Public Affairs, Langley
AFB, Va.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
