<HEADER>
A6706 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-RANGERS-FLYERS-45     03-27 0799
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-RANGERS-FLYERS-450&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS LEFT BLEEDING, DAZED AND FADING FAST 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Every now and then, a single image seems to sum
up an entire game, maybe even a whole season. One of those images
could be seen here Saturday, late in Philadelphia's 3-1 victory
that helped reduce the Rangers' dwindling playoff hopes to rapidly
dying dreams. In the picture was Petr Nedved, the Rangers'
first-line center, on his hands and knees, dazed, with blood
pouring from three cuts around his right eye.
</P>
<P>
   Near him stood Eric Lindros, big No. 88 of the black-clad
Flyers, his stick still in his hands, with 3 minutes 30 seconds
remaining in the game. Lindros just watched Nedved bleed until the
referee, Kerry Fraser, sent him to the penalty box with a
double-minor for high-sticking.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Rangers put five of their 22 shots on John
Vanbiesbrouck during the ensuing manpower advantage, they could not
beat him, or overcome the two goals by Valery Zelepukin and the
single tally by Karl Dykhuis. Kevin Stevens had given the Rangers a
1-0 lead on a fluky, blooper shot just 1:09 into the game. The
result left the Rangers six points out of a playoff berth with nine
games left.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Rangers General Manager Neil Smith said the team
would request a league review of the incident, which could lead to
a suspension of Lindros. Nedved said that hard hitting _ he took
plenty of it Saturday _ was part of the game, but that sticks
around the eyes were ``a different story.'' Lindros said: ``He
hooked my arm. I came back when my arm was hooked and,
unfortunately, my stick caught him in the head.'' Nedved needed
stitches for his cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said he called Colin Campbell, the former Rangers coach
who is the National Hockey League's vice president in charge of
discipline. Smith said Dave Checketts, the president of Madison
Square Garden, will call Gary Bettman, the NHL commissioner. The
Flyers, winners of three consecutive games after going 12 games
without a victory, are to play in Detroit on Sunday afternoon in a
network television match between two top contenders for the Stanley
Cup. A suspension of Lindros would be a courageous move by
Campbell, who has declined to suspend Lindros for other more
damaging incidents this season. However, Lindros was fined $1,000
for a stick-swinging incident in December.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't expect anything; I respect whatever they do,'' Smith
said, referring to league discipline and discussing Lindros'
history of rough play. ``Sooner or later, somebody's eyeball is
going to be laying on the ice, and he's going to be skating around
saying, `Geez, I didn't know I did it.' We've seen him do it about
20 times since he's been in the league.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Nedved absorbed many hits during the game, some of them clean
and legal, as the Flyers tried to intimidate the smaller Rangers.
Earlier, Nedved was checked hard by Dan McGillis, Chris Therien and
Lindros. After Sandy McCarthy jostled the Rangers' Wayne Gretzky,
McCarthy and Craig Berube picked simultaneous fights with Chris
Tamer and Darren Langdon.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were physically stronger than we were, no question about
it,'' said Rangers Coach John Muckler, whose team no longer has the
traded Ulf Samuelsson and the injured Jeff Beukeboom, both rugged
defensemen. Muckler praised Nedved and his team. ``We didn't back
down,'' Muckler said. ``I thought Petr was awesome.'' Nedved led
the Rangers with four shots.
</P>
<P>
   The result left the Rangers with a 1-3-2 record in their last
six games and kept them six points behind Boston in the race for
the final playoff berth in the Eastern Conference. With only nine
games remaining, the 10th-place Rangers also trail ninth-place
Florida by one point. They missed the playoffs last season and have
not missed the tournament in two consecutive seasons in more than
two decades. The Bruins were to play later Saturday night, in
Toronto. Either Carolina, which leads in the Southeast, or Florida
will win that division, and all divisional winners get automatic
playoff berths, meaning the Rangers would most likely have to catch
Boston to qualify.
</P>
<P>
   Back behind the bench for the Flyers was Coach Roger Neilson,
returning from a two-game suspension because he threw a stick on
the ice to protest a referee's decision more than a week ago while
his team played its 12th straight game without a victory (0-8-4).
Despite their recent successes, the Flyers are still an anxious
team that has fallen from the Eastern Conference lead.
</P>
<P>
   McCarthy, one of the new arrivals, said Saturday, ``The whole
team played big and tough.'' Lindros added, ``On our losing streak,
we never lost all our confidence.''
</P>
</TEXT>
