<HEADER>
A6707 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PARAGUAY-TURMOIL-HNS &LR;      03-27 1267
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PARAGUAY-TURMOIL-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
STRONGMAN APPEARS TO PULL STRINGS IN PARAGUAYAN CONFLICT;
EX-GENERAL DENIES ROLE IN VICE PRESIDENT'S DEATH
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
By JOHN OTIS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   c. 1999 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Houstoun Chronicle &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ASUNCION, Paraguay _ Cashiered army Gen. Lino Oviedo has been
called everything from the savior of Paraguay to the president's
evil twin.
</P>
<P>
   With his fiery speaking style, Oviedo has played a powerful role
in the country's politics for a decade _ even though he has never
held elective office.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Oviedo was back in the headlines following an
outbreak of violence that threatens to topple the 7-month-old
government of President Raul Cubas, who faces an impeachment trial.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Vice President Luis Argana _ one of Oviedo's
staunchest political foes _ was killed in the Paraguayan capital of
Asuncion by gunmen dressed in military fatigues.
</P>
<P>
   Argana's backers accused the cashiered general of the crime and
clashed with pro-Oviedo demonstrators outside the Congress
building. On Friday night, police and army troops moved in with
armored cars, tear gas and rubber bullets. Rumors of a military
coup circulated. In the melee, four people were killed, and scores
were injured.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was Paraguay's Tiananmen Square,'' said political
scientist Michael Carter, who noted that this landlocked South
American nation of 5 million people is normally peaceful.
</P>
<P>
   The sudden bloodletting jump-started a campaign to oust Oviedo's
close friend and political protege, President Cubas. The lower
house of Congress impeached Cubas on Wednesday, and his trial in
the Senate began Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone in the country blames the president and Gen. Oviedo''
for Argana's death, said Walter Bower, president of the lower house
of Congress. ``Oviedo is the Al Capone of Paraguayan politics.''
</P>
<P>
   Oviedo's political rise began in 1989, when he took part in a
military coup that ended the 34-year dictatorship of Alfredo
Stroessner. Toting a grenade, Oviedo marched into Stroessner's
quarters and demanded his resignation.
</P>
<P>
   He became army chief under President Juan Carlos Wasmosy, who
became Paraguay's first freely elected civilian leader in 1993.
Three years later, Oviedo led an aborted putsch against Wasmosy's
beleaguered government and was briefly jailed.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after his release from prison, Oviedo began his own run for
the presidency. He rose to the top of the polls by speaking
Guarani, the Indian language popular in the countryside, by
focusing on impoverished peasant communities and by espousing a
populist platform.
</P>
<P>
   He was disqualified from the race and sent back to the stockade,
however, after the Supreme Court ruled that he was obligated to
serve a 10-year prison sentence for his role in the coup attempt.
Oviedo was replaced on the Colorado Party ticket by his
running-mate, Cubas.
</P>
<P>
   After winning the 1998 election and taking office, Cubas
immediately released Oviedo from prison.
</P>
<P>
   Led by Vice President Argana, also of the Colorado Party, many
politicians claimed that Cubas had violated the constitution by
freeing Oviedo. They immediately began a drive to impeach the new
president.
</P>
<P>
   ``This democracy is not working, because Cubas doesn't have the
least bit of leadership,'' said Juan Dario Monge, a Colorado Party
deputy. ``He is controlled by Lino Oviedo. He is simply a puppet.''
</P>
<P>
   In the midst of the effort to oust the president, Argana was
gunned down. Police have uncovered no evidence linking Oviedo to
the crime. Still, many politicians accuse him of playing a role in
the slaying, partly because Oviedo has made violent threats in the
past.
</P>
<P>
   During a rally last December, Oviedo said he would ``bury
alive'' the Supreme Court justices who had upheld his conviction in
the coup attempt. Later, a group of his followers fired shots at
the windows of the court building.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Oviedo's popularity remained strong.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lino Oviedo is the only one who can save the country from its
misery,'' one demonstrator said last week. The protester wore a red
T-shirt with the defiant words: ``I'm for Oviedo and what of it?''
</P>
<P>
   One European diplomat said that, after decades of dictatorship
and unbroken rule by the all-powerful Colorado Party, Paraguay
lacks dynamic civilian leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``Paraguayans are used to having someone strong at the helm. And
the only strongman in the country is Lino Oviedo,'' the diplomat
said.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, one Paraguayan newspaper speculated that Argana's
assassination may have been carried out by drug dealers in exchange
for receiving protection from the armed forces for their
operations.
</P>
<P>
   Oviedo is said to have amassed a fortune as he moved his way up
through the military. Bower and other politicians claim that he has
been involved in drug trafficking, contraband smuggling and other
illegal activities, but they admit that they have no proof.
</P>
<P>
   According to a Western diplomat, another rumor making the rounds
is that a paramilitary group organized by Oviedo killed Argana.
</P>
<P>
   Oviedo, who turned himself in to military authorities last week
at President Cubas' request, says he is innocent of the slaying and
points out that the assassination simply added to the momentum to
impeach President Cubas.
</P>
<P>
   Before Argana was slain, it appeared that the Senate lacked the
two-thirds majority vote necessary to oust the president. But
legislators claim that since the assassination, they have picked up
enough votes to convict him.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only ones who are hurt by this are me and President
Cubas,'' Oviedo told the Buenos Aires newspaper Clarin. ``This is a
plot designed to destabilize the presidency.''
</P>
<P>
   If Cubas is impeached, he would be replaced by Senate president
Luis Gonzalez Macchi.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, hundreds of army troops and marines cordoned off
the Congress building to prevent more violence. The smell of tear
gas and burned-out cars lingered in the air. Several legislators
reportedly wore bullet-proof vests as they entered the building to
begin deliberations.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the backers of Cubas and Oviedo said they would take up
arms to defend the presidency. Argana's supporters, meanwhile,
accused pro-Oviedo forces of placing snipers on one of the
structures adjacent to the Congress building.
</P>
<P>
   As he prepared for his trial defense on Saturday, Cubas took
time out to calm people's nerves in a nationwide address.
</P>
<P>
   ``Paraguay has always been a country of peaceful people,'' Cubas
said. ``Never again should we allow our ideas to be stained with
blood or to generate acts of violence.''
</P>
<P>
   Those loyal to Oviedo and Cubas claim that the impeachment
amounts to a power grab engineered by former members of
Stroessner's Cabinet.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Argana, who was in line to become president had
Cubas been ousted, headed the Supreme Court during the final years
of the Stroessner dictatorship. At the time, the Stroessner
government held hundreds of political prisoners, according to
Soledad Villagra of the Center for Justice and International Law, a
human rights group.
</P>
<P>
   Posters have gone up all over Asuncion proclaiming: ``No to the
past. No to the dictatorship. No to impeachment.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if Cubas is convicted, the Western diplomat predicted that
Oviedo would probably survive the controversy, perhaps by going
into self-imposed exile for a few years, then returning to campaign
for the presidency once more.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't imagine that he's going to go back to jail,'' the
diplomat said. ``What saves Lino Oviedo is that the entire
political class is discredited. There are no white knights.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
