r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-LAKERS-RODMAN-LAD     03-27 0679
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-RODMAN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RODMAN LATE TO PRACTICE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A no-go in the fourth quarter Friday night, a
no-show for 75 minutes at Saturday's practice, Dennis Rodman is
testing once more the patience and understanding of Lakers
teammates and management.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: He's still a Laker, for now. And still the starting
power forward, for today anyway.
</P>
<P>
   And whatever's bugging him _ an unknown because he left without
speaking to reporters _ is resolved, according to coach Kurt
Rambis.
</P>
<P>
   After showing up at 12:15 p.m. for an 11 a.m. practice at
Southwest College, Rodman engaged in animated discussion with
general manager Mitch Kupchak while his teammates worked out. Then,
following a short film session that Rodman did not attend, he met
with coach Kurt Rambis for nearly 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just a coach-player meeting. I think a lot of things
were resolved in there . . . to my satisfaction,'' Rambis said.
``Do I expect him to be late anymore? I won't know that until the
next time something comes up.''
</P>
<P>
   The tardy arrival _ which was unexcused and will earn him
another fine _ came less than a week after Rodman returned from an
eight-day absence during which he attended to personal business,
gambled in Las Vegas and drew fines of $100 per day.
</P>
<P>
   Coincidence or no, Saturday's events followed Rodman's refusal
to re-enter Friday night's game against the Sacramento Kings, which
might have cost the Lakers a win.
</P>
<P>
   Rambis summoned him with about three minutes left, but Rodman
sent word, through assistant coaches, that his muscles were tight
from sitting too long. Minutes later, the Kings' Chris Webber
tipped in an offensive rebound for the winning basket, while the
seven-time rebounding champion sat on the bench.
</P>
<P>
   Rambis, who initially called the benching a coaching decision,
seemed frustrated over the incident but declined to say whether it
was related to Rodman's skipping practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if it's troublesome, or (if) I appreciate the
honesty that he is too stiff, because with some (older) players . .
. you sit on the bench a while, you do get really stiff,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But the Lakers long ago set up a stationary bike at Rodman's
request to let him stay warm and loose during games, and he has not
used it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course it's the player's responsibility to be ready to
play,'' Rambis said.
</P>
<P>
   Rodman got his first start of his Lakers career on Friday and
will probably start again today against New York, but Rambis,
admitting he is ``disappointed,'' wouldn't commit to keeping Rodman
in the starting lineup.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will talk about that further, too,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   How much longer can the Lakers tolerate the insubordination and
disappearances? If there's a cutoff point, Kupchak isn't saying.
But the team isn't prepared to waive Rodman just yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's an option for any player with any behavior that doesn't
seem to be working at that point in time. That's always an
option,'' Kupchak said, ``but that's really not something that
we're prepared to talk about right now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, he's late. It's not the first time he's been late,''
he said. ``It's not something that we totally did not expect, and
certainly at this point in time our position is that we will
tolerate it.''
</P>
<P>
   But is it a problem for the team? ``Of course it is,'' Derek
Harper said. ``What are you going to do? It's not my place to worry
about all of that. . . I don't have time to be focused on Dennis
and what he's doing.''
</P>
<P>
   After Rodman arrived, along with his talent agent Steve Chasman
and two bodyguards, he requested the meeting with Rambis.
</P>
<P>
   ``Through our discussion, I understood why his frustration led
him to be late,'' Rambis said, ``and we worked through his
frustration to what I feel is our satisfaction. . . .''
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel that it was a very positive discussion,'' he said. ``I
believe there's going to be a lot of positive things that will come
out of that discussion.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
