<SLUG> BC-HKN-DEVILS-BLACKHAWKS-400&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEVILS' RALLIES AREN'T ENOUGH IN A TIE GAME 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By ALEX YANNIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ Two days after an important home victory
against Pittsburgh, the New Jersey Devils struggled to salvage a
4-4 tie Saturday with the Chicago Blackhawks, the worst team in the
Western Conference.
</P>
<P>
   Even to gain the tie against a lowly team that was playing
without two of its best players, the Devils had to come from behind
twice in the third period.
</P>
<P>
   Brendan Morrison and Jason Arnott scored the goals after Petr
Sykora scored in the first period and Ken Sutton in the second for
the Devils.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it was another disappointing performance at home for a
team that leads the Atlantic Division with 88 points and an overall
record of 39-22-10, but is only 15-13-8 at Continental Arena.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Devils were playing without Scott Stevens and Lyle
Odelein and did not have Martin Brodeur in goal, the result was all
the more disappointing considering that the Blackhawks were missing
Doug Gilmour and Boris Mironov and last week traded away their
longtime captain, Chris Chelios.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pittsburgh is a better club than Chicago,'' said Morrison, who
scored his 13th goal of the season. ``We should win these games.
The only good thing is that we came back in the third and got a
point.''
</P>
<P>
   Coach Robbie Ftorek was unhappy over the Devils' having failed
all five times in a total of 10 minutes with the man advantage
despite the fact that Chicago is the worst team in the National
Hockey League at killing penalties.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't work hard enough in practice,'' Ftorek said. ``If
you don't work hard enough in practice, it comes into the game.''
</P>
<P>
   The Devils' power play showed some promise in the 5-3 victory
over Pittsburgh two days ago with two goals on three attempts. But
it fizzled Saturday afternoon, especially on the Devils' first
attempt, when they did not have a shot against Mark Fitzpatrick,
who faced 35 shots, including five in overtime.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils also looked insecure on defense without Stevens and
Odelein. Stevens missed his fifth game with a strained groin, while
Odelein missed his third game with a bruised right knee. Stevens
may play Sunday in Florida against the Panthers, who are fighting
for a playoff spot.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't play a sound game positionally like we usually do
and like we should in order to be successful,'' Ftorek said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Chris Terreri made his first start in goal in 14 games and did
not look particularly sharp. He faced 26 shots, one in the
overtime, and allowed goals to Jamie Allison, Ed Olczyk, Dave
Manson and Eric Daze.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had pretty good legs after being out for so long,'' said
Terreri, who could have prevented the goal by Daze, which went
between Terreri's legs for Chicago's fourth goal, 8 minutes 52
seconds into the third period.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils tied it when Arnott scored on a backhander 21 seconds
later to complete the scoring.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chicago is a team not in the playoffs, and their players play
hard for a spot on the team next year,'' Terreri said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came back with two goals in the third, and every point you
earn is important,'' said Bobby Holik, who returned after serving a
two-game suspension for slashing and breaking the left index finger
of Igor Korolev of Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   Terreri made his first start since Feb. 19 and took fewer than
four minutes to have an impact in this game. He denied Olczyk from
close range on Chicago's first attempt and in the same sequence
started the play that led to the Devils' first goal.
</P>
<P>
   Terreri controlled the puck after the save and gave it to Brad
Bombardir, who sprang Sykora with a pass down the left wing. Sykora
skated in alone on Fitzpatrick and beat the goalie with a
backhander for his 25th of the season, 3:49 into the game, on the
Devils' first shot on goal.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago took control shortly afterward, and Allison tied it with
his second goal of the season, 8:52 into the game, when he
deflected Aleksei Zhamnov's shot from the left point past Terreri.
Sutton regained the lead for the Devils with his first goal, five
minutes into the middle period, when he beat Fitzpatrick from the
left side after a pass from Sergei Brylin. But Chicago took the
lead going into the third period. After Olczyk tied the score with
his eighth goal of the season, a power-play goal with 7:44 left in
the second, Manson gave the Blackhawks the lead with his fourth of
the season with 3:28 left.
</P>
<P>
   SLAP SHOTS:
</P>
<P>
   The Devils have had plenty of success against teams in the
Atlantic Division and the Eastern Conference, and nine of their
remaining games are within the conference. They have only two games
left against the Western Conference, against Anaheim and Nashville.
</P>
</TEXT>
