<HEADLINE>
WALTRIP FINDS SPEED TO EARN CUP BERTH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ I can't count the times I've hunted down
Darrell Waltrip at a racetrack during the past three seasons to get
his opinion on the latest NASCAR phenom, some time-honored NASCAR
tradition, some hot NASCAR trend.
</P>
<P>
   A three-time Winston Cup champion and the Jeff Gordon of his
day, Waltrip has settled comfortably into the role of elder
statesman after 27 years.
</P>
<P>
   But yesterday morning, the statesman was about out of breath.
Waltrip walked into the garage area at Texas Motor Speedway needing
to run the lap of his life. Fresh out of face-saving provisionals
under NASCAR's complicated qualifying system, Waltrip needed to
make the Primestar 500 on merit. On pure speed.
</P>
<P>
   Hate to admit it, but I didn't think he had a chance.
</P>
<P>
   Move up the required 10 spots, to 36th, during second-round
qualifying? After failing to make any of the first five races of
1999 on speed? You'd have a better shot at finding an open lane on
I-35W headed to the speedway.
</P>
<P>
   Which is precisely when Waltrip went out and pulled a fast one
on me, and all the nonbelievers.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after his crew changed a blown engine and after only two
practice laps, Waltrip qualified the No. 66 Big Kmart Ford 32nd at
186.554 mph. Instead of facing a roomful of media ready to write
his obituary, Waltrip looked inside himself and 'fessed-up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today was big,'' said Waltrip, NASCAR's winningest active
driver with 84 victories. ``Today was one of those times when you
have to reach deep down inside and say, `Can I do this?'
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time you got a car you know should be in the top 25 and
you're 41st or 46th or whatever, who do you look to? Do you look to
the racing gods? No, you look to the driver.''
</P>
<P>
   Waltrip is with a new team fielded by Travis Carter and Carl
Haas, and there is some leeway there for those intangibles known as
inexperience and chemistry. But Waltrip, 52, is well-aware that he
is the one element in this mix of men and machinery that has a
proven record.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do any of you folks know who has the most poles of anybody in
the garage area right now?'' Waltrip said. ``Has anybody looked
lately?''
</P>
<P>
   It's Ol' D.W. with 59, most in NASCAR's modern era, which dates
from 1972. The flip side of that, however, is the fact that Waltrip
has not won a pole since November 1995 at Atlanta Motor Speedway.
That was 101 Cup races ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``People in the garage have probably got more faith in me than I
got in myself right now,'' Waltrip said. ``I've been dragging
around, kinda having pity parties and feeling sorry for myself. To
walk through the garage and see the guys in there... I don't
believe I felt that good since I won the Daytona 500 \Rin 1989\S.
It was that kind of feeling. A feeling of relief.''
</P>
<P>
   QUICK HITS
</P>
<P>
   Irvan's investment plan
</P>
<P>
   You probably have a retirement program at your place of
employment. NASCAR Winston Cup regular Ernie Irvan has one where he
works, too, and it began paying its first dividend this weekend at
TMS.
</P>
<P>
   The 40-year-old Irvan is a 50/50 partner with Mark Simo in a
start-up Cup team. Two-time Busch Grand National champion Randy
LaJoie qualified the No. 14 Federated Auto Parts Ford 14th for
today's race, the first of an abbreviated schedule.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an investment,'' said Irvan, driver of the No. 36 M&AMP;Ms
Pontiac. ``If we can make this program work, and keep sponsorship,
it's an investment for the future. My deal is to look out for Ernie
Irvan 10 years down the road. I probably won't be a Winston Cup
driver 10 years down the road. If I'm not, what am I going to be
doing? Well, if you already have the process in place for owning a
Winston Cup team, then maybe you can make it work.''
</P>
<P>
   Irvan and Simo, who owns the No Fear line of sportswear, know
NASCAR is hot stuff.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you crunch the numbers, it makes sense,'' Irvan said.
``We've been very fortunate to qualify for this race. We may not
make any more of the other seven we're supposed to run. But right
now, everything looks good.''
</P>
<P>
   McReynolds on rebound
</P>
<P>
   Mike Skinner's 32nd-place finish at Darlington Raceway on Sunday
was the first pothole encountered by the 1997 Cup rookie of the
year and crew chief Larry McReynolds this season.
</P>
<P>
   Skinner, driver of the No. 31 Lowe's Chevrolet and fifth in the
Cup standings this year, crashed at TMS last year and finished
33rd. But that was before team owner Richard Childress switched
crew chiefs.
</P>
<P>
   ``One year ago, I was just about ready to quit racing,'' said
McReynolds, who was working with seven-time Cup champion Dale
Earnhardt.
</P>
<P>
   They had won the season-opening Daytona 500, but Earnhardt spent
most of the weekend in Fort Worth complaining about an ill-handling
No. 3 GM Goodwrench Service Chevrolet.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the Daytona 500 on, it was a complete disaster,''
McReynolds said. ``It looked like we didn't even know what made a
car roll forward. I've never been a quitter, but we were struggling
so bad with the 3 team that I was looking in the mirror and saying,
`Self, maybe racing has just run off and left you.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I even had some preliminary conversations with World Sports,
which handles TNN, TBS and CBS, about is there a future for Larry
here? Can we make it happen. I mean, I was that close to just
hanging it up.''
He did the math
</P>
<P>
   Roush teammates Jeff Burton and Mark Martin, winners of the
first two Cup events at TMS, started from the fifth and seventh
positions, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   That is in line with statistics compiled by That's Racin'
colleague David Poole, motorsports writer for ``The Charlotte
Observer''. Poolefound that 62.08 percent of the winners at all
tracks currently on the Cup circuit started in the top five. That
bodes well today, then, for Kenny Irwin, Bobby Labonte, Steve Park,
Terry Labonte and Ward Burton.
</P>
<P>
   Pole-sitter Irwin should be especially pumped, because 169 of
915 races (18.47 percent) run at current tracks have been won from
the No. 1 slot.
</P>
<P>
   Poole currently is compiling a NASCAR fan's guide for the proper
pronunciation of names of French Formula One drivers.
</P>
<P>
   Cope survives bubble
</P>
<P>
   The last driver to crack the Primestar 500 lineup by speed
yesterday was Derrike Cope, whose struggles with TMS date to last
year.
</P>
<P>
   Cope crashed during first-round qualifying last April, when
water began seeping through Turn 1. He rebroke two ribs injured at
Atlanta Motor Speedway and did not attempt to requalify.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday, he moved from 39th to 36th and into the field with a
flyer at 185.995 mph. Like Waltrip, Cope and team owner Chuck Rider
had no provisionals to cash in _ and a big-name sponsor to cater to
on race day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been getting grayer and grayer by the moment,'' Cope,
driver of the No. 30 Jimmy Dean Pontiac, said as he waited on the
bubble. ``It's one of those racetracks where the margin of error is
very, very little.''
</P>
<P>
   Last words
</P>
<P>
   ``This weekend proved a lot to me, it proved a lot to my team _
that we can do this, and we have to do this.'' _ Waltrip, after
qualifying for the Primestar 500 on speed
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
