r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-BUSCH-RACE-TEX     03-27 0654
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-BUSCH-RACE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAIN, WRECKS MARK MARTIN'S THIRD TITLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ The racing surface is repaved, reconfigured,
revamped and gets rave reviews, but the latest NASCAR race at Texas
Motor Speedway produced something that looked a lot like a rerun.
</P>
<P>
   More wrecks. More weather problems. And another Mark Martin
victory.
</P>
<P>
   Martin won the Busch Grand National Coca-Cola 300 yesterday, his
third victory in the five stock car races at the track. He did it
because of the weather and the wrecks.
</P>
<P>
   Martin conceded he had no chance to win until Matt Kenseth
wrecked on lap 143.
</P>
<P>
   ``Under no scenario could we compete with him,'' said Martin,
who won the BGN race in 1997 and the Winston Cup race last year.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't have to compete with anybody down the stretch because
he had the No. 60 Winn-Dixie Ford in front when rain stopped the
race after 163 of the scheduled 200 laps.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today was our lucky day,'' Martin said. ``We were in good
position to capitalize on the problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Burton, Martin's Roush Racing teammate, was second in the
No. 9 Track Gear Ford. He won the Winston Cup race in Darlington,
S.C., last week when rain shortened that event.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we'd have won today's race, we'd have been arrested for
grand larceny,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Green finished a hard-luck third. If rain had stopped the
two laps earlier, he might have had the victory. He was out front
when a caution flag came out on lap 152 because of a four-car
wreck, but he didn't have a third gear. He had no chance on the
restart, and Martin and Burton got around him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Third is a bonus for us,'' Green said. ``If the rain had come
a couple of laps earlier, it would have been a big bonus for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, this race wasn't a complete rerun of the first two,
problem- plagued years. This time, the wrecks and the weather
weren't the track's fault.
</P>
<P>
   The racing surface was wet because of the rain, not water
seeping through the track.
</P>
<P>
   And the wreck that decided the race was caused by a combination
of Kenseth's inexperience and zealousness.
</P>
<P>
   Kenseth had far and away the dominant car. He moved the No. 17
DeWalt Tools Chevrolet from fifth to first by the eighth lap. He
pulled away from the field, leading by as much as four seconds. He
led 88 of the first 100 laps.
</P>
<P>
   ``Matt had everybody covered today,'' Martin said.
</P>
<P>
   It appeared as though the only thing that could stop Kenseth
would be the rain.
</P>
<P>
   The start of the race was delayed more than 21/2 hours, and at
about the 110-lap mark, crews were anxiously watching the weather
radar to see if more rain was coming. Teams did not want to come in
under green-flag conditions and be caught in the pits if rain
started falling again.
</P>
<P>
   The race indeed turned on green-flag pit stops, but not because
of the rain. It happened because of a wreck between Casey Atwood
and Jeff Krough in lap 142.
</P>
<P>
   Martin had pulled into the pits, but knowing a caution was
coming, he exited without stopping to stay on the lead lap.
</P>
<P>
   Kenseth, who already had pitted and was a lap down, raced around
to try and get his lap back. Instead, he got caught up in the wreck
coming around Turn 4. He was sideways across the start-finish line
and went into the grass.
</P>
<P>
   The once-dominant car now had front end and side sheet metal
damage, and wasn't a factor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Matt was doing his best to get us back on the lead lap, and he
just overdid it,'' crew chief and owner Robby Reiser said. ``It was
just one of those things.''
</P>
<P>
   More than the rain, Kenseth's wreck put a damper on Martin's
victory. The 40-year-old Martin has become the 27-year-old
Kenseth's mentor, and is expected to be part owner of a Winston Cup
team for Kenseth next season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was more disappointed to see him have trouble than I was
elated to win the race,'' Martin said.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
