<SLUG> BC-CAR-TMS-NOTEBOOK-TEX </SLUG>
 
Youngsters show their age 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STAR-TELEGRAM STAFF 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Adam Petty and Casey Atwood, both promising young Busch Grand
National series drivers, weren't yesterday. The inexperienced
18-year-olds were involved in wrecks and unable to finish the
rain-shortened Coca-Cola 300 at the Texas Motor Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   Petty, who started third in the No. 45 Spree Chevrolet, crashed
on Lap 86 when his car hit the wall in Turn 2. He had fallen out of
the top 20 before leaving the race. He finished 39th.
</P>
<P>
   A frustrated Petty was quick to blame his youth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just being young and dumb,'' said Petty, the grandson of
NACSAR legend Richard Petty and son of Winston Cup regular Kyle
Petty. ``I was trying to do something my car wouldn't do. I am
really down on myself right now.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, it's all my fault. I just got stupid.''
</P>
<P>
   Atwood's troubles stemmed from car trouble that led to driving
trouble. The driver of the No. 27 Castrol GTX Chevrolet had a
front-end vibration that wasn't fixed with a four-tire change. That
led to something breaking inthe right front-end of his car, forcing
it to get loose out of Turn 4.
</P>
<P>
   The loss of control triggered a crash with Jeff Krogh's No. 56
Clearwater Forest Chevrolet.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cars went around me, and something broke in the right
front and went and just took off into the wall,'' Atwood said. ``I
took out a bunch of cars. I hate it for everybody, but there's
nothing we can do.''
</P>
<P>
   After starting in the No. 18 position, Atwood finished 35th. He
was running in the top 10 before the crash on Lap 143 of the
163-lap race. _ Rick Herrin
GORDON CRASHES OUT AGAIN
</P>
<P>
   For the third time in three races, Jeff Gordon got tangled up in
a wreck at Texas Motor Speedway. Yesterday it was during the
Coca-Cola 300 in the No. 24 Pepsi Chevrolet, co-owned by his wife,
Brooke, and Winston Cup crew chief Ray Evernham.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon had been running third, but the crew mismanaged its
mileage and he pitted around Lap 140. Moments later, the day's
fifth caution came out at Lap 152 after a four-car wreck involving
Bobby Hillin Jr., Barry Bodine, Phil Parsons and Jimmy Spencer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We put ourselves out of sequence and should've have been
running back there \R12th\S,'' Pepsi crew chief Patrick Donahue
explained. ``When you get out of sequence like that, those things
will happen.''
</P>
<P>
   On Lap 158, Gordon got tagged by the fallout from a Turn 2
tangle between the No. 3 AC Delco Chevy driven by Dale Earnhardt
Jr. and Jeff Purvis' No. 4 Lance Snacks Chevrolet.
</P>
<P>
   The race ended at Lap 163.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hasn't been that nice for us,'' Evernham admitted. ``But
we're lucky that car isn't in a ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon finished the race in 13th place. _ Stacy Feducia
</P>
<P>
   TELECAST CHANGE
</P>
<P>
   The rain that delayed the start of yesterday's race by more than
2 1/2 hours also forced CBS to cut away from the Coca-Cola 300
before it was finished. The network shifted the telecast to The
Nashville Network, its cable network, at 3:14 p.m. That's when CBS
began its coverage of the NCAA Final Four basketball game between
Ohio State and Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   The race telecast had been scheduled from noon to 3 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew we were going to disappoint somebody,'' said CBS
spokeswoman LeslieAnne Wade. ``But we're trying to satisfy the
biggest audience we can. It's really a numbers game.'' _ David A.
Markiewicz
WINSTON CUP APPEAL
</P>
<P>
   The appeal of Winston Cup drivers racing in the Busch Grand
National series was showcased in yesterday's Coca-Cola 300.
</P>
<P>
   And they delievered with three Cup drivers finishing in the top
five, highlighted by Mark Martin's victory. Jeff Burton was second,
and Primestar 500 pole-sitter Kenny Irwin claimed fifth. More
impressive, half of the top 20 finishers were Cup drivers.
</P>
<P>
   Fourteen of the 43 drivers in yesterday's race will compete
today in the Primestar 500. _ Rick Herrin
</P>
<P>
   TYLER JET MAKES FIELD
</P>
<P>
   Phil Hammer, the crew chief for Rich Bickle's 10-10-345 Lucky
Dog Pontiac, had a tough decision to make yesterday. Should he make
a run in second-day Winston Cup qualifying?
</P>
<P>
   His car was 26th fastest Friday after pole qualifying for the
Primestar 500. The top 25 had locked in their spots in the field,
and 26th almost certainly was good enough.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, the 26th fastest car after qualifying for the
Busch Grand National Coca-Cola 300 stood on its time and had to use
a provisional to make the field when speeds improved the next day.
</P>
<P>
   Hammer's decision was made easier after the morning practice
session.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only four or five cars had gone faster than our speed,''
Hammer said. ``Eleven had to do it to knock us out of the race.''
</P>
<P>
   The car owned by Tim Beverley of Tyler stood on its speed. Four
second-day qualifiers went faster, but Bickle was safely in at No.
30, a relief for the team that failed to qualify at Darlington
(S.C.) Raceway last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll start 30th,'' Hammer said. ``A really good day would be
if we can finish in the top 20. I'd be satisfied with that. That
would be another step forward for us.'' _ Simon Gonzalez
</P>
<P>
   STUNT DRIVER MISSES FIELD
</P>
<P>
   Stanton Barrett should have joined Hammer in standing on his
time.
</P>
<P>
   Barrett, driver of the No. 90 Suburban Lodge Ford, was 36th
after first-day qualifying and on the bubble. The first 36 cars
make it in on speed, with the final seven spots being filled with
provisionals, based on car owner points.
</P>
<P>
   Car owner W.C. ``Junie'' Donlavey and Barrett elected to attempt
to re-qualify yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt like we could run stronger,'' Donlavey said.
</P>
<P>
   It was the wrong decision. Their lap of 185.573 mph was 41st
fastest, and the team doesn't have a provisional.
</P>
<P>
   If they had stood on the first-day lap of 186.136, they would
have made it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love this sport, but it's pretty cruel sometimes,'' Barrett
said. ``I came here to race. Now I'll have two qualifying laps
running through my mind for a couple of weeks. What if we had done
this? What if we had done that?''
</P>
<P>
   A disappointed Donlavey tried to look at the bright side.
</P>
<P>
   ``We won't have to fight that crowd tomorrow,'' he said. _ Simon
Gonzalez
</P>
<P>
   TOUGH CORNERS
</P>
<P>
   During Busch practice Thursday, Turn 2 at Texas Motor Speedway
was the turn that some drivers had some trouble negotiating.Turn 2
claimed some victims, but Turn 4 claimed some as well.
</P>
<P>
   But it was not because of the track.
</P>
<P>
   Of the six caution periods in the Coca-Cola 300 yesterday, five
were caused when cars hit either the wall in Turn 2 or Turn 4.
</P>
<P>
   The final caution of the day came out on Lap 158, when Dale
Earnhardt Jr., Jeff Purvis and Jeff Gordon were involved in a
chain-reaction wreck in Turn 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody was checking up in front of me, and I could not get
slowed down,'' Earnhardt said. ``It would have done me no good to
get on the breaks.''
</P>
<P>
   Other victims who hit the wall in turns 2 and 4 were Lyndon
Amick (Turn 4), Adam Petty (Turn 2) and Casey Atwood (Turn 4).
Amick hit the wall after he made contact with pole-sitter Dave
Blaney.
</P>
<P>
   Petty damaged the front end of his car after hitting the wall,
and Atwood said something happened in the front end of his car
before he hit the wall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got a little out of the groove coming off Turn 2,'' Petty
said. ``You get out of the groove out there and you go straight
into the wall.'' _ Len Hayward
</P>
<P>
   G. BODINE FAST, SAFE
</P>
<P>
   Geoffrey Bodine had one of the fastest cars Friday. He turned
the fastest lap _ 190.101 mph _ of any Winston Cup driver in
Friday's afternoon practice.
</P>
<P>
   But rain yesterday shed his speed in the qualifying.
</P>
<P>
   Bodine, driver of the No. 60 Power Team Chevrolet, qualified
26th (the highest a second-round qualifier can start) for today's
PrimeStar 500 after morning rains forced him to play it safe. His
qualifying lap time was 28.504 after posting a field-best 28.347
lap time in the third practice Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just wanted a good lap,'' said Bodine, who is 29th in the
Cup point standings. ``If it would have been dry, I would have gone
for a record, but it was wet and I went into a conservative mode.
There's no sense in being stupid.''
</P>
<P>
   Bodine said his practice speeds, all over 190 mph, came
relatively easy and said his team and the rest of the drivers are
aware of his car's ability.
</P>
<P>
   ``The car is faster than that, and everybody knows it,'' Bodine
said.
</P>
<P>
   Bodine, whose last victory came in 1996 at Watkins Glen,
finished 32nd in last year's Cup race at the Texas Motor Speedway.
_ Rick Herrin
</P>
<P>
   EARLY INCIDENT
</P>
<P>
   Pole-sitter Dave Blaney said he did not have enough to keep up
with the leaders in yesterday's Coca-Cola 300. In the early portion
of the race, however, his No. 93 Amoco Pontiac was running well
enough to give him a good, solid finish.
</P>
<P>
   But in the 72nd lap, Blaney's luck changed for the worse. Blaney
and Lyndon Amick touched entering Turn 4, with Blaney suffering
some front-end damage that made his car tough to handle.
</P>
<P>
   The rain, however, brought the race to a halt with 37 laps
remaining, and it helped the former Sprint Car champion end with a
strong eighth-place finish.
</P>
<P>
   ``It did hurt \Rthe car\S quite a bit because it would not
handle near as good after that and actually it did not run as
good,'' Blaney said. ``The body was pulling so much air, but we
were pretty good early on because we rode in fourth there for a
long time.''
</P>
<P>
   This finish was much better for Blaney this time in the
Coca-Cola 300; last season he finished 34th.
_ Len Hayward
TOUGH BUSCH LUCK
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Lepage said he was wondering if Texas Motor Speedway will
ever let him finish a Busch Grand National race. For the past two
years Lepage has finished 40th or worse. In yesterday's race he
finished 43rd and had the distinction of being the first car in the
garage after leaving with less than 20 laps completed.
</P>
<P>
   In both races, the transmission has kept Lepage from finishing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It must be that Texas just does not like me,'' said Lepage,
who also drives the No. 16 Primestar Ford in the Winston Cup
series. ``All of the sudden I got up to speed and it started to
vibrate and I thought we might have a wheel loose or something. We
came in and changed all four tires, and the vibration was still
there. At least we did not wreck.''
</P>
<P>
   Lepage has participated in all six Busch Grand National races
this year and yesterday's finish broke a string of two consecutive
top-10 finishes. The Vermont native came into the event second in
Busch points but fell to eighth. _ Len Hayward
</P>
<P>
   IMPROVEMENT FOR SCHRADER
</P>
<P>
   Look at the stats this season for Ken Schrader in the No. 15
Oakwood Homes Busch car and they don't look good. In three races
this season, Schrader has finished 38th, 18th and 38th.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday, however, Schrader had some good luck and came away
with a seventh-place finish.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have struggled here before, we have crashed and we have
taken 18th,'' the Winston Cup regular said. ``So right now, we will
take seventh.''
</P>
<P>
   Schrader added that there could be a chance for a second groove
to develop in today's Primestar 500.
</P>
<P>
   ``The second groove was trying to work, but that is one of those
things where the other driver has to work with you,'' he said. _
Len Hayward
TEXAS CONNECTION
</P>
<P>
   The luck of Texas natives Terry Labonte and Bobby Hillin Jr.
varied in the Coca-Cola 300.
</P>
<P>
   Despite coasting in with an empty gas tank on his first pit
stop, Corpus Christi native Labonte went on to finish 14th in the
No. 44 Slim Jim Chevy.
</P>
<P>
   Midland native Hillin, however, got caught in the backstraight
accident that brought out the caution flag on Lap 152. Hillin
slowed to avoid a spinning Barry Bodine and was tagged from behind
by Brett Bodine. Hillin finished 34th in the No. 8 Clean Shower
Chevy.
_ Johnny D. Boggs
</P>
<P>
   BRIEFLY
</P>
<P>
   The No. 84 Three Stooges Beer Chevrolet, driven by Ken Bouchard,
became the first car to withdraw from the Primestar 500 field.
Bouchard suffered a concussion when his car tagged the Turn 2 wall
in his qualifying attempt Friday and was transported to Parkland
Memorial Hospital. Bouchard remained at Parkland yesterday in
stable condition.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Grissom, who finished 10th in the 1997 and '98 Winston Cup
races at TMS, replaced Tony Raines as driver of the No. 74 Bace
Motorsports Chevy in the Coca-Cola 300. Raines suffered a
concussion after crashing in Turn 2 during practice Friday and was
released from Harris Methodist Hospital yesterday. Grissom, who
failed to qualify for the BGN field as a replacement driver for the
injured Bobby Labonte, finished 40th in Raines' Monte Carlo after
encountering engine problems.
nn
</P>
