<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-TPC-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Duval tops survival test at TPC
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By EDDIE SEFKO &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PONTE VEDRA BEACH, Fla. _ In honor of the Final Four on
Florida's opposite coast, the Tournament Players Course at Sawgrass
decided to do its best Duke imitation and run up the scores.
</P>
<P>
   Everywhere you looked Saturday at The Players Championship,
there were big numbers. Even the new generation's king, David
Duval, wasn't above the ballooning scores, although his didn't rise
as much as most.
</P>
<P>
   Duval weathered five bogeys, but avoided any disastrous holes,
to shoot 2-over-par 74 and claim a one-shot lead going into the
final 18 holes today.
</P>
<P>
   This is all you need to know about how tough it was to play the
Tournament Players Course at Sawgrass on Saturday: Six players
broke par-72 and 14 shot in the 80s.
</P>
<P>
   Long hitters saw their drives run off the hard fairways and into
hairy rough. Any shot missed around the rock-hard greens trickled
into ankle-deep rough. The result was a scoring average of 76.24
strokes.
</P>
<P>
   Duval stands _ or teeters, as the case may be _ at 4-under 212
for the tournament, one stroke ahead of Phil Mickelson and Skip
Kendall. The 4-under total is the highest score to lead at The
Players after 54 holes since 1982. Nick Price, Scott Hoch and Colin
Montgomerie were two strokes further back at 215.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was tough out there and that was reflected in the scores,''
said Duval, who is threatening to win the tournament that is in his
back yard, just a few miles from his home in Jacksonville Beach.
``We just got kicked around. It played as difficult certainly as
this course ever has and maybe as tough as any course I've ever
played.''
</P>
<P>
   By any standards, it was a brutal day of golf. Generally,
Augusta National is considered as difficult a test of golf as pros
see. But the TPC on Saturday was in the same class.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was as hard and as fast as I've seen at Augusta,'' said
Mickelson, one of the six who beat par with a 71. ``It was
extremely difficult. I've never been faced with chips around the
greens where the sole purpose is to just get it on the green, not
getting it close.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great mental challenge every hole. And there's a
certain amount of relief after each hole. But it's only
temporary.''
</P>
<P>
   Most players didn't get relief until the sun went down and they
could get away from the TPC at Sawgrass. Even then, they had to
face the reality that, most likely, they'll get the same nasty
treatment today in the final round since conditions aren't expected
to change.
</P>
<P>
   From the very beginning, everybody expected Saturday to be a
survival test. Even when he birdied two of the first four holes,
Duval knew better than to be lulled into a false sense of security.
</P>
<P>
   He was sailing along after those early birdies at 8-under par
with a five-shot lead on the field.
</P>
<P>
   But on the par-4 5th hole, Duval couldn't get up and down from
the fringe and it was the first of four bogeys in six holes.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we had to do this every week, not a lot of people would
play golf,'' Duval said. ``I knew we were in for a jolly good time.
You can access the greens. But you can't access the holes. And if
you miss the greens, it's pretty much an automatic bogey.''
</P>
<P>
   Or worse. Joe Ozaki, who started the day leading Duval by a
stroke, was one of the 14 players who couldn't break 80.
</P>
<P>
   There were a ton of lowlights as scores rocketed upward.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody was more exasperated than Davis Love III, who started the
day at 4-under par. He triple-bogeyed the first hole when he needed
four wedge shots to get his ball to stay on the table-top green.
Near the end of his round, he had a quadruple-bogey at No. 17 after
hitting two balls in the water. The bookend 7s nuked his otherwise
solid round. He was 1-under on his other 16 holes.
</P>
<P>
   Life was tough for everybody.
</P>
<P>
   Duffy Waldorf was 3-under par for the tournament as he reached
the 18th tee. Eight strokes later, he was licking his wounds with a
75 for the day and sitting at 1-over for the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Curtis Strange started the day tied for fourth place, shot 78
and called the course ``laughable'' because of the way it was
playing.
</P>
<P>
   The course was dry, hard and, if you weren't on the fairway or
green, you were in rough up to your socks. And there was a lively
breeze that blew at varying speeds throughout the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``On days like this, you have to figure out the wind and then
deal with it,'' said Steve Stricker, whose 70 got him to even-par
for the tournament and was tied for low round of the day. ``I was
hoping for a good round and I have a feeling I'll move up. In these
conditions, everybody is going to face situations where you're
staring at the possibility of a big score. That's when you have to
cut your losses and move on.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I shot even-par and was very happy with it,'' said Mark
Calcavecchia, who had a chip-in for birdie on No. 11 to anchor his
round. ``On the final seven holes, there were only two birdie
holes, 14 and 16. On the rest of them, you can forget it.''
</P>
<P>
   And when the dust settled, Duval was on the perch of another
victory. He already has had two this year, shot a final-round 59 at
the Bob Hope Chrysler Classic and been a threat virtually every
time he's touched a club.
</P>
<P>
   Winning in his hometown would be a nice addition to his
collection of achievements already this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
