<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCONN-OHIOST-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCONN IS TOO MUCH FOR OHIO STATE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By JUDY BATTISTA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ Jim Calhoun pumped his fists twice and
then, one by one, embraced the players who had carried him to the
brink of a national championship. There was Khalid El-Amin, the
rotund point guard, and Richard Hamilton, the silky shooter. Ricky
Moore, the defensive whiz, was next.
</P>
<P>
   When he was through, Calhoun emitted just the slighest sigh and
burst into a smile. These great Connecticut players, who had made
the Huskies one of the favorites for the title since the start of
the season, played the kind of taut game that wins championships.
And finally, come Monday, the Huskies will help decide one.
</P>
<P>
   Riding the stellar offense of Hamilton and El-Amin, who combined
for 42 of Connecticut's 64 points, and lock-down defense from
Moore, Connecticut reached its destiny Saturday night with a 64-58
victory over Ohio State. The Huskies (33-2), in their first Final
Four, will play in Monday's national championship game.
</P>
<P>
   ``With all the success they have enjoyed in the past decade, for
them to get a chance to play for the national championship is
fitting,'' Ohio State Coach Jim O'Brien said.
</P>
<P>
   This team has been called Calhoun's most talented, and all
season the expectation was that Calhoun should make the Florida
flight plans early. But the Huskies have failed to put together a
dominant performance, struggling against Gonzaga even to reach the
Final Four. Saturday night, the many facets of Connecticut's game
fit together well, the defense feeding Connecticut's fast-break
offense to pound Ohio State (27-9) in transition and the offense
building such a big lead that Ohio State could not find its way
back. Connecticut had a nine-point lead with seven minutes left in
the first half but led by just 36-35 at the half. Then, the Huskies
opened a 10-point lead in the second half with Hamilton and El-Amin
leading the way and this time, the margin was enough for the
defense to take over. Ohio State hit just 8-of-33 field goal
attempts in the second half (24 percent) and struggled as if on a
slippery slope that kept getting steeper.
</P>
<P>
   ``We spurted and played terrifically well full court and then
when we _ particularly in the first half _ got a lead, we relaxed
on offense and then on defense,'' Calhoun said. ``We gave up easy
hoops and out-of-bounds plays and we allowed them right back in.
Coming out in the second half, there was no way we could allow them
to come back from 10 down that easy. They could come back, but not
that easy.''
</P>
<P>
   Nothing came easily for Ohio State. The Buckeyes' backcourt is
the most important part of the team, scoring more than half of
their tournament points. Scoonie Penn and Michael Redd are the only
two Buckeyes who averaged in double figures. But Connecticut
identified the threat and then destroyed it.
</P>
<P>
   Penn, who was hounded by Moore all night, scored just 11 points
on 3-of-13 shooting and Redd, who relies on Penn to get him the
ball, scored 15 points on 7-of-18 shooting. Calhoun has maintained
that Moore is the best perimeter defender in the nation _ he said
Saturday night that Moore cut the head off the dragon that is Penn
_ and on one play midway through the second half Moore gave ample
evidence to back Calhoun's confidence.
</P>
<P>
   First, he stayed so close to Penn that Penn forced a terrible
shot that missed. Then, as the ball bounced long off the rim, Moore
retrieved it before it went out of bounds and launched a long
outlet pass to El-Amin. El-Amin put up a perfect alley-oop pass,
which Rashamel Jones laid in. That play gave Connecticut its
10-point lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't let me breathe the whole time,'' Penn said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Still, Ohio State did not go away quietly and Calhoun's fear
that Ohio State would come back was realized.
</P>
<P>
   This has been a remarkable season for the Buckeyes, coming from
the bottom of the Big Ten last season to a stirring run through the
tournament. The Buckeyes played with all the tenacity _ if not the
skill level _ they showed throughout this season. They were down by
just 57-54 with 4 minutes 12 seconds remaining after Redd followed
a Connecticut shot clock violation with a layup. But then the poor
free throw shooting that has plagued Ohio State all season _ and
which at one point inspired O'Brien to call in a sports
psychologist _ resurfaced. In the final 2:53 of the game _ with
Connecticut's lead at four _ Ohio State was just 4-of-9 from the
line.
</P>
<P>
   That gave the Huskies all the breathing room they needed. With
1:35 remaining, the Huskies worked the shot clock with Ohio State
trying to deny Hamilton the 3-pointer. Finally Penn, at 5-10, ended
up on the 6-6 Hamilton. Hamilton saw the mismatch and shot a
leaning 8-footer over Penn with just one tick left on the shot
clock. That gave Connecticut a 61-55 lead and, effectively, the
game. When, a minute later, Ohio State missed two straight shots,
Hamilton clenched his fists and finally smiled.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think our pride stepped up a little bit,'' El-Amin said.
``We felt threatened that their backcourt was going to try to outdo
us.''
</P>
<P>
   No need to worry. Connecticut had played the game it needed to
play. Perhaps it was still not its best game _ it was not as
flawless as the Huskies' crushing of St. John's in the Big East
final _ but it was enough.
</P>
<P>
   Calhoun patted El-Amin on the back as he left the dias in the
news conference after the game and that was all the celebration
there would be for Saturday night. There was a long sleepless night
of work ahead for Calhoun, work he said he was thrilled to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we have a better basketball game in us,'' he said. ``I
hope we have it Monday night.''
</P>
</TEXT>
