<SLUG> BC-CAR-DALE-JR.-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EARNHARDT JR. SALVAGES FINISH IN TOP 10 DESPITE EARLY EXIT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By David A. Markiewicz 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Even a couple of post-race peanut butter and
jelly sandwiches couldn't console Dale Earnhardt Jr. yesterday as
he stood outside his hauler in the gloom of a rainy spring
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't the minor physical damage he suffered in a lap 158
crash that troubled him. It was the thought of wrecking his car and
failing to defend his Busch Grand National Coca-Cola 300 title at
Texas Motor Speedway that was disturbing.
</P>
<P>
   The crash ``wasn't that bad,'' Earnhardt said, ``but it was hard
enough to tear up a race car. We can heal bones, but it's a shame
to tear up them race cars.''
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt might have found some solace in the outcome, though.
The downpour that ended his day early gave him a 10th-place finish.
As Earnhardt knew, it was the best ending he could have expected,
considering the events of the day.
</P>
<P>
   As he climbed out of his No. 3 ACDelco Chevrolet into the rain
for the last time yesterday, Earnhardt had observed: ``If it rains,
it's a top 10; if not, it's junk.''
</P>
<P>
   His car might have been junk _ banging into Jeff Purvis' Lance
Snacks Chevrolet still left his car running, but not in good
condition _ but the result wasn't. The washout garnered him
valuable points toward a possible second consecutive NASCAR Busch
Series driving championship.
</P>
<P>
   Still, ``It's not the boost we'd like,'' Earnhardt said. ``We
won the race here last year, but the field was much tougher this
year.''
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt's day started with misfortune when his car suffered a
cut tire, and he fell behind a lap. He fought his way back to the
lead lap, but then came the crash.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were trying to get back up to the front where we hadn't
been all day and went down into the corner and a couple of guys
checked up,'' Earnhardt explained.
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt won seven of his 31 races last year while driving his
father's car. His TMS victory was the first of his career in 16
starts.
</P>
<P>
   This season, Earnhardt Jr. ranks sixth in the point standings
and is fifth in money earned. But it hasn't exactly been the cruise
of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt attributed that to competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the addition of a few Winston Cup veterans and a couple
more competitive Busch teams than we had last year, it's definitely
stronger each week,'' Earnhardt Jr. said. ``We're going to have to
get our stuff together if we're going to win this championship.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
