<HEADER>
A6939 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-OHIOST-UCONN28-CO     03-27 0624
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-OHIOST-UCONN28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ohio State's magical quest falls short
 &HT;    By Gary Nuhn
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ Scoonie Penn wore two new shirts Saturday
_ No. 35 and Ricky Moore.
</P>
<P>
   He wore No. 35 because he couldn't find his usual Ohio State
game jersey, No. 12.
</P>
<P>
   He wore Ricky Moore because Moore is Connecticut's 6-foot-2
senior defensive grandmaster.
</P>
<P>
   Scoonie, wearing all this new apparel, hit his first two shots,
then went 1-for-11 the rest of the way and Ohio State's first visit
to the NCAA Final Four in 31 years ended on the cutting-room floor.
</P>
<P>
   The final was UConn 64, OSU 58, in a national semifinal where
the concept of offense was as lost as if it dropped into one of
Florida's infamous sinkholes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, Ricky cut the head of the dragon off,'' said UConn
Coach James Calhoun.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't just Moore on Scoonie, but that was the main
bottleneck because Scoonie starts every Ohio State play and ends a
lot of them, too. This night, Scoonie played with Moore attached to
him like a Siamese Twin.
</P>
<P>
   Calhoun said at first he didn't know whether he was going to put
Moore on Scoonie or on Michael Redd, the Buckeyes' leading scorer.
</P>
<P>
   ``But after watching tape,'' he said, ``I knew as Scoonie goes,
so goes Ohio State.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus did Moore wrap himself around Scoonie like a fur coat and
leave him only occasionally in the next 40 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe I got one or two open looks the whole game,'' Scoonie
said. ``Usually on defense, you'll find guys who take their eye off
you a couple of times. He didn't. Like when Michael would be there
at the top of the key ready to make his move, usually my guy will
go over and help out. Ricky never went over.''
</P>
<P>
   Ricky didn't lose that number.
</P>
<P>
   In the UConn dressing room, Moore laughed when he heard that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why should I?'' he said. ``Redd can do that all day and I'm
not going over there. I figure someone else can help on Redd. I had
my hands filled with Scoonie.''
</P>
<P>
   Redd was also stopped. He got four baskets on fast breaks, but
out of OSU's regular offense, he was 3-for-14.
</P>
<P>
   But even with its head lying on the ground, the Ohio State
dragon staggered around and made life tough for UConn. Every time
the Huskies seemed as if they had the game in their pocket, the
Buckeyes rushed back. Just before the half a nine-point UConn lead
disintegrated to one.
</P>
<P>
   In the UConn lockerroom, Moore was furious. He began screaming,
``How can we let a 10-point lead get away?''
</P>
<P>
   Fellow guard Khalid El-Amin tried to calm him. ``Stop
panicking,'' El-Amin told Moore. ``You're starting to sound too
much like coach.''
</P>
<P>
   UConn built a 10-point lead at 51-41, but the dragon fought back
and cut it to 59-55 with two minutes to go.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the killer play. UConn's Jake Voskuhl fumbled the ball
near the free throw line, then tried to tap it to El-Amin at the
sideline. But El-Amin had left the area. With no one there, Voskuhl
raced over and grabbed his own pass.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was traveling,'' said OSU Coach Jim O'Brien.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the officials allowed UConn to call a 20-second
timeout.
</P>
<P>
   The Huskies scored on that possession, the Buckeyes missed four
shots and four free throws in the last 1:42 and the turnaround
season, the improbable season, the magnificent season ended with a
thud.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went from 8-22 one season to the Final Four the next,''
Scoonie said. ``It was a great accomplishment.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not that big of a deal to me right now,'' said
O'Brien. ``The big picture is so much more important.''
</P>
<P>
   In the big picture, the dragon didn't die, it just went into
hibernation until next October.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
