<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-27 22:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6940 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-LIPTON-525&AMP;ADD-NY     03-27 0926
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-LIPTON-525&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KRAJICEK WINS FINAL AS THE BACKUP ACT 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By ROBIN FINN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KEY BISCAYNE, Fla. _ Before Richard Krajicek and Sebastien
Grosjean, the pair of marquee also-rans who toiled Saturday in the
final of what had become an anticlimactic men's event at the Lipton
Championships, marched out to battle on the sun-blasted stadium
court Saturday afternoon, they nearly had to ask permission to use
it.
</P>
<P>
   Tennis does not often treat its male conquistadors like
second-class citizens. But here at the Lipton, Williams-mania has
descended with a bang on the eve of the sport's first
sister-against-sister finale since the Watson siblings tangled at
Wimbledon in 1884.
</P>
<P>
   Feminism, and one Florida-based African-American family, rule
the roost this year.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow Krajicek and Grosjean were able to wangle a
2-hour-39-minute lease on the stadium, and Krajicek, the hottest
performer on the men's tour but an uncomfortable performer Saturday
because of a queasy stomach, used it for a 4-6, 6-1, 6-2, 7-5
victory. That solved the identity of the men's 1999 Lipton
champion; the identity of the women's champion remains a Williams
family secret until Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   But Richard Williams, whose two teen-age daughters, Venus and
Serena, will face each other Sunday for the Lipton's women's title,
already calls the pristine green stadium at this $7 million event
``Venus' house.''
</P>
<P>
   After all, his 18-year-old daughter Venus is the defending
champion and has beaten her 17-year-old sister in both their
professional meetings.
</P>
<P>
   Williams said Saturday that Sunday's showdown between the
sixth-seeded Venus and the 16th-seeded Serena, now undefeated in 16
straight matches following her brash semifinal dismissal of
top-ranked Martina Hingis, has the makings of a present and future
classic.
</P>
<P>
   ``As you probably heard me say in the past, my girls would be
No. 1,'' Williams said. ``We're planning so long, worked so hard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Serena is probably playing like the best player on the tour
right now, but I don't know if anyone could beat Venus.''
</P>
<P>
   But Saturday the Williams girls lent the stadium spotlight to
the men.
</P>
<P>
   The history-making done by the seventh-seeded Krajicek, the
first Dutchman to reach the Lipton final, and the 74th-ranked
Grosjean, not just the first Frenchman but also the lowest-ranked
men's finalist in the tournament's 15-year tenure, rated on a
smaller scale than that reserved for the much-ballyhooed women's
finale. But certainly it was of pivotal importance to both of them.
</P>
<P>
   The final represented the continuing comeback of Krajicek, who
underwent knee surgery last year and is still pursuing the
excellence he displayed when he served and volleyed his way to the
1996 Wimbledon title. It was also a breakthrough for Grosjean. This
was the first professional final for the 20-year-old Grosjean, who
had to be wondering if he would ever replicate the peak he hit in
his junior career when he reigned as the world No. 1 in singles and
doubles in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Both Krajicek and Grosjean collected high-stakes scalps during
their Lipton campaigns. Krajicek detonated his serve and demolished
Pete Sampras, who nonetheless reclaims the No. 1 spot. Grosjean
brushed away three match points and stunned top-seeded Carlos Moya.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In their opening set, the sniper skills of Grosjean, whose
razor-sharp passing shots from the backcourt had served as his
passport to this round, made inroads on the vaunted Krajicek serve.
After trading breaks in the third and fourth games, Grosjean rifled
a backhand crosscourt pass to gain a break point and went ahead by
4-3 when Krajicek netted his backhand approach. A forehand that
Grosjean knifed down the line brought him the opening set, but in
the second, the 27-year-old Krajicek soothed his nerves by
re-invigorating his serve and converted the set with a
match-leveling service winner.
</P>
<P>
   Krajicek took a two-sets-to-one lead when a backhand return from
Grosjean clipped the net and skipped wide at set point of the third
set. They traded breaks midway through the fourth set, locking it
up at 4-4, but Krajicek got the pivotal break in the 11th game and
needed to serve for the match just once. With his 24th ace at match
point, he had his title. The victory elevated Krajicek to a
career-best ranking of No. 4 in the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't feel good, but I didn't panic, and I picked my points
to use my energy,'' Krajicek, who blamed his problems on nerves and
a stomach ailment, said. ``I was definitely not hoping for a fifth
set.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dutchman's successful, and somewhat predictable, performance
against the gutsy but outgunned Grosjean landed him his 17th career
title and extended his circuit-leading hot stretch to 13 of his
last 14 matches.
</P>
<P>
   His quarterfinal loss to Brazil's Gustavo Kuerten at Indian
Wells, Calif., is sandwiched between the title here Saturday and
one on Feb. 28 in London, where he soldiered through despite
attending the funeral of his friend, Menno Oosting, on the morning
of the semifinal.
</P>
<P>
   While Krajicek dedicated his London victory to Oosting, a
doubles specialist and Davis Cup veteran who died Feb. 22 in a car
accident in Belgium, this title came under happier circumstances
and could be dedicated to his daughter, Emma, who celebrated her
first birthday Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The Williams sisters insisted they would both celebrate on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really, really hope it's super tennis,'' Venus Williams
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
