r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-NBA-COLUMN-LADN     03-27 0823
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THEY WON'T TAKE ANY MORE BULL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Whether it's opposing teams, NBC or fans, the
Chicago Bulls no longer get much respect around the league.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the Bulls played the Atlanta Hawks before 62,000 at
the Georgia Dome. This year, they played the same club before just
more than 8,000 at Georgia Tech.
</P>
<P>
   But even the downtrodden Bulls place boundaries on how much
strong-arming they'll take, and that limit was reached this week in
Charlotte.
</P>
<P>
   The low point occurred when undrafted rookie Brad Miller scored
25 points in a 19-point Hornets victory, and went nuts after a dunk
by doing his ``Herman Munster'' dance down the court.
</P>
<P>
   Bulls forward Mark Bryant took offense, and hit Miller with a
flagrant elbow to the nose that bloodied him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Miller is a young guy and I think he will learn just to go out
and play ball,'' said Bryant, who apparently had a lesson plan
already drawn up. ``All the showboating isn't necessary. He played
extremely well, but being a vet, you can't let somebody make you
look silly.''
</P>
<P>
   ``To be honest, the best play of the night was when Mark fouled
that guy pretty hard,'' Keith Booth said. ``Any time a team is
going to rub it in, you want to set the tone.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bulls weren't the only team giving protocol lessons this
week.
</P>
<P>
   Detroit's Jerome Williams learned this when he stole the ball
from Milwaukee's Michael Curry, who was trying to dribble out the
game's final seconds of the Bucks' 115-86 victory.
</P>
<P>
   Curry shoved Williams in the back, and said his message for the
Detroit forward was, ``Don't try to pad your stats at my expense.''
</P>
<P>
   As if they understood, no teammate came to Williams' aid, when
he recollected himself off the floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I thought there was something that needed to be done, I
would've taken care of it myself,'' said Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Pay cut? Vancouver rookie Mike Bibby exhibited his youthful
innocence with a group of reporters in the America West Arena
locker room before the Grizzlies-Suns game last Monday.
</P>
<P>
   After talking about the rigors of travel, and the continuous
games that take a toll on his legs, Bibby said: ``It's all right.
I'm getting paid more money.''
</P>
<P>
   ``!ital!More money?'' said teammate Shareef Abdur-Rahim, who was
sitting nearby.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did you hear that?'' seven-year pro Tony Massenburg said. ``He
got six-figures in college. He is getting seven now.''
</P>
<P>
   Bibby laughed it off, and shot back to Abdur-Rahim, ``Let's talk
about `Reef' at Cal.'' He then said, ``I'm talking about the per
diem.''
</P>
<P>
   Blow it up: After the Warriors played their last regular-season
game ever at the Sports Arena on Wednesday, Bimbo Coles was told he
wouldn't have to play there anymore (although the teams do have an
exhibition slated there next preseason).
</P>
<P>
   ``Great. They can blow it up if they want,'' Coles said. ``It's
a depressing building. You come in here and there's no energy in
the building, kind of blah. The biggest thing is I'm glad I wasn't
traded here, or I would have had to play here like another 15
games.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the ever-sensitive Clippers brass doesn't mind getting
ripped by a guy named Bimbo.
</P>
<P>
   Expert analysis: Charles Barkley doesn't have much respect for
the Eastern Conference: ``Take Miami and Indiana and Orlando out of
the East and you might as well blow the rest of them up,'' Sir
Charles said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're terrible. We don't even pay attention to the East.
It's a dogfight out here (in the West) every night. Am I surprised?
Yeah, I'm surprised Miami and Indiana aren't 20 games ahead of
everyone else. That's the only thing I'm surprised about. And
Orlando started fast, but they're folding now. So you really have
only two teams over there, and that's it. Two. The West is brutal.
We don't even want to talk about the Eastern Conference, they're so
bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Return of KJ? Veteran point guard Kevin Johnson, who hasn't
played since leaving the Phoenix Suns last season, has informed the
Milwaukee Bucks he is interested in coming out of retirement.
</P>
<P>
   It must have been the drugs: Heat coach Pat Riley dismissed
former Bulls coach Phil Jackson's belief that the champion will be
``tainted'' and the shortened season will not produce a ``real''
champion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still think it's the effects of that window pane that he
took in the '70s,'' Riley said. ``Those synapses don't fire like
they used to. What the hell does he know? He's stumping for Bill
Bradley, he should have no opinion on the NBA.''
</P>
<P>
   Riley, smiling, added: ``I say that all in jest. He would love
it to be tainted because he was the only one who tasted victory the
last six years (actually 6 of 8). He doesn't want to give anybody
credit.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The NBA column appears Sundays in the Daily News. Staff Writer
Scott Wolf can be reached via e-mail at Scwolf1aol.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
