<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-27 22:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6944 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-MAIN-BOS-1ST-L     03-27 1294
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MAIN-BOS-1ST-LEDE-WRITE-THRU </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     US STEALTH FIGHTER DOWNED; PILOT IS RESCUED 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Updates with loss of jet)  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER AND LOUISE D. PALMER AND  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A US F-117A stealth fighter, the most advanced in
the American arsenal, was reported down Saturday night over
Yugoslavia in the first allied loss in four days of punishing
attacks intended to disable Yugoslavia's war-making machine.
Pentagon sources reported that a rescue mission pulled the pilot
out safely from Yugoslav territory.
</P>
<P>
   The downing of what was long considered a virtually invulnerable
warplane occurred as NATO shifted its air war to concentrate
primarily on Serb tanks and troops in the separatist province of
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Serb troops, meanwhile, defied NATO's aerial siege and stepped
up their deadly attacks on ethnic Albanian civilians in Kosovo,
increasing pressure on the Clinton administration and US allies to
consider launching a ground war to halt the atrocities.
</P>
<P>
   The stunning images of a burning plane, first shown on Serbian
TV early Sunday in Yugoslavia, showed tail markings that identified
it as part of a squadron based at Holloman Air Force Base in New
Mexico. Pentagon officials confirmed the loss of the plane but gave
no indication what brought it down. There was no further
information on the rescue of the pilot, CNN quoted Pentagon
officials as saying.
</P>
<P>
   Stealth fighters, which served with distinction in the Gulf War,
had crashed before because of pilot error or mechanical problems,
but never in combat. Serbian TV said this plane crashed west of the
Yugoslav capital of Belgrade, near the Bosnia border.
</P>
<P>
   There had been pressure to expand the targets and geographical
reach of the air war to a riskier phase to try to stop the Serb
killings of ethnic Albanians in Kosovo. A NATO official warned that
``dark things are happening'' in Kosovo, including reports of Serb
forces murdering members of the ethnic Albanian leadership,
rounding up and killing military-age men, and bombing and burning
villages.
</P>
<P>
   The developments occurred amid growing pleas from ethnic
Albanians in Kosovo for NATO troops to fight Serb security forces
on the ground, and US officials confronted the public's enduring
reluctance since the Vietnam War to commit US soldiers to foreign
wars. ``We welcome the strikes, but we demand that NATO ground
troops come into Kosovo as quickly as possible,'' said a spokesman
for the Kosovo Liberation Army, which is fighting for autonomy for
ethnic Albanians who represent about 90 percent of the province's
population.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton said last week he had no plans to send combat
troops to Kosovo, and officials at the White House and Pentagon
Saturday reiterated his position.
</P>
<P>
   In his weekly radio address, Clinton called for NATO ``to stay
the course'' in order ``to defuse a powder keg at the heart of
Europe.'' Clinton made no reference to the potential for US
involvement in a ground war. But in a letter to congressional
leaders that was released Friday night, he said he had dispatched
100 Marines to defend the US Embassy in neighboring Macedonia, and
he raised the possibility of sending an unspecified number of
additional troops to conduct operations such as combat search and
rescue, intelligence support, surveillance, and reconnaissance in
the region.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sound military planning may also call for sending a limited
number of additional US military personnel to Macedonia in support
of ongoing operations,'' Clinton said in the letter. Although he
expressed confidence Saturday in the outcome of the NATO operation,
he reported no progress in curbing the alleged Serb war crimes. In
fact, Clinton said, ``Serb troops have continued attacks on unarmed
men, women, and children.''
</P>
<P>
   British Defense Secretary George Robertson provided a bleaker
assessment. ``There are clear signs now that an all-out Serbian
offensive against the Kosovo Albanian people has started and
violence is widespread,'' Robertson said. ``The Serbs are
bombarding villages to the point of obliteration.''
</P>
<P>
   Amid the brutality, thousands of Kosavars continued to flee to
neighboring countries. More than 250,000 people already have been
displaced, and the State Department Saturday projected that more
than 500,000 could be driven from their homes in the conflict.
Human rights groups reported that a Kosovo political nerve center
was burned down, as was a food warehouse operated by the Mother
Teresa organization.
</P>
<P>
   NATO Secretary General Javier Solana, in forgoing ground troops,
ordered allied military forces to expand their attack by targeting
the Serb operation in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The strategy could place NATO pilots at greater risk because the
jets and helicopters will be required to fly closer to the ground
to hit tanks, artillery, and mobile command posts.
</P>
<P>
   But the decision to begin the assault, dubbed Phase Two of
Operation Allied Force, was seen as an indication that NATO leaders
are confident the first stage of the attack crippled much of
Yugoslavia's air defense system and command and control facilities.
In Aviano, Italy, US combat pilots, speaking to reporters for the
first time since the operation began, expressed surprise at the
minimal opposition they have encountered. ``We have not seen
anywhere near the amount of aircraft weaponry employed that we
thought we would see,'' said one Navy pilot, who was not permitted
to identify himself.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton signed off Saturday on the second phase of the operation
after meeting at the White House with his foreign policy advisers
and speaking with British, French, and German leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Solana gave the order to the supreme allied commander, US Army
General Wesley Clark. ``I have taken this decision with the support
of all allied governments, which are determined to bring a halt to
violence in Kosovo and prevent further humanitarian catastrophe,''
Solana said.
</P>
<P>
   NATO officials said warplanes and cruise missiles will continue
to strike military targets throughout Yugoslavia as part of the
effort to force Milosevic to accept a peace agreement that grants
autonomy to the ethnic Albanians in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   In massive raids Friday night and early Saturday, NATO aircraft
flew 249 sorties, and Tomahawk cruise missiles were seen soaring
across the Belgrade skyline before they detonated. Serbian state
radio reported that NATO missiles and bombs destroyed a military
barracks, a munitions dump, and a telecommunications site. New
attacks began late Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time since the strikes began, Serbian television
also reported that nonmilitary targets were hit, including a
factory and a pharmaceutical plant on the outskirts of Belgrade.
NATO officials denied those reports.
</P>
<P>
   Crowds also demonstrated outside embassies in Berlin, Rome,
Athens, Vienna, and London. Some protesters clashed with police.
Others hurled objects at the embassies of NATO nations. And some
burned US flags and shouted anti-American slogans.
</P>
<P>
   Disagreement over the NATO mission also festered among US
political leaders. Delivering the Republican weekly radio address,
Senator John Ashcroft of Missouri said the Clinton administration
had yet to articulate a clear plan for the mission.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our duty obligates us to demand a clearly focused mission for
our soldiers,'' Ashcroft said. ``They deserve the complete
commitment of every American and the certain leadership of the
commander-in-chief.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, in his radio speech, said maintaining peace in Europe
is a vital US interest. ``Through two World Wars and a long Cold
War, we saw that it was a short step from a small brushfire to an
inferno, especially in the tinderbox of the Balkans.''
</P>
</TEXT>
