<SLUG> BC-HKN-ISLES-SENATORS-375&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE ASCENDING SENATORS CRUSH THE DESCENDING ISLANDERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By TARIK EL-BASHIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNIONDALE, N.Y. _ Ted Donato's stay on Long Island was brief _
just five months _ but that was enough time for him to form strong
opinions on the New York Islanders' sad situation.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest problem? There has been too much player turnover,
Donato said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've made a lot of moves over the last three years, so
there's not a lot of stability,'' said Donato, who last Saturday
was dealt to the Ottawa Senators for a fourth-round draft pick,
another player affected by the Islanders' salary dumping. ``People
look at the team and say, `Where's it going?' That's the problem
they have.''
</P>
<P>
   Donato returned to Nassau Coliseum Saturday night and scored
Ottawa's second goal as the Eastern Conference-leading Senators
embarrassed the Islanders, 7-3, in front of 11,491 fans. The
Islanders are 0-11-3 in their last 14 games against the Senators.
</P>
<P>
   Zigmund Palffy, Joe Sacco and Zdeno Chara scored for the
Islanders. Wade Flaherty made 29 saves for New York. Marian Hossa
(twice), Donato, Radek Bonk, Aleskei Yashin (twice) and Andreas
Dackell scored for Ottawa. Ron Tugnutt made 20 saves for the
Senators.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at the Senators,'' said Donato, a left wing who
underachieved in 55 games as an Islander (seven goals, 11 assists)
after coming from Boston in a trade last November. ``Ottawa has a
lot of young, talented players. Guys like Radek Bonk and Wade
Redden _ guys they've stayed with. And now they are starting to
reap the benefits. Now, they have the opportunity to be good, not
for one or two years, but for a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   The Islanders and the Senators were in similar positions three
years ago. They built young, talented teams through heady draft
choices. Both teams were full of potential, it seemed. But since
then, the teams have gone in opposite directions.
</P>
<P>
   The Senators were patient with their young players. They
nurtured them, let them grow together and learned to win together.
Now they are legitimate contenders.
</P>
<P>
   The Islanders were not patient. Mike Milbury, the Islanders'
general manager, went for quick fixes, and that has got the team
into the predicament it finds itself in today. The Islanders are
the second-worst team in the National Hockey League, a hodgepodge
of veterans, journeymen and leftovers.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   At one time, the Islanders had Bryan Berard, one of the most
exciting puck-rushing defensemen in the game, but he was traded to
Toronto for goalie Felix Potvin this season. They had Bryan McCabe
and Todd Bertuzzi, but they were traded to Vancouver for Trevor
Linden.
</P>
<P>
   Some would argue that Berard, McCabe and Bertuzzi are not as
talented as the Senators' young players _ Yashin, Dackell, Shawn
McEachern, Magnus Arvedson and Jason York _ but they were talented
enough to build a team around.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't here long enough to understand the whole dynamic of
what was going on here with ownership and management,'' Donato
said. ``I didn't have an understanding of the direction things were
going in. Having said that, there are probably guys here that have
been around for a while and don't understand what direction the
team is going in either.''
</P>
<P>
   There are also external forces, like ownership problems and
difficulties getting a new arena, that are dragging down the
Islanders, Donato acknowledged.
</P>
<P>
   ``They need a new building,'' he said. ``I think the people on
Long Island deserve it. A new building would show, `Hey we're
serious and we're going to be successful.'''
</P>
<P>
   As for the new life last week's trade has given him, Donato
said: ``It's the best situation to go somewhere everybody's upbeat
and positive. This is a real fun time of year. Unfortunately, when
you're not going to the playoffs, like the Islanders, it's not fun.
So this is a great opportunity for me. It's a breath of fresh
air.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
