<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-27 22:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6947 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-DODGERS-JOHNSON-L     03-27 1545
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-JOHNSON-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS' JOHNSON DOES IT HIS WAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   VERO BEACH, Fla. _ Davey Johnson wanted to fish, play golf and
live a normal life, which he did after walking out on $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   After a year, however, he realized something was missing.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson needed baseball. He spent part of last year scouting
Ireland and Scotland for a Japanese team, but it wasn't enough. He
is a baseball lifer. He needed Major League Baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I probably would have taken any job,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   But not just anyone would take (begin ital)him(end ital).
</P>
<P>
   Johnson has always won, but that doesn't mean he'll always find
a job. He finished first with the Mets twice and won a World
Series, then spent two years without a manager's job.
</P>
<P>
   He won in Baltimore, making the playoffs both years, only to
leave the same day he was named the American League's Manager of
the Year. He didn't manage the next season.
</P>
<P>
   Even the Dodgers did not want him. Not at first.
</P>
<P>
   General manager Kevin Malone enticed Felipe Alou into
considering the position only to have the Montreal Expos skipper
remain in Canada. Then, and only then, did the Dodgers pursue
Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't take much convincing on the Dodgers' part.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson doesn't care that he was the second choice. What matters
to Johnson is he was the right choice. Just ask him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's a lot of managers who would not have been as
prepared to handle this job as me, having managed in a major
market,'' said Johnson, alluding to his stint with the Mets. ``It's
a job, I think, for an experienced manager.''
</P>
<P>
   That is the quintessential Davey Johnson. His confidence borders
on cockiness, but there is much truth to it.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I take a job, it's my job to solve the problems,''
Johnson said. ``It's my job to make sure there are no major
problems for the organization, for the general manager. That's what
I have to do. Basically, the challenge for me is to do the little
things that make the difference between winning and losing.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson is all about the little things. He's about moving
runners over, about hitting to the opposite field. He's about
manipulating a bullpen, and sometimes his players. He is not about
the superstars because they will take care of themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson is detail-oriented but not obsessive. He isn't in his
office examining flow charts of every player, nor is he looking at
matchups to find out what his third baseman hits during Monday
afternoon games on artificial turf.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson's a baseball man with a mathematician's degree, a
combination that allows him to play the numbers game better than
most managers. He's a thinker, but he doesn't get caught up in
documenting everything.
</P>
<P>
   He might not sleep at the ballpark, he might not study film all
night, but he's always thinking baseball. Always.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's very complex,'' Malone said. ``With what he's
been through, the experiences he's had, the opportunities, the
success, I would say there's a lot of complexity to him. I would
say that's a strength.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of people not being able to read him, or understand him
or misunderstand him, has probably been advantageous for him. They
may miscalculate his strengths and therefore he beats you.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Johnson way
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Johnson beats you. He wins his way. He loses his way. And
when the time comes he'll bow out, making you think it was his way.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson solicits the input of his coaching staff and his general
manager. He consults his players about potential decisions.
</P>
<P>
   But when it comes to making a decision, Johnson has the final
say.
</P>
<P>
   ``Baseball, and decisions in baseball, are not made by a
committee,'' Johnson said. ``It's like anything else. You listen to
everybody, you delegate authority and you're able to look at more
areas, the whole picture. You get input from everybody you can to
make the best possible decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're going to make a decision on a pitcher, you don't
want to ask your pitching coach because you're liable to get in a
tie. Now, you have a tie, a deadlock, so you do nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson's also called a player's manager, though it doesn't mean
the players are running the clubhouse. It means Johnson gives you
his trust, until he sees fit to take it away.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're responsible enough to take care of your business,
he'll let you do it,'' first baseman Eric Karros said. ``Guys are
given their freedom to be responsible for themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said he's always been that way, even when he was
managing in the minor leagues _ where, of course, he won. Three
years of minor-league managing produced a pair of first-place
finishes, and he carried his approach to the Mets. In his first
year, 1984, he took a downtrodden Mets franchise and gave them
credibility by finishing second. Johnson won 90 games for the first
of six times. And during those Mets years an impressionable
teen-ager was hanging around the clubhouse. It was Gary Sheffield,
the nephew of pitcher Doc Gooden.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've gotten to learn about the game from watching the Mets
play the game when he was winning there,'' said Sheffield, now
Johnson's left fielder in Los Angeles. ``He's a fierce competitor.
He communicates well. He talks to you after every at-bat. He's
involved.''
</P>
<P>
   In the 10 full seasons Johnson has managed in the big leagues,
he's never finished below second place. Among active managers,
Johnson's .575 winning percentage (985-727) is the best.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson won the 1986 World Series title with the Mets and has
won five division titles.
</P>
<P>
   He wins, but not many people can figure out why or how.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if anyone can put a finger on it, as to why he
wins so much,'' Baltimore Orioles pitcher Mike Mussina said. ``I
really didn't deal with him much. A pitcher's relationship with the
manager is much different than a pitcher and pitching coach. About
the only time I dealt with him was (on the pitcher's mound during
games). But I know he wins.''
</P>
<P>
   Malone didn't fully understand Johnson's managerial skills until
the two were united in Baltimore. Malone quickly learned.
</P>
<P>
   ``He knows how to rest veterans when they need a day off, he
knows how to utilize his bench,'' Malone said. ``He knows how to
utilize his bullpen and he knows when to take the starters out. He
knows how to get matchups he wants. I don't think you can be as
successful as he has been without being well-rounded and strong in
a lot of areas.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The flip side
</P>
<P>
   But with Johnson's winning comes his reputation for rubbing
owners the wrong way.
</P>
<P>
   With the Mets, Johnson's relationship with the front office
deteriorated rapidly. It happened right after Gary Carter and Keith
Hernandez ended their Mets careers.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets and Johnson parted less than two months into the 1990
season. The Mets haven't been to the playoffs since.
</P>
<P>
   It took Johnson, the winningest manager in Mets history
(595-417), nearly three years to land another managerial job. He
ended up in Cincinnati with owner Marge Schott in a relationship
doomed from the moment Schott's St. Bernard ran onto the Riverfront
Stadium carpet.
</P>
<P>
   But Johnson, who took over for Tony Perez in late May, won
division titles in his two full seasons with the Reds. At the close
of the second division championship, which culminated with an
Atlanta Braves sweep in the National League Championship Series,
Johnson left the Reds quietly so Ray Knight could take over.
</P>
<P>
   Schott didn't like the fact Johnson was living with his
girlfriend, who is now his wife.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my opinion he's the best manager in baseball at running a
pitching staff,'' said Cincinnati general manager Jim Bowden, who
hired Johnson with the Reds. ``(Schott) wanted to fire him. I
respect ownership. You have to have loyalty. But he is a phenomenal
baseball manager.''
</P>
<P>
   True to form, Johnson wound up with another team, the Baltimore
Orioles, who were looking for a playoff appearance. That lasted two
seasons before public feuding with owner Peter Angelos forced
Johnson to think again about golf courses instead of baseball
diamonds.
</P>
<P>
   With the Orioles, Johnson won 186 games. And if not for an
overzealous kid in Yankee Stadium's right-field seats in the
American League Championship Series, the 1996 Orioles might have
reached the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   Yet no managing offers came his way. Not until Alou said no
thanks.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson's detractors point out that along with Johnson's
victories come his problems.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the reason Johnson ruffles management is because he is
honest and strong-willed. Most owners are not willing to be told
how things should be done.
</P>
<P>
   So Johnson moves on. He leaves because he knows only one way to
do it, his way. Besides, it works. It has worked for nearly two
decades at every level.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson is 56 and is with his fourth organization in nine years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always a challenge, and I like challenges. I think
challenges are the spice of life,'' Johnson said. ``I think this is
a challenge here. I hope this is my last job. I admire and respect
a lot of people in this organization, being here. Where do you go
from here? I would say this is going to be it for me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
