<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-DUKE-MICHST28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Duke holds off Michigan State
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ If ever Duke, the seemingly-invincible
team , looked vunerable and ripe for the taking, it was at the 8:33
mark of Saturday night's Final Four semifinal with Michigan State.
</P>
<P>
   Elton Brand, the All-American center who had been dominating the
game, was on the bench with four fouls. Michigan State's Charlie
Bell had just sank a pair of free throws to bring the Spartans to
within three points, 51-48.
</P>
<P>
   Duke was missing its free throws and looking a little uncertain.
A crowd of 41,340 buzzed with the possibility of one of the NCAA
tournament's most monumental upsets.
</P>
<P>
   But at that moment, guard Trajan Langdon showed why they call
him the ``Alaskan Assassin.''
</P>
<P>
   With the pressure of a season of great expectations on the line,
the senior from Anchorage sank a a 3-point shot to put the Blue
Devils up by six. The shot appeared to have a calming effect on
Duke, which went on to win 68-62 and advance to Monday night's
championship game with UConn.
</P>
<P>
   Duke (37-1) has now won 32 straight games dating back to
November 28. The Blue Devils will be going for their first national
championship since 1992 and their third this decade.
</P>
<P>
   Brand, the national player of the year, finished the game with
18 points and 15 rebounds. Augusta's William Avery had 14 points.
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Devils held Mateen Cleaves, Michigan State's
All-American guard, to only five of 16 shots from the field and 12
points.
</P>
<P>
   Up 12, 32-20, at halftime, Duke threatened to run away from
Michigan State in the opening minutes of the second half when
Avery's basket put the Blue Devils up by 14.
</P>
<P>
   But the Midwest Regional champions would not go away, fighting
back to close the gap to four, 43-39, on Thomas Kelley's layup with
13:29 remaining.
</P>
<P>
   Duke got five straight points from Brand to go up by seven,
48-41, with 12:34 left. But then Brand had to go to the bench after
commiting his third foul with 12:04 remaining.
</P>
<P>
   Brand came back after a TV timeout at the 11:12 mark, but then
picked up his fourth foul on a charging call with 10:12 left. Duke
led 50-44.
</P>
<P>
   Even after Langdon's big shot, Michigan State climbed back to
within four, 54-50, with 7:09 left. Avery then provided the
heroics, scoring five straight points to put the Blue Devils up by
nine, 59-50, with 6:14 left.
</P>
<P>
   Brand finally came back with 4:44 remaining and Duke holding a
seven-point lead. The Blue Devils had weathered the storm.
</P>
<P>
   Duke jumped out to a 12-point lead, at halftime behind the sheer
power of Brand, who outmuscled the Michigan State front line for
eight points and 13 rebounds in the first 20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   While Brand was controlling things inside, Duke's perimeter
defense was holding the Spartans to nine-for-31 shooting (29
percent). Cleaves hit only one of his four first-half shots.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
