<HEADER>
A6951 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-NETS-CAVALIERS-40     03-27 0767
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NETS-CAVALIERS-400&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VAN HORN SITS OUT ANOTHER NETS LOSS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By CHRIS BROUSSARD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ With their best frontcourt player
cheering from the sideline ina slick three-button suit, the New
Jersey Nets turned in what may have been their most inspiring
performance of the season Saturday night at Continental Arena.
Keith Van Horn, his sprained right ankle too tender to play,
watched as a Nets lineup that included his new and unheralded
teammates, Jamie Feick and Mark Hendrickson, pushed the Cleveland
Cavaliers to the brink before losing, 109-99.
</P>
<P>
   With their great preseason expectations having drowned beneath
the rush of a 5-23 record, the Nets cannot be satisfied with a
moral victory, but they should receive a little consolation in this
one.
</P>
<P>
   The Nets rallied from deficits of 13 points in the second
quarter and 10 points in the third to take an 84-82 lead on a
3-pointer by Stephon Marbury two and a half minutes into the final
period. It was nip and tuck for the next four minutes, but
consecutive 3-pointers by the Cavaliers and three monumental
turnovers by the Nets ended the suspense.
</P>
<P>
   After Jayson Williams answered a 3-pointer by Derek Anderson
with a layup to pull the Nets within 92-91, Johnny Newman sank
another 3-pointer to give Cleveland some space with 5 minutes 26
seconds left. Chris Carr, who had 19 points and nine rebounds in
his second start at small forward, turned the ball over on the
Nets' ensuing possession, and after Corie Blount scored to make it
97-91, Williams had the ball yanked away from him by Shawn Kemp.
</P>
<P>
   Fouled on the other end, Kemp hit a free throw to put the
Cavaliers ahead by 98-91, and then Kerry Kittles turned the ball
over. Brevin Knight, Cleveland's point guard from nearby East
Orange, N.J., sealed the Nets' fate by hitting an 18-foot jumper to
make it 100-91 with three minutes remaining.
</P>
<P>
   Marbury, hitting four 3-pointers for the second straight game,
led the Nets with 26 points and six assists. Williams followed with
16 points and 11 rebounds, and Feick, a 6-foot-8-inch forward who
started in Van Horn's spot, had 12 points and 11 rebounds. The Nets
shot a season-high 47.4 percent from the field.
</P>
<P>
   Kemp led the Cavaliers, who made 30 of 45 free throws, with 26
points, including 12 from the free-throw line, and Knight had 17
points to help lift Cleveland (14-12) to its third victory in three
games with the Nets this season.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Van Horn wanted desperately to play. He warmed up on his heavily
taped ankle but, realizing his attempt was futile, he stopped
moments before the game. The loss of his roughly 20 points a game
would seem to have doomed the Nets, but his teammates responded
well to playing without their lead man.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, who is averaging only 7.4 points, was impressive in
the first half, making 5-of-6 shots to score 11 points. A limited
player offensively, Williams reached deep into a bag of moves that
few knew he had and scored on jump shots, driving layups and one
running hook.
</P>
<P>
   Before the game, Williams did not want to accept that his
favorite teammate would not play. But when it was decided that Van
Horn would not go, he knew his game would have to change. ``I've
got to score the ball Saturday night, I guess,'' Williams said
before the game. ``I have to be a post presence. We're going to try
to post up Stephon and work through him, and I'll have to be more
offensive-minded as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Taking a page from the playbook of the Indiana Pacers, who
posted their burly point guard Mark Jackson in defeating the Nets
on Friday, the Nets sent Marbury down to the block. The 6-2 point
guard was supposed to post Cleveland's Knight, who is 5-9, but
playing with his back to the basket is not one of Marbury's
strengths.
</P>
<P>
   Late in the first quarter, Coach Don Casey scrapped that game
plan and let Marbury return to the perimeter, where he drilled two
3-pointers to help the Nets stay in the game. Strangely, offense
was not a problem before intermission, as the Nets shot 52.5
percent and were remarkably in sync with the newcomers Feick and
Mark Hendrickson getting a good deal of playing time.
</P>
<P>
   Defense, however, was another issue. Cleveland, always among the
league's lowest scoring teams, ran up 59 first-half points. Kemp
used his girth to draw fouls and hit free throws to score 10.
Wesley Person sank jumpers in adding another 10 points, and Knight
overwhelmed Marbury numerous times on his way to 11 first-half
points.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
