<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RODMAN IS LEAST OF LAKERS' WOES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Dennis Rodman wouldn't explain himself to
reporters, so we can only imagine why that reboundin' fool showed
up too late to practice with the Lakers on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe he just hates to be around guys who can't get their act
together.
</P>
<P>
   Rodman's shenanigans might be the team's most spectacular
problem, but he's far from the only headache for the team that
suddenly has lost back-to-back games at the Forum and five out of
eight overall.
</P>
<P>
   Things have gone haywire since a 10-game winning streak got
everybody's hopes up, so haywire that general manager Mitch Kupchak
said during the practice at L.A. Southwest College, ``To some
degree, (Rodman's unpredictability) is a `constant.' ''
</P>
<P>
   He was half-joking, more or less.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't Rodman's fault the Lakers lost an eight-point lead
against the .500 team from Phoenix Wednesday night. It wasn't
Rodman's fault the Lakers lost a 19-point lead against the .429
team from Sacramento Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   His latest lateness _ a day after he mysteriously sat out the
fourth quarter against Sacramento _ forced Rodman and his (begin
ital)tres(end ital) -Hollywood agent to hold half-hour chats with
Kupchak and coach Kurt Rambis. Which is bad because it took time
away from straightening out everything else:
</P>
<P>
   The `F' in `D': The Lakers' defense failed completely in the
third quarter Friday, when Sacramento scored 40 points _ 22 on
shots in the paint _ making Corliss Williamson look like George
McGinnis.
</P>
<P>
   How else could the Lakers lose a game in which they scored 109
points, shot 54 percent, had their highest assist total (29) in a
month and led by six in rebounds?
</P>
<P>
   ``Defense isn't skill. Defense is hard work and a mindset,''
guard Derek Harper said. ``We need to make defense a priority.''
</P>
<P>
   The March 10 trade that brought Glen Rice and J.R. Reid to Los
Angeles, and sent Eddie Jones and Elden Campbell to Charlotte, cost
the Lakers their best defensive player. Only Harper, Rodman and
Robert Horry are noted for defense. Might the team be ill-equipped
to defend however hard it tries?
</P>
<P>
   ``No. You can play defense if Kevin is out there, if Mark is out
there, if Howard is out there, if Tim is out there,'' Harper said,
naming the reporters in front of him. ``Anybody can play defense.''
</P>
<P>
   He's never seen us play, but we get the point.
</P>
<P>
   Complacency: Maybe having the league's best center, best outside
shooter, best rebounder and hottest 20-year-old guarantees nothing.
</P>
<P>
   (begin ital)Now(end ital) they hit the low point of the season?
</P>
<P>
   ``Anytime we get a big lead, we have a tendency to free-lance,''
Horry said after the Lakers lost the 19-point lead to Sacramento.
``It's not just us doing it, a lot of teams do it.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we want to be a championship team, we have to play defense
24/7.''
</P>
<P>
   That's 24 hours, seven days a week, not 24 minutes off, seven
minutes on.
</P>
<P>
   Cold Rice: Rice might be rusty, but he's also having to work too
hard to get his shots. He was 5 for 12 against Phoenix, and was 3
for 7 before four jumpers in the last 3{ minutes against Sacramento
revived the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   Rice, like Jones before him, doesn't always seem to be part of
the offense. Will that improve with time? Or is this proof that
with Bryant and Shaquille O'Neal dominating the shots column,
three's a crowd?
</P>
<P>
   Name tags: They have a new head coach, a new assistant, new
starters at four positions and a 50 percent roster turnover since
losing the Western Conference championship series last May. And
they've had only one break as long as two days between games to get
used to each other in practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't be surprised if these guys are a little
shell-shocked,'' Kupchak said.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers are 4-5 since the Rice trade. Meanwhile, Charlotte is
6-3.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, those stats can be misleading, or how do you explain
Cleveland being 5-1 since signing ex-Laker Corie Blount?
</P>
<P>
   Rambis must be shell-shocked, since he's been on the job a month
and is still surprised how much an NBA head coach has to do (all
those interviews!).
</P>
<P>
   His first elective lineup change, starting Rodman over Travis
Knight at forward, blew up on Rambis Friday when the Lakers were
outscored 16-10 to open the game.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was the byplay with Rodman, who apparently refused to
re-enter the game, claiming his 38-year-old legs stiffened during a
long second-half sit.
</P>
<P>
   Rambis indicated the problem was dealt with ``to my
satisfaction'' when the coach and player met behind a closed door
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Good for him, because there are other problems to solve. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-27-99 2308EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
