u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-UPDATE1STLD-HN     03-27 1167
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-UPDATE1STLD-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
U.S. PLANE DOWNED IN YUGOSLAVIA BUT PILOT IS RESCUED
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By GREG McDONALD &QL;
</P>
<P>
   c. 1999 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A U.S. stealth fighter plane went down Saturday
near Belgrade as the NATO alliance broadened its targets to include
Serb troops, tanks and artillery in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   A U.S. military search and rescue team found and rescued the
pilot of the U.S. F-117A Nighthawk stealth fighter, the Pentagon
said. Officials would not confirm what caused the plane to crash.
But Yugoslavian television reported that the stealth fighter had
been brought down by Serb air-to-ground missiles about 30 miles
west of the Yugoslavian capital.
</P>
<P>
   The television footage aired in Belgrade and over CNN showing
the wreckage of the burning plane and identified it as part of the
8th Fighter Squadron out of Holloman Air Force Base in New Mexico.
The identifying marks ``AF 806'' and ``Air Combat Command'' could
be seen on the wreckage.
</P>
<P>
   The television report said two other NATO aircraft also had been
shot down and German crewmen captured. German authorities disputed
that account.
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon and NATO officials cautioned that the Belgrade
government ``is a master at propaganda,'' as one spokesman put it.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. radar-evading stealth fighter is one of the most
sophisticated aircraft in the U.S. arsenal. It was bombing targets
in Yugoslavia on the fourth day of the allied air assault.
</P>
<P>
   Stealth planes based at Holloman have been flying from Aviano
Air Base in Italy as part of the NATO offensive.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, reports of ethnic Albanian villages being razed and
civilians being executed by the Yugoslav army and security police
continued to filter out of Kosovo, heightening the concern of
Western leaders that thousands of people may have been slaughtered
since the allied offensive began on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at NATO headquarters in Brussels said the expanded and
more pointed NATO attacks on military positions inside Kosovo are
aimed at trying to stop what one alliance aide described as the
``systemic and organized campaign'' by the Serbian-dominated
Belgrade government to wipe out the predominantly Albanian
population of the separatist province.
</P>
<P>
   At the White House, President Clinton used his weekly radio
address to call attention to the ``brutal military offensive'' he
said is being carried out by the forces of Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic. He urged Americans to continue to support the
NATO operation designed to force Milosevic to accept a peace
agreement on Kosovo that Albanian separatists have already signed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Serb troops have continued attacks on unarmed men, women and
children. That is all the more reason for us to stay the course,''
Clinton said. ``We must, and we will continue until Milosevic
accepts peace or we have seriously damaged his capacity to make
war.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We asked these people of Kosovo to accept peace, and they did.
We cannot let them down now,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   The intensified allied air campaign began shortly after NATO
Secretary General Javier Solana gave the order to U.S. Gen. Wesley
Clark, the alliance's supreme commander, to ``initiate a broader
range of air operations'' directed specifically at troops and
weapons inside Kosovo. The order came after Clinton conferred with
British Prime Minister Tony Blair and other allied government
leaders by telephone. All agreed, said one U.S. official here, that
it was ``time to start putting it to (Milosevic's) forces on the
ground in Kosovo that are carrying out the killing.''
</P>
<P>
   NATO officials in Brussels said the broader attack would include
strikes at tanks and other heavy weapons, army and police command
posts, supply depots and other facilities that provide back up to
the Serb troops.
</P>
<P>
   But they emphasized that there were no plans to commit any NATO
ground forces to Kosovo. That position was stressed as well by
administration officials here and by British Foreign Secretary
Robin Cook.
</P>
<P>
   ``The United States has no intention of sending ground troops to
fight in Kosovo, and the Department of Defense is not doing any
planning that would enable such a deployment,'' said Pentagon
spokesman Kenneth Bacon.
</P>
<P>
   Cook also shot down the idea of sending in ground troops to help
stop what he said was an ongoing ``spring offensive'' by Serb
forces that Milosevic had been planning for months.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not have the intention of committing ground troops,''
Cook said in an interview with CNN, adding that it would take
several months to assemble a force in the area large enough ``to
fight its way in.''
</P>
<P>
   Cook used the interview to warn Milosevic that he would be held
accountable as ``a war criminal'' for the killing in Kosovo when
the NATO operation dubbed Allied Force is brought to an end.
</P>
<P>
   As NATO moved into what it called a more intensified phase of
the bombing campaign, air raid sirens sounded across Yugoslavia to
indicate the approach of allied aircraft and of Tomahawk cruise
missiles fired from a U.S. warship in the Adriatic. The Milosevic
government called for calm, telling people that the strikes were
being directed at military targets only.
</P>
<P>
   Although NATO officials said that the bombing and missile
strikes Saturday night would be concentrated more and more on Serb
forces in Kosovo, they stressed that Yugoslavia's extensive air
defense system would still be hit as well.
</P>
<P>
   Allied commanders have given few details about the extent of
damage inflicted on the Yugoslavian military, but they said
Milosevic's air defenses had been severely hurt.
</P>
<P>
   Before Saturday, U.S. pilots returning from bomb runs to the
Aviano air base in Italy reported little resistance from the Serb
air defense systems. They speculated that most of them had either
been taken out or were being held back for use later when NATO
planes begin coming in ``lower and slower,'' as one pilot put it,
to make more precise hits on targets.
</P>
<P>
   On the diplomatic front Saturday, Milosevic rejected a plea from
leaders of neighboring states who met with him in Belgrade to press
the case for a peaceful settlement. But the Yugoslav dictator said
his country would never accept a peace plan that allows NATO
peacekeeping forces into Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``The citizens of Yugoslavia are unanimous in their resolve not
to allow, at any cost, the enemies to occupy their country,'' he
said in the statement.
</P>
<P>
   Some foreign diplomats reported that Milosevic had been pleased
to see reports of anti-American and anti-NATO demonstrations across
Europe in recent days, including demonstrations and assaults on
Saturday outside various embassies in London, Rome, Berlin, Athens
and Vienna. Some demonstrators clashed with police, burned U.S.
flags and shouted anti-American slogans.
</P>
<P>
   The diplomats also suggested that a statement of support sent to
him from Russian President Boris Yeltsin had only reinforced his
resolve not to give in to NATO demands.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
