<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-JEFF-GORDON-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOUR FRIENDLY NEIGHBORHOOD SUPERSTAR IS A REGULAR JEFF
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN LYONS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ He is the Michael Jordan of his sport.
</P>
<P>
   At times, however, Jeff Gordon might as well be named Jeff
Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon has the big bucks, the cool shades and the handsome-
movie-star smile. But with the fan-friendly atmosphere of NASCAR,
Gordon, 27, is at times as relatively accessible as your next-door
neighbor. Any Joe Jordan off the street _ with proper credentials,
of course _ could walk into the garage area at Texas Motor Speedway
and shake hands with his favorite driver.
</P>
<P>
   Some Regular Joes have done just that this weekend. And the
hospitable Gordon, who has won three of the past four Winston Cup
points titles and has become the sport's pop icon, tries to
accommodate their wishes, shaking as many hands and signing as many
autographs as time allows.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon, who wears his wedding ring while driving, represents
``The Good Guy'' for many of his fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like Jeff because he seems to be a real good family man and
he is down to earth,'' said Mike Swanson, 40, of Dallas, who had
one of the special passes that allow fans to get near Gordon's
garage area. ``He doesn't blow off people who want autographs. He
tries to make time for people.''
</P>
<P>
   It has been tough for Gordon to make time this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   He'll start eighth in today's Primestar 500 Winston Cup race. He
finished 13th in yesterday's rain-shortened Coca-Cola 300 Busch
Grand National race. He ran in the Busch series to get more time on
a track where he wrecked while running in the Winston Cup races in
1998 (finishing 31st) and 1997 (30th).
</P>
<P>
   All of the practices and qualifying have made for a taxing week.
On Friday, after a 55-minute practice for the Busch race in his No.
24 Pepsi Chevrolet, Gordon ran to his No. 24 DuPont Automotive
Finishes Chevy to begin preparations for today's Winston Cup race.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes for a long weekend and it's hard work, but I enjoy it
_ I'm having fun with it,'' Gordon said.
</P>
<P>
   So is Eddie Gossage, the vice president and general manager of
TMS. Yesterday's race was one of only five Busch events that Gordon
plans to compete in this year. With today's Primestar 500, that
means racing fans will have two chances to see Gordon. And that,
Gossage said, translates into more respect for the track and more
revenue for TMS.
</P>
<P>
   ``In terms of ticket sales, we are already 16,000 ahead \Rafter
the Busch race\S of where we were this time last year,'' Gossage
said. ``We sell our stars, and that's why the ticket sales are
ahead, and part of that is because of Jeff Gordon.''
</P>
<P>
   The TMS people have not had to do much to sell Gordon. The
people around him have done quite a job. He wrote his autobiography
in 1997. Earlier this month, he was on the cover of ``Fortune'' and
``ESPN The Magazine''.
</P>
<P>
   In the coming weeks he is to be featured in ``Esquire'' and on
the CBS program ``60 Minutes II''. He makes 40 two-hour appearances
for his sponsors, which include DuPont Automotive Finishes, Pepsi,
Quaker State, Chevrolet, and Close-Up toothpaste. Of the 125 media
requests that he gets a week, he has time for just five. His
likeness is on billboards touting a youth magazine, soft drinks and
milk.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jeff is great with people, and he doesn't complain about being
a star or the position he is in,'' said Charles Hudson, a
public-relations official for the DuPont side of Gordon's marketing
team. ``He knows that what he does helps the sport of racing, and
it helps his sponsors. But he is genuine. The way you see him in
the media or with his sponsors is the same way that you see him
when he's just sitting around off-camera drinking a soda.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon is widely acknowledged as one of the biggest reasons for
the increased popularity of NASCAR.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has changed a lot of things, brought a huge awareness to
the sport,'' said Dale Jarrett, who has finished third, second and
third in the points races the past three years. ``We've always had
the crowd base from 25-65, but Jeff has brought the younger crowd,
10 years old and up. It is important for the sport that we get fans
at a young age because that'll give us fan support for a long time.
And then, you have kids much younger who want to be race drivers.''
</P>
<P>
   Three-time NASCAR points champion Darrell Waltrip recalled that
he won nearly $875,000 in 1982 when he won his second Cup title.
Gordon earned more than $9 million last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other day, I asked him for change for a hundred,'' Waltrip
said of Gordon. ``He said, `That ``is'' change.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Things are different now, and he's a big reason.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
