<HEADLINE>
USC'S ABDUL-MALIK MAKES MOVE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ USC defensive end Sultan Abdul-Malik believes his
days at the position are over as he attempts to play outside
linebacker in spring practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an all-season thing. It's a mutual decision with the
coaches,'' Abdul-Malik said. ``I think it's my best chance to be
successful to take it to the next level.''
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot-4 Abdul-Malik was a second-team All-Pac-10 performer
last season but was worried his weight (240 pounds) was too light
to play the position in the NFL. Ironically, Abdul-Malik wants to
lose 10 pounds to play linebacker.
</P>
<P>
   That means his position change sounds permanent, at least in
Abdul-Malik's opinion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm adjusting to it well. It's going to be a short process for
me,'' he said. ``I was originally a linebacker in high school and
converted to a defensive end when I got here.''
</P>
<P>
   With Abdul-Malik moving to linebacker, Lonnie Ford has now
switched from linebacker to defensive end. Ford was a tight end his
first two seasons at USC, but also played defensive end in high
school.
</P>
<P>
   Making the grade: Wide receiver R. Jay Soward marveled at some
of the gossip he heard surrounding his absence from the football
program during winter practices.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard everything from I had drug problems to I was stupid
and I was throwing away my education,'' Soward said. ``(People)
really didn't understand.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas the punt returner: Freshman Jason Thomas has begun
working on punt returns in practice. It might sound strange for a
quarterback, but his speed makes him a natural returner.
</P>
<P>
   ``He might be a real candidate to do that,'' USC coach Paul
Hackett said.
</P>
<P>
   Helping out: Former Washington offensive line coach Steve Morton
is coaching USC's tight ends in spring practice, but he has not
accepted the job full-time.
</P>
<P>
   Morton, who interviewed for but did not get the head-coaching
position at the University of North Dakota this week, will wait to
see if he can get an offensive line position at another school.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm volunteering right now,'' Morton said. ``I was looking for
something to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Morton is still being paid by Washington through June, which is
the earliest USC could begin paying him if he accepts the job.
</P>
</TEXT>
