<SLUG> BC-BKN-HILL-COLUMN-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLAZING A NEW TRAIL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A roll call of the 12 Portland Trail Blazers may sound a pinch
less than dirty, but it wouldn't be a shock to learn they are being
coached by Lee Marvin.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, some Blazers are swell citizens, but let's just say one or
two others are quite aware that Miranda is not the last name of a
woman who worked with a pile of fruit strapped to her head.
</P>
<P>
   They are a team with a record ... the best in the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   A cinch explanation for this is an abundance of talent; the
Blazers have more depth than beatnik poetry. Thanks to the shrewd
maneuvers of Prez/GM Bob Whitsitt, the roster includes nine former
NBA lottery picks, although none of the original selections
belonged to Portland.
</P>
<P>
   This haul has left Coach Mike Dunleavy with a squad that is
two-deep at each position:
</P>
<P>
   The shooting (and we do not use the term loosely) guards are
Isaiah Rider and Jim Jackson. Glower forward is maintained by Brian
Grant and Rasheed Wallace, with bouncy Jermaine O'Neal - in his
third season after skipping from high school to the NBA - in the
wings. Arvydas Sabonis occupies the center position, backed by
shot-blocker Kelvin Cato. Small forward is where you'll find scorer
Walt Williams and defensive mercenary Stacey Augmon. The point
guards are jitterbug Damon Stoudamire and veteran Greg Anthony, who
applies more defensive pressure than a mother-in-law who's overdue
for grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   Convincing these guys to share the wealth could put Dunleavy in
line for Coach of the Year. The strategy for beating
post-lockout-schedule fatigue (and opponents) with superior numbers
is much easier to sell, of course, as the victories pile up.
Without such success, this team might turn into the Donner Party.
</P>
<P>
   But don't pencil in Portland as the Western Conference's top
seed just yet. The Blazers, whose bills are settled by Paul Allen,
have zoomed through the season's opening half on a schedule that
was a bit Microsoft. Half two includes four games with the Lakers,
three with San Antonio and three with Vin Baker-less Seattle. There
is a solo trip to Houston and a game in Utah, where the Jazz could
be in position to annex the conference's catbird seat.
</P>
<P>
   One place you won't find the Blazes is the lottery, but Whitsitt
may have the Clippers and Grizzlies on speed dial.
</P>
<P>
   Subhead No Shanghai surprise
</P>
<P>
   The next NBA Draft - which looks brutally deficient at the
center position - may receive an upgrade from China.
</P>
<P>
   (Editor's note: insert drum roll here). And now ... the starting
lineup for your Shanghai Sharks (a professional club team) includes
a 7-foot-5, 18 year old named Yao Ming, who may decide to chase his
dream of playing in the NBA this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's being worked on right now,'' said one NBA scout who
recently traveled to China for a look at Ming. ``He could be in the
NBA next season.''
</P>
<P>
   Even factoring in the hyperbole that zings around basketball
campfires, Ming could be the biggest thing to leave China since the
U.K.
</P>
<P>
   But he's not exactly anonymous in the United States, having
impressed the sharpies at last summer's Nike Camp in Indianapolis.
He also played center for a San Diego-based team that participated
in several U.S. tournaments last July.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's very good,'' said the scout of the 270-pound Ming. ``He
needs some upper-body strength and some work playing with his back
to the basket, but he could be outstanding. At the worst, he's Rik
Smits.''
</P>
<P>
   (Editor's note: Smits is the Dutch-born Indiana Pacer who has
averaged 15 points per game through 10 NBA seasons; if you're
looking for a center, you could do a lot worse.)
</P>
<P>
   subhead Con-Vince-d
</P>
<P>
   With a slight bow to a few unlawful dribbling escapades by
Sacramento King Jason Williams, the most electrifying rookie to hit
the NBA is Toronto's Vince Carter.
</P>
<P>
   But despite his eye-popping athletic ability, many NBA watchdogs
questioned the 6-foot-7 Carter's shooting skill. Let's see ... the
kid made 41 percent of his 3-point attempts as a junior at
Carolina. Considering his talent and fierce approach to competing,
that would have been good enough for us.
</P>
<P>
   One reason for Carter's success is the Raptors' decision to keep
him at forward. Yeah, Carter has the requisite speed and quickness
to play guard, but the switch would have made matching up more of a
problem for him than for the other team.
</P>
<P>
   The 76ers couldn't resist the temptation of moving Jerry
Stackhouse to guard, even though the 6-6 ex-Tar Heel had - like
Carter -- been used exclusively at forward in college.
</P>
<P>
   Only time will tell if this Carter can lead the Raptors to the
promised land with the same drama presented by Joe Carter and the
Blue Jays.
</P>
<P>
   Subhead Shot-clock violations
</P>
<P>
   If, as his nickname suggests, Allen Iverson is The Answer, the
question must be: ``Who thrilled the league office by firing
super-agent David Falk?'' ... Losing Antonio McDyess and John ``Hot
Rod'' Williams and replacing them with Tom Gugilotta and Luc
Longley has not worked wonders for the Phoenix fast break. Jason
Kidd must feel like Jeff Gordon behind the wheel of a station
wagon. ...The Utah Jazz payroll is the league's fourth lowest;
obviously, their favorite play is not the pick-and-bankroll. ...
Eleven starting NBA centers (38 percent) were born outside the U.S.
The number does not include the Pistons' center, who was born in
Fresno as Brian Williams, then re-born on a cliff in Tibet as Bison
Dele.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
