<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-27 23:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6968 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-STRIKES-0328-2     03-27 1280
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-STRIKES-0328-2NDLD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDs: recasts lede; updates with NATO pilot rescue
 &HT;    SERBS CLAIM TO SHOOT DOWN NATO PLAN, AS NATO EXPANDS BOMBING
CAMPAIGN
 &HT;    With FIGHTER-BOX-0328; KOSOVO-REFUGEES-0328.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ NATO lost an F-117A Nighthawk stealth fighter over
the skies of Yugoslavia Saturday evening, but the unidentified
pilot was rescued safely and returned to an allied military base.
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon spokesman Kenneth Bacon announced the rescue and
reiterated that the loss of the plane, the most advanced in the
U.S. arsenal, had not dampened NATO resolve in the clash with
Yugoslavian President Molosevic.
</P>
<P>
   Bacon said it has not been determined whether the F-117A was hit
by Yugoslavian anti-aircraft fire or crashed as a result of a
malfunction or pilot error.
</P>
<P>
   The dramatic announcement came as Serbian television broadcast
images of twisted burning aircraft wreckage -- a stark reminder of
the tragedy and human cost of modern warfare for which President
Clinton has tried to prepare the American public.
</P>
<P>
   Serbian television images of the fiery plane wreckage clearly
showed a U.S. Air Force insignia and an ``Air Combat Command''
insignia that is typically displayed on F-117A Nighthawks.
</P>
<P>
   The loss of the $45 million F-117, which is designed for
missions into highly defended areas, came hours after Clinton, in
his weekly radio address, urged NATO to ``stay the course'' and
allied forces decided to expand their attacks to include Serbian
ground forces.
</P>
<P>
   But with Serbian forces reportedly intensifying atrocities
against ethnic Albanians in the southern province of Kosovo, a sign
that the NATO bombing has been ineffective in its objective of
slowing the Serb assault, Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic
vowed to pay ``any cost'' to keep NATO peacekeeping troops out of
his country.
</P>
<P>
   The war of words, weapons and television images suggested little
chance for a quick resolution to the conflict that, after four days
of intense bombing by NATO warplanes, is threatening to spread
beyond an area that Clinton described as ``a powder keg at the
heart of Europe.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the president said the bombing of Yugoslavia was
necessary ``to prevent a wider war'' involving other European
countries, two Yugoslav helicopters flew over neighboring
Bosnia-Herzegovina before turning back when confronted by NATO jet
fighters Saturday. On Friday, also over Bosnia, NATO F-15 warplanes
shot down two Yugoslav MiG-29 jet fighters that crossed over the
border about 25 miles from Tuzla, base for the 6,900 U.S. troops
taking part in the NATO peacekeeping operation in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   NATO's targeting of Serbian ground troops in Kosovo, the
increasing flood of ethnic Albanians into Macedonia, the
Yugoslavian violation of air space in Bosnia-Herzegovina and the
spreading protests in European cities underscored the dilemma NATO
leaders face: whether to send ground troops into Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   The White House and NATO officials moved swiftly Saturday to
dampen speculation that ground forces would be needed, especially
to stop the alleged ``ethnic cleansing'' by Serbian troops and
thugs against ethnic Albanians in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can accomplish our objective through air power,'' said
David Leavy, spokesman for Clinton's National Security Council.
</P>
<P>
   ``The United States has no intention of sending ground troops to
fight in Kosovo, and the Department of Defense is not doing any
planning that would enable such a deployment,''' Pentagon spokesman
Kenneth Bacon said.
</P>
<P>
   The increasing reports of atrocities in Kosovo prompted NATO
Secretary General Javier Solana Saturday to widen the range of
bombing targets to include Serbian tanks, artillery and troops in
Kosovo. In Brussels, Solana said he was ``determined to bring a
halt to violence in Kosovo and prevent further humanitarian
catastrophe'' with what was dubbed ``Phase Two'' of the bombing
mission.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton agreed to proceed with the next phase of airstrikes
after meeting with his foreign policy team and speaking with
leaders of key NATO allies Italy, Germany, Britain and France.
``All the leaders agreed that . . . it was time to broaden or
deepen the attack,'' said Leavy.
</P>
<P>
   This new phase of the NATO assault will be more dangerous,
however. To attack tanks and soldiers on the ground will require
NATO planes to swoop within range of Serb weaponry, which includes
1,400 anti-aircraft artillery, 100 surface-to-air missiles and an
undetermined number of shoulder-launched missiles similar to
American Stinger missiles.
</P>
<P>
   The Serbian army, which numbers about 30,000 soldiers, have
waged a 13-month siege of terror that has forced more than 350,000
ethnic Albanians from their homes.
</P>
<P>
   British Defense Minister George Robertson said an ``all-out Serb
offensive against the Albanian population'' of Kosovo has begun,
with scores of people murdered and villages destroyed. But he
insisted, ``This is not happening because of NATO. The violence was
going on before we began.''
</P>
<P>
   NATO spokesman Jamie Shea emphasized that NATO battle plans do
not call for the use of ground troops. But he also acknowledged
that air power alone will not entirely prevent Serbian brutality
against ethnic Albanians. ``It's not possible to do that from the
air,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Some 12,000 NATO ground troops, including 400 Americans, are in
Macedonia training for entry into Kosovo as part of a peace
settlement, but not as an invading, offensive force.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, for the first time since the NATO assault began, air
raid sirens screeched in Belgrade as allied bombs rocked the
suburbs of the Yugoslavian capital. Still, Milosevic remained
defiant, issuing a statement once again rejecting any Kosovo peace
plan that includes the stationing of NATO troops in Serbia's
southern province.
</P>
<P>
   ``The citizens of Yugoslavia are unanimous in their resolve not
to allow at any cost the enemies to occupy their country,'' the
statement said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, in his weekly radio address, said the Serbian attacks
on unarmed ethnic Albanians in recent days was ``all the more
reason for us to stay the course'' until Milosevic ``accepts peace
or we have seriously damaged this capacity to make war.''
</P>
<P>
   In the weekly Republican radio address, Sen. John Ashcroft,
R-Mo., questioned Clinton's leadership in the crisis.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our troops must receive a clear military mission,'' Ashcroft
said. ``Our leaders must construct a a strategy and timetable to
achieve that mission. Third, our soldiers deserve an exit strategy
that can bring them home safely.''
</P>
<P>
   Minutes after Clinton's broadcast, a U.S. Navy ship fired two
Tomahawk cruise missiles at what a defense official called
``targets of opportunity'' near Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   Then, as the skies cleared after a heavy day of rain over Aviano
Air Base, more than 50 warplanes screamed off the runway for the
fourth straight day of bombing against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   With few neutral observers on the ground in Yugoslavia, it is
difficult to determine the extent to which the NATO bombing has
weakened Milosevic. The air raid sirens in Belgrade went off after
the explosions in the suburbs, suggesting that NATO had weakened
Yugoslavia's formidable air defense system.
</P>
<P>
   Leavy said reconnaissance efforts were under way to verify
allegations of fresh Serb aggression against the Kosovars. He said
U.S. officials would turn over any evidence of war crimes to the
U.N. Tribunal in The Hague for possible prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
