<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOYSRANCH-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MURDER CHARGES FILED AGAINST BOYS RANCH 5 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DENNIS WAGNER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pinal County prosecutors, once forced to drop a manslaughter
indictment against five Arizona Boys Ranch employees, have filed
new charges accusing the defendants of first-degree murder.
</P>
<P>
   The criminal complaint, filed Thursday in Pinal County Superior
Court, also accuses the former ranch employees of child abuse in
the March 2, 1998, death of 16-year-old Nicholaus Contreraz.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is absolutely beyond reality,'' said Darrow Soll,
co-counsel for defendant Montgomery Hoover. ``No one has ever
thought that this was a first-degree murder case.''
</P>
<P>
   The indictment says the defendants committed first-degree murder
by killing Contreraz as they committed, or attempted to commit,
child abuse. Under Arizona law, first-degree murder charges may be
filed when a death occurs during the commission of a felony.
</P>
<P>
   Hoover was initially indicted Sept. 30 along with Geoffrey S.
Lewis, Montgomery Hoover, Michael M. Moreno, Troy M. Jones and
Linda Babb. All five pleaded innocent at an arraignment in October.
</P>
<P>
   Then, early this year, charges were dismissed by prosecutors who
blamed a technical problem in empaneling the grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   Defense lawyers said the indictment was dropped because some
jurors admitted being aware of previous abuse at Boys Ranch and
because the entire panel was given prejudicial evidence and
testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides have been preparing for an April 13 preliminary
hearing, with defense lawyers pressing Assistant County Attorney
Janna Vanderpool to clarify the criminal charges and provide
discovery materials.
</P>
<P>
   They got their response in the mail Friday _ a new criminal
complaint for first-degree murder.
</P>
<P>
   Vanderpool could not be reached for comment. Charles Ratliff, a
spokesman for the Pinal County Attorney's Office, said he was not
aware that murder charges had been lodged.
</P>
<P>
   Defense lawyers, meanwhile, blasted Vanderpool.Soll said he
suspects the prosecutor submitted the murder complaint out of
vindictiveness _ retaliating againsttenacious defense efforts to
dismiss the indictment and obtain discovery materials.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to wonder if this is simply a response to aggressive
lawyers,'' Soll added.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Chornenky, attorney for Lewis, said he does not know if
vengefulness is involved, but one thing is clear: ``The prosecutor
doesn't know what's going on. She is ill-prepared.''
</P>
<P>
   The new complaint offers alternative charges against each
defendant. All five are accused of first-degree murder or _ ``in
the alternative'' _ manslaughter. They also are charged with child
abuse or _ ``in the alternative'' _ causing or allowing injury to a
child.
</P>
<P>
   Chornenky vowed to seek an immediate dismissal.
</P>
<P>
   He said that his client is innocent, and that none of the
defendants did anything even close to first-degree murder. By
accusing the defendants of such a severe crime, Chornenky said,
Vanderpool committed an ``abuse of discretion'' that could ruin
their lives.
</P>
<P>
   Contreraz, a Sacramento boy with an extensive criminal record,
died of severe lung ailments at a Boys Ranch boot camp in Oracle.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators concluded that he had been sick for days, but was
subjected to work, exercise, punishment and ridicule by employees
at the residential program for juvenile offenders.
</P>
<P>
   The medical examiner discovered 2{ quarts of pus in the lining
of Contreraz's lungs, plus more than 70 cuts, bruises and other
wounds on his body.
</P>
<P>
   Because Contreraz was constantly vomiting and suffered from
diarrhea, he was seen repeatedly by Babb, the Boys Ranch nurse. But
he was considered a malingerer, and the infection was never
diagnosed.
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses said staffers forced Contreraz to do push-ups over a
pail containing excrement-soiled clothing, and made him dine while
sitting on a toilet. Child Protective Services workers documented
abuse or neglect on the part of 17 ranch employees, but only five
face criminal charges.
</P>
<P>
   Boys Ranch's 50-year history is checkered with allegations of
mistreatment. Critics blame the organization's tough, hands-on
method of rehabilitating juvenile violators. Defenders say juvenile
offenders routinely make false accusations of abuse.
</P>
<P>
   Since Contreraz's death, ranch operations have dissolved. The
Department of Economic Security has refused to renew the non-profit
organization's license until major reforms are implemented. Five of
six campuses are closed, the resident population has dwindled from
about 600 to 40, and most employees have been laid off.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Thomas, longtime president of Boys Ranch, left several
months ago. New leadership is trying to rebuild with revised
policies, guidelines and programs. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
