r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-CROUSE-COLUMN-COR     03-27 0931
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-CROUSE-COLUMN-CORRECTED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOUDY GIVES WOMEN'S SOCCER A LIFT
</HEADLINE>
 VERSION-LADN (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Validation can scream at you from the stands of a packed Olympic
stadium outside of Atlanta. Or it can sneak up on you like dinner
on a hectic day.
</P>
<P>
   Julie Foudy was eating at a Thai restaurant in Laguna Beach with
her husband recently when an elderly Iranian gentleman at a nearby
table looked at her quizzically.
</P>
<P>
   ``Soccer?'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes!'' she replied.
</P>
<P>
   ``World Cup?'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes!'' she answered.
</P>
<P>
   Foudy is a veteran of two World Cups and is training full-time
with the U.S. team for her third. But in the restaurant that day,
the stranger wanted only to talk about her broadcasting work for
ESPN during the men's World Cup last summer. He spoke effusively in
his native tongue, leaving his son to translate the words into
praise that made Foudy blush.
</P>
<P>
   After the man had returned to his meal, Foudy's husband Ian
Sawyers leaned across the table and whispered, ``What he just said
means more to me than any write-up in the paper.''
</P>
<P>
   Foudy nodded knowingly. In the world in which she was raised,
her insightful commentary on ESPN was perfectly natural, like
Geraldine Ferraro pontificating on politics. But the real world
Foudy knows to be different. It's a place where some subjects
supposedly remain beyond a woman's comprehension no matter the
qualifications she brings to the task.
</P>
<P>
   It's not right, merely true: Reggie Miller can riff on WNBA
games and no one bats an eye, but Cammi Granato does radio color
commentary for the Kings and gets all kind of guff.
</P>
<P>
   Foudy was determined that, if nothing else, her detractors would
not be able to question her preparedness. She spent four solid
months leading up to the month-long broadcasting assignment reading
up on the participating players, memorizing names and watching
reams of game film. Intensity-wise, her pre-med studies at Stanford
were a friendly compared to what she put herself through to get
ready for her first T.V. gig.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to prove I had a lot of knowledge in the sport, that
I wasn't just on (the air) because they wanted a woman,'' Foudy
said. ``That was a big motivation.''
</P>
<P>
   That's why, when an Iranian gentleman in a restaurant or two
Brazilian men on an airplane or an Englishman in a pub compliments
Foudy on her soccer expertise, the attacking midfielder feels no
small sense of fulfillment.
</P>
<P>
   One more defense punctured.
</P>
<P>
   But the breakaway career move can wait.
</P>
<P>
   Foudy's soccer excellence is all she'll be honing for the next
few months. Along with the rest of the national team, she is
focusing on this summer's World Cup. Norway is the defending
champion, having wrested the title from the U.S. in 1995. The U.S.
is the host country so there is much to gain _ and lose _ besides
the championship itself.
</P>
<P>
   A U.S. victory could be just the kick this country needs to
establish a women's pro league, which most people agree is
essential if the U.S. is to establish any depth beyond its pool of
national-team players.
</P>
<P>
   A poor showing would slow the momentum created by the women's
gold-medal performance in Atlanta and likely prove the naysayers
right. Already Foudy, 28, has heard it snidely suggested in certain
circles that the only thing less likely to excite the U.S. public
than an international soccer marathon is a women's international
soccer marathon.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's still so many critics out there saying we can't pull
it off, that it's so risky to have the World Cup here,'' Foudy
said. ``We don't care. We feel energized having the World Cup in
the U.S. We like that challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   The World Cup final will be held at the Rose Bowl on July 10.
The Americans will get their first collective look at the pitch
today when they meet Mexico in their first match since their
second-place finish (behind China) at the Algarve Cup in Portugal.
</P>
<P>
   Foudy will be the blur in the middle. Employed as a defensive
midfielder during the 1995 World Cup and 1996 Olympics, Foudy is
the beneficiary of a 4-3-3 offensive scheme that allows her to play
a more attacking role.
</P>
<P>
   The change has been good for her. Foudy joked that it was like
``getting rid of the ball and chain.''
</P>
<P>
   The chance to analyze all those World Cup games last summer
didn't hurt, either. In dissecting other people's games, she
learned much that was useful about her own.
</P>
<P>
   ``I find myself playing better this year than I have in the past
and I don't think it's a coincidence,'' Foudy said. ``Watching so
many games totally helped my game.''
</P>
<P>
   Foudy admits she is looking forward to the day when she sees her
husband more than her teammates. She can clearly picture herself in
a career in T.V., talking about something other than soccer.
</P>
<P>
   But all in good time. Foudy realizes her mission in soccer is
not quite accomplished when she goes somewhere and someone says to
her, innocently enough, ``Oh, you play soccer? But you look so
feminine.''
</P>
<P>
   The times, thankfully, they are a'changing. Foudy got a letter
the other day from a high school soccer player. The girl wrote that
her best friend was a boy who was a huge fan of women's soccer.
They watched the U.S. national team's matches together and it ``was
some of the greatest moments they shared together.''
</P>
<P>
   By the time Foudy got to the part about the boy's death from a
terminal disease, she was in tears. Sometimes it's easy to forget
you're making a difference until someone takes the time to tell
you. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
