<SLUG> BC-OBIT-CONANT-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOWELL CONANT, TOOKCOVER SHOTS OF STARS FOR `LIFE' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JANELLE COWGILL  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Howell T. Conant, a photographer whose shots of Grace Kelly and
other celebrities landed on the covers of ``Life'' and other
magazines, has died.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Conant, who was 83, died at his Carefree home on March 11.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Conant is best-known for his striking photographs of Kelly,
whom he met when she first arrived to model in New York. His first
photos of her won a ``Photoplay'' magazine cover and a spot in
``Collier's.'' Her career _ and his _ took off.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Conant was born March 13, 1916, in Wisconsin to a family of
photographers, including his father and grandfather. He attended
the Art Center School in Los Angeles and studied art at the
University of Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
   After college, Mr. Conant joined the Navy and was a photographer
during World War II. While in Waikiki, Hawaii, Mr. Conant met his
future wife, Dorothy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just sitting there, and he was on his surfboard and he
just pulled that surfboard right up to my feet,'' she said. ``We
were married 30 days later. I guess you could say it was meant to
be.''
</P>
<P>
   The couple moved to New York City, which was their home for 45
years. Mr. Conant opened his studio there and did a lot of
advertising work.
</P>
<P>
   He went to work for ``Life'' magazine and became close friends
with Kelly.
</P>
<P>
   ``She requested him whenever she knew that she would have a
cover,'' Dorothy Conant said.
</P>
<P>
   His numerous photographs of the Academy Award-winning actress
were collected in a book, ``Grace.''
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Conant's portfolio includes ``Life'' covers of actresses
Elizabeth Taylor, Audrey Hepburn and Claudia Cardinale, plus shots
of beaches and Olympic swimmers.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Conant also photographed former Presidents Hoover, Johnson,
Nixon and Kennedy _ official portraits coupled with candid family
shots.
</P>
<P>
   An avid pilot, Mr. Conant flew to most of his assignments in his
twin-engine Piper Comanche.
</P>
<P>
   He fell in love with Arizona's weather and Indian lore while on
assignment for a magazine story highlighting renowned architect
Paolo Soleri.
</P>
<P>
   For a while, the Conants stayed at the Carefree Inn whenever
they flew to Arizona. Then, 12 years ago, they bought a home in Sky
Ranch, complete with its own hangar.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from photography, Mr. Conant divided his time between
deep-sea fishing and scuba diving. The couple had a fishing boat
they took with them on trips to the Bahamas.
</P>
<P>
   Dorothy Conant said that her husband was a good fisherman,
reeling in swordfish and ``anything else that would bite.''
</P>
<P>
   He was also one of the first people to dive near a German
submarine that had sunk off the coast of New England. His deep-sea
photographs later grew into a television documentary.
</P>
<P>
   ``He really enjoyed the creativity of what he did,'' his wife
said. ``That is what he enjoyed most.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his wife, Mr. Conant is survived by his
daughters, Carol Richter-Blum, Sarah Martabano and Susan; son,
Howell T. II; 12 grandchildren; and one great-grandchild.
</P>
<P>
   Private services were held in Carefree. The family is planning a
memorial service later this summer off Rhode Island. &QL; 
Janelle Cowgill can be reached at 444-8332 or at
janelle.cowgill &LR; pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-27-99 2335EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
