u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-DUKE-MICHST-350&AMP;A     03-27 0867
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-DUKE-MICHST-350&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLUE DEVILS SURVIVE A SCARE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By JOE DRAPE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ The Michigan State Spartans put Duke on
the floor, put elbows in the Blue Devils' ribs and, for a couple of
minutes at least, put them on the ropes of elimination. One Duke
star, Elton Brand, was on the bench with four fouls. Another star,
Trajan Langdon, found his shooting stroke as icy as the playgrounds
of his native Alaska.
</P>
<P>
   But all Duke needed to propel its way to the National Collegiate
Athletic Association championship game against Connecticut on
Monday night was one pretty play to transcend an ugly game as the
Blue Devils bounced hard-nosed Michigan State out with a 68-62
victory Saturday night. What it proved was that close games or not,
the Blue Devils' 32-game winning streak was built on the same kind
toughness as the 22-game streak the Spartans had clawed out.
</P>
<P>
   Duke now has both its men's and women's teams in the NCAA
finals, the women taking on Purdue for their title on Sunday night
in San Jose, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Duke did it Saturday night despite shooting just 8-of-22 from
free-throw line down the stretch and shooting just 45 percent from
the field for the game.
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Devils began their tightrope walk with elimination with
10 minutes 12 seconds left in the game when Brand, who was on his
way to a dominating 18-point, 15-rebound performance, made a mental
mistake. Brand ripped down his 14th rebound and decided to lead the
Blue Devils' fast break. He already had three fouls and had
teammates on either side and only guard Mateen Cleaves defending.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot-8-inch Brand should have given the ball up, but he
kept it long enough to bull over Cleaves and pick up his fourth
foul on a charge with the Blue Devils ahead by 50-42. The Spartans
needed just two minutes to cut the deficit to 51-48 on two free
throws by Charlie Bell.
</P>
<P>
   But Langdon, who had just hit 2-of-8 shots up to that point and
would finish with seven points, picked a perfect time to find his
range. He faked Bell on the perimeter and fired up a fall-away
3-pointer to put the Blue Devils up by 54-48.
</P>
<P>
   When Brand returned with 4:44 remaining, Duke was ahead by
59-52.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The scales of history were weighted in favor of Duke. The Blue
Devils were trying to reach their sixth championship game in eight
Final Four appearances under Krzyzewski. They were also trying to
keep Blue Devil Airlines in the air _ the university president,
Nannerl O. Keohane, and the athletic director, Joe Alleva,
chartered a plane to shuttle between here and San Jose, Calif.,
where the women's team plays in the title game against Purdue.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Tom Izzo of Michigan State was looking to make his first
championship appearance and to return the Spartans to basketball
prominence 20 years after the Magic Johnson-led team beat Larry
Bird and Indiana State for the national title.
</P>
<P>
   The notoriously slow-starting Spartans remained true to form in
a leaden first half that was notable for how poorly Michigan State
executed its game plan in falling behind, 32-20.
</P>
<P>
   The Spartans intended to keep the ball away from Brand down low,
but the 6-foot-8-inch Peekskill, N.Y., native reached through
cracks like he had glue on his fingers and scored six of the Blue
Devils' first 11 points on his way to an eight-point, 12-rebound
first half. With Brand bulling his way along the blocks and Shane
Battier and Corey Maggette flashing through the middle, the Blue
Devils pounded a strong rebounding team on the boards, 26-14, in
the half.
</P>
<P>
   The Spartans had outrebounded 35 opponents this season and in
four tournament games had pulled down an average of 11 more than
offensive boards. But Brand and company out-rebounded them on the
offensive end, 11-6, for 13 second-chance points in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   Michigan State had hoped to reduce the Blue Devils to Stone Age
basketball on the offensive end with smothering man-to-man defense.
To some extent it worked, forcing a Duke team averaging better than
50 percent shooting from the field into 42.4 percent shooting in
the half, and just 14.3 percent from beyond the 3-point line.
</P>
<P>
   But the Spartans were an abysmal 29 percent from the field and
missed their last five shots of the half. Their bench, which had
outscored its opponents' reserves in all but one game, mustered
only six points. The team's leading scorer, Morris Peterson, could
not find his stroke, shooting just 2-of-8.
</P>
<P>
   It was the Duke reserves who provided the only highlights of the
first half and kept the Spartans from clawing closer. Maggette, the
freshman whom National Basketball Association scouts are eager to
get into the league, looked as if he were strapped with rockets
when he picked a rebound off the glass on the defensive end, drove
the length of the floor and picked up the foul. He made the basket
and the free throw and the Blue Devils were ahead, 20-10.
</P>
<P>
   Two minutes later on a breakaway, Maggette showed why he has
earned comparisons to Michael Jordan with a split-legged dunk. He
led the Blue Devils in the first half with nine points.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
