<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-27 23:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6988 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POLICE-KILLING-AZR &LR;      03-27 1266
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLICE-KILLING-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEXICAN TEEN HELD IN DEATH OF POLICE OFFICER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE YOZWIAK  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ A teenager who entered Arizona illegally from Mexico
confessed Saturday to the ambush-killing of Phoenix police Officer
Marc Atkinson, authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   Felipe Petrona-Cabanas, 17, was booked into Maricopa County Jail
for investigation of first-degree murder, attempted murder and
aggravated assault.
</P>
<P>
   He was transferred Saturday from a hospital to Phoenix police
headquarters for questioning after being wounded in a gunbattle
Friday with a citizen who came to Atkinson's assistance. Sgt. Mike
Torres, a police spokesman, said police would not make details of
Petrona-Caban as' statement public Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Torres said the armed citizen, Rory Vertigan, probably kept the
gunman and two other armed men from fleeing to the safety of their
hometowns in Mexico. The other men also were arrested and held on
lesser charges.
</P>
<P>
   Traces of the shooting were visible Saturday afternoon at the
site: A bloodstain was on the road where Atkinson's car crashed
into a power pole. A bullet hole was in a wall at the side of
Bristow Optical.
</P>
<P>
   But other aftermaths were less visible.
</P>
<P>
   Parents from nearby neighborhoods voiced new fears.
</P>
<P>
   ``Daytime is when when you feel safe letting your kids out to
play,'' said Linda Rodriguez, whose family lives about a mile from
the shooting site.
</P>
<P>
   Belinda Milburn of Phoenix, a teacher's aide, dropped by a
basket of mums at a makeshift shrine at the shooting scene.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know there has been a war over drugs and crime but they are
being so blatant here,'' she said. ``This was not a shooting _ this
was an assassination.''
</P>
<P>
   It all started simply enough on Friday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Atkinson and two other Maryvale precinct patrol officers
followed through with a police initiative to crack down
aggressively on drug dealing.
</P>
<P>
   Based on a tip, the three officers went to the Scoreboard
Tavern, 2831 N. 35th Ave., where police believed drugs were being
dealt in the bar parking lot from a white Lincoln Continental.
</P>
<P>
   But Atkinson, 28, and the others were unable to determine who
inside the bar had been driving the car.
</P>
<P>
   As the officers waited for the car to leave, two of them were
called away on other assignments, Torres said. He gave the
following account of Friday's events:
</P>
<P>
   When three men emerged from the bar and got into the Lincoln,
only Atkinson was left to tail them.
</P>
<P>
   They got a good head start. Atkinson barely kept the car in
sight as it rapidly turned east on Thomas Road, north on 31st
Avenue, east on Catalina Avenue and north on 30th Avenue, where it
stopped in the middle of the street.
</P>
<P>
   Atkinson, who had patrolled the neighborhoods of West Phoenix
for five years, briefly lost sight of the car before he turned
north on 30th Avenue, his vision blocked by a building.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Atkinson turned, Petrona-Cabanas had already jumped
out of the driver's seat and had drawn his .357-caliber revolver.
</P>
<P>
   Atkinson never had time to draw his own pistol. Petrona-Cabanas
fired at least twice, striking Atkinson twice in the head as the
officer sped by, eventually ramming his squad car into a light
pole.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, Torres said, the three men could easily have
disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   But behind Atkinson was Rory Vertigan, who saw Petrona-Cabanas
shoot Atkinson.
</P>
<P>
   Vertigan pulled to a stop behind the Lincoln, got out of his car
and exchanged gunfire with Petrona-Cabanas. One of the shots from
Vertigan's Glock 31 pistol wounded Petrona-Cabanas, piercing
through his upper-left shoulder from behind.
</P>
<P>
   Petrona-Cabanas collapsed and later was taken to a hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Police Chief Harold Hurtt said Vertigan's actions were legal,
because Vertigan believed he was acting to prevent imminent harm to
himself or others, the general rule for lawful use of deadly force.
Hurtt praised Vertigan as ``one of the true heroes of our time.''
</P>
<P>
   The other two men in the Lincoln _ Oscar Garcia-Martinez, 22,
and Oberlin Cabanas-Salgado, 26 _ also got out of the car and began
to run. Garcia-Martinez carried a pistol. Cabanas-Salgado had a
shotgun. Neither, however, fired his weapon.
</P>
<P>
   They tried to hide, but they were soon captured after witnesses
pointed police in the direction they tried to escape.
</P>
<P>
   One man was captured in a restroom of Bristow Optical on the
northwestern corner of 30th Avenue and Catalina. The other was
captured nearby.
</P>
<P>
   Police discovered as much as a pound of cocaine in the Lincoln.
The drug was already sorted into one-eighth-ounce bags known as
``eight balls,'' a common quantity that is easily exchanged without
detection between dealers and users.
</P>
<P>
   Petrona-Cabanas was taken to Good Samaritan Regional Medical
Center. He was released from the hospital Saturday, questioned at
Phoenix police headquarters and then booked into Maricopa County
Jail.
</P>
<P>
   Torres said that Petrona-Cabanas was read his rights, but there
was no attorney present during his questioning. Torres anticipated
that the courts would appoint an attorney for him.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia-Martinez was held on an outstanding warrant for
investigation of failure to appear in court on a previous drug
charge.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia-Martinez and Cabanas-Salgado were held for investigation
of entering the country illegally and illegal possession of
firearms.
</P>
<P>
   Hurtt said he would personally pursue the case against
Petrona-Cabanas and see that he was prosecuted to the fullest
extent of the law. If Petrona-Cabanas is found guilty and is
sentenced to death, Hurtt said he would request to be present for
the execution.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, investigators were trying to determine why
PetronaCabanas had such a violent reaction to Atkinson's pursuit.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix police said the men all come from farming communities
near Acapulco in the Mexican state of Guerrero. They told police
they had come to the United States to find work, but could not get
any.
</P>
<P>
   Petrona-Cabanas has been in the United States about seven
months. His cousin, Cabanas-Salgado, has been here for three
months, and Garcia-Martinez has been in this country for perhaps
three or four years, police said.
</P>
<P>
   The timing of Friday's attack was curious, police said, because
a large-scale surveillance of West Phoenix drug stash houses has
been ongoing for weeks by the Joint Drug Intelligence Group, made
up of federal, state and local police agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Torres said extensive drug surveillance usually traces the
source of drugs in the Valley to rich, powerful families in Mexico.
Often, he said, illegal aliens who cannot find work in the United
States are recruited to sell smaller quantities of drugs on Valley
streets.
</P>
<P>
   Hurtt said Phoenix police were not pursuing any other particular
individuals who might be connected with the killing of Atkinson.
</P>
<P>
   To help heal the deep psychological wounds inflicted on the
Valley's law-enforcement officers, and the community at large,
Hurtt on Saturday ordered upwards of 120 additional officers onto
the streets.
</P>
<P>
   Hurtt also called on motorists to drive night and day with their
headlights on, at least for the next few days, as a show of support
for law enforcement throughout Maricopa County, which this month
has seen four officers killed or wounded in the line of duty.
</P>
<P>
   Officers began wearing black bands of mourning Saturday across
their badges, Hurtt said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This could have happened to any one of us,'' he said. &QL; 
Also contributing to this story were Republic reporters Maureen
West and Mark Shaffer. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
