</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-FINAL-4-BICKLEY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS FINAL FOUR NEEDED SOME EXCITEMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN BICKLEY  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. - Magic was in the stands, sitting with his
father, hoping against hope that his old school was primed for a
miracle.
</P>
<P>
   On the court, magic was nowhere to be found.
</P>
<P>
   And now it's up to Connecticut to compete. To provide a
much-needed dose of drama. To save the tournament from a crude
coronation and the yawn of a new era.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we have a better basketball game in us, and I hope we
have that Monday night,'' Huskies Coach Jim Calhoun said, and let's
hope he's right.
</P>
<P>
   Without the element of unpredictability, the NCAA Tournament is
nothing. And on Saturday - a day that normally serves as the apex
of drama, normally the best 80 minutes of a three-week extravaganza
- everything went painfully according to form.
</P>
<P>
   A Duke team that would not be seriously threatened. A Michigan
State team green with envy. A Connecticut team continuing to teeter
between greatness and self-destruction. A bunch of Buckeyes happy
to have made the cut.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, over the last couple of days, the only suspense
centered on whether Kato Kaelin was really in town for the
proceedings. He was.
</P>
<P>
   Duke has now played 1,525 minutes of basketball this season.
They have trailed for 111 minutes, and not once on Saturday. And
over 38 games, a season that started in Alaska and is ending in
Florida, the Blue Devils have trailed for only 24 minutes in the
second half.
</P>
<P>
   Not that Duke played all that well against Michigan State. They
missed 13 free throws and 9-of-13 three-point attempts. But in the
first half, they made a travesty of the one Spartan advantage -
offensive rebounding - and had a 10-point lead before Jim Nantz
could utter his first clich.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you have to give it to Duke,'' Michigan State coach
Tom Izzo said. ``For taking our game in the first half ... for
taking the best part of our game and really taking it to us. They
just pounded us on the boards in the first half.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh, the Spartans tried to make it interesting. Once they climbed
within three, once within four. Both times, Duke responded within
seconds, each time draining a three-pointer on the ensuing
possession.
</P>
<P>
   Game, set, mismatch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time we started to make a little bit of a run, they
answered with something,'' Mateen Cleaves said. ``And that's why
they're a great team.''
</P>
<P>
   Great enough to parlay a day of bad basketball into one of the
most boring Final Fours in memory? That is the mission facing
Calhoun's troops.
</P>
<P>
   For a while, it looked like Connecticut had turned the corner.
Twice, the Huskies threatened to blow away the Buckeyes, and they
should have. Ohio State is a nice team, but three weeks ago, they
lost to Illinois. They have one player with any name recognition,
and that guy - Scoonie Penn - was stuck with a nameless jersey when
his uniform turned up missing Saturday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, for a while, the Huskies looked very much like Duke's
equal. Khalid El-Amin was brilliant, Richard Hamilton was scoring
at will and the whole team raced up and down the court as if their
shorts were on fire.
</P>
<P>
   Inevitably, the brilliance faded. Not enough to buoy the
Buckeyes. But just enough to raise the same old questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had them on the ropes a couple of times and we never put
them away,'' El-Amin said. ``But we're glad we got the `'.''
</P>
<P>
   If El-Amin and Hamilton can duplicate their performances on
Monday, maybe Connecticut has a shot. Especially if they can feed
off the defensive brilliance of Ricky Moore, who hounded Penn into
submission on Saturday, setting the tone for the triumph.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ricky Moore is the best defensive player I've ever coached,''
Calhoun said. ``We've played a lot of great guards and they all
seem to have bad shooting nights.''
</P>
<P>
   Too bad he can't check Elton Brand.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, predictability and boredom are setting in, two words you'd
never associate with the climax of March Madness. And now it's up
to Connecticut to save the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   An upset isn't necessary, but is a close game too much to ask? &QL; 
Dan Bickley can be reached at 602-444-8253 or at
dan.bickley(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
