r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-CUBA-GOMEZ-AZR &LR;      03-27 1223
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-CUBA-GOMEZ-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CUBA AND BASEBALL: A NATION'S LOVE AFFAIR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HAVANA - Martin Dihigo is a name that carries as much weight in
Cuba as Fidel Castro or Jose Marti.
</P>
<P>
   Because he became the first Cuban-born player inducted into the
Hall of Fame in Cooperstown, his name may actually be held in a
higher standing than any politician here, at least privately.
</P>
<P>
   Dihigo, who once pitched both games of a doubleheader and batted
cleanup while in his mid-40s in 1946 for the province of Las Tunas,
is an unparalleled legend in Cuban baseball. That his entire career
was played in the relative obscurity of the Negro Leagues only
strengthens his standing in Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Today the Baltimore Orioles will become the first major league
club in 40 years to play in Cuba, a game that has the people here
in a frenzy and enraged at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   Make no mistake, baseball is THE national pastime in Cuba, with
boxing a distant second, barely registering a blip on the screen
when it is placed next to the pride of the island.
</P>
<P>
   Cuba's love affair with baseball is thought to have started when
the native Indians played a game called Batos back in the 1860s, a
crude version of what we know today as baseball, and solidified
when U.S. sailors brought the game in the ensuing decades.
</P>
<P>
   The reality, according to the so-called ``baseball scientists''
who make up the respected elite of those who hash out baseball
arguments and theories on a daily basis, insist baseball played
second fiddle to soccer until sometime in the 1940s.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's true,'' said 84-year-old Esteban Hernandez-Lopez, who
heads a local social club of hard-core baseball aficionados.
``Soccer was a bigger sport here. Remember, this was a Spanish
colony. But then the Cuban player started making his way to the
major leagues, and soccer hasn't been heard of since.''
</P>
<P>
   Now Cuba will host a major league game at Estadio Latinoamerica,
where Games 1 and 2 of the Cuban version of the World Series took
place with Havana's Industriales sweeping the first two games
against Santiago in the best-of-seven series, which heads to the
eastern province of Santiago for Monday's Game 3.
</P>
<P>
   What has the local fans in a quiet uproar is the Cuban
government's decision to allow fans into the historic game by
invitation only, meaning the true Cuban baseball fan will not be
allowed to watch what many consider the most important baseball
game ever to take place in Cuba since Fidel Castro assumed power in
1959.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why, after all these years, we the Cuban people who built that
stadium, have filled it for years, why can't we go now?,'' asked
taxi driver Rene Hernandez. ``I'm not a baseball fan, so I wouldn't
go anyway. But it's a total lack of respect. These is a town that
follows baseball _ they are the ones who should be at the game. The
ones who will be here don't even care about baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   Aside from only the privileged being allowed entry to Estadio
Latinoamerica, this will not be a game between the Baltimore
Orioles and the Cuban National Team, as it's being billed.
</P>
<P>
   None of the players on either Industriales, Havana's club that
is considered the equivalent of the Yankees here, and Santiago, a
club from a far-eastern province that is well-known as Cuban
President Castro's favorite club.
</P>
<P>
   ``Granma,'' the Cuban communist newspaper, said of the Cuban
select club that will play Baltimore, ``This selection enters the
game with discipline and dediction and constitutes a representation
of patriotic valor which identifies Cuban sports.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Lopez: ``What they're doing is setting up an excuse. If
Cuba loses, they can say it was only the third- or fourth-best team
they could put together. If Cuba wins, they can in turn say they
beat the imperialists without having their best club. It's a shame
all the best Cuban players won't play against the Orioles. We, the
people, want to see our best at every position on the field.''
</P>
<P>
   This is a country where a child is basically born with a
baseball glove and bat in his hands, where he or she has no choice
but to become a passionate fan.
</P>
<P>
   During Game 2 of the final here, a controversial call was made
when the home plate umpire ruled a ball in play after the pitcher
dove and missed a bunt attempt down the third base line.
</P>
<P>
   Santiago's players all converged on the plate umpire, with the
first baseman actually flinging his glove at the face of the
umpire, smacking him in the cheek. No players were ejected. It can
safely be argued that such a fracas on the streets would have
elicited jail time for several people.
</P>
<P>
   But in a place where there is no doubt, baseball is and will
forever be king. Children play the game anywhere they can find an
empty field or alley with as few as four players and as many as 20.
It's also a country that demands the most from its players, whether
domestic or foreign.
</P>
<P>
   Don Newcombe, the National League Rookie of the Year in 1949,
was actually booted out of the Cuban winter leagues that same
winter because ``he was getting hit too hard,'' said Guillermo
Cosio, another one of Cuba's baseball scientists.
</P>
<P>
   Through the years, Cubans have made a serious impact in the
major leagues, starting with Adolfo Luque, a 27-game winner for the
Cincinnati Reds in 1923, and leading all the way up to El Duque
Hernandez, who helped the Yankees win last season's World Series.
</P>
<P>
   In between, there have been names such as Minnie Minoso, Tony
Perez, Luis Tiant, Campy Campaneris, Jose Canseco, Rafael Palmeiro
and Rey Ordonez, who sat on the bench for Industriales behind
current shortstop German Mesa.
</P>
<P>
   The game here is played with a flare that would be misunderstood
in the majors for arrogance. During a rally by Industriales in Game
1 Friday night, six players began doing an imitation of the Radio
City Rockettes in the dugout after a key two-run home run by first
baseman Antonio Scull in the bottom of the eighth that led to a 3-2
victory.
</P>
<P>
   Even at the sandlot level, the players display a panache that
was commonly attached to the Cuban player of the 1950s and '60s.
Just about everyone remembers how Campaneris wiggled his bat back
and forth, trying to intimidate a pitcher. Or how Tiant completely
turned his back to the batter before delivering his pitches.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Cuban ballplayer has always maintained a certain level of
acceptance for being someone who knew the game inside and out,''
said St. Louis Manager Tony La Russa. ``That's why they were
considered among the best from outside the United States in the
'60s.''
</P>
<P>
   Now the United States has sent the Orioles to face the Cubans.
Many people in Havana's streets believe this could lead to a
warming of relations between the two rival nations. It's a
viewpoint that seems to have some weight considering the enormity
of the occasion.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason this game may be the start of something, is because
our national pastime is the same as your national pastime,'' said
Javier Valdes, 44, a mechanical engineer. ``It is one aspect of
common ground the two nations have and may very well lead to
something very important occurring. We, the Cuban people, are
certainly hoping so.'' &QL; 
Pedro Gomez can be reached at 602-444-2364 or at
pedro.gomez(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
