<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCONN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOORE LIFTS UCONN TO TITLE GAME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ The game ended and Connecticut trotted
out its marquee players, guards Richard Hamilton and Khalid
El-Amin. They stood in front of the cameras and sat behind the
microphones. Their names flashed on the giant scoreboards next to
impressive point totals.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton had 24 and El-Amin 18, but neither deserved credit as
player of the game.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut escaped Ohio State 64-58 Saturday night in Tropicana
Field and advanced to its first NCAA title game because of a tough,
quiet senior guard named Ricky Moore. He made one basket and had
one assist, but that doesn't reflect his impact on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   It's Moore, you see, who's the best defensive player in the
Final Four.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the best defensive player I've ever coached,'' UConn boss
Jim Calhoun said.
</P>
<P>
   Moore's assignment Saturday was Ohio State point guard Scoonie
Penn, the Big Ten Player of the Year who scored 48 points in South
Regional victories over Auburn and St. John's. As Baron Davis is to
UCLA and Andre Miller to Utah, so is Penn to the Buckeyes.
</P>
<P>
   But against Moore's smothering defense, Penn scored just 11
points on 3-of-13 shooting _ his lowest totals in a non-blowout in
three months.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wanted him to shoot tough shots,'' Moore said. ``I was
taking away the drive first. The second option was jump shots. He
did a couple times.''
</P>
<P>
   Sure, Hamilton and El-Amin were superb. Hamilton even hit the
game's biggest shot _ a 10-footer from the right side with 1:43
remaining that gave the Huskies a 61-55 lead. But without Moore's
defense, it would have been Ohio State's game. The Buckeyes did not
hit their free throws (9 of 18), and they didn't have Penn's
production in crucial situations.
</P>
<P>
   ``He did a great job covering me,'' Penn said. ``He just didn't
let me breathe the whole time.''
</P>
<P>
   The Huskies scored most of their points in transition; when the
pace slowed, their half-court offense was ineffective. They had
little inside presence _ frontliners Jake Voskuhl and Kevin Freeman
combined for seven points _ and they committed 14 turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, Connecticut provided no evidence it's ready for
Duke in Monday's title game. If anything, Saturday seemed to
indicate the Huskies are headed for a whipping.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't play at the top of our game,'' Freeman said. ``I
don't think we played particularly well, but things like that
happen. We got too relaxed and let them come back. We know we have
to be more aggressive Monday.''
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's game had an appealing rhythm. The Huskies jumped to a
nine-point lead midway through the first half, then watched Ohio
State produce a 10-0 response. The second half mirrored the first _
UConn in command early, Ohio State late. When smooth sophomore
Michael Redd's layup cut the deficit to 57-54 with 4:13 remaining,
the Huskies appeared on the brink of implosion.
</P>
<P>
   But El-Amin converted an eight-footer, then Hamilton struck from
the right side. In a blink, Connecticut had recovered to a
six-point lead. With Moore close enough to check for cavities,
Penn's last-gasp 3-pointers had no chance, and neither did the
Buckeyes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically (Moore) cut the head of the dragon off,'' Calhoun
said. &UR;
</P>
</TEXT>
